<pb n="xvii">




<div2>
<poem r="italic">

<comhd2><idref>Z200646696</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>[The leaves which in the autumn of the years]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646696</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>[The leaves which in the autumn of the years]</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028163</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028163</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>[The leaves which in the autumn of the years]</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">The leaves which in the autumn of the years
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Fall auburn&hyphen;tinted from their parent trees,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Swept from dismembered boughs by ruthless breese,
</l><l ln="4        ">Through Winter's weary reign of want and fears
</l><l ln="5        ">Will lie in drifts; and when the snowdrop cheers&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Frail firstling of the flowers&mdash;they still are there,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;There still, although the balmy southern air
</l><l ln="8        ">And budding boughs proclaim that Spring appcars.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">So lost hopes severed by the stress of life
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Unburied lie before our wistful eyes,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;&indent;Though none but we regard their fell dccay; 
</l><l ln="12      ">And ever amid the stir of worldly strife
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Fresh aims and fuller purposes arise
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Between the faded hopes of yesterday.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="3">

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200646697</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

MISCELLANEOUS PIECES. <attbytes>15Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646697</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646698</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646698</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028164</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028164</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> strong River of Thought has an ayechangeful course,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Yet for ever it springs from the same changeless source
</l><l ln="3        ">Where God&hyphen;given Truth in its grandeur doth reign,
</l><l ln="4        ">The regal physician of Man's mental pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Sometimes in high joyance it glideth along
</l><l ln="6        ">With glamour of music and gladness of song:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">While borne on its bosom gay pleasure&hyphen;boats sail,
</l><l ln="8        ">Rejoicing a while in the light laughing gale.</l></stanza>

<pb n="4">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Sometimes like the stream which has sunk under ground,
</l><l ln="10      ">Yet still keeps its course mid the darkness profound,
</l><l ln="11      ">Unknown and alone it must hold on its way,
</l><l ln="12      ">Till emerging at length in the full light of day.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Sometimes like the mountain's fierce torrent it flows,
</l><l ln="14      ">And all that can hinder its progress o'erthrows;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Possessing the power of immutable right,
</l><l ln="16      ">And strong in the strength of invincible might.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Crass Ignorance surely succumbs to its sway,
</l><l ln="18      ">As boldly it takes its all&hyphen;conquering way,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">While keen&hyphen;sighted Knowledge appears in its train,
</l><l ln="20      ">The sweetener of pleasure, the soother of pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Unceasingly hated by many, yet some
</l><l ln="22      ">Unceasingly love it, though oft they are dumb.
</l><l ln="23      ">Yet whatever betides, and wherever it flows,
</l><l ln="24      ">'Tis the noble who love it, the weak who oppose</l></stanza>

<pb n="5">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Great River of Thought! our strange world doth not know
</l><l ln="26      ">The evil you check, and the good you bestow:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">May Time teach the lesson, 'twill then comprehend
</l><l ln="28      ">How well and how often you prove its true friend.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="8">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646699</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WHISPERING WINDS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646699</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHISPERING WINDS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028165</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028165</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHISPERING WINDS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Whispering</hi> winds strange musings carry
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To our hearts as they sweep by:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Thoughts that often thrilling tarry
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Though the winds may wailing die.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">To the sailor, watchful pacing
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;On the deck of ship at sea,
</l><l ln="7        ">Bring they dreams of danger facing,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Mid the tempest's mockery.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">To the exile, hoping, fearing,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Wandering on an alien strand,
</l><l ln="11      ">Bring they memories endearing
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of his much&hyphen;loved Father&hyphen;land.</l></stanza>

<pb n="9">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">To the weary heavy&hyphen;hearted
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Often bring they thoughts of peace,
</l><l ln="15      ">Of the peace where, pain departed,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Woe and weariness shall cease.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Sometimes bring they only sorrow
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;To the stricken in their train,
</l><l ln="19      ">Imaging a dread to&hyphen;morrow
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Which will but augment their pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Bring they unto some new pleasure
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And each trace of care destroy,
</l><l ln="23      ">While to others yield a measure
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Of distress that mars their joy.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Yet these forms of varied feeling
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;In this feature all agree,
</l><l ln="27      ">That o'er every soul is stealing
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Thought of an Eternity.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="10">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646700</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HELPFULNESS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646700</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HELPFULNESS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028166</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028166</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HELPFULNESS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Behold</hi> a fine tree growing in a field,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Apart from any other, and alone,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;With nothing to preserve it or to shield
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;It from the wind, yet it is ever known
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;To thrive as well as trees whose lot is thrown
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In sheltered woods, saved from the wintry blast.
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;And first from it in spring is heard the tone
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Of singing birds; for, while its branches last,
</l><l ln="9        ">It is a blessing where its lonely lot is cast.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="10      ">&indent;How well if often thus with man it were,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;For surely cheering others on their way
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Would wondrously relieve our ceaseless care,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;And dissipate the gloom of Life's drear day,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;By teaching us that Love will truly pay
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;An hundredfold again what we bestow
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Upon our brother toilers; none can say
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;The blessings that we reap when thus we show
</l><l ln="18      ">Our sympathy for men by sharing in their woe.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="11">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646701</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE SOURCE OF SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646701</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE SOURCE OF SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028167</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028167</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SOURCE OF SONG.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">What</hi> maketh the true poet sing?
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Is it sense of deep injuries thrown
</l><l ln="3        ">On the weak by the strong, which sting
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;His heart, till to song he is prone?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Is it sight of some beautiful lake
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;All aflame with the dying sun's rays,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">O'er whose breast the acacias shake
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Soft tresses of feathery sprays?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Is it thought of some beautiful form
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;That fays well might deign to assume; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Displaying with ardour full warm,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;How noble is youth's early bloom?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Is it thought of his dear mother&hyphen;land,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;The deep longing that she be supreme:
</l><l ln="15      ">Aspiration as loyal as grand,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Which to sons should be more than a dream?</l></stanza>

<pb n="12">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Is it pleasure in physical health&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;The supreme unacquirable dower,
</l><l ln="19      ">Far greater in blessing than wealth,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And almost as mighty in power?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Is it simple desire to excel?
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Or ambition that's highest and best,
</l><l ln="23      ">Which longs among mankind to dwell,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To show by true life what is blest?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">With such things the poet must strive,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And sometimes they impel him to sing,
</l><l ln="27      ">Till in fortunate hour they may drive
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Him for aid to re&hyphen;touch his lute's string.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">But the primary cause which impels,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;More resistless than aught of these things,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="31      ">Is this: that within him there dwells
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;A soul which but lives when he sings.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="13">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646702</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A STORM SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646702</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A STORM SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028168</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028168</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A STORM SONG.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> surges in anger are beating
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;On the rocks and the shingle&hyphen;strewn shore,
</l><l ln="3        ">And though with a hiss aye retreating,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;They come in fierce fury once more.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Most sternly the billows are breaking
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In wreaths white with purest of spray,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Still further their great wrath awaking,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;As forward they dash on their way.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">The wild wailing wind that is blowing,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The dreariness far out to sea,
</l><l ln="11      ">The feelings that come without knowing
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;In truth what their nature may be.</l></stanza>

<pb n="14">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">All these, and much more now oppress me
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;As musing I gaze on the strand:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet though in some sense it distress me,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;How noble a storm is,&mdash;how grand!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">The ships in the bay are so swaying,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Their cables can scarce bear the strain:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Their beams with the water are playing
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;While sailing is utterly vain</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">As the gale is against them completely; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;The rain how it ceaselessly falls,
</l><l ln="23      ">Clouds scud o'er the sky, ah how fleetly!
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And harsh are the sea&hyphen;birds' shrill calls.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">The storm is now spent and departed
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And yet its effects still remain,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">Two mothers are made broken&hyphen;hearted,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Their boys will not greet them again.</l></stanza>

<pb n="15">

<stanza><l ln="29      ">How wondrous it is that Creation
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Is aye in perpetual strife,
</l><l ln="31      ">And shows not, for man's emulation,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;How calmness should regulate life!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Can it be that when Man in his madness
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;To Evil at first became thrall,
</l><l ln="35      ">All Nature was forced with sore sadness
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;To join his unspeakable fall?</l></stanza></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="16">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646703</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG FOR POLAND IN 1878.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646703</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG FOR POLAND IN 1878.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028169</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028169</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG FOR POLAND IN 1878.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Ah</hi>, how cruel the thraldom and bitter the bonds
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of our wretched and down&hyphen;trodden nation!
</l><l ln="3        ">Not a throb of our hearts but in anguish responds
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To the sight of such dire desolation:
</l><l ln="5        ">And in scarce&hyphen;spoken words we are heard to declare
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Woe hath made us wellnigh broken&hyphen;hearted,
</l><l ln="7        ">Dark and dreary the prospect; dear Poland, despair,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Since thy liberty now hath departed.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Other peoples get freedom, while we in the dust
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Alone and forsaken are lying; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Ever lower and lower continually thrust,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Men's love of their country fast dying.
</l><l ln="13      ">While the Government check with malicious intent
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Any change for our good which is started.
</l><l ln="15      ">Dark and dreary the prospect; let Poland lament,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Since her liberty's light hath departed!</l></stanza>

<pb n="17">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">No! Revenge on the tyrants who work us such ill
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Mid their bland hypocritical prating:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">And arouse ye, undaunted, remembering that still
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Retribution is certainly waiting.
</l><l ln="21      ">Let our nation awake which now slumbering lies!
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Not a moment be longer down&hyphen;hearted!
</l><l ln="23      ">For rejoicing may come if proud Poland arise,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And her freedom return which departed.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="18">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646704</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WHAT ALL MAY DO.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646704</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHAT ALL MAY DO.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028170</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028170</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHAT ALL MAY DO.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Our</hi> past life must perish,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Our future arise,
</l><l ln="3        ">And oft what we cherish
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Most speedily dies:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">There are griefs for whose changing
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;We helplessly long,
</l><l ln="7        ">Though we feel our arranging
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Is hopelessly wrong:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">But if we live rightly,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;We have in our power
</l><l ln="11      ">To gather up brightly,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;From each fading hour,
</l><l ln="13      ">A thought&hyphen;woven treasure
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of justly&hyphen;earned joy,
</l><l ln="15      ">Whose bountiful measure
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;No grief can destroy.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="19">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646705</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>REWARD OF PARLIAMENTARY
DOCILITY.

<subhead r="smcap">A Brother to a Sister.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646705</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>REWARD OF PARLIAMENTARY DOCILITY.  A Brother to a Sister.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028171</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028171</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>REWARD OF PARLIAMENTARY DOCILITY.  A Brother to a Sister.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<prologue r="smcap">My dear&mdash;</prologue>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">As words though sincere,</l></firstl>
</pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="2        ">                                    Are at best but &lsquo;small beer,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="3        ">My party (in office) have made me a peer:
</l><l ln="4        ">A step which the press I do hope won't deem queer,
</l><l ln="5        ">Nor question its justice, not slightingly sneer,
</l><l ln="6        ">(What I've done to deserve it is not very clear,
</l><l ln="7        ">Save doing as bid, when divisions were near&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Thus causing our Whip's drooping spirits to cheer,)
</l><l ln="9        ">But be that as it may, I subscribe myself here
</l><l ln="10      ">John Anthony <hi r="smcap">Snobbins</hi>,</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="11      ">                                 (<hi r="italic">now</hi>) <hi r="smcap">Lord Abinmere</hi>.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="23">

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200646706</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SONNETS ON THE POWER OF
THOUGHT. <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646706</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300646707</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>In Converse.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646707</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>In Converse.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028172</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028172</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>In Converse.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Who</hi> can predict what power for distant days
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Toward good or ill lies centred in a Thought
</l><l ln="3        ">Which flashing through the mind unmeant, unsought,
</l><l ln="4        ">Is uttered suddenly in careless phrase?
</l><l ln="5        ">Ill that no future good can stingless make
</l><l ln="6        ">In the effects wrought by its blighting force;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Great good that floweth from the all&hyphen;good Source,
</l><l ln="8        ">The Fount from which all purity we take.
</l><l ln="9        ">Sometimes thought's mighty aims in secret lurk
</l><l ln="10      ">And labour silently, their aim concealed,
</l><l ln="11      ">Until the crisis comes; sometimes revealed
</l><l ln="12      ">They zealously pursue their varied work.
</l><l ln="13      ">Reflecting wisely thus may we be taught
</l><l ln="14      ">Not rashly to express each flippant thought.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="24">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300646708</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>In Writing.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646708</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>In Writing.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028173</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028173</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>In Writing.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">If</hi> so it be with speech, how much the more
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With written language! Speech perforce decays,
</l><l ln="3        ">'Neath Time's destroying touch. Ere many days
</l><l ln="4        ">Gone is mayhap the fruit which wise words bore:
</l><l ln="5        ">That written doth remain,&mdash;its import not
</l><l ln="6        ">Dependent on frail Memory's brittle thread
</l><l ln="7        ">To keep it safe, or number with the dead
</l><l ln="8        ">At her capricious will. None can say what
</l><l ln="9        ">Momentous destiny may be assigned
</l><l ln="10      ">To some brief trivial letter. Authors too
</l><l ln="11      ">Who lightly pen, to please the public view,
</l><l ln="12      ">Works strenuous and yet stained with vice, will find
</l><l ln="13      ">A day of certain retribution come
</l><l ln="14      ">When all their loud excuses will be dumb.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="25">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300646709</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>In Art.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646709</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>In Art.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028174</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028174</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>In Art.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> power of Thought in art! Who has not found
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And marked its subtle influence? We see
</l><l ln="3        ">Its magic in a picture wondrously,
</l><l ln="4        ">Whose canvas by its presence made renowned
</l><l ln="5        ">Bears witness to the fact. When we behold
</l><l ln="6        ">A stately building, and perceive the skill
</l><l ln="7        ">Which shapes each column at the sculptor's will
</l><l ln="8        ">Till it attains at length th' exquisite mould
</l><l ln="9        ">That he has long desired. When we are thrilled
</l><l ln="10      ">By some soft cadence rippling on the ear
</l><l ln="11      ">Of sweetest music,&mdash;as though far and near
</l><l ln="12      ">With a celestial choir the air were filled:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Then, and then always, may we truly find
</l><l ln="14      ">What power of thought lies in the human mind!</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="26">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300646710</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>In Proverbs, &amp;c.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646710</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>In Proverbs, &amp;c.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028175</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028175</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>In Proverbs, &amp;c.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> power of Thought in Proverbs!&mdash;oftentimes
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">We find its glittering essence centred there,
</l><l ln="3        ">All crystallized, as if indeed it were
</l><l ln="4        ">A bright and flawless diamond.&mdash;Silly Rhymes
</l><l ln="5        ">Which oft we hear repeated are not dross
</l><l ln="6        ">Entirely,&mdash;here and there rare pearls of thought
</l><l ln="7        ">Appear upon their surface, genius&hyphen;wrought; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Had they not been, we must have borne a loss.
</l><l ln="9        ">O mighty power of Thought, it may not be
</l><l ln="10      ">Within the sphere of any man to find
</l><l ln="11      ">Thought undiscovered by a brother&hyphen;mind,
</l><l ln="12      ">Though deep and boundless is thy shoreless sea:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">And yet thy potent pathway is the groove
</l><l ln="14      ">In which, by thee propelled, the change&hyphen;girt world doth move.</l></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="27">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646711</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN MEMORY

OF

<hi r="italic">The gallant men who fell fighting at Isandhlwana,
South Africa, in a surprise by the Zulus</hi>,
23<hi r="italic">d January</hi> 1879.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646711</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN MEMORY  OF  The gallant men who fell fighting at Isandhlwana, South Africa, in a surprise by the Zulus, 23d January 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028176</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028176</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN MEMORY  OF  The gallant men who fell fighting at Isandhlwana, South Africa, in a surprise by the Zulus, 23d January 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Elegy</attgenre><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Steadfast</hi> they stood,&mdash;nor feared to face the foe
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Though twenty&hyphen;fold outnumbered,&mdash;calm, alone
</l><l ln="3        ">They bore the brunt of battle on them thrown,
</l><l ln="4        ">And bravely strove against the ignoble blow:
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet doubtless mid the din of deadly strife
</l><l ln="6        ">Came softened thoughts of home and loved ones dear:
</l><l ln="7        ">And many a prayer was prayed in faith sincere
</l><l ln="8        ">That they might meet anew in deathless life.
</l><l ln="9        "><hi r="italic">We</hi> mourn their loss (a wound Time scarce can heal)&mdash; 
</l><pb n="28">
<l ln="10      ">Yet we are proud such courage doth remain
</l><l ln="11      ">Among us. May we soon efface the stain
</l><l ln="12      ">From England's flag,&mdash;while more and more we feel
</l><l ln="13      ">A sense of joy, which in our hearts will stay,
</l><l ln="14      ">That Britain still can boast these &lsquo;heroes of to&hyphen;day.&rsquo; 

</l><signed><hi r="italic">Feb.</hi> 22<hi r="italic">d</hi>, 1879.</signed></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="30">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646712</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>VIOLET.</mainhead> <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646712</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>VIOLET.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028177</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028177</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>VIOLET.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>7Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&lsquo;<hi r="smcap">A tale</hi> of sorrow&rsquo;? Ay, I know,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">One fraught with sharp and sudden woe,
</l><l ln="3        ">A story of undoubted truth,
</l><l ln="4        ">Beclouding all my sunny youth; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And though with arbitrary sway
</l><l ln="6        ">Stern Time has turned my locks to grey,
</l><l ln="7        ">Though furrowed wrinkles on my brow
</l><l ln="8        ">Proclaim that I am ag&egrave;d now,
</l><l ln="9        ">Though signs of trouble you may trace
</l><l ln="10      ">In the expression of my face,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Though trembling is my bloodless hand,
</l><l ln="12      ">And scarcely under due command,
</l><l ln="13      ">Though devious is my tottering tread,
</l><l ln="14      ">Though bent with weight of years my head; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Though my whole look, my gait, my air,
</l><l ln="16      ">Show sad though common signs of care,
</l><l ln="17      ">Yet fadeless, unforgotten, clear,
</l><l ln="18      ">To mental sight its scenes appear.
</l><pb n="31">
<l ln="19      ">Of sisters I had only one
</l><l ln="20      ">As playmate,&mdash;brothers I had none.
</l><l ln="21      ">A lovely rose&hyphen;lipped child was she,
</l><l ln="22      ">Dear as my very life to me; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Now, almost mournful in their birth,
</l><l ln="24      ">Rise thoughts of these dead days of mirth; 
</l><l ln="25      ">I see her framing daisy&hyphen;chains
</l><l ln="26      ">While I assist, and for my pains
</l><l ln="27      ">Receiving, as repayment meet,
</l><l ln="28      ">The chaplet from her when complete.
</l><l ln="29      ">And as o'er both the restless years
</l><l ln="30      ">Resistless rolled their hopes and fears,
</l><l ln="31      ">They only bound us by a bond
</l><l ln="32      ">More durable and just as fond.
</l><l ln="33      ">O happy he who thus hath known
</l><l ln="34      ">Such union ere his lot was thrown
</l><l ln="35      ">Amid the changes and the strife
</l><l ln="36      ">And heart&hyphen;wounds of the world's strange life!
</l><l ln="37      ">Even dreams of such communion to the bruised and wearied soul,
</l><l ln="38      ">Are ever found the truest balm to make it strong and whole.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="32">

<pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="39      ">Yes: years rolled on, with little change
</l><l ln="40      ">For us in Duty's daily range.
</l><l ln="41      ">My sister&mdash;Violet her name,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="42      ">In beauty grown, remained the same
</l><l ln="43      ">In character. Her guileless grace,
</l><l ln="44      ">Almost a proverb in the place,
</l><l ln="45      ">To those she loved exceeding fond,
</l><l ln="46      ">And gentle unto all beyond.
</l><l ln="47      ">Ever for right most firm and strong,
</l><l ln="48      ">Aye valiantly rebuking wrong,
</l><l ln="49      ">And seeking in whatever mood
</l><l ln="50      ">To shun the ill and do the good.
</l><l ln="51      ">Her figure pleasing as her mien,
</l><l ln="52      ">Her summers numbering seventeen; 
</l><l ln="53      ">Her rippling hair of darkest hue,
</l><l ln="54      ">Her eyes not oft describ&egrave;d blue,
</l><l ln="55      ">But some rare tint,&mdash;and pen can ne'er
</l><l ln="56      ">Portray the radiance glowing there.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="57      ">There was a youth whom Violet thought
</l><l ln="58      ">Worthy her love, and he had caught
</l><l ln="59      ">A kindred flame of chaste desire; 
</l><l ln="60      ">A truer love could none require,
</l><l ln="61      ">Parents and friends were satisfied,
</l><l ln="62      ">And well they might be; all descried
</l><pb n="33">
<l ln="63      ">That union of such virtuous worth
</l><l ln="64      ">Would prove the happiest on earth.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="65      ">Our lawn stretched to a deep broad stream:
</l><l ln="66      ">On summer eves 'twas like a dream
</l><l ln="67      ">To watch the gentle moonbeams play
</l><l ln="68      ">Across its wide and glittering way; 
</l><l ln="69      ">To trace the tremor of the trees
</l><l ln="70      ">Slow moving in the soft night breeze,
</l><l ln="71      ">And as on either side they bend
</l><l ln="72      ">Each towards the other as a friend
</l><l ln="73      ">Talking with comrade dear,&mdash;to think
</l><l ln="74      ">These trees, converse they, on this river's brink?</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="75      ">On the stream's tide we kept a boat,
</l><l ln="76      ">Not often did it idly float
</l><l ln="77      ">In peace near to the summer shore; 
</l><l ln="78      ">For one alone could ply its oar
</l><l ln="79      ">With pleasure. In the sultry noon,
</l><l ln="80      ">With bees and birds and trees in tune,
</l><l ln="81      ">How sweet to glide in it, and screen
</l><l ln="82      ">'Neath willows from the scorching sheen; 
</l><l ln="83      ">Thus Violet full oft had been.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="34">

<pdiv><l ln="84      ">And so one day&mdash;the heat was great,
</l><l ln="85      ">And, we conjecture, to abate
</l><l ln="86      ">Its force, she to the water dipped
</l><l ln="87      ">To lave her hands,&mdash;in quickly slipped
</l><l ln="88      ">The boat's light oar; that then she tried
</l><l ln="89      ">To reach it, bending on one side,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="90      ">Till gone too far to stay, 'twould seem,
</l><l ln="91      ">She slid into the treacherous stream.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="92      ">Too late an oarless boat was found,
</l><l ln="93      ">And near, a maiden, soul&hyphen;less, drowned,
</l><l ln="94      ">In whose fair face and gloomless mien
</l><l ln="95      ">Death in his gentlest form was seen.
</l><l ln="96      ">One lover more o'erwhelmed with grief,
</l><l ln="97      ">Whose tears as yet brought no relief,
</l><l ln="98      ">Who, righteous and untouched by guile,
</l><l ln="99      ">Ne'er sought another maiden's smile; 
</l><l ln="100    ">A brother who through all his coming years
</l><l ln="101    ">Will strive to dry his brethren's bitter tears.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="102    ">&lsquo;A common story, this,&rsquo; I hear one say,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="103    ">&lsquo;Not worth the telling.&rsquo; Nay, stern critic, nay; 
</l><pb n="35">
<l ln="104    ">Each man's heart&hyphen;tragedy, if truly told,
</l><l ln="105    ">Will interest some, although to most 'tis cold
</l><l ln="106    ">And commonplace. No case of mental pain
</l><l ln="107    ">Which crushes not, but strengthens, can be vain.</l></pdiv></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="36">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646713</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HEART ECHOES.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646713</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HEART ECHOES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028178</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028178</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HEART ECHOES.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">While</hi> the sunlight's glory dying
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;&indent;Tints the pebbly sea&hyphen;kissed strand,
</l><l ln="3        ">And the night&hyphen;chilled breezes sighing,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;&indent;See the shadows wrap the land&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Faint, yet powerful, sad, yet tender,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;Come fond thoughts of vanished years,
</l><l ln="7        ">Waking sweet soul&hyphen;thrills that render
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;Joy that is akin to tears.
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Ah, how real are these dreams!
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And the past the present seems.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">Visions of a gentle maiden
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;Beautiful and pure as fair,
</l><l ln="13      ">And of eves whose gales love&hyphen;laden
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Wanton with her auburn hair; 
</l><pb n="37">
<l ln="15      ">For 'twas when soft summer's beauty
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;&indent;Made the earth with gladness rife
</l><l ln="17      ">First I felt, as well as duty,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;What deep joy might be in life:
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Ah, how real are these dreams!
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And the past the present seems.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Memories are swiftly thronging
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;&indent;Of that span of treasured past,
</l><l ln="23      ">When the joy to me belonging
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;&indent;Was, alas! too bright to last:
</l><l ln="25      ">Still do I remember clearly
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;&indent;What I asked with trembling voice,
</l><l ln="27      ">And her words, &lsquo;I love you dearly,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;&indent;And am proud to be your choice.&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Ah, how real are these dreams!
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;And the past the present seems.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="31      ">We were &lsquo;wedded, happy&hyphen;hearted,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;&indent;And our future path seemed bright,
</l><l ln="33      ">Who could tell we should be parted,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;&indent;Love's glad sun obscured in night?
</l><pb n="38">
<l ln="35      ">Yet before another spring&hyphen;tide
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;&indent;Shed abroad its myriad charms,
</l><l ln="37      ">Bitter blow! my darling left me,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;&indent;Dying calmly in my arms.
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;Ah, how real, fraught with woe,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Rise these dreams of long ago!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">Still amid my sore dejection,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;&indent;In its comfort ever new,
</l><l ln="43      ">Comes the soothing, sweet reflection,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;&indent;To each other we were true.
</l><l ln="45      ">For some end God sendeth sorrow,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;&indent;And when this at length is gained
</l><l ln="47      ">I shall meet my bride in Heaven
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;&indent;Happy, holy, and unstained.
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;<hi r="italic">There</hi> no longer fraught with woe
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Rise the dreams of long ago.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="39">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646714</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE POET'S POWERLESSNESS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646714</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE POET'S POWERLESSNESS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028179</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028179</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE POET'S POWERLESSNESS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Unto</hi> the poet's mental eye how clear
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Appears a scene he would in wise words weave
</l><l ln="3        ">Into the varied texture of his verse!
</l><l ln="4        ">A scene it is of beauty unsurpassed,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Of hoary mountains whose gigantic peaks
</l><l ln="6        ">Approach the sky,&mdash;of a fair wooded vale,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And of a rushing rivulet, whose sound
</l><l ln="8        ">Re&hyphen;echoes in his ears. A simple theme
</l><l ln="9        ">Methinks to handle, yet at once he finds
</l><l ln="10      ">How hard it is to choose the magic words
</l><l ln="11      ">With which to make the spell he trusts will bind
</l><l ln="12      ">The senses of his readers. Ever thus
</l><l ln="13      ">He feels it in description,&mdash;also when
</l><l ln="14      ">Depicting subtle feelings of the soul,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Indeed in every subject meet for song:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">And so he feels that words are at the best
</l><l ln="17      ">Most ineffective colours to paint well
</l><l ln="18      ">A theme Imagination&hyphen;glorified.</l></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="40">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646715</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE OMNIPRESENCE OF POETRY.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646715</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE OMNIPRESENCE OF POETRY.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028180</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028180</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE OMNIPRESENCE OF POETRY.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">There</hi>'s poetry in everything,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;If poets could but find
</l><l ln="3        ">How best its subtle power to bring
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To breathe upon the mind.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">It lurks in all of Nature's store,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Alike on land and main,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Where far from shore the breakers roar,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And on the quiet plain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">'Mid lofty mountains whose proud peaks
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Appear to pierce the sky,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">In valleys where the farmer seeks
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;His busy tasks to ply.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">'Mid scenes where babbling brooklets haste,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Engirt with flowery strand; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Where man's harsh turmoil makes a waste
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Of erst a beauteous land</l></stanza>

<pb n="43">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">In mighty cities never dumb
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;With sounds of human life,
</l><l ln="19      ">In villages where seldom come
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Cares born of human strife.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">'Mid friends and kindred everywhere,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;In talks with those we love
</l><l ln="23      ">When happy intercourse we share;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;In thoughts of things above.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Enwove with every feeling here,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Part of each joy and pain,
</l><l ln="27      ">And permeating love sincere
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Which never can be vain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">For Poetry's white hands can mould,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;From all of Earth, pure leaven;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="31      ">And who shall say it will not hold
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;A noble place in Heaven!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="44">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646716</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>FRAGMENT FOR MUSIC.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646716</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>FRAGMENT FOR MUSIC.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028181</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028181</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FRAGMENT FOR MUSIC.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Softly</hi> swaying
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Are the flowers,
</l><l ln="3        ">Scents betraying
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;'Mid the showers:
</l><l ln="5        ">Gently moving
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Are the trees,
</l><l ln="7        ">Not reproving
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The rude breeze.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Stars shine quiet
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Though the storm's
</l><l ln="11      ">Cloudlets riot
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;O'er their forms:
</l><l ln="13      ">Moonrays mildly
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Shed their light,
</l><l ln="15      ">Though still wildly
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Wails the night.</l></stanza>

<pb n="45">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Mountains never
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In their might
</l><l ln="19      ">Care if ever
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Lost to sight:
</l><l ln="21      ">Plants must wither
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And be lost
</l><l ln="23      ">When comes thither
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Biting frost.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Lower creatures
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Scarce complain,
</l><l ln="27      ">Nor their features
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Change with pain; 
</l><l ln="29      ">Though Toil's burden
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Ne'er is done,
</l><l ln="31      ">Though no guerdon
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Can be won.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">At each season
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Man makes moan
</l><l ln="35      ">Though glad reason
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Is his own;&mdash; 
</l><pb n="46">
<l ln="37      ">Notwithstanding
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;In his might
</l><l ln="39      ">Earth commanding,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Wrong or right.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="47">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646717</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AN EVENING LANDSCAPE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646717</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AN EVENING LANDSCAPE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028182</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028182</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AN EVENING LANDSCAPE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Lyric</attgenre><attgenre>Heroic couplets</attgenre></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> sun has set, and shades of evening close,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And all around there reigns profound repose; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And not a sound is heard, save when the breeze
</l><l ln="4        ">In fitful gusts comes rustling through the trees; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And with its facile force their branches sways,
</l><l ln="6        ">Like spectres moving in the moon's faint rays.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Ah, little change the face of nature knows,
</l><l ln="8        ">Compared with life's oft&hyphen;changing joys and woes,
</l><l ln="9        ">And while poor, puny man departs as fast
</l><l ln="10      ">As smoke is scattered by the wintry blast; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Its aspect will continue as of yore,
</l><l ln="12      ">Till God decrees that Time shall be no more.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="48">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646718</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE GUERDON OF TRIBULATION
NOT INCURRED BY GUILT.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646718</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE GUERDON OF TRIBULATION NOT INCURRED BY GUILT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028183</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028183</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE GUERDON OF TRIBULATION NOT INCURRED BY GUILT.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Oh</hi> say not that the world is sad
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Without redeeming feature,
</l><l ln="3        ">Oh say not that the world is glad
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And holds no hopeless creature.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">No life is ever filled with woe
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;However great its sadness,
</l><l ln="7        ">No lot can be all joy, although
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Most glorious seems its gladness.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">With endless grief Life is not fraught,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Nor with all bliss and beauty,
</l><l ln="11      ">By varied influence we are taught
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;How to fulfil our duty.</l></stanza>

<pb n="49">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">If happy be our lot assigned,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of sorrow slight our burden,
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet work on still with steadfast mind
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Assured shall be our guerdon:</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">But a crown more rich to those shall be
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;From pain much less exempted,
</l><l ln="19      ">If conquering the same foes as we,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Although more sorely tempted.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Thus every woe our souls within,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Though stern its present sadness,
</l><l ln="23      ">If meekly borne, nor caused by sin,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Augments our future gladness.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="51">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646719</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE TRUE TREASURE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646719</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE TRUE TREASURE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028184</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028184</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE TRUE TREASURE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Living</hi> brings us bitter sorrow,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Oft our hearts refuse submission,
</l><l ln="3        ">While we yearn for a to&hyphen;morrow
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Which shall change our dark condition.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Love may bring us bitter sadness
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When we find our love can never
</l><l ln="7        ">More impart the sense of gladness
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Which we thought it would for ever.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Joy may bring us bitter trouble,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Faith give place to Falsehood's anguish,
</l><l ln="11      ">Hope may prove an empty bubble
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;When bereft of it we languish.</l></stanza>

<pb n="52">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Worldly peace may bring us only
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;More of pain and less of quiet,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">And departing leave us lonely,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Battling in the world's rude riot.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Faith in man may bring delusion,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Oftentimes, when it has perished,
</l><l ln="19      ">We discover with confusion
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;'Twas a phantom that we cherished.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Trust in God is truest treasure,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;For of change it holds no leaven,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">If we live aright, its measure
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Makes us holy, worthy Heaven.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="53">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646720</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>EDGAR VANNING:

<subhead>A SKETCH.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>28Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646720</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028185</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028185</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>28Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<list><caption r="italic">PERSONS.</caption>

<item><hi r="smcap">Edgar Vanning</hi>.&mdash;<hi r="italic">A young man near the close
of a successful University career</hi>.</item>

<item><hi r="smcap">Alethea Stanton</hi>.&mdash;<hi r="italic">His betrothed</hi>.</item></list>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646721</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE I. <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646721</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">Edgar's college rooms. <hi r="smcap">Edgar</hi> seated at a table, holding in his hand
an open letter, which informs him that he has succeeded in
obtaining a much&hyphen;coveted University honour.</stage>

<speaker r="smcap">Edgar.</speaker>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Truly</hi> a grand&mdash;a noble thing is life,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And with what joy a young man's life is fraught,
</l><l ln="3        ">When, with a mind matured, a happy heart,
</l><l ln="4        ">And resolution firm, he gazes forth
</l><l ln="5        ">Upon the boundless world! He knows its snares,
</l><pb n="64">
<l ln="6        ">Its pitfalls, and its quicksands; yet to him
</l><l ln="7        ">'Tis given to avoid them. He is not
</l><l ln="8        ">A foolish simple boy fired with strange thoughts
</l><l ln="9        ">Of schemes impracticable, which should cure
</l><l ln="10      ">The ills that are the bane of social life
</l><l ln="11      ">In these our modern days.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="12      ">                                      Yet though he feels
</l><l ln="13      ">Not youth's enthusiasm, nor its sense&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">So all&hyphen;absorbing that success is sure:
</l><l ln="15      ">Though conscious of his failures and his faults,
</l><l ln="16      ">Though knowing well his many weaknesses,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="17      ">Yet hath he self&hyphen;respect, and knoweth too
</l><l ln="18      ">His capabilities;&mdash;and hopes, ay, longs
</l><l ln="19      ">By steadfast effort to effect some good,
</l><l ln="20      ">Which shall, however small, still serve to show
</l><l ln="21      ">That all his life hath not been barrenness.
</l><l ln="22      ">But these are stern thoughts&mdash;let them pass&mdash;there flows
</l><l ln="23      ">The fresh untrammelled blood of buoyant life
</l><l ln="24      ">Full joyous through my veins; my mind is clear,
</l><l ln="25      ">My intellect is cultured, and I hope
</l><l ln="26      ">My heart is happy. I have lately said
</l><l ln="27      ">That life to such is gladness, let me not
</l><l ln="28      ">Belie so recent words.</l></pdiv>
<pb n="65">
<pdiv><l ln="29      ">                                 Ay, when I think
</l><l ln="30      ">Of that great love which nestles in my soul,
</l><l ln="31      ">Like a fair darling child of three years old
</l><l ln="32      ">On her fond father's breast:&mdash;when it is true
</l><l ln="33      ">That this love hath its guerdon, I should be
</l><l ln="34      ">For ever gladsome: I remember well
</l><l ln="35      ">The retinue of unreturning years
</l><l ln="36      ">And many a day and hour which made them up,
</l><l ln="37      ">Since she, who is my heart's desire, and I
</l><l ln="38      ">Had our first meeting. We were children both&mdash; 
</l><l ln="39      ">Our parents were firm friends, and we were thrown
</l><l ln="40      ">Often together: and as Dante loved
</l><l ln="41      ">His Beatrice, so I Alethea,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="42      ">Save that his Beatrice was proudly cold,
</l><l ln="43      ">While my Alethea was meek and kind;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="44      ">And that as children we ne'er <hi r="italic">thought</hi> of love,
</l><l ln="45      ">Although we loved so young we cannot tell
</l><l ln="46      ">When love at first began. What subtle joy
</l><l ln="47      ">It is to think that we are one in heart,
</l><l ln="48      ">Together soon to tread Life's hardened ways!
</l><l ln="49      ">What peace to me to think&mdash;a brief time past&mdash; 
</l><l ln="50      ">There comes to me a help&hyphen;meet truly meet,
</l><l ln="51      ">No speaker of sham sentiment, or words
</l><l ln="52      ">Of mawkish weary platitudes, but one
</l><pb n="66">
<l ln="53      ">Who strengthens me to do the right, who strives
</l><l ln="54      ">To urge me on to goodly deeds and great.
</l><l ln="55      ">O how refreshing oft it is to leave
</l><l ln="56      ">My studies stern, and theories dim and cold,
</l><l ln="57      ">To commune with reality so bright!
</l><l ln="58      ">How sweet to bring at last the rich reward
</l><l ln="59      ">Of lengthened brain&hyphen;wrought labour, and to say
</l><l ln="60      ">&lsquo;Thy sympathy hath helped me to succeed.&rsquo;</l></pdiv></div3>

<pb n="67">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646722</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE II. <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646722</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">A quiet summer evening. <hi r="smcap">Alethea</hi> standing in a secluded part of 
the garden of her home adjacent to an old plantation.
<hi r="smcap">Time</hi>.&mdash;A few days before the day fixed for her marriage.</stage>

<speaker r="smcap">Alethea.</speaker>

<l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A few</hi> days more! Ah what a change for me,
</l><l ln="2        ">A happy change! O kind few days that bring it&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">A blissful change! Speed swift bright days that bring it,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">A change the sense of which thrills through my soul,
</l><l ln="5        ">And makes it burst its bonds and soar in song.

</l><pdiv r="italic">
<stanza><l ln="6        ">A few days more, a few days more,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Ah what a change for me!
</l><l ln="8        ">Then I shall enter through Love's door
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;To full felicity.
</l><pb n="68">
<l ln="10      ">No more alone to bear one fear,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Or have an untold dread,
</l><l ln="12      ">To leave my path, his sweet voice hear
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;And choose his path instead.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="14      ">A few days more, then it will be
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;My duty to obey,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">A duty pleasant, joyous, free
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;As warbler's winsome lay.
</l><l ln="18      ">I'll seek to do each fond behest,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;To merit each fond smile,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="20      ">I'll strive to make his life more blest
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;His sadness to beguile.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="22      ">He praises oft my sunny hair,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;And lauds my peach&hyphen;bloom cheeks,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">I would I were far far more fair
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;When thus my dear one speaks.
</l><l ln="26      ">I feel unworthy him, and yet
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;He takes me for his wife,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="28      ">I'll yield to him&mdash;to pay my debt&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;The service of my life.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pb n="69">

<l ln="30      ">How calming is this tranquil evening hour
</l><l ln="31      ">Of sylvan solitude! The tall old oaks
</l><l ln="32      ">Near which I stand have seen full many a year,
</l><l ln="33      ">And sheltered many a maiden such as I
</l><l ln="34      ">Beneath their branches, and in future time
</l><l ln="35      ">Will shelter many more. My favourite flower,
</l><l ln="36      ">The white convolvulus, climbs in the hedge
</l><l ln="37      ">In spotless beauty as it used to do
</l><l ln="38      ">In summers long gone by; and as it will,
</l><l ln="39      ">Fanned by the breath of summers yet to come; 
</l><l ln="40      ">Nature is all unchanged, and yet to me
</l><l ln="41      ">How changed it seems to&hyphen;night! Despite my joy
</l><l ln="42      ">A curious sense of sadness steals upon me,
</l><l ln="43      ">When I reflect that guileless happy days
</l><l ln="44      ">Of thoughtless youth are now for ever past,
</l><l ln="45      ">That though life's grandest, highest, gift is mine,
</l><l ln="46      ">A love returned tenfold, yet doubtless too
</l><l ln="47      ">A share of sorrow is appointed me!</l></div3>

<pb n="70">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646723</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE III. <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646723</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">A dull autumn morning. <hi r="smcap">Alethea</hi> at a window looking out on
the depressing prospect.
<hi r="smcap">Time</hi>.&mdash;Several months after.</stage>

<speaker r="smcap">Alethea.</speaker>

<pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> blow is softened now by kindly Time,
</l><l ln="2        ">And I can breathe again. On this the day
</l><l ln="3        ">Poor Edgar starts for clearer sunnier skies
</l><l ln="4        ">I first can ponder on these dreary weeks
</l><l ln="5        ">Which lately heavily have passed away.
</l><l ln="6        ">How different from the glad and trustful days
</l><l ln="7        ">I thought they would have proved!</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="8        ">                                                  When first I heard
</l><l ln="9        ">That he was stricken by a sickness sore,
</l><l ln="10      ">A sickness nigh to death, I scarcely felt
</l><l ln="11      ">Deep sorrow, but a paralysing pain
</l><l ln="12      ">My senses dulled. I had no power to think,
</l><l ln="13      ">And life seemed dead within me; but at length
</l><l ln="14      ">Came slowly back to me the happy thought,
</l><pb n="71">
<l ln="15      ">Yes&mdash;happy even 'mid such grief as mine:
</l><l ln="16      ">My loved one needed help, and oh what joy
</l><l ln="17      ">Was mine to give it, and I almost blessed
</l><l ln="18      ">The form of his distress, that at the least
</l><l ln="19      ">It did not keep me from him. For what woe
</l><l ln="20      ">Unspeakable must be endured by those
</l><l ln="21      ">Whose loved ones have been smitten, and who know
</l><l ln="22      ">That they are suffering helpless and alone,
</l><l ln="23      ">And that the same disease which tortures keeps
</l><l ln="24      ">Apart from them the dear ones whose kind voice
</l><l ln="25      ">And sympathetic touch is their chief stay.
</l><l ln="26      ">If such a case of misery were mine,
</l><l ln="27      ">Contagion's direst mischief I would brave
</l><l ln="28      ">If I could thereby comfort those I love.</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="29      ">A chill received when heated and fatigued
</l><l ln="30      ">One day in Summer's youth&hyphen;time (when the breeze
</l><l ln="31      ">Had Winter's breath still on it) was enough
</l><l ln="32      ">To lay my Edgar low. Physicians came
</l><l ln="33      ">And went, with faces grave and measured tread; 
</l><l ln="34      ">The case was serious, they said, and none
</l><l ln="35      ">Could tell the issue. They were clever men
</l><pb n="72">
<l ln="36      ">Nor meant to be unkind; yet when I saw
</l><l ln="37      ">Them watch his pangs of pain and laboured breathing
</l><l ln="38      ">With interest all professional and cold,
</l><l ln="39      ">It wellnigh made me mad.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="40      ">                                    The crisis came
</l><l ln="41      ">And passed;&mdash;the point once turned, he slowly gained
</l><l ln="42      ">A little strength. The cautious doctors said
</l><l ln="43      ">His youth would grapple on the side of life,
</l><l ln="44      ">And he might yet recover. But for him
</l><l ln="45      ">Should be no more of hard and brain&hyphen;wrought toil
</l><l ln="46      ">Or anxious eager thought:&mdash;his life must pass
</l><l ln="47      ">In quiet,&mdash;and his winters he must spend
</l><l ln="48      ">For several years abroad. Thus he will leave
</l><l ln="49      ">Chill England's shores to&hyphen;day. Ah cruel blast
</l><l ln="50      ">And muddy cold grey sky that drives him from me!
</l><l ln="51      ">Oh callous North&hyphen;wind, couldst thou not restrain
</l><l ln="52      ">Thy blighting force and let my darling live
</l><l ln="53      ">In the same land as I? Life&hyphen;giving Sun,
</l><l ln="54      ">Oh why dost thou not shine, when, if thou didst,
</l><l ln="55      ">It would rejoice so many yearning hearts!</l></pdiv></pdiv></div3>

<pb n="73">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646724</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE IV. <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646724</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">Early morning. <hi r="smcap">Edgar</hi> standing on a balcony enjoying the
fresh balmy air and watching the last traces of the sunrise
die away in the sky.</stage>

<speaker r="smcap">Edgar.</speaker>

<pdiv><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">So</hi> yesterday was Christmas&hyphen;day, and yet
</l><l ln="2        ">Such weather joyous and unwinter&hyphen;like,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">In truth such weather as in recent years
</l><l ln="4        ">We northerners but rarely have received
</l><l ln="5        ">In sunless seasons which we summer call
</l><l ln="6        ">Merely from force of custom.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">                                          Many trees
</l><l ln="8        ">Retain their leaves&mdash;and fair it is to see
</l><l ln="9        ">Green leaves at Christmas&hyphen;time, while gorgeous flowers,
</l><l ln="10      ">Which never bloom in Britain save when placed
</l><l ln="11      ">In houses cramped and stifling with damp heat,
</l><l ln="12      ">Display their beauty in the open air.
</l><l ln="13      ">A few days since I saw&mdash;exquisite sight!
</l><pb n="74">
<l ln="14      ">An avenue of fine camellia plants,
</l><l ln="15      ">And all in fullest flower! and as I looked
</l><l ln="16      ">Up the long vista while the luscious red
</l><l ln="17      ">Commingled in my vision with the white,
</l><l ln="18      ">And as I further gazed upon the scene
</l><l ln="19      ">Of which they were the centre, and drank in
</l><l ln="20      ">Its wondrous loveliness, I felt deep joy
</l><l ln="21      ">That still amid its mingled pain and grief
</l><l ln="22      ">Such sweetness is preserved on earth to soothe
</l><l ln="23      ">And elevate men's thoughts. They who have lived
</l><l ln="24      ">Only in climates where the fickle weather
</l><l ln="25      ">Is changeful as the winds, can never know
</l><l ln="26      ">The bliss of living where, come calm or storm,
</l><l ln="27      ">No blighting blast can reach to wither up
</l><l ln="28      ">Our vital energies and make our life
</l><l ln="29      ">A misery. This is not such a clime
</l><l ln="30      ">As Italy's in winter, where the sun
</l><l ln="31      ">Makes summer as its warm rays penetrate,
</l><l ln="32      ">But in the shade the cutting searching wind
</l><l ln="33      ">Blows keenly from the snowy Apennines; 
</l><l ln="34      ">Nor such a clime as that whose azure waves
</l><l ln="35      ">Reflect with dazzling force the Day&hyphen;king's heat
</l><l ln="36      ">Upon the olive&hyphen;groves and pine&hyphen;clad crags
</l><pb n="75">
<l ln="37      ">Of the gay Riviera;&mdash;but whose warmth
</l><l ln="38      ">Dies with the day, and night is damp and cold.
</l><l ln="39      "><hi r="italic">Here</hi> winds are never cold nor ever harm
</l><l ln="40      ">With treacherous touch the trustful invalid,
</l><l ln="41      ">Who, lured by the soft sunlight, walks abroad.
</l><l ln="42      ">Here balmy night is pleasant and as mild
</l><l ln="43      ">As is the day, while the defiled sea&hyphen;shore
</l><l ln="44      ">Appears, at least at night, most beautiful
</l><l ln="45      ">Viewed from a distance; and the dotted lights
</l><l ln="46      ">From many a cottage on the lone crag&hyphen;sides
</l><l ln="47      ">Vie with the stars from out the deep blue sky
</l><l ln="48      ">In forming a fair circlet round the bay
</l><l ln="49      ">Like flashing jewels round the shapely arm
</l><l ln="50      ">Of youth&hyphen;dowered maid.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="51      ">                                 What were the lines I strung
</l><l ln="52      ">Together, to employ an idle hour?</l></pdiv>

<pdiv r="italic">
<stanza><l ln="53      ">Christmas in the summer sunshine! O how beautiful it seems,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="54      ">Clothed in gladness are its moments, realising poets' dreams,
</l><pb n="76">
<l ln="55      ">While its hours pass swiftly from us, how we wish they were for aye,
</l><l ln="56      ">That their bright and buoyant pleasure with its guilelessness might stay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="57      ">Christmas in the summer sunshine! softly blows the scented breeze
</l><l ln="58      ">And its coming stirs the frondage of the stately staid palm&hyphen;trees.
</l><l ln="59      ">Calm the noble realm of Ocean, fair the dotted fishing skiffs,
</l><l ln="60      ">And the verdant cactus growing on the gaunt uprising cliffs.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">All of Flora's cultured beauty freely is revealed to view,
</l><l ln="62      ">And among the vine&hyphen;clad ridges of sweet wild&hyphen;flowers not a few,
</l><l ln="63      ">Soft azaleas, rich gardenias, ope their blossoms to the air,
</l><l ln="64      ">With the rose, and trained geranium:&mdash;while its wild type too is there.</l></stanza>

<pb n="77">

<stanza><l ln="65      ">Fitting the moon's glorious radiance for the people as they pass
</l><l ln="66      ">On the eve of merry Christmas, to and from the midnight mass; 
</l><l ln="67      ">And for strolling serenaders who invade the silent hours
</l><l ln="68      ">With what doubtless they consider some of music's choicest flowers.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="69      ">Christmas in the summer sunshine! neither snow nor frost are here,
</l><l ln="70      ">Which, though they may charm the healthy, fill the invalid with fear; 
</l><l ln="71      ">And in sooth, with dear ones round him, spends he happily the day,
</l><l ln="72      ">Pining not for that loved treasure&mdash;his chill home so far away.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="73      ">Yet! 'tis the far away that makes me sad,
</l><l ln="74      ">For distance is indeed a barrier,
</l><l ln="75      ">Let bards say what they will; for though I <hi r="italic">hope</hi> 
</l><l ln="76      ">Hale health is coming back, I sometimes <hi r="italic">feel</hi> 
</l><pb n="78">
<l ln="77      ">As though I had not very long to live; 
</l><l ln="78      ">And if 'tis so, it seems a cruel fate
</l><l ln="79      ">To have to spend my few remaining days
</l><l ln="80      ">So far away from those my heart holds dear,
</l><l ln="81      ">But chiefly from the one my whole soul loves.</l></pdiv></div3>

<pb n="79">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646725</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE V. <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646725</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">A quiet spot in the garden of Edgar's home. Several months afterwards.
<hi r="smcap">Edgar</hi> and <hi r="smcap">Alethea</hi>.</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="smcap">Edgar.</speaker>

<pdiv><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> doctors think that I shall ne'er be well.
</l><l ln="2        ">They do not say so openly, but still
</l><l ln="3        ">It is not hard to understand the drift
</l><l ln="4        ">Of their calm&hyphen;spoken diplomatic phrases
</l><l ln="5        ">About &lsquo;much care&rsquo; and &lsquo;quiet&rsquo; and &lsquo;escape
</l><l ln="6        ">From English winters to the sunny south;&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And when I asked if my complaint were cured,
</l><l ln="8        ">They hesitated, hemmed, then, smiling, said,
</l><l ln="9        ">&lsquo;Alleviated were the better term.&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="10      ">Ah, it is hard to hear a cruel fate
</l><l ln="11      ">Thus subtly hinted at in civil words
</l><l ln="12      ">And courteous commonplaces, and to have
</l><l ln="13      ">One's hopes annihilated in soft tones,
</l><l ln="14      ">Meant to be pitiful, perchance, but which
</l><l ln="15      ">Seem by their wily softness but to scorn
</l><pb n="80">
<l ln="16      ">And counterfeit a kindness not heart&hyphen;felt.
</l><l ln="17      ">'Tis bitter to reflect my roll of years
</l><l ln="18      ">Will probably be briefer than of those
</l><l ln="19      ">My comrades&mdash;and no better men than I
</l><l ln="20      ">(And this when life to me was ever sweet).
</l><l ln="21      ">'Tis bitter to reflect that theirs may be
</l><l ln="22      ">The bright career of steadfast earnest toil
</l><l ln="23      ">Towards some right worthy goal, which, gained at last,
</l><l ln="24      ">Rewards them with a name, while unto me
</l><l ln="25      ">'Tis given but to spend in listless calm
</l><l ln="26      ">My few remaining days.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="27      ">                                 But bitterer still
</l><l ln="28      ">It is, that I must loose you now, my love,
</l><l ln="29      ">From cherished vows which we have interchanged.
</l><l ln="30      ">For 'twere not right that I should link your fate
</l><l ln="31      ">With mine as now it is, and bring perchance
</l><l ln="32      ">On others&mdash;innocent&mdash;the hopeless bane
</l><l ln="33      ">Of cureless sickness which I feel myself.
</l><l ln="34      ">Grief is the rule of this our carthly life,
</l><l ln="35      ">And joy but the exception; wherefore then
</l><l ln="36      ">Should I expect of joy a greater share
</l><l ln="37      ">Than is apportioned unto thousands who
</l><l ln="38      ">Have suffered, still are suffering, or will suffer
</l><pb n="81">
<l ln="39      ">As helplessly as I:&mdash;and surely too
</l><l ln="40      ">My mind should be far calmer than is his
</l><l ln="41      ">Who sowed himself the seeds of his disease,
</l><l ln="42      ">Whose every pang is now intensified
</l><l ln="43      ">By keen remorse, and seething in whose soul
</l><l ln="44      ">No thought save one&mdash;the ever&hyphen;gnawing thought
</l><l ln="45      ">But for himself what he would now have been.
</l><l ln="46      ">Yet oh, Alethea, 'tis crushing grief
</l><l ln="47      ">To lose you, darling, were it not my duty,
</l><l ln="48      ">My duty thought and prayed about for weeks,
</l><l ln="49      ">I could not say the word to set you free.</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="smcap">Alethea.</speaker>

<l ln="50      ">The word to set me free! that were indeed
</l><l ln="51      ">Most difficult to say, for we are bound
</l><l ln="52      ">Indissolubly:&mdash;and though, Edgar dear,
</l><l ln="53      ">You tell me that for us all hope is o'er
</l><l ln="54      ">Of earthly union: yet there still remains
</l><l ln="55      ">A radiant future seen through mists of tears,
</l><l ln="56      ">Since present life is not our whole existence.
</l><l ln="57      ">Your name means &lsquo;happy honour,&rsquo; and mine own
</l><l ln="58      ">&lsquo;Truth:&rsquo;&mdash;if we live our little span of days
</l><l ln="59      ">Worthy of such high names, it will be well
</l><pb n="82">
<l ln="60      ">With us, whate'er may come. Yet when I look
</l><l ln="61      ">On your poor face and mark the touch of pain,
</l><l ln="62      ">Then, though I feel that doubtless you are right
</l><l ln="63      ">In that you say, it makes me doubly sad
</l><l ln="64      ">To think the fate that makes you suffer so,
</l><l ln="65      ">Remorseless and unsatisfied, compels
</l><l ln="66      ">You thus to blight your life; but if fond love
</l><l ln="67      ">And sympathy can cheer, you yet may find
</l><l ln="68      ">Some earthly joy remaining even to you.</l></pdiv></div3>

<pb n="83">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646726</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SCENE VI. <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646726</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EDGAR VANNING:  A SKETCH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stage r="italic">Midwinter in a certain little island abroad. A pretty room with
opened windows overlooking a lovely garden, and a still lovelier
prospect beyond.
<hi r="smcap">Time</hi>.&mdash;A few years afterwards, towards sunset, and only a few
days before Edgar's death. <hi r="smcap">Edgar</hi> and <hi r="smcap">Alethea</hi>.</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="smcap">Edgar.</speaker>

<l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Truly</hi> a grand, a noble thing is life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="2        ">This most I feel when I am passing from it; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And life is fair, whatever cynics say.
</l><l ln="4        ">But yesterday I lay upon my couch
</l><l ln="5        ">And looked upon the clear wide&hyphen;stretching bay,
</l><l ln="6        ">Far, far beneath me shimmering in the sun.
</l><l ln="7        ">I saw th' exquisite azure of the sky,
</l><l ln="8        ">The dainty outlines of palm&hyphen;branches shown
</l><l ln="9        ">More clearly by the strong light showered upon them,
</l><l ln="10      ">The countless clustering vines and varied trees
</l><l ln="11      ">In all the gentle ever&hyphen;pleasing glow
</l><pb n="84">
<l ln="12      ">Of vegetation almost tropical,
</l><l ln="13      ">Which makes each cultivated garden here
</l><l ln="14      ">Appear a paradise. Banana&hyphen;trees
</l><l ln="15      ">I saw with all their load of luscious fruit
</l><l ln="16      ">The graceful guava&hyphen;trees with light&hyphen;green leaves
</l><l ln="17      ">The loquats with their deeper verdant tints,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">The little plant they call &lsquo;Brazilian cherry,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="19      ">With bright green leaves, and fruit of strawberry size,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="20      ">The stately yam&hyphen;tree with its blossoms white
</l><l ln="21      ">And lily&hyphen;like;&mdash;fair to the eye indeed,
</l><l ln="22      ">A tree whose oval leaves afford good shade
</l><l ln="23      ">In summer. Surely it is strangely sweet
</l><l ln="24      ">To loiter in such gardens when cool Night
</l><l ln="25      ">Has conquered the fierce ardour of the day,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">And see the meek moon rise o'er azure seas,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">And view the tranquil heavens don their jewels,
</l><l ln="28      ">And hear mach&ecirc;tes swift tingling forth an air
</l><l ln="29      ">Of music,&mdash;haply a soft mazy dance.
</l><l ln="30      ">Yet, dear Alethea, it is decreed
</l><l ln="31      ">That I must leave you, darling, but although
</l><l ln="32      ">'Tis sad to leave you and this beauteous world,
</l><l ln="33      ">'Tis sweet to die amid such loveliness.
</l><pb n="85">
<l ln="34      ">And daily I thank God that He hath not
</l><l ln="35      ">Condemned me to this sickness slow and sure
</l><l ln="36      ">Immured in one close room from day to day,
</l><l ln="37      ">Through the long, lagging, weary winter&hyphen;time,
</l><l ln="38      ">But given me the means wherewith to dwell
</l><l ln="39      ">In climate such as this where balmy air
</l><l ln="40      ">And sunshine even in winter, are not wanting; 
</l><l ln="41      ">A climate where the invalid can pass,
</l><l ln="42      ">However languid, many happy hours
</l><l ln="43      ">Communing with God's fair earth out of doors.
</l><l ln="44      ">Do you remember, dear, some years ago
</l><l ln="45      ">You told me if fond love and sympathy
</l><l ln="46      ">Could soothe me that I surely should be cheered?
</l><l ln="47      ">And you have kept your word: I have been cheered,
</l><l ln="48      ">And comforted, and though no marriage&hyphen;bond
</l><l ln="49      ">Has been between us as we once had hoped,
</l><l ln="50      ">Our souls have been as one. Take my poor thanks
</l><l ln="51      ">For coming thus to sojourn where I dwelt
</l><l ln="52      ">And giving me your loving tireless care
</l><l ln="53      ">'Mid all my pain and suffering, made less hard
</l><l ln="54      ">To bear by your kind presence.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="86">

<pdiv>
<speaker r="smcap">Alethea.</speaker>

<l ln="55      ">                                             I am glad
</l><l ln="56      ">It was my lot to render you this service,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="57      ">A service small indeed compared with love
</l><l ln="58      ">Such as I bear you, darling.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="smcap">Edgar.</speaker>

<l ln="59      ">                                          When I die,
</l><l ln="60      ">Let me be buried in my native land,
</l><l ln="61      ">Not here, although I love this sea&hyphen;girt shore,
</l><l ln="62      ">Where graveyards are embowered mid beauteous trees,
</l><l ln="63      ">And overlook mayhap light rippling waves
</l><l ln="64      ">As blue as the deep azure heavens above them,
</l><l ln="65      ">Round whose rude tombs the scented roses cling.
</l><l ln="66      ">And still bloom on throughout the sunny year.
</l><l ln="67      ">But let me rather lie where chilling rain
</l><l ln="68      ">And bitter sleet shall in the winter&hyphen;time
</l><l ln="69      ">Beat on my resting&hyphen;place. For what care I
</l><l ln="70      ">Though placid snows spread o'er my quiet grave
</l><l ln="71      ">Their spotless mantle, though wild wintry winds
</l><pb n="87">
<l ln="72      ">Sweep o'er it, be it only undisturbed.
</l><l ln="73      ">And if 'twere here, perchance it would not be
</l><l ln="74      ">For ever left in pcace. Alethea,
</l><l ln="75      ">For <hi r="italic">Time</hi> we shall be separated soon,
</l><l ln="76      ">But do not grieve o'ermuch. For me 'twill be
</l><l ln="77      ">A glad release from pain, and you and I
</l><l ln="78      ">Shall meet in yon pure Home of Love at last.</l></pdiv></div3></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="91">

