<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A BISCAYAN SUNSET.

<subhead r="smcap">April 17th, 1879.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646728</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A BISCAYAN SUNSET.  April 17th, 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028186</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028186</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A BISCAYAN SUNSET.  April 17th, 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A golden</hi> halo gilds the sky,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And the wind&hyphen;unruffled sea,
</l><l ln="3        ">A scene it is where poet's eye
</l><l ln="4        ">Could subtle loveliness descry
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;Unweariedly.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="6        ">Hark! from afar the deep&hyphen;toned roar
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Of the Atlantic surge&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Yon sail will soon be seen no more
</l><l ln="9        ">Now light&hyphen;illumed: 'tis fleeting o'er
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;The sea&hyphen;scape's verge.</l></stanza>

<pb n="92">

<stanza><l ln="11      ">The stars appear&mdash;strange visions rise; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of man's dim destiny
</l><l ln="13      ">How typical are these calm skies!
</l><l ln="14      ">While like to man the sad sea lies
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Troubled though free.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="16      ">No wing&egrave;d wanderer slowly cleaves
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;The silence in his flight;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">His burning throne the Warmth&hyphen;King leaves
</l><l ln="19      ">While the fair firmament receives
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;The crown'd Queen Night.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="93">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646729</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC,
FRANCE.

<subhead r="smcap">April 18th, 1879.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646729</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC, FRANCE.  April 18th, 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028187</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028187</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC, FRANCE.  April 18th, 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Day</hi> hath departed, save a few faint streaks
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of light that fleck the bosom of the sky; 
</l><l ln="3        ">These, and these only, stay to testify
</l><l ln="4        ">Of proud Night's conquest. Hark! that sound bespeaks
</l><l ln="5        ">Our nearness to the Ocean, and I see
</l><l ln="6        ">Its ripples at my feet;&mdash;a soft clear song
</l><l ln="7        ">Is brceze&hyphen;borne from a vessel's deck along.
</l><l ln="8        ">The crew with musical monotony
</l><l ln="9        ">Raise anchor swiftly, and the ship doth glide
</l><l ln="10      ">In silence, save for the chant growing low
</l><l ln="11      ">Wave&hyphen;wafted landwards. Little doth she know
</l><l ln="12      ">If calms will come, or fiercest storms betide:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Alas, o'er life's strange sea we all must sail
</l><l ln="14      ">Like her, nor know if calm or tempest will prevail.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="94">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646730</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON A DISTANT PROSPECT OF THE
PYRENEES.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646730</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON A DISTANT PROSPECT OF THE PYRENEES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028188</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028188</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON A DISTANT PROSPECT OF THE PYRENEES.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Majestic</hi> snow&hyphen;crowned mountains distant far,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Yet to man's seeming near! How oft we feel
</l><l ln="3        ">In life 'tis even thus! though there the view,
</l><l ln="4        ">That seems so close before us full and fair,
</l><l ln="5        ">May ne'er be realized, while here it needs
</l><l ln="6        ">But purpose long&hyphen;sustained to gain the goal
</l><l ln="7        ">And prove the seeming real.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="8        ">                                         Whilst I gaze
</l><l ln="9        ">Upon your cloud&hyphen;capt summits, thoughts arise
</l><l ln="10      ">Telling of eager spirits not a few
</l><l ln="11      ">Who like to me have looked in ages past,
</l><l ln="12      ">Filled with the selfsame dream of human change,
</l><l ln="13      ">And your immutability compared
</l><l ln="14      ">With man's brief mundane course. How many too
</l><l ln="15      ">Have lounged and looked on your cloud&hyphen;piercing peaks,
</l><l ln="16      ">Nor felt the deep reflection such a scene
</l><pb n="95">
<l ln="17      ">Is fitted well to give! Strange! but 'tis so,
</l><l ln="18      ">And will be ever while the world endures; 
</l><l ln="19      ">That which to one seems passion&hyphen;fraught, sublime,
</l><l ln="20      ">Another views,&mdash;deems fine,&mdash;and passes on.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="96">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646731</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A DIRGE OF DECAY.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646731</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A DIRGE OF DECAY.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028189</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028189</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A DIRGE OF DECAY.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016942">Near Argelez in the Department of the Hautes Pyr&eacute;n&eacute;es, France,
are several ruins of old castles said to have been built by
the English in the 15th century.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Within</hi> these walls
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Now half&hyphen;forgotten, lonely and decayed,
</l><l ln="3        ">Only the birds their resting&hyphen;place have made,
</l><l ln="4        ">And scarce a step within them ever falls.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;Yet doubtless here
</l><l ln="6        ">Stupendous deeds of valour have been wrought,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Deeds that to many thousands then were fraught
</l><l ln="8        ">With heart&hyphen;felt weal or deep and direful fear.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;Brave of the brave
</l><l ln="10      ">Our soldiers must assuredly have been,
</l><l ln="11      ">So long to hold for our proud Island&hyphen;queen
</l><l ln="12      ">This land which then seemed far across the wave.</l></stanza>

<pb n="101">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Yes, far from aid,
</l><l ln="14      ">From friends, from home, must have appeared their lot,
</l><l ln="15      ">And yet (O courage great!) they faltered not,
</l><l ln="16      ">Nor, filled with craven terror, were afraid;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;Not even though
</l><l ln="18      ">Full oft encompassed, like unto a stag
</l><l ln="19      ">By hounds engirt; but rallied round their flag,
</l><l ln="20      ">And kept its honour stainless from the foe.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&indent;Why is it then
</l><l ln="22      ">That low in ruins are these castles laid?
</l><l ln="23      ">It is because old courage had decayed,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">It is because old fire had left our men.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;This should we learn
</l><l ln="26      ">While earth remaineth thus,&mdash;wars cannot cease; 
</l><l ln="27      ">That everything hath limits,&mdash;even peace; 
</l><l ln="28      ">So let the lamp of ancient courage burn.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="102">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646732</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>LINES ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF
BAR&Eacute;GES FROM ST. SAUVEUR, HAUTES
PYR&Eacute;N&Eacute;ES, FRANCE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646732</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LINES ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF BAR&Eacute;GES FROM ST. SAUVEUR, HAUTES PYR&Eacute;N&Eacute;ES, FRANCE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028190</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028190</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF BAR&Eacute;GES FROM ST. SAUVEUR, HAUTES PYR&Eacute;N&Eacute;ES, FRANCE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Lo!</hi> what a glorious prospect is revealed
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of mountains, snow, and verdant loveliness; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Upon the sloping sides of monarch heights
</l><l ln="4        ">Reposes now the mist, most gracefully,
</l><l ln="5        ">In wreaths almost transparent; presently
</l><l ln="6        ">Its mass divides, and clear against the sky
</l><l ln="7        ">Appears each giant summit grandly calm,
</l><l ln="8        ">And seeming proud that its lone God&hyphen;wrought strength
</l><l ln="9        ">So long defies decay. One ever feels
</l><l ln="10      ">In gazing on such scenes how weak is man,
</l><l ln="11      ">Yet still how much his art hath made increase
</l><l ln="12      ">To this rare store of beauty. Each small patch
</l><l ln="13      ">Perceived upon the mountain&hyphen;side, reclaimed
</l><pb n="103">
<l ln="14      ">From barren wilderness, hath wondrous power
</l><l ln="15      ">To cheer the eye. To me it often seems
</l><l ln="16      ">As though no prospect were indeed complete
</l><l ln="17      ">Without some trace of toil to leaven it.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="104">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646733</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>FROM LA RAILL&Egrave;RE
TO PONT D'ESPAGNE AND LAC DE GAUBE.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646733</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>FROM LA RAILL&Egrave;RE TO PONT D'ESPAGNE AND LAC DE GAUBE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028191</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028191</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FROM LA RAILL&Egrave;RE TO PONT D'ESPAGNE AND LAC DE GAUBE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">O path</hi> which seems to have a loveliness
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;More than of Earth,
</l><l ln="3        ">How can one who has viewed thy scenes express
</l><l ln="4        ">The thoughts that unto them have owed their birth?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">How can he tell of all the wondrous way
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Where grandeur vies
</l><l ln="7        ">With beauty, rich and rare, to bear the sway
</l><l ln="8        ">In winning and retaining ravished eyes?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">How can he tell of rocks and ridges wild
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Which lie around?
</l><l ln="11      ">Of mighty mountain&hyphen;peaks on high up&hyphen;piled?
</l><l ln="12      ">Of ceaseless cataracts' majestic sound?</l></stanza>

<pb n="105">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">How can he well describe rich&hyphen;foliaged trees
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;That screen the sides?
</l><l ln="15      ">Blown to and fro by gentle summer breeze,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">In chasms where the vale the rocks divides.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">How can he well describe the stately pines
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Steadfast and strong?
</l><l ln="19      ">(True type of one whose sun not always shines,
</l><l ln="20      ">And yet who bravely bears grief's load along.)</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">High&hyphen;foaming C&eacute;rizet can he portray?
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Beyond the power
</l><l ln="23      ">Of language even feebly to convey
</l><l ln="24      ">Its peerless beauty, wonder&hyphen;working dower.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Much less the wilder falls at Pont d'Espagne
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Truly sublime,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">Whose weird white floods sing songs of sturdy strain,
</l><l ln="28      ">For aye the same in nature&hyphen;ordered time.</l></stanza>

<pb n="106">

<stanza><l ln="29      ">When Lac de Gaube is reached, how can he tell
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;The silent sight
</l><l ln="31      ">Of snow and glaciers? Soon our bosoms swell
</l><l ln="32      ">With feelings half of fear, half of delight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">The fairy rainbow tints which o'er the falls
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Glimmer and play,
</l><l ln="35      ">The stilly clearness of the lake enthralls,
</l><l ln="36      ">Yes this and all, in us soon holds full sway.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">Though none can well describe these scenes, shall not
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;They in the mind
</l><l ln="39      ">Remain to bring forth fruit, a gladsome spot
</l><l ln="40      ">In memory, a gift for good designed!</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="109">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646734</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT ORTHEZ

<subhead>SONNET</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646734</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT ORTHEZ  SONNET</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028192</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028192</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT ORTHEZ  SONNET</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016943">On seeing a Sham Fight of French Troops at Orthez, in exactly the
same position as those occupied by the English and French
Armies in the memorable action of February <hi r="roman">14</hi>th, <hi r="roman">1814</hi>.</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A February</hi> day in years long fled,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A fiercely raging battle hour by hour,
</l><l ln="3        ">At length gained by a mind of mighty power
</l><l ln="4        ">Through wonder&hyphen;working skill.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">                                            French troops are spread
</l><l ln="6        ">Along the ridge of hills and fertile vales
</l><l ln="7        ">Where that stern strife was once. For mimic war
</l><l ln="8        ">They are arranged precisely as of yore,
</l><l ln="9        ">Is the result as in the old men's tales
</l><l ln="10      ">Who saw the real conflict? Nay, not so,
</l><l ln="11      ">The French now hold the heights. Fictitious foes
</l><l ln="12      ">Are beaten by the patriots who oppose.
</l><l ln="13      ">&lsquo;The English hounds who wrought our pride's o'erthrow,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Doubtless thinks many a soldier, &lsquo;now would feel,
</l><l ln="15      ">If they were here once more, the force of Frenchmen's steel.&rsquo;</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="113">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646735</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE ESCORIAL, 1879.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646735</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE ESCORIAL, 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028193</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028193</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE ESCORIAL, 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016944"><hi r="smcap">The</hi> Escorial, a glooming pile, standing at the foot of the Guadarrama
range of mountains, is the burial&hyphen;place of the Spanish
Kings, and it is so vast that it looks imposing even amid
natural grandeur.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> sternly the Escorial stands,&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The burial&hyphen;place of kings,
</l><l ln="3        ">Who at disloyal Death's commands
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Must leave their princely things,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And hie to this stupendous pile,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;That looks so cold and lone,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Where nature scarcely dares to smile,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And verdure seems unknown,&mdash;</l></stanza>

<pb n="114">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">To this sad spot where Summer's glare
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Beats fiercest and most strong,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Where swooping from his mountain lair
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Winter abideth long.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Ah, yes, it must be change indeed
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;From grandeur such as theirs
</l><l ln="15      ">To such a spot to come with speed,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;To be Corruption's heirs.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">For evermore to lay aside
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Insignia of power,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">All&hyphen;humbled stately monarch pride
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In death's still awful hour.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">And yet 'twere better thus to be
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Entombed 'mid marble walls,
</l><pb n="115">
<l ln="23      ">Where even his foot who comes to see
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;In seeming reverence falls,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Than to be huddled with the rest
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;In some dank burial&hyphen;ground,
</l><l ln="27      ">Where in a few years' time at best
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;One's place could not be found.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Men prate that Nature ne'er obtains
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Her long&hyphen;predestined dues,
</l><l ln="31      ">And show that we with mighty pains
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Should alter all our views</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">On points of sepulchre. For me,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Though o'er it fall Oblivion's frost,
</l><l ln="35      ">I trust for aye my grave shall be
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Neither disturbed nor lost.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="119">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646736</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>LINES

ON PASSING IN AN EXPRESS TRAIN THROUGH BADAJOZ,
<subhead>NOTED FOR ITS FAMOUS SIEGE DURING THE
PENINSULAR WAR.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646736</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LINES  ON PASSING IN AN EXPRESS TRAIN THROUGH BADAJOZ, NOTED FOR ITS FAMOUS SIEGE DURING THE PENINSULAR WAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028194</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028194</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES  ON PASSING IN AN EXPRESS TRAIN THROUGH BADAJOZ, NOTED FOR ITS FAMOUS SIEGE DURING THE PENINSULAR WAR.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">And</hi> is this Badajoz? where once was heard
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The clash of arms, and breaching cannons' roar,
</l><l ln="3        ">Where from the dim&hyphen;lit parallels came forth
</l><l ln="4        ">The forlorn hope at Duty's stern command?
</l><l ln="5        ">Where swords and bayonets bristled on cold walls,
</l><l ln="6        ">And multitudes of marksmen sought to stay
</l><l ln="7        ">The assailing columns in their onward course?
</l><l ln="8        ">Where, when the town was gained, grim Plunder stalked
</l><l ln="9        ">Amid its devastated streets, and made
</l><l ln="10      ">Them ghastlier even than War?
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Years yield strange fruit
</l><l ln="12      ">Of alteration in forsaken paths; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Yet was I strangely struck with the great change
</l><l ln="14      ">Wrought here in Badajoz.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">                                    Can it be true
</l><l ln="16      ">That here a most prosaic railway&hyphen;station
</l><l ln="17      ">Is now erected, with its telegraph,
</l><pb n="120">
<l ln="18      ">Poor restaurant, and porters to be &lsquo;tipped&rsquo;?
</l><l ln="19      ">And that of travellers, who tread its platform
</l><l ln="20      ">When trains a moment stop, scarce any think
</l><l ln="21      ">Of that bold siege which for all coming years
</l><l ln="22      ">Has blazoned &lsquo;Badajoz&rsquo; on Fame's high scroll?</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="122">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300646737</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>CINTRA in 1879.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646737</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>CINTRA in 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028195</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028195</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>CINTRA in 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Cintra</hi>, our Byron gave thy name to fame
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">By his description grand, and sweet, and true; 
</l><l ln="3        ">But though thy &lsquo;mountain's ever beauteous brow&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="4        ">And many other objects are unchanged,
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet altered are full many of the scenes
</l><l ln="6        ">On which the poet looked, and mused and sang.
</l><l ln="7        ">No &lsquo;frugal monks their little relics show&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="8        ">To strangers at &lsquo;Our Lady's house of woe.&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="9        ">One sees their tiny cells, their cork&hyphen;wood walls,
</l><l ln="10      ">Honorius's cave, and that is all.
</l><l ln="11      ">The former home of &lsquo;England's wealthiest son&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="12      ">No longer has its &lsquo;portals gaping wide,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Its &lsquo;halls deserted,&rsquo; or great &lsquo;giant weeds&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Within its garden ground:&mdash;but it is fair,
</l><l ln="15      ">Fair as the lordly traveller declared
</l><l ln="16      ">It was of yore. While &lsquo;Marialva's dome&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="17      ">Is changed in that 'tis now historical,
</l><pb n="123">
<l ln="18      ">Its fame a lasting one, whilst in his day
</l><l ln="19      ">Its interest was eclipsed by other themes
</l><l ln="20      ">Of ever&hyphen;varying War:&mdash;the deed performed
</l><l ln="21      ">Within its gates too recent not to be
</l><l ln="22      ">Left unto record of the daily gossip,
</l><l ln="23      ">And comments of the press which rarely live.
</l><l ln="24      ">All now is different:&mdash;a classic scene
</l><l ln="25      ">Thou standest, Cintra, clothed with more of fame
</l><l ln="26      ">(To English minds at least) from Byron's words
</l><l ln="27      ">Than from thy matchless beauty, could that be.
</l><l ln="28      ">And mayhap, in the years to come, some poet
</l><l ln="29      ">Treading the self&hyphen;same scenes will tell how one,
</l><l ln="30      ">A writer of poor verses, tried to tell
</l><l ln="31      ">What changes there had been since Byron wrote; 
</l><l ln="32      ">And he, in turn, with glowing eloquence
</l><l ln="33      ">Will paint with poet's art the tide of Change
</l><l ln="34      ">On Cintra since these lines were given forth.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="127">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646738</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A LEST&Eacute; SUNRISE IN MADEIRA.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646738</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LEST&Eacute; SUNRISE IN MADEIRA.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028196</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028196</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A LEST&Eacute; SUNRISE IN MADEIRA.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Many</hi>&hyphen;hued the sky this morn,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Beautiful the day is born,
</l><l ln="3        ">Fleecy clouds on every side
</l><l ln="4        ">Sunshine's coming seem to hide,
</l><l ln="5        ">But the other cloudlets stand
</l><l ln="6        ">Ready waiting its command.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Ay, they are a gorgeous group,
</l><l ln="8        ">Almost each tint in the troop,
</l><l ln="9        ">Red, and light blue, and maroon,
</l><l ln="10      ">And some white appearing soon,
</l><l ln="11      ">And a glorious purple shade
</l><l ln="12      ">Over all is deftly laid.</l></stanza>

<pb n="128">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">O'er the mountains purple clouds
</l><l ln="14      ">Of deep colour hang, like shrouds; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Purple masses faint are shed
</l><l ln="16      ">O'er the Ocean's wave&hyphen;strewn bed,
</l><l ln="17      ">Fine the light which now one sees,
</l><l ln="18      ">On the palms and tropic trees.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">Swiftly fades the splendid sky
</l><l ln="20      ">To a dimly purple dye; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Gently stirs the landward breeze
</l><l ln="22      ">Shapely&hyphen;formed banana&hyphen;trees.
</l><l ln="23      ">Dawn's first freshness wears away,
</l><l ln="24      ">And begins the balmy day.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="129">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646739</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MADEIRA&mdash;MOONLIGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646739</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MADEIRA&mdash;MOONLIGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028197</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028197</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MADEIRA&mdash;MOONLIGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Stealing</hi> softly o'er the mountains,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Skirting Funchal's scattered town,
</l><l ln="3        ">To the eastward, comes the moonlight
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Flinging its effulgence down; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Making every object glitter
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In its clear and tranquil sheen,
</l><l ln="7        ">While the Ocean lately troubled
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Seemeth lapt in peace serene.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Subtle moonlight! how thy radiance
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;With a magic often shown
</l><l ln="11      ">Touches and refines a landscape
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;With a glamour all thine own!
</l><l ln="13      ">So thou causest here the houses
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Mean, nay squalid, in the light,
</l><l ln="15      ">To appear a pearly pureness
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Rather than a dirty white.</l></stanza>

<pb n="130">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">For the filth and streets so narrow,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;With vile odours bred by day,
</l><l ln="19      ">Save for Nature's glorious grandeur,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Takes admiring thoughts away; 
</l><l ln="21      ">But the moonbeam maketh all things
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Gain at least a semblance meet,
</l><l ln="23      ">Till at length the wide&hyphen;spread prospect
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Has an aspect almost sweet.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="131">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646740</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646740</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028198</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028198</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<signed><hi r="italic">Feb.</hi> 19, 1880.</signed>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">'Tis</hi> fashionable now to say
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">That skill displayed in war is wrong,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;That they who formed our England's sway,
</l><l ln="4        ">And made her empire firm and strong,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;Were callous cut&hyphen;throats nothing less,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">Who joyed in war for its own sake,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Who yearned to banish happiness,
</l><l ln="8        ">Who loved with blood their thirst to slake.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;And yet while landing here to&hyphen;day,
</l><l ln="10      ">On the same shore which years ago
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Saw from its crag&hyphen;encircled bay
</l><l ln="12      ">Our Nelson's only overthrow,</l></stanza>

<pb n="132">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;I thought, Do those who grub and prose,
</l><l ln="14      ">And by their lights their betters try,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Perform their life&hyphen;tasks more than those
</l><l ln="16      ">Whose task is but &lsquo;to do or die&rsquo;?</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="135">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646741</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GIBRALTAR.

<subhead>1880.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646741</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GIBRALTAR.  1880.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028199</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028199</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GIBRALTAR.  1880.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&lsquo;<hi r="smcap">Sweet</hi> Seville&rsquo; has been sung&mdash;and Cadiz too
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;By Byron, for the beauty of her girls,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Yet know I not that one hath given thy due
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To thee on whose proud crest the cloud&hyphen;wreath curls.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Let me attempt thy praise, then, for I know
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;That worthier pens will write of foreign towns,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">For now no place has praise with us, if so
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;It be mayhap a jewel of our Crown's.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&lsquo;Sweet Seville's&rsquo; Guadalquivir, famed in song,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Is nothing save a nearly stagnant stream.
</l><pb n="136">
<l ln="11      ">The beauty of the Cadiz maiden throng
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Exists,&mdash;but in a &lsquo;poet's airy dream.&rsquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Here in Gibraltar all retains an air
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of honest truth. Odourless streets are clean,
</l><l ln="15      ">And everything is made the most of, where
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Man's art avails to soften down the scene.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">The gardens of the Alameda, full
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Of semi&hyphen;tropic plants and shady trees,
</l><l ln="19      ">Pleasant to lounge in their recesses cool
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;On summer eves to catch the soft sea&hyphen;breeze.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Yet great the toil and patience must have been
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Before at last was made such rocky ground
</l><l ln="23      ">To nourish shrub, or plant, or aught of green.
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Cheering it is to hear the home&hyphen;like sound</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Of English tongues,&mdash;to see our cared&hyphen;for men,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Contrasted with the Spaniards wan and weak,
</l><l ln="27      ">Guarding their posts, as they with eager ken
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Look on our cannon, which have but to speak&mdash;</l></stanza>

<pb n="137">

<stanza><l ln="29      ">To put their lines to rout. How lovely gleams
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;The Rock at sunrise! The grey looming clouds
</l><l ln="31      ">Glow in the new&hyphen;born light like glorious dreams,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;While Shadow still the tranquil bay enshrouds.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Ay, grim Gibraltar, thou indeed art fair!
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And more than that, a place in which one may
</l><l ln="35      ">Live with true home&hyphen;like comfort, and a share
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Of a good climate, brightening Life's dull day.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="138">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646742</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GRANADA.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646742</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GRANADA.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028200</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028200</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GRANADA.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Fair</hi> Granada, our masters of the pen
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Have written much of thee, and not a few
</l><l ln="3        ">Who ne'er have seen thee, hold dream&hyphen;wrought and fair,
</l><l ln="4        ">A city in their fancy by thy name
</l><l ln="5        ">Seen clearly in their mental eyes, as if
</l><l ln="6        ">'Twere mirrored in their senses. Thus with me; 
</l><l ln="7        ">But when I saw, my fond ideal fell.
</l><l ln="8        ">It was not that thy famed Alhambra hill
</l><l ln="9        ">Lacked grandeur, or its silent courts were void
</l><l ln="10      ">Of architectural wealth, or that the Vega,
</l><l ln="11      ">Shut in by mountains and the silent snows,
</l><l ln="12      ">Was aught save fair; yet still the impression stays
</l><l ln="13      ">Unceasingly within me, caused perchance
</l><l ln="14      ">By narrow Spanish streets, dull, dirty, white,
</l><pb n="139">
<l ln="15      ">Or likelier that the sight of scaffoldings
</l><l ln="16      ">And fresh&hyphen;wrought antique work amid the old
</l><l ln="17      ">In the Alham bra's courts destroy their charm.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="142">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646743</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE CERTOSA OF PAVIA; 

<subhead>A GREAT ITALIAN CONVENT, AND GRAND WORK OF ART.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646743</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE CERTOSA OF PAVIA;   A GREAT ITALIAN CONVENT, AND GRAND WORK OF ART.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028201</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028201</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE CERTOSA OF PAVIA;   A GREAT ITALIAN CONVENT, AND GRAND WORK OF ART.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Great</hi> monument of human skill!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">How vast must be the power and scope
</l><l ln="3        ">Of minds which can conceive,&mdash;of hands
</l><l ln="4        ">That shape such edifices rare;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And doth the splendid sight not show
</l><l ln="6        ">Convincingly how wondrous is
</l><l ln="7        ">The grandeur, mightiness of Man,
</l><l ln="8        ">Despite his body frail, and train
</l><l ln="9        ">Of weary woes, which almost ever
</l><l ln="10      ">Attends him, ere King Death with sway
</l><l ln="11      ">Imperious demands his spoil?
</l><l ln="12      ">And do such sights not educate,
</l><l ln="13      ">If we may phrase it thus, the soul,
</l><l ln="14      ">Leading us far more to believe
</l><l ln="15      ">In the proud majesty of Art?
</l><l ln="16      ">The marble cuttings exquisite
</l><pb n="147">
<l ln="17      ">Near the high altar, the mosaics
</l><l ln="18      ">Gorgeous; yet though so finely wrought,
</l><l ln="19      ">Designed in truly simple taste,
</l><l ln="20      ">The stately stalls of workmanship
</l><l ln="21      ">Replete with loveliness and rich
</l><l ln="22      ">In cunning inlaid work. The aspect
</l><l ln="23      ">Of the exterior, the carvings
</l><l ln="24      ">So realistic near the door&mdash; 
</l><l ln="25      ">The outer door&mdash;of Roman coins
</l><l ln="26      ">(Though strange to see these Pagan heads)
</l><l ln="27      ">At entrance to a Christian church.
</l><l ln="28      ">All, all make up a noble whole,
</l><l ln="29      ">And fill the heart with feelings which
</l><l ln="30      ">'Twere better that it ne'er forgot.</l></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="149">

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200646744</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SONGS AND LYRICS. <attbytes>77Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646744</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>

<pb n="151">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646745</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE LATE AUTUMN IS DYING.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646745</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE LATE AUTUMN IS DYING.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028202</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028202</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE LATE AUTUMN IS DYING.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> late Autumn is dying,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Dead leaves strew the land&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Signs of sorrow now lying
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;On every hand; 
</l><l ln="5        ">While I walk full of sadness
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In a garden once fair,
</l><l ln="7        ">Where before all was gladness,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;I find trouble there.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">In a hedge&hyphen;row wind&hyphen;shaken
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;To wildest unrest,
</l><l ln="11      ">Forlorn and forsaken,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;I see a bird's nest,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Its soft down decaying&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Its fledglings all flown,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Nought save the shell staying
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Deserted and lone.</l></stanza>

<pb n="152">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Then the thought cometh cleaving
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;The depths of my mind&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Soon we too must be leaving
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Our loved homes behind,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">The drear tomb will enclose us,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Life's pilgrimage o'er,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&ldquo;And the place that now knows us
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Shall know us no more.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="153">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646746</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>UNFULFILLED YEARNINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646746</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>UNFULFILLED YEARNINGS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028203</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028203</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>UNFULFILLED YEARNINGS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">When</hi> Summer's sweetest influence
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Is shed o'er plain and hill,
</l><l ln="3        ">And Nature gains her recompense
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;For working Winter's will,
</l><l ln="5        ">We feel a void&mdash;a weary sense
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of something wanting still.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">In Autumn, when each searing leaf
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;With sorrow aye is fraught,
</l><l ln="9        ">And every garnered golden sheaf
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Yields fruit for saddest thought,
</l><l ln="11      ">We feel a void&mdash;our spirits' grief
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;For something vainly sought.</l></stanza>

<pb n="154">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">When Winter with his ice&hyphen;cold hand
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Grasps giant&hyphen;like the ground,
</l><l ln="15      ">And stiff and stark lies all the land
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;In frost's firm fetters bound,
</l><l ln="17      ">We feel a void&mdash;we understand
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;'Tis something still unfound.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">When Spring returns with fairest face,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Filling the earth with song,
</l><l ln="21      ">And gladness seems in every place,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And love and life are strong,
</l><l ln="23      ">Ah me! even then we fail to trace
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;The dream for which we long.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="155">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646747</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GLAD DREAMS OF THE FUTURE
COME O'ER US.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646747</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GLAD DREAMS OF THE FUTURE COME O'ER US.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028204</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028204</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GLAD DREAMS OF THE FUTURE COME O'ER US.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Glad</hi> dreams of the Future come o'er us,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;All radiantly spotless and bright,
</l><l ln="3        ">And bid us look up&mdash;for before us
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Are vistas of boundless delight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">O come when our bosoms are weary,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Life&hyphen;burdened and longing for rest,
</l><l ln="7        ">And point through the darkness still dreary
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To a land which by sunlight is blest.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">O come when the world has been gaining
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;O'er our souls an insidious sway,
</l><l ln="11      ">Our fickle rash footsteps restraining
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;From wandering out of the way.</l></stanza>

<pb n="158">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">O come, that o'er all of Earth's changes
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Your light as a guide may be shed,
</l><l ln="15      ">Whether like unto others, or strange is,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;The path that in Life we must tread.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">And when finished at length is Life's story,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Completed its words and its acts,
</l><l ln="19      ">Then burst on our sight in your glory
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Not as <hi r="italic">dreams</hi>, but <hi r="italic">immutable facts</hi>.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="159">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646748</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG OF HOPE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646748</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG OF HOPE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028205</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028205</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG OF HOPE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> vinery's foliage
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In Autumn grows sere,
</l><l ln="3        ">For its wealth of bright beauty
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Fades out with the year:
</l><l ln="5        ">All its branches, where lately
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Grape clusters were spread,
</l><l ln="7        ">Become barren and sapless
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And seem as though dead.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">But long ere the soft Spring
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Clothes the land in glad green,
</l><l ln="11      ">On its boughs beauteous blossoms
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Are lavishly seen,
</l><l ln="13      ">As it uses the warmth
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Which is placed in its power,
</l><l ln="15      ">And so rallies more swiftly
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;From Winter's rude hour.</l></stanza>

<pb n="160">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Thus if we, when some sorrow
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;O'erwhelming appears,
</l><l ln="19      ">And which threatens to banish
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The light of our years,
</l><l ln="21      ">Would the blessings still left
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;In our service employ,
</l><l ln="23      ">Then whate'er be the issue,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;'Twould bring us but joy.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="161">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646749</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HOW OFT ARISE TO SOOTHE OUR WOE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646749</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOW OFT ARISE TO SOOTHE OUR WOE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028206</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028206</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HOW OFT ARISE TO SOOTHE OUR WOE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> oft arise to soothe our woe,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And dissipate our sadness,
</l><l ln="3        ">Fond dreams of faces long ago
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;When life was love and gladness.
</l><l ln="5        ">Like, yet unlike the lights that guide
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The storm&hyphen;tossed o'er the ocean,
</l><l ln="7        ">They in our secret souls abide,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Cherished with deep devotion.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">The halcyon Past seems to possess,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;When we review its story,
</l><l ln="11      ">One radiance of happiness,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Nor cloud to dim its glory; 
</l><pb n="162">
<l ln="13      ">So ah, 'tis well, when lonely lies
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Life's pathway girt with sorrow,
</l><l ln="15      ">That sometimes visions fair should rise
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Which from our Past we borrow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="165">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646750</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HAPPINESS HERE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646750</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HAPPINESS HERE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028207</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028207</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HAPPINESS HERE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">There</hi> is happiness, dearest&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;True happiness here,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Though the troubles thou fearest
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Perchance may appear:
</l><l ln="5        ">For mid every emotion
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of weal or of woe,
</l><l ln="7        ">Our depths of devotion
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;No respite shall know.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yes,&mdash;in Life's twisted tissue
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Of gladness and grief,
</l><l ln="11      ">Love, whate'er be the issue,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Still renders relief.
</l><l ln="13      ">So there's happiness, dearest&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;True happiness here,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Though the troubles thou fearest
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Perchance may appear.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="166">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646751</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG IN THE SOUTH.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646751</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG IN THE SOUTH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028208</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028208</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG IN THE SOUTH.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> proud sun is setting, most fair to behold,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Going down to his rest in a garment of gold,
</l><l ln="3        ">And, like a young maiden who wishes good&hyphen;bye
</l><l ln="4        ">To her dear chosen lover, deep blushes the sky,
</l><l ln="5        ">All its beautiful tints, ah! how fair to behold
</l><l ln="6        ">As the sun goeth down in his garment of gold.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Light blue and dark blue and purple are there,
</l><l ln="8        ">Red, brown, and golden with bounty how rare!
</l><l ln="9        ">Black clouds o'er the mountains, white clouds o'er the sea,
</l><l ln="10      ">And a landward breeze cometh soft, joyous, and free.
</l><l ln="11      ">A prospect how glorious in truth to behold
</l><l ln="12      ">As the sun goeth down in his garment of gold.</l></stanza>

<pb n="167">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">All wondrously blent as He only can do
</l><l ln="14      ">Who gives to each tint its own delicate hue,
</l><l ln="15      ">Who makes Nature's paintings so gorgeously grand,
</l><l ln="16      ">That man can but copy, not daring to stand
</l><l ln="17      ">In rivalry open. Yes, fair to behold
</l><l ln="18      ">Is the sun going down in his garment of gold.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="168">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646752</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TWILIGHT MEMORIES.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646752</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TWILIGHT MEMORIES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028209</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028209</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TWILIGHT MEMORIES.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> once I loved the twilight hour
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of Summer's blissful day,
</l><l ln="3        ">While watching from each leafy bower
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The daylight die away,
</l><l ln="5        ">And clasping in mine own the hand
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of one I loved the best,
</l><l ln="7        ">Whose converse soothed, as the sight of land
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Doth mariners distressed.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Right bravely he had borne his part
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;In Earth's incessant strife,
</l><l ln="11      ">Still labouring on with dauntless heart
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Amid the ills of Life.
</l><l ln="13      ">Had known adversity and pain,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Hopes blighted&mdash;bitter wrong,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet all to sour his soul were vain:
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;In Heaven&hyphen;born strength 'twas strong.</l></stanza>

<pb n="169">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">And oft he talked of his vanished years
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In the gentle gloaming tide,
</l><l ln="19      ">Bidding me all my joys and fears
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Implicitly confide,
</l><l ln="21      ">And wisely would my future trace,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Then leaving things of Time,
</l><l ln="23      ">In raptured tones and with upturned face
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Would speak of themes sublime.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">His that strange wordless eloquence,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Always a wondrous power,
</l><l ln="27      ">Which sways the soul with a force intense
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;In the calm of such an hour.
</l><l ln="29      ">And when I walk where shadows steal
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;O'er Summer's fairy view,
</l><l ln="31      ">I never, never fail to feel
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;That influence anew.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="170">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646753</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A WINTRY MOOR AT NIGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646753</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A WINTRY MOOR AT NIGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028210</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028210</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A WINTRY MOOR AT NIGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">My</hi> way led o'er a wintry waste
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;&indent;When evening shades were falling,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;And the soft sheep&hyphen;bells rung in haste
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;&indent;The fleecy flocks were calling,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;For still a few had strayed afield
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;To wander mid the heather,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Seeking the food the hill&hyphen;sides yield
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;Despite such withering weather.
</l><l ln="9        "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A wintry moor! A wintry moor!
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;Alone at dark of night,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Where in the world may one procure
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;More desolate a sight?</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">&indent;Black barren rocks were on the right,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Uprising bleak and lone,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Like the fabled forms of men of might
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;&indent;Fast petrified to stone.
</l><pb n="171">
<l ln="17      ">&indent;And far and wide on every side,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;The mazy mist extended,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Slowly its mass did upwards glide,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;Till with the sky it blended.
</l><l ln="21      "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A wintry moor! etc.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="22      ">&indent;I thought of deeds of darkness done
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;&indent;On that drear waste so lonely!
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;That there had perished many an one
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;&indent;For lack of succour only.
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And I strode along with swifter pace,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;&indent;A thrill o'er my bosom stealing,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Reaching at last my resting&hyphen;place
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;&indent;With pleasurable feeling.
</l><l ln="30      "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A wintry moor! etc.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="172">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646754</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SEA SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646754</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SEA SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028211</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028211</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SEA SONG.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">I could</hi> not as a landsman live,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;&indent;Pursuing his poor pleasure,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Each dull delight his course may give
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;&indent;Has nought in it to measure
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;With the true transport of the soul,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;O'er every sense prevailing,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;When 'neath our feet the wild waves roll,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;We o'er the ocean sailing.
</l><l ln="9        "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A sailor's life! a sailor's life!
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;Upon the swelling sea,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Whose surges roar in ceaseless strife&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;A sailor's life for me.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">&indent;I love it when in summer&hyphen;time
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;It lies, all ill concealing,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;And o'er its ripples comes the chime
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;&indent;Of church&hyphen;bells softly stealing.
</l><pb n="173">
<l ln="17      ">&indent;I love it when in grandest storm,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;Like some great monster playing; 
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;It spurns on high the vessel's form,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;To mock it ere its slaying.
</l><l ln="21      "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A sailor's life! etc.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="22      ">&indent;Then, as our voyage is nearly gone,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;&indent;And soon to port returning,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;I love the waves which waft me on
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;&indent;To soothe my constant yearning.
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And when the dear land is espied&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;&indent;Dispelling all our sadness&mdash; 
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;I bless the swiftly flowing tide
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;&indent;Which bears me on to gladness.
</l><l ln="30      "><hi r="italic">Chorus</hi>. A sailor's life! etc.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="174">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646755</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WHY DO I TRACE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646755</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHY DO I TRACE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028212</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028212</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHY DO I TRACE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Why</hi> do I trace
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;On your loved face
</l><l ln="3        ">Such weary wealth of sorrow,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where late beamed joy
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;With nought to cloy,
</l><l ln="6        ">Caused by the cares to&hyphen;morrow?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">&indent;The world I know
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Is full of woe,
</l><l ln="9        ">Encircled round with trouble,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Yet merely sighs
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;And mournful eyes,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">But make our griefs redouble.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Look up in haste!
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Nor longer waste
</l><l ln="15      ">Your life in weak bemoanings;&mdash; 
</l><pb n="175">
<l ln="16      ">&indent;Cast grim Despair
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;From out his lair!
</l><l ln="18      ">You've known enough of groanings.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">&indent;No skies o'ercast
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;One whit more fast
</l><l ln="21      ">Because we thus are cheerful,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Clouds come apace
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;With frowning face
</l><l ln="24      ">Full oft when we are tearful.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;Then may we here
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Spurn foolish fear,
</l><l ln="27      ">Nor let fond Hope forsake us,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;So having joy
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;With nought to cloy
</l><l ln="30      ">Until the storm o'ertake us.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="176">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646756</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A PRACTICAL THEORY OF LIFE.</mainhead> <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646756</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A PRACTICAL THEORY OF LIFE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028213</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028213</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A PRACTICAL THEORY OF LIFE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>7Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">When</hi> musing on the course of Life
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;How many seem its phases,
</l><l ln="3        ">Yet every one of them is rife
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;With trebly tangled mazes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And though our prospects all are fair,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;A scene made for enjoying,
</l><l ln="7        ">Some canker&hyphen;worm intrudeth there
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Our perfect bliss destroying.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">One man is strong and has delight
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Merely in Life's possessing,
</l><l ln="11      ">But pinching Poverty's bleak blight
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Marreth his every blessing.</l></stanza>

<pb n="177">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Another's wealth and friends agree
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To lavish pleasures on him,
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet look, alas! 'tis clear to see
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Disease's curse upon him;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Disease&mdash;for which weak human skill
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Gives scant alleviation,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">He is doomed to dread Existence still
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Despite his smiling station.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">A third has pulse of purest health
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Which yields him nought save gladness,
</l><l ln="23      ">But private griefs amid his wealth
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Impart a sense of sadness.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">If we the daily deeds recite
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Which form Life's <hi r="italic">present</hi> measure,
</l><l ln="27      ">The <hi r="italic">wrong</hi> preponderates o'er the <hi r="italic">right</hi>,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;And suffering over pleasure.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">And thus whate'er our lot may be,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Our life is but a bubble,
</l><l ln="31      ">Blown from some bleak and cruel sea
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;By the tornado Trouble.</l></stanza>

<pb n="178">

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Ah! what a mystery is this!
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And yet if we revolve it,
</l><l ln="35      ">Perchance we may not muse amiss,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;But find a clue to solve it.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">It oft appears absurd to believe
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;In a God of infinite kindness,
</l><l ln="39      ">Who, seeming paradox, can leave
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Us in such woe and blindness,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">In perfect Goodness&mdash;omnipotent Power,
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Permitting Evil to enter
</l><l ln="43      ">Its fair dominions, and to shower
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Such griefs on man, their centre,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="45      ">But if we accept the sceptic view,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Denying a God and Life's fruition,
</l><l ln="47      ">What do we gain even were that true?
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;For it is merely demolition</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="49      ">Of many hopes which man holds dear
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Of a swiftly coming morrow,
</l><l ln="51      ">When we shall know with joy sincere
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;No sense of sin or sorrow,</l></stanza>

<pb n="179">

<stanza><l ln="53      ">Without revealing to our sight
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;A future fair and clearer:
</l><l ln="55      ">Nay, leaving all in deepest night&mdash; 
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Far darker, lone and drearer.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="57      ">For we still must bear the woes of Life
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;With the longings which oft come o'er us
</l><l ln="59      ">Whilst seeing no rest beyond its strife,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;Save nothingness before us.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">While a Heavenly hope amid our woe
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Will cheer our Life's endeavour,
</l><l ln="63      ">And yield us nought save good, although
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;At death it may fly for ever.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="65      ">Thus, even if we set aside
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;Religion's proofs completely,
</l><l ln="67      ">It gives more joy our minds to guide
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;Till, apprehending meetly</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="69      ">That doubtless though upon the earth
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Our path is oft perplexing,
</l><l ln="71      ">Its lack of love and chastened mirth
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;Our spirits sorely vexing,</l></stanza>

<pb n="180">

<stanza><l ln="73      ">There must exist a place which gained
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Through faith and strong endeavour,
</l><l ln="75      ">What seems unjust will be explained,
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Or rectified for ever:&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="77      ">That there's a God who made Man's mind
</l><l ln="78      ">&indent;With certain comprehension,
</l><l ln="79      ">But yet Who has seen fit to bind
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;Its limits of extension.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="81      ">Who also deemed it best for Man
</l><l ln="82      ">&indent;Here to experience sadness,
</l><l ln="83      ">As training for a higher plan
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;Of grandly growing gladness.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="85      ">Thus human Reason's utmost sphere
</l><l ln="86      ">&indent;Of thought is reached full early; 
</l><l ln="87      ">And thus to us men's lots appear
</l><l ln="88      ">&indent;So often dealt unfairly.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="89      ">That Life's dark mysteries but transcend,
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;Not <hi r="italic">contradict</hi> our reason,
</l><l ln="91      ">And so when earthly life shall end
</l><l ln="92      ">&indent;There comes a sun&hyphen;lit season,</l></stanza>

<pb n="181">

<stanza><l ln="93      ">When with enlarged God&hyphen;given powers
</l><l ln="94      ">&indent;And intellects commanding,
</l><l ln="95      ">One bliss of Heaven's bright halcyon hours
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;Shall be the understanding</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="97      ">Of problems which distressed the sage
</l><l ln="98      ">&indent;Of deepest skill and learning,
</l><l ln="99      ">But now that we have burst our cage
</l><l ln="100    ">&indent;Are easy of discerning,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="101    ">While &ldquo;themes with which we cannot cope&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="102    ">&indent;Fade 'neath our Heavenly vision,
</l><l ln="103    ">&ldquo;And Earth's worst phrenzies, marring hope,
</l><l ln="104    ">&indent;<hi r="italic">Will</hi> mar <hi r="italic">not</hi> Hope's fruition.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="182">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646757</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>EVENING THOUGHTS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646757</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EVENING THOUGHTS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028214</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028214</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>EVENING THOUGHTS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">It</hi> was evening, and sadness
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Around me was cast&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">For rejoicing and gladness
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Too swiftly were past.
</l><l ln="5        ">Then methought with deep anguish,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In Life's dreary day,
</l><l ln="7        ">All we love must soon languish
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And wither away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ah! how futile each token
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Of love given here,
</l><l ln="11      ">Merely made to be broken
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;When friendships grow sere; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Though sweet youth's summer morning
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Dawned balmy and bright,
</l><l ln="15      ">Yet our sorrow soon scorning,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;It darkened to night.</l></stanza>

<pb n="183">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Thus in bitter bewailing
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;I poured forth my grief,
</l><l ln="19      ">When this glad hope prevailing
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Gave richest relief:
</l><l ln="21      ">As the blossoms of May&hyphen;time
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Must fade and grow sere,
</l><l ln="23      ">Ere the ripe Autumn gay time
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Of fruit can appear,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">So Love's bright buds immortal
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Must seemingly die,
</l><l ln="27      ">Ere within Heaven's portal
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;They blossom on high,
</l><l ln="29      ">In fruition for ever
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;To each constant soul
</l><l ln="31      ">Who through faithful endeavour
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Gains Life's glorious goal.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="184">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646758</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THOUGHT&hyphen;LINKS.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646758</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THOUGHT&hyphen;LINKS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028215</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028215</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THOUGHT&hyphen;LINKS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Mysterious</hi> are the links that firmly bind
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Our trains of thought together. First we brood
</l><l ln="3        ">On some small trivial matter&mdash;tiny germ
</l><l ln="4        ">Of somewhat grander musings&mdash;then we find
</l><l ln="5        ">A thread is woven with our thought, and lo
</l><l ln="6        ">It leads to higher themes!&mdash;vast vistas new
</l><l ln="7        ">For serious contemplation:&mdash;and we gain
</l><l ln="8        ">Sublimest heights, while God&hyphen;reflected thoughts
</l><l ln="9        ">Transcending Reason flood our human mind.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="186">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646759</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>JOY AND GRIEF.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646759</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>JOY AND GRIEF.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028216</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028216</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JOY AND GRIEF.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Nought</hi> gives <hi r="italic">true</hi> happiness unless it touch
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Some chord of subtle feeling in the soul,
</l><l ln="3        ">And thus what oft appear most trivial things
</l><l ln="4        ">Impart such great delight:&mdash;a kindly phrase,
</l><l ln="5        ">A friendly greeting in the street, or snatch
</l><l ln="6        ">Of melody but for a moment heard:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Or even some phrases in a general talk
</l><l ln="8        ">Addressed to others, heard through being near.
</l><l ln="9        ">Each of us is an instrument, but each
</l><l ln="10      ">Is in some notes at least diversely strung
</l><l ln="11      ">From all our fellows. The musician Joy
</l><l ln="12      ">With mystic power can play upon our hearts,
</l><l ln="13      ">And through the heart can ope the hidden door
</l><l ln="14      ">That guards the sanctuary of the soul.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">Grief has an equal power, and quickly finds
</l><l ln="16      ">The portals of the soul, but having found,
</l><pb n="187">
<l ln="17      ">He enters not to play with skilful touch,
</l><l ln="18      ">But roughly beats with rude untutored hand
</l><l ln="19      ">Upon responsive tender notes, and so
</l><l ln="20      ">Instead of music only discord comes.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="189">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646760</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AFTER FIVE YEARS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646760</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AFTER FIVE YEARS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028217</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028217</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AFTER FIVE YEARS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">After</hi> five years!</l></firstl>
</pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="2        ">                          What changes will have come
</l><l ln="3        ">Among the circle of our firmest friends!
</l><l ln="4        ">Some will have gone to widely severed lands,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">While others&mdash;than whom none seemed closer bound
</l><l ln="6        ">In silken chains of love&mdash;will then perchance,
</l><l ln="7        ">Urged by some paltry source of petty feud,
</l><l ln="8        ">Made greater by their pride, have ceased to meet
</l><l ln="9        ">In harmony. And silent callous Death
</l><l ln="10      ">Will certainly have stayed the mortal course
</l><l ln="11      ">Of not a few, though friends we have not now
</l><l ln="12      ">We shall know then.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">                             In circumstances also
</l><l ln="14      ">What changes will have dawned! The man esteemed
</l><l ln="15      ">Almost a pauper now may then have wealth
</l><pb n="190">
<l ln="16      ">Unbounded,&mdash;he whose store of riches seems
</l><l ln="17      ">Limitless now may be a beggar then.
</l><l ln="18      ">He who enjoys the bliss of nerveless health
</l><l ln="19      ">May then be broken down and weak of limb,
</l><l ln="20      ">While he who now an invalid, though dowered
</l><l ln="21      ">With youth, his ills all conquered, may be strong.</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="22      ">What alterations will have come to pass
</l><l ln="23      ">Throughout the world! Peace in the place of war
</l><l ln="24      ">Or war in place of peace; and the appearance
</l><l ln="25      ">Of present party strife in politics
</l><l ln="26      ">Will then be altered quite,&mdash;while topics new
</l><l ln="27      ">Will eagerly be canvassed. Many names
</l><l ln="28      ">Novel to us will then have sprung to fame
</l><l ln="29      ">In Life's inconstant whirl, while designations
</l><l ln="30      ">Notorious now may even be then forgotten.
</l><l ln="31      ">Yet there is one thing while the Earth remains
</l><l ln="32      ">That will not change, and that one thing is&mdash;Change.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="195">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646761</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MATERNAL LOVE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646761</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MATERNAL LOVE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028218</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028218</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MATERNAL LOVE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Maternal</hi> love is ever tender and kind,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">From sinful dross of selfishness refined; 
</l><l ln="3        ">In infant years it is a tender guide
</l><l ln="4        ">To keep us safe from harm on every side; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And when our cherished childhood's days are past,
</l><l ln="6        ">It nerves us to endure the world's rough blast.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Its mellowed memory is with us still,
</l><l ln="8        ">In joy or sorrow, happiness or ill,
</l><l ln="9        ">And like some beauteous flower of growth sublime,
</l><l ln="10      ">Transplanted for awhile to this chill clime,
</l><l ln="11      ">It sheds its sweetest fragrance on our way,
</l><l ln="12      ">Reviving drooping hearts in Life's dark day.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="200">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646762</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>PARTING WORDS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646762</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>PARTING WORDS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028219</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028219</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>PARTING WORDS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> oft the parting words of loved ones dear
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Are cherished fondly all our lifetime here,
</l><l ln="3        ">And Memory, in calm reflection's hour,
</l><l ln="4        ">Recalls them to the mind with vivid power; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And frequently most bitterly we feel
</l><l ln="6        ">The impotence of Time our grief to heal.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Ah! tender parting words, how soon is felt
</l><l ln="8        ">Your influence the hardest heart to melt&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">And as a babe upon its mother's breast
</l><l ln="10      ">Is soothed unconsciously to quiet rest,
</l><l ln="11      ">So gradually it steals o'er each sad soul,
</l><l ln="12      ">And holds our feelings in its firm control.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="201">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646763</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HOMEWARD.</mainhead> <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646763</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028220</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028220</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HOMEWARD.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>7Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646764</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I. <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646764</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Each</hi> moment nearing fast her home,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A ship is cleaving through the foam,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Home! ah, how sweet to those
</l><l ln="4        ">Who in strange lands have absent been,
</l><l ln="5        ">But still recalling each loved scene&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Their heart with rapture glows.
</l><l ln="7        ">Thus there is boundless joy on board,
</l><l ln="8        ">And jocundly with one accord
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Are all prepared to land; 
</l><l ln="10      ">For when this last long night is done
</l><l ln="11      ">Their hopes rise with the morrow's sun,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Their haven is at hand.
</l><l ln="13      ">Some sense&hyphen;o'erstrain&egrave;d cannot sleep,
</l><l ln="14      ">And through the watches wakeful keep,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Longing for dawn of light; 
</l><pb n="202">
<l ln="16      ">The deck is paced by dauntless men,
</l><l ln="17      ">The night is dark, save now and then
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;When stars appear in sight.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646765</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646765</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="19      ">What was that crash! that dismal sound
</l><l ln="20      ">Which echoes through the darkness round&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;That sharp soul&hyphen;stricken scream?
</l><l ln="22      ">The glance doth on confusion fall,
</l><l ln="23      ">Those on the deck are wild, and all
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Is like a dreadsome dream.
</l><l ln="25      ">The ship has struck not far from shore,
</l><l ln="26      ">But boisterously the billows roar,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;Along a rock&hyphen;bound bay; 
</l><l ln="28      ">Two boats are manned to put to land,
</l><l ln="29      ">And struggling hard to gain the strand,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Pull through the blinding spray,
</l><l ln="31      ">Leaving the rest to face their fate as best they may.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646766</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
III. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646766</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="32      ">The scene so lately still and calm
</l><l ln="33      ">Seems nothing now save loud alarm,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And dread and direful woe&mdash; 
</l><pb n="203">
<l ln="35      ">One sight of sorrow meets the eye
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;On deck or down below.
</l><l ln="37      ">While wind and seething waters vie
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;In working ill around,
</l><l ln="39      ">Like sorcerers resolved to try
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Their secret arts profound.
</l><l ln="41      ">Shrill shrieks are heard on every side,
</l><l ln="42      ">And none now aid nor seek to guide
</l><l ln="43      ">&indent;The mad unresting crowd,
</l><l ln="44      ">Who, scarce aware of what they do,
</l><l ln="45      ">Pace passionately the deck; a few
</l><l ln="46      ">Murmur a prayer heartfelt and true,
</l><l ln="47      ">Or bitter moans&mdash;or curses too
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;In accents lewd and loud.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646767</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
IV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646767</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="49      ">Down in a cabin lies a child
</l><l ln="50      ">Heedless of death or tumult wild,
</l><l ln="51      ">By sleep with blissful dreams beguiled:
</l><l ln="52      ">A man reclines, removed a space,
</l><l ln="53      ">&indent;Scarce entered middle life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="54      ">Yet in whose face you well may trace
</l><l ln="55      ">&indent;Sad signs of care and strife.</l></div4>

<pb n="204">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646768</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
V. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646768</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="56      ">Now to the infant's side he springs,
</l><l ln="57      ">And very speedily he brings
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;His charge from down below.
</l><l ln="59      ">He casts one glance upon the storm,
</l><l ln="60      ">Then tightly grasps the tiny form&mdash; 
</l><l ln="61      ">&indent;Nor shrinking seems to know.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646769</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VI. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646769</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="62      ">His thoughts revert to long ago,
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;When fragile as this little child,
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;A mother's love upon him smiled
</l><l ln="65      ">As it assuaged each infant woe:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="66      ">And taught him to be true and brave
</l><l ln="67      ">&indent;In this weak world of sordid strife,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;And even content to part with life
</l><l ln="69      ">Did it perchance another save.
</l><l ln="70      ">And then he prays to One above
</l><l ln="71      ">To guide him in this deed of love.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646770</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646770</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="72      ">From the doomed ship without delay
</l><l ln="73      ">Through the wild waves he cleaves his way,
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Needing surpassing strength
</l><pb n="205">
<l ln="75      ">And dauntless courage thus to dare
</l><l ln="76      ">To hold his burden and to bear
</l><l ln="77      ">&indent;A swim of such a length.
</l><l ln="78      ">The ruthless waters round him roll,
</l><l ln="79      ">He well&hyphen;nigh loses all control&mdash; 
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;Yet still he struggles on; 
</l><l ln="81      ">And clasping to his breast the child,
</l><l ln="82      ">He grapples with the billows wild
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;Till strength is almost gone.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646771</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VIII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646771</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="84      ">But see! his task is nearly o'er,
</l><l ln="85      ">If he can swim a few yards more,
</l><l ln="86      ">They surely reach the longed&hyphen;for shore; 
</l><l ln="87      ">Brief moments now their fate will show
</l><l ln="88      ">Whether it be of weal or woe.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646772</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
IX. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646772</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="89      ">And still he shapes his steadfast course
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;Straight onward to the land,
</l><l ln="91      ">Yet with each stroke makes less the force
</l><l ln="92      ">&indent;Which he can still command.
</l><l ln="93      ">But all seems well&mdash;an instant more
</l><l ln="94      ">Will see them safely on the shore.</l></div4>

<pb n="206">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646773</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
X. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646773</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOMEWARD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="95      ">Sudden a gasp&mdash;a gurgling sound&mdash; 
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;A short convulsive groan,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="97      ">And nothing now is heard around
</l><l ln="98      ">&indent;Save the fierce storm alone.
</l><l ln="99      ">For he has sunk to rise no more,
</l><l ln="100    ">Exhausted with the conflict sore,
</l><l ln="101    ">And as a rain&hyphen;drop falling on a lake
</l><l ln="102    ">Ripples its surface, yet can scarcely break
</l><l ln="103    ">The depths beneath, so softly thus sinks he
</l><l ln="104    ">Into the Ocean of Eternity.</l></div4></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="207">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646774</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AN OCEAN GLOAMING.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646774</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AN OCEAN GLOAMING.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028221</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028221</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AN OCEAN GLOAMING.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">I pray</hi> you, hark,&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">What is it that each seems to crave,
</l><l ln="3        ">As over each mid&hyphen;ocean wave
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;It groweth dark?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;The angry gale
</l><l ln="6        ">Strikes our stout ship in mockery,
</l><l ln="7        ">And now they fiercely fight to see
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Who shall prevail.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;The seething spray
</l><l ln="10      ">Dashes on high, and has the whole
</l><l ln="11      ">Range of the deck without control
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Under its sway.</l></stanza>

<pb n="208">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Our sturdy ship's
</l><l ln="14      ">Tossings and creaks are like to pain,
</l><l ln="15      ">And ofttimes in the surging main
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Her beams she dips.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;Look, just in sight,
</l><l ln="18      ">Two creamy piles of foam between,
</l><l ln="19      ">A little barque is rolling seen
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Mid gathering night.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&indent;A signal goes
</l><l ln="22      ">Quick up her mast and there remains; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&ldquo;Where now she is,&rdquo; the mate explains,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;&ldquo;She scarcely knows,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;And asks that we
</l><l ln="26      ">Should tell her.&rdquo; Swiftly our reply
</l><l ln="27      ">Runs up the mast, and then we try
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;To find if she</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">&indent;Perceives the sign,
</l><l ln="30      ">Ere yet she's out of sight. Full slow
</l><l ln="31      ">Pass the dread hours ere Morning's glow
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Makes Night to pine,</l></stanza>

<pb n="209">

<stanza><l ln="33      ">&indent;And die away.
</l><l ln="34      ">But when the light is come at length,
</l><l ln="35      ">We're sheltered safe from Ocean's strength
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Within the bay.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="210">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646775</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SUMMER SCENE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646775</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER SCENE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028222</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028222</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SUMMER SCENE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Bright</hi> beams of sunlight gild the lawn,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And the whole landscape seems as drawn
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;From some enchanter's treasure;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">The songsters carol loud and clear,
</l><l ln="5        ">Ah, how I dearly love to hear
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Their sweet melodious measure.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">And while I loiter 'neath the trees,
</l><l ln="8        ">Delicious perfumes by the breeze
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Are wafted from the hay&hyphen;field,
</l><l ln="10      ">Where village urchins pleasure court,
</l><l ln="11      ">And making round the ricks their sport,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Transform it to a play&hyphen;field.</l></stanza>

<pb n="211">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Must this fair vision fade away?
</l><l ln="14      ">It must&mdash;and for its death to&hyphen;day
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;I feel a sense of sorrow; 
</l><l ln="16      ">But gladness comes to fill its place
</l><l ln="17      ">When Hope reminds with smiling face&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&ldquo;'Twill live again to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="212">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646776</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>SUMMER SORROW.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646776</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>SUMMER SORROW.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028223</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028223</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SUMMER SORROW.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Each</hi> season hath its sadness, and for me
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Summer not least of all. I know not why,
</l><l ln="3        ">But though its sylvan beauty soothes my soul
</l><l ln="4        ">Into delicious reveries; while birds,
</l><l ln="5        ">Discoursing music, fill my dreamy mind
</l><l ln="6        ">With melodies, and thoughts, and deep delight,
</l><l ln="7        ">I never felt before&mdash;yet still there lurks
</l><l ln="8        ">Within my heart a strange unfathomed grief,
</l><l ln="9        ">Which, even amidst harsh Autumn's ravages,
</l><l ln="10      ">Or grim old Winter's storms, I rarely feel.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="213">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646777</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SUMMER EVENING IN THE WOODS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646777</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER EVENING IN THE WOODS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028224</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028224</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SUMMER EVENING IN THE WOODS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">How</hi> beautiful the forest looks to&hyphen;night,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The trees just moving in the still calm air; 
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;And very many of the birds delight
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;In warbling forth their notes without a care.
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;The graceful boughs which erst were gaunt and bare
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Have donned their fairest dress; the insects keep
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;A dreamy, murmuring revel everywhere; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;But in the woodland glades, so dark and deep,
</l><l ln="9        ">Save but for these few sounds, all nature seems to sleep.</l></stanza>

<pb n="214">

<stanza><l ln="10      ">&indent;The stars come slowly out, and very soon
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;The summer day in peace and calmness ends; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;And by&hyphen;and&hyphen;by, as rises slow the moon,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Her light with splendour on the scene descends:
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;While she amid the clouds her pathway wends
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Majestic as a queen, and they stand near
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Like courtiers round her throne; each object lends
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Fresh beauty to the landscape dim, yet clear
</l><l ln="18      ">Enough to let its wondrous loveliness appear.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">&indent;Scenes like to this exert a mighty power
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;To soothe us, and to cause our minds to stray&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;If only for a brief and transient hour&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;From weary cares which fill them day by day; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;And soon our thoughts fly swiftly far away
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To some bright reminiscence of the past,
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;And for a while engrossed with it they stay; 
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And when our reverie is done at last,
</l><l ln="27      ">How deeply we regret such moments fly so fast!</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="215">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646778</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TWILIGHT THOUGHTS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646778</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TWILIGHT THOUGHTS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028225</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028225</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TWILIGHT THOUGHTS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> charming is the summer eve, removed from cities far,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where Nature's spotless loveliness nought intervenes to mar; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Where wild&hyphen;rose and convolvulus are woven in the hedge,
</l><l ln="4        ">And buttercups and foxgloves gay rise from the brooklet's edge; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Where zephyrs waft their sweetest scents adown the waving wood,
</l><l ln="6        ">And the soothing songs of Nature's choir impel us to intrude:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">When shadows creep across our path, and Day is well&hyphen;nigh dead,
</l><l ln="8        ">'Tis then that Summer ever seems her glamour best to spread.
</l><pb n="216">
<l ln="9        ">Where in this weary world can more of perfect peace be found,
</l><l ln="10      ">Than when on such a scene we gaze in sympathy around?
</l><l ln="11      ">And often will some fair wild flowers more truly touch the heart
</l><l ln="12      ">Than the resplendent trophies of rare botanic art; 
</l><l ln="13      ">The sweet&hyphen;briar which, perchance unseen, pours perfume on the air,
</l><l ln="14      ">I would not barter for what proved the florist's proudest care; 
</l><l ln="15      ">I'll leave the rich their bowers of art in which to rear rare flowers,
</l><l ln="16      ">Enough for me each common plant in Summer's gloaming hours.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="217">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646779</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A LESSON IN THE GLOAMING.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646779</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LESSON IN THE GLOAMING.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028226</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028226</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A LESSON IN THE GLOAMING.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">One</hi> even of a summer's day
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I walk scarce whither knowing,
</l><l ln="3        ">Save by a river's side I stray
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where balmy winds are blowing.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">'Tis the loved hour of twilight's close,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When o'er the landscape stealing,
</l><l ln="7        ">The last faint ray of sunset glows,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Its beauty half revealing.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Rich foliage hides the rippling stream
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;From the fair view completely,
</l><l ln="11      ">And gently as in halcyon dream,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Its murmur softly, sweetly,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Comes zephyr&hyphen;borne, as on I move
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;With light heart void of sadness,
</l><pb n="220">
<l ln="15      ">Nor caring what to&hyphen;morrow prove,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;So that to&hyphen;day be gladness.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Sudden is heard the plash of oars,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;A sense of pleasure bringing,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">While plaintively a rower pours
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;His soul thus out in singing:</l></stanza>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="21      ">In Summer's choicest day,
</l><l ln="22      ">When round each fragrant spray
</l><l ln="23      ">The blithesome breezes stray&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Ah, what delight!
</l><l ln="25      ">But brightest days contain
</l><l ln="26      ">The seeds of future pain,
</l><l ln="27      ">And Winter comes again,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Their bliss to blight!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Not so the joys of <hi r="italic">Mind</hi>,
</l><l ln="30      ">Unfathomed, unconfined,
</l><l ln="31      ">They soar and leave behind
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Trammels of Earth:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="33      ">They teach mankind to face
</l><l ln="34      ">Both honour and disgrace,
</l><l ln="35      ">And gain at last the Place
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Which gave them birth.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">The boat sweeps on,&mdash;the words depart
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;In cadences alluring,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="39      ">But they have pierced my flippant heart,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;And left a mark enduring.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="221">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646780</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MEADOW MUSINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646780</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MEADOW MUSINGS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028227</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028227</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MEADOW MUSINGS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">While</hi> treading with purest of pleasure
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The pathways grass&hyphen;grown of the fields,
</l><l ln="3        ">The thought that will come without measure
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Is strange as the fruit that it yields.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">We dream that on spot we are standing
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;To gaze on the glorious view&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Perchance some stern Druid commanding
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Perform&egrave;d his orisons due,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ere vengeful and fierce as his foeman,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And eager for spoil and applause,
</l><l ln="11      ">He ventured to meet the bold Roman
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To fight in his dear country's cause.</l></stanza>

<pb n="222">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Some Saxon, it may be, with sadness
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Here mourned the mailed Norman's advance,
</l><l ln="15      ">And on the morrow he ended his madness
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;At the point of the enemy's lance.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Perchance after great baron's wassail&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In days when such doings were rife,
</l><l ln="19      ">With feudal foes here fought each vassal
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In bitter inglorious strife.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Or the Roundhead recounted the glory
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Of routing the gay Cavalier,
</l><l ln="23      ">Nor wept, while reciting the story,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For former companions a tear.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">And still as the swiftly winged Ages
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Press on with impetuous pace,
</l><l ln="27      ">The fools of the Earth and its sages
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;May pause for a while in this place.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Then darting away, will commingle
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;In the turmoil with which Life is fraught,
</l><l ln="31      ">And never again will they single
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;This spot out for care or for thought.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="223">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646781</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>FLOWER&hyphen;GATHERING.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646781</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>FLOWER&hyphen;GATHERING.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028228</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028228</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FLOWER&hyphen;GATHERING.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Two</hi> merry children in a meadow see,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With faces all aglow with Childhood's glee&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">While finding fragrant flowrets here and there
</l><l ln="4        ">To weave into a chaplet fresh and fair,
</l><l ln="5        ">Till of the sweet wild flowers they gaily make
</l><l ln="6        ">A guerdon to reward the pains they take.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">So 'tis, methinks, amid Life's tedious toil,
</l><l ln="8        ">And sordid strife and harassing turmoil; 
</l><l ln="9        ">As surely as we seek, we pleasures find,
</l><l ln="10      ">Which bring kind Hope to cheer each mournful mind:
</l><l ln="11      ">And our attempts to seize them oft repay
</l><l ln="12      ">By showering blessings on our weary way.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="224">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646782</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GARDEN MUSINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646782</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GARDEN MUSINGS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028229</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028229</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GARDEN MUSINGS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Ah</hi>, what a sadness wells within our soul
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Whilst loitering in garden where erewhile
</l><l ln="3        ">We used to hold sweet interchange of thought
</l><l ln="4        ">With a dearly lov&egrave;d lost one; and to know
</l><l ln="5        ">Such days are dead for ever! That for us,
</l><l ln="6        ">Though May&hyphen;time blossoms make the orchard trees
</l><l ln="7        ">Most beauteous to behold, and every sense
</l><l ln="8        ">In bliss is saturated by the wealth
</l><l ln="9        ">Of Nature's charms profusely spread around,
</l><l ln="10      ">There yet remains enthroned within our heart
</l><l ln="11      ">A deep, dull void, which nought on earth can fill.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="225">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646783</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A COMPARISON.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646783</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A COMPARISON.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028230</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028230</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A COMPARISON.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> landscape bright is very fair to see,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And all around the birds are blithely singing; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And yonder to that venerable tree
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Tenaciously the ivy's boughs are clinging.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">But soon the tree is felled and ta'en away,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;And each slight tendril from its trunk is taken; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And now the ivy's beauty will decay,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Bereft of its support, lone, and forsaken.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">So frequently it happens with us all,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Round some lov'd object twin'd is our affection,
</l><l ln="11      ">But soon 'tis snatched away beyond recall,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;And leaves us nothing save its recollection.</l></stanza>

<pb n="226">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Then deepest grief and anguish rend the breast,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And oft we seem to hear a voice repeating:
</l><l ln="15      ">&ldquo;Our life is but a shadow at the best,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And nought abides, but all is brief and fleeting.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="229">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646784</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN TENEBRIS LUX.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646784</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN TENEBRIS LUX.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028231</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028231</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN TENEBRIS LUX.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">'Tis</hi> night, and darkness as a pall
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Enwraps the sable scene,
</l><l ln="3        ">Nor doth one glimmering ray recall
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where sunshine erst hath been.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Till the moon peereth 'neath a cloud
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;'Mong floods of borrowed light,
</l><l ln="7        ">And piercing through the landscape's shroud,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Dispels the gloom of night.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">So 'tis in life; mid deepest woe,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Oft drawing nigh despair,
</l><l ln="11      ">God&hyphen;borrowed beams alone still show
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;That joy abideth there.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="230">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646785</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A MORNING MEDITATION.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646785</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A MORNING MEDITATION.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028232</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028232</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A MORNING MEDITATION.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Now</hi> the black night will speedily be gone,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And the delicious dawning draweth near&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Charming each sense, while calmly gazing on
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The freshly budding beauty which is here; 
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Almost a paradise doth soon appear,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Dowered with a glittering flood of dewdrops bright; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;As the sun's radiance from a higher sphere
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Seems to produce, even by its gladsome sight,
</l><l ln="9        ">In careworn human hearts a wonderful delight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="10      ">&indent;Ah! who at sunrise could be aught save glad!
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;For 'tis a prototype of perfect day,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;When we shall wake to bliss, no longer sad,
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;And feel the glowing God&hyphen;begotten ray
</l><pb n="231">
<l ln="14      ">&indent;Which bids us fling aside all fears which may
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Still cleave to us; and with enraptured soul
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Speed to the land where trouble flees away
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Before His presence, that long&hyphen;looked&hyphen;for goal,
</l><l ln="18      ">Where all Earth's weary wounds for ever are made whole.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="232">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646786</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE WARBLERS' MISSION.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646786</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE WARBLERS' MISSION.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028233</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028233</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE WARBLERS' MISSION.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">One</hi> bright day, sad and weary,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I wandered the fields,
</l><l ln="3        ">Which often, when dreary,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Much happiness yields,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet not softest of sighing
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of sweet summer breeze,
</l><l ln="7        ">Nor the beauties near lying,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;My burden could ease.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">But a bird's note of gladness,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Clear borne on the air,
</l><l ln="11      ">Changed my sense of strange sadness
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;And sorrowful care;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">And full soon o'er me stealing,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;In place of my grief,
</l><l ln="15      ">Came a rapturous feeling
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Of peace and relief.</l></stanza>

<pb n="233">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Then I wondered if pinions
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Were given birds thus
</l><l ln="19      ">To work, mid God's dominions,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;A mission to us;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Of shedding, midst sadness,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Rejoicing and love,
</l><l ln="23      ">And through soothing and gladness,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To guide us above.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">So perchance they flew ever,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Devoting their days
</l><l ln="27      ">With ceaseless endeavour
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;To carolling praise:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">As true types, though terrestrial,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Till song&hyphen;time be o'er,
</l><l ln="31      ">Of the angels celestial
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Who chant and adore.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="234">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646787</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MIDNIGHT MUSINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646787</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MIDNIGHT MUSINGS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028234</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028234</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MIDNIGHT MUSINGS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> moonbeams' pure brightness
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Has entered my room,
</l><l ln="3        ">Thus shedding some lightness
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where late all was gloom.
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet it leaves much uncertain
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Which Day would make clear,
</l><l ln="7        ">For the Night's darksome curtain
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Still lies dim and drear.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">So, methinks, as in sadness
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;I restlessly toss,
</l><l ln="11      ">'Tis with dreams of past gladness
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Our spirits that cross:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Though oftentimes cheering
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Our souls by their light,
</l><l ln="15      ">We by their appearing
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Perceive our deep night.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="235">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646788</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;'TIS GONE.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646788</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;'TIS GONE.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028235</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028235</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;'TIS GONE.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;<hi r="smcap">'Tis</hi> gone,&rdquo; with mournful voice we say,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When some great joy departs; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And we pursue our weary way
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;With sad and heavy hearts.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&ldquo;'Tis gone,&rdquo; with gladsome voice we cry,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When grief or pain is o'er:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And all the prospect far and nigh
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Is brighter than before.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Seems it not strange that keenest woe
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;This phrase can thus express,
</l><l ln="11      ">And yet be often used to show
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The highest happiness?</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="236">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646789</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

ACROSTICS. <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z300646789</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd3>


<div4>
<poem><comhd4><idref>Z400646790</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>BURNS.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646790</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BURNS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL4028236</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL4028236</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BURNS.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Born</hi> of the people with a dower of song;&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Unlearnt in academic lore, yet strong; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Ranging each chord of lyric minstrelsy
</l><l ln="4        ">'Neath genius&hyphen;tutored fingers grandly free; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Still sweet and clear thy tones for Time eterne shall be.</l></poem>
</div4>


<pb n="238">


<div4>
<poem><comhd4><idref>Z400646791</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>COWPER.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646791</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>COWPER.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL4028237</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL4028237</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>COWPER.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Lyric</attgenre><attgenre>Heroic couplets</attgenre><attgenre>Eulogy</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Calm</hi> and clear&hyphen;toned the music of thy song,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of depths diviner than to bards belong,
</l><l ln="3        ">Who scale Parnassian heights with sordid aim:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">Pure as a ray of brightly flashing flame
</l><l ln="5        ">Eradiating from Truth's torch to show
</l><l ln="6        ">Rash Man a heavenward path amid Life's woe.</l></poem>
</div4>


<pb n="239">


<div4>
<poem><comhd4><idref>Z400646792</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE ELDER HOOD.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646792</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE ELDER HOOD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL4028238</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL4028238</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE ELDER HOOD.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> brilliant and how versatile art thou,&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of every style a master. Deep&hyphen;souled thought
</l><l ln="3        ">On many themes is here, rare puns, and now
</l><l ln="4        ">Disports a freak of fancy genius&hyphen;fraught.</l></poem>
</div4>


<pb n="240">


<div4>
<poem><comhd4><idref>Z400646793</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>KIRKE WHITE.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646793</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>KIRKE WHITE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL4028239</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL4028239</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>KIRKE WHITE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Kind</hi> and true&hyphen;hearted was thy youthful life,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In every manly attribute most rife; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Rich in a mind rare cultured, and which sought
</l><l ln="4        ">Knowledge with pursuit keen, and ever thought
</l><l ln="5        ">Each effort well repaid that learning brought.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="6        ">Wise thought on such as thee doth cheer the heart,
</l><l ln="7        ">Having their course before us as a chart,
</l><l ln="8        ">In which is shown a way whereby each one,
</l><l ln="9        ">Though sore the toil and scorching be Life's sun,
</l><l ln="10      ">Elated shall receive God's glad &ldquo;Well done.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div4>
</div3>

<pb n="241">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646794</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646794</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028240</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028240</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646795</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646795</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Long</hi> years ago a peasant boy
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Lives as his widowed mother's joy,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Her cherished firstborn son; 
</l><l ln="4        ">For though her love the others share,
</l><l ln="5        ">They are but babes&mdash;for them the care
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of life has scarce begun.
</l><l ln="7        ">While the brave brother manfully
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Strives steadfastly to gain their bread,
</l><l ln="9        ">Resolved to do as well as he
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Is able in their father's stead.</l></div4>

<pb n="242">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646796</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646796</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="11      ">He little learning could acquire,
</l><l ln="12      ">Except when sitting at the fire,
</l><l ln="13      ">When work was done on a wintry night,
</l><l ln="14      ">But then it was his chief delight
</l><l ln="15      ">To linger o'er some well&hyphen;conned page,
</l><l ln="16      ">Dowered with the wisdom of the sage.
</l><l ln="17      ">His thought for every lesser one
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;How charming 'twas to view; 
</l><l ln="19      ">And often would he join the fun
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;As leader of the crew.
</l><l ln="21      ">Yet sometimes when apart from man,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Upon the lone hill&hyphen;side,
</l><l ln="23      ">His future anxiously would scan,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And long for one to guide
</l><l ln="25      ">His steps to higher spheres of life,
</l><l ln="26      ">If even through severest strife.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646797</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
III. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646797</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="27      ">But soon his mood would grow more gay,
</l><l ln="28      ">Like lark which soars at dawn of day; 
</l><l ln="29      ">And then before his eyes would play
</l><l ln="30      ">Visions of regions far away.
</l><pb n="243">
<l ln="31      ">Yet calmly he resolved to stay
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Till some brief years were o'er,
</l><l ln="33      ">And then a fond farewell to say,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And leave his native shore,
</l><l ln="35      ">Boldly to seek his fortune there,
</l><l ln="36      ">And never yield him to despair.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646798</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
IV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646798</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="37      ">The time now comes to say farewell,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;That word how full of sadness!
</l><l ln="39      ">And yet for aught which one may tell
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;The harbinger of gladness.
</l><l ln="41      ">At least to think so sore he tries
</l><l ln="42      ">When with stout heart but wistful eyes
</l><l ln="43      ">&indent;He bids them not to grieve,
</l><l ln="44      ">Saying they soon shall have surprise
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;Which they will scarce believe.
</l><l ln="46      ">Then gently doth bright dreams unfold
</l><l ln="47      ">Of his return with wealth untold.</l></div4>

<pb n="244">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646799</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
V. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646799</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A LIFE&hyphen;CHRONICLE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="48      ">Long years have passed, and now once more
</l><l ln="49      ">He views again his native shore; 
</l><l ln="50      ">Nor has his stay been spent in vain,
</l><l ln="51      ">For ere he crosses now the main
</l><l ln="52      ">He has of gold an ample store,
</l><l ln="53      ">And better still a well&hyphen;earned name
</l><l ln="54      ">For honest worth, with nought of shame.
</l><l ln="55      ">His now indeed a bright career,
</l><l ln="56      ">In which each blessing given man here
</l><l ln="57      ">Is granted to him, as if sent
</l><l ln="58      ">As guerdon for his past content,
</l><l ln="59      ">While amid much labour patiently
</l><l ln="60      ">He strove against grim poverty; 
</l><l ln="61      ">And succouring the deep&hyphen;distressed,
</l><l ln="62      ">Proved now the passion of his breast.
</l><l ln="63      ">So when at length in death he slept
</l><l ln="64      ">Many a mourner for him wept.</l></div4></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="245">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646800</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A DREAM OF LONG AGO.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646800</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A DREAM OF LONG AGO.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028241</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028241</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A DREAM OF LONG AGO.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">A dream</hi> of youth comes o'er me&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;A dream of long ago,
</l><l ln="3        ">When life was light before me,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Nor knew the taint of woe.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">'Tis of a sun&hyphen;lit village
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Built by the bright sea's strand,
</l><l ln="7        ">With widespread fields in tillage
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Stretching on every hand,&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Save on one side where moorland
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The landscape closes in,
</l><l ln="11      ">Which, though men deemed it poor land,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Was dowered with blooming whin.</l></stanza>

<pb n="246">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Here there were boundless pleasures
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;For me, a town&hyphen;bred boy; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Here first I found the treasures
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;That country&hyphen;folk enjoy.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Great was my bliss bird&hyphen;nesting,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;When butterflies I sought,
</l><l ln="19      ">Or when in quiet resting
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;On turf with fragrance fraught.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Its charms indeed were legion,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;With its odours of wild flowers; 
</l><l ln="23      ">It seemed a fairy region
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To spend the halcyon hours.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Once with a strange emotion,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;I found a blackbird's brood,
</l><l ln="27      ">And watched the dam's devotion,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Yet dreaded to intrude.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">I loved this moorland dearly,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;With its spots for rest and play&mdash; 
</l><l ln="31      ">And in my day&hyphen;dreams clearly
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Still see it day by day.</l></stanza>

<pb n="247">

<stanza><l ln="33      ">How pretty looked the river&mdash; 
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Which gave the spot its name&mdash; 
</l><l ln="35      ">As its wavelets used to quiver
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Beneath the sunset's flame,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">Which dyed them with a lightness
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;That soon must disappear,
</l><l ln="39      ">Fit emblem of the brightness
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Which human life has here.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">What sport to watch the fishers
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;As they left their homes at morn&mdash; 
</l><l ln="43      ">Surrounded with well&hyphen;wishers,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Holding dread and fear in scorn!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="45      ">And how gladsome were the greetings
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;When they returned at night,
</l><l ln="47      ">And merry were the meetings,
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;For faces all were bright.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="49      ">Life here had much of gladness
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Despite its dull day's round,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="51      ">And less of care and sadness
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Than oft in cities found.</l></stanza>

<pb n="248">

<stanza><l ln="53      ">How great was my diversion
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;(I was but eight years old)
</l><l ln="55      ">When I went a short excursion,
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;A cart my chariot bold.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="57      ">As onward thus I travelled
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Mid balmy summer air,
</l><l ln="59      ">Life's skein for me was ravelled
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;With bliss in place of care.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">I saw them cutting fuel
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;To feed their wintry fire,
</l><l ln="63      ">And, ah, I thought it cruel
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;When bidden to retire.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="65      ">How pleasant the postman meeting,
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;With his merrily sounding horn,
</l><l ln="67      ">And his grave yet gladsome greeting
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;Bestowed on me each morn.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="69      ">While the village people ever,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Though rude and unrefined,
</l><l ln="71      ">To me seemed good and clever
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;Because they all were kind.</l></stanza>

<pb n="249">

<stanza><l ln="73      ">Ah, vision calm and cheering!
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Soul&hyphen;soothing none the less,
</l><l ln="75      ">Despite the callous sneering
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;Cold cynics may profess.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="77      ">Thy memories shall not perish
</l><l ln="78      ">&indent;Whate'er betide of grief&mdash; 
</l><l ln="79      ">Yes, evermore I'll cherish
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;This dream to bring relief.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="252">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646801</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IMAGINATION'S HARVEST.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646801</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IMAGINATION'S HARVEST.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028242</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028242</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IMAGINATION'S HARVEST.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Oh</hi>, how powerless we seem to secure Fancy's dream,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Though before our rapt gaze it be floating; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And to garner a mine of the rich gems that shine,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Yet are lost for the lack of our noting.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Thus in sickness sometimes, like strange musical chimes,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Come sweet visions enchanting to meet us; 
</l><l ln="7        ">But they pass from our sight like a bird in its flight,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And are gone ere their gladness can greet us.</l></stanza>

<pb n="253">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Then, if buoyant in health, they deny us their wealth,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;And leave us to commonplace duties; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Though with bliss Life is fraught, we scarce harbour a thought
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of their wondrous though swift&hyphen;fleeting beauties.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">While oft in our mind when their traces we find,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;We would pen their pure brilliance for others,
</l><l ln="15      ">But the glories we see, though entrancing they be,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Are as nought in the eyes of our brothers.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="255">

