<pb n="257">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646803</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HUBERT.</mainhead> <attbytes>14Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646803</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HUBERT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028243</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028243</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HUBERT.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>14Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div4><comhd4 r="italic"><idref>Z400646804</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
Scene I. <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646804</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HUBERT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<stage>&mdash;The garden of a Manor House on a summer evening.</stage>

<list><caption r="italic">Dramatis Person&aelig;.</caption><item>&mdash;Sir Ralph Harton, a frail old man, whose wife
had been dead for years.</item> <item>Hubert, his only child in opening
manhood.</item></list>

<stage><hi r="italic">Time</hi>.&mdash;Immediately after the breaking out of the Civil War, 1642.</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Hurrah!</hi> at length the people spring
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To vindicate their right,
</l><l ln="3        ">And vainly now shall strive the King
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To vanquish them in fight.
</l><l ln="5        ">At last Laud's long despotic course
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Draws ruin in its train,
</l><l ln="7        ">Soon Hampden's words of frenzied force
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The victory shall gain&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">While Charles will rue with deep remorse
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The part which he hath ta'en.
</l><l ln="11      ">For England's might shall rise in fight
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Throughout the groaning land&mdash; 
</l><pb n="258">
<l ln="13      ">And War's harsh sound be heard around
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Our homes on every hand.
</l><l ln="15      ">Our wrongs shall be wiped out in gore,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;We'll vanquish what was vaunted,
</l><l ln="17      ">And so it shall be said once more
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;That Britons are undaunted.
</l><l ln="19      ">Then shall we hold a Parliament
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Untrammelled, true, and free; 
</l><l ln="21      ">The Stuart's line will aye repent
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Their deeds of tyranny.
</l><l ln="23      ">Secret intrigues shall not affright,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Nor unordained taxation&mdash; 
</l><l ln="25      ">And life will prove a dear delight
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;To each one in the nation!</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Sir Ralph.</speaker>
<l ln="27      ">And yet, my son, this coming strife
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Will yield us grievous woe; 
</l><l ln="29      ">Though risking life where death is rife,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;God grant you ne'er may know
</l><l ln="31      ">The agony a father feels
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;When from his fond child parted; 
</l><l ln="33      ">Wounds such as these Time seldom heals,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;But leaves him broken&hyphen;hearted.
</l><l ln="35      ">What anguish 'tis to separate
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;When Nature's ties are nearest!
</l><pb n="259">
<l ln="37      ">Ah! cruel is the withering fate
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Which tears me from my dearest.
</l><l ln="39      ">Still go, my son, nor lingering stay,
</l><l ln="40      ">All private wishes must give way
</l><l ln="41      ">When the public weal in a righteous cause
</l><l ln="42      ">Demands a defence for our ancient laws.
</l><l ln="43      ">Yet even when the cause is one
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;To which my thoughts respond,
</l><l ln="45      ">How hard it seems to lose thee, son; 
</l><l ln="46      ">I long to gaze beyond
</l><l ln="47      ">The darkness which enshrouds thy lot
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Amid the surging strife&mdash; 
</l><l ln="49      ">Of Gertrude, Hubert, think'st thou not?
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Gertrude thy promised wife.
</l><l ln="51      ">Her father hastes with all his men
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;To take the monarch's side; 
</l><l ln="53      ">Will he permit his daughter then
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;To be a traitor's bride?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<l ln="55      ">Lately on evening calm as this
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;We met in woodland yonder,
</l><l ln="57      ">Sealing our troth with fervent kiss,
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Knowing we had grown fonder,
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;Yet 'twas our lot to ponder
</l><l ln="60      ">On what, alas! we now must do; 
</l><pb n="260">
<l ln="61      ">So sadly passed our interview,
</l><l ln="62      ">Feeling it was our parents' due,
</l><l ln="63      ">At least, that we should meet no more
</l><l ln="64      ">Until the present strife was o'er.
</l><l ln="65      ">And thus our pressing grief we strove to smother,
</l><l ln="66      ">By vowing constant faith to one another.
</l><l ln="67      ">So still to me is Gertrude dear,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;We do not part for ever; 
</l><l ln="69      ">Then, father mine, thy spirit cheer,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Though now we're forced to sever.</l></pdiv></div4>

<div4><comhd4 r="italic"><idref>Z400646805</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
Scene II. <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646805</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HUBERT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<stage>&mdash;A room in the Manor House. Hubert and Gertrude
alone.
<hi r="italic">Time</hi>.&mdash;Three years afterwards.</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<l ln="1        ">Alas! my honoured father dead,
</l><l ln="2        ">A blighting blow indeed has sped
</l><l ln="3        ">When I was absent; Gertrude, love,
</l><l ln="4        ">Thou seem'st a being from above
</l><l ln="5        ">Sent to relieve my crushing woe,
</l><l ln="6        ">By bliss which mortals rarely know.
</l><l ln="7        ">Few words may tell why I am here,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;In thy dear face delighting,
</l><pb n="261">
<l ln="9        ">Blessed be the cause which brings thee near,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Our severed ties uniting.
</l><l ln="11      ">How weary is this woeful time
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of pillaging and slaughter!
</l><l ln="13      ">No party deeming war a crime,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Blood flowing fast as water.
</l><l ln="15      ">The golden grain one rarely sees
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;That all are now requiring,
</l><l ln="17      ">Few buds upon the orchard trees,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Which ruthless foes are firing,
</l><l ln="19      ">Shrieks of despair borne by the breeze
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Whence peasants are retiring.
</l><l ln="21      ">The hurried tramp of arm&egrave;d men,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;The musketry's rude rattle,
</l><l ln="23      ">The cries and imprecations when
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Amid the brunt of battle.
</l><l ln="25      ">Such are the sounds which greet mine ear,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Till, saddened with the fray,
</l><l ln="27      ">I come, my love, to rest me here,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;If only for a day.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Gertrude.</speaker>
<l ln="29      ">My story too is very brief,
</l><l ln="30      ">But 'tis a tale of truest grief.
</l><l ln="31      ">Ah! Hubert, I felt lone and drear
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;When thou went'st forth to fight the foe,
</l><pb n="262">
<l ln="33      ">And none were left my soul to cheer
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Along its path of loveless woe.
</l><l ln="35      ">The links seemed loosed which brightly bound
</l><l ln="36      ">Our hopes and hearts in love profound.
</l><l ln="37      ">My father grew morose and stern,
</l><l ln="38      ">And harshly swore that I should learn
</l><l ln="39      ">My folly thus to thwart his will
</l><l ln="40      ">By loving a rebel Roundhead still,
</l><l ln="41      ">And that he would go forth and bring
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;For me another lover&mdash; 
</l><l ln="43      ">Who dauntlessly would serve the King,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;As I should soon discover.
</l><l ln="45      ">While thus beset on every side,
</l><l ln="46      ">With none to counsel or to guide,
</l><l ln="47      ">I scarce knew what I ought to do,
</l><l ln="48      ">Then to Sir Harton's house I flew,
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;Craving protection there; 
</l><l ln="50      ">And graciously with features pale
</l><l ln="51      ">He gravely listened to my tale,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Granting me all my prayer.
</l><l ln="53      ">He let me take a daughter's part&mdash; 
</l><l ln="54      ">Loving me dearly from his heart; 
</l><l ln="55      ">But feebler grew he day by day,
</l><l ln="56      ">Dreaming of thee who wert away,
</l><pb n="263">
<l ln="57      ">Endangered in the deadly fray; 
</l><l ln="58      ">And oft he longed as erst of yore
</l><l ln="59      ">To mount his stately steed once more
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;To join thee in the field.
</l><l ln="61      ">But lacking strength, &ldquo;Heaven's will be done,
</l><l ln="62      ">Though strong the yearning for my son,
</l><l ln="63      ">&indent;Whom God protect and shield.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="64      ">I need not tell thee how his strength
</l><l ln="65      ">Stole stealthily away: at length
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;He knew that death was near,
</l><l ln="67      ">And like a wan and sickly child,
</l><l ln="68      ">By sleep when blissfully beguiled,
</l><l ln="69      ">&indent;He died without a fear.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<l ln="70      ">Thanks, Gertrude darling, for thy care,
</l><l ln="71      ">Ah! had I but been near to share
</l><l ln="72      ">Thy deep devotion to my sire,
</l><l ln="73      ">It had been more mine own desire,
</l><l ln="74      ">Than that by deeds of might my name
</l><l ln="75      ">Should win in war a soldier's fame.
</l><l ln="76      ">This is no time for honeyed word,
</l><l ln="77      ">Yet what from thy sweet lips I've heard
</l><l ln="78      ">Has bid me bless and love thee more
</l><l ln="79      ">Than in the peaceful days of yore.
</l><l ln="80      ">But, Gertrude, I must leave thee now&mdash; 
</l><pb n="264">
<l ln="81      ">&indent;I may no longer tarry; 
</l><l ln="82      ">For I my good steed must allow
</l><l ln="83      ">&indent;Three hours in which to carry
</l><l ln="84      ">His master unto his command
</l><l ln="85      ">&indent;Of Levellers the nearest band.
</l><l ln="86      ">The struggle now is nearly done,
</l><l ln="87      ">&indent;With Cromwell none can cope&mdash; 
</l><l ln="88      ">When a great conflict has been won
</l><l ln="89      ">&indent;Gone is each royal hope.
</l><l ln="90      ">Thy sire and mother are in Spain
</l><l ln="91      ">(Having in safety crossed the main); 
</l><l ln="92      ">Then with my vassals still abide,
</l><l ln="93      ">&indent;Nor from my home depart&mdash; 
</l><l ln="94      ">Until I come to call thee bride
</l><l ln="95      ">&indent;With blithely beating heart.
</l><l ln="96      ">Oh! give me now a last embrace,
</l><l ln="97      ">&indent;One glance of thy bright eye
</l><l ln="98      ">Will nerve me aught on earth to face,
</l><l ln="99      ">&indent;Even though it be to die.</l></pdiv></div4>

<div4><comhd4 r="italic"><idref>Z400646806</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
Scene III. <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646806</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HUBERT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>
<stage>&mdash;Interior of a wretched hovel. Hubert lying
wounded. Group of soldiers.
<hi r="italic">Time</hi>.&mdash;A few days later.</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker>1<hi r="italic">st Sol.</hi></speaker>
<l ln="1        ">'Tis sad our captain too should feel
</l><l ln="2        ">The stroke of the Malignants' steel,
</l><pb n="265">
<l ln="3        ">In fight so fearless, brave, and bold,
</l><l ln="4        ">He scarcely seemed of mortal mould; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And yet among the wounded he
</l><l ln="6        ">Would tender as a woman be.
</l><l ln="7        ">The dying heard with joy his tread,
</l><l ln="8        ">Invoking blessings on his head.
</l><l ln="9        ">So kind to all, so gentle too,
</l><l ln="10      ">He gave to each his proper due,
</l><l ln="11      ">And ever exercised his power
</l><l ln="12      ">To check us in a wanton hour.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker>2<hi r="italic">nd Sol.</hi></speaker>
<l ln="13      ">Cease, ere he wakes&mdash;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<stage r="italic">(Opening his eyes&mdash;)</stage>
<l ln="14      ">                              Why am I here,
</l><l ln="15      ">In this abode so bare and drear?
</l><l ln="16      ">Why this strange mist before mine eyes,
</l><l ln="17      ">Whence phantoms of the past arise?
</l><l ln="18      ">Why this weak trembling of the frame,
</l><l ln="19      ">And feelings which I cannot name?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker>1<hi r="italic">st Sol.</hi></speaker>
<l ln="20      ">Thou'rt wounded, Captain, but we feel
</l><l ln="21      ">Assured our leech thy hurt can heal.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker r="italic">Hubert.</speaker>
<l ln="22      ">Nevermore, my race is run,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;Here I shall not long remain,
</l><l ln="24      ">All my life on earth is done&mdash; 
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Save, perchance, some hours of pain.
</l><pb n="266">
<stage r="italic">(Delirious.)</stage>
<l ln="26      ">Gertrude darling, come to me,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;Even mid the din of strife.
</l><l ln="28      ">When shall I the dear day see
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;When I rapturous call thee wife?
</l><stage r="italic">(Again he is conscious.)</stage>
<l ln="30      ">Approach, my men, I grow more weak,
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;My strength speeds swift away,
</l><l ln="32      ">Then promise me while yet I speak
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;My mandate to obey.
</l><l ln="34      ">When I am dead, with charger fleet
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Unto my home repair,
</l><l ln="36      ">And tell the lady Gertrude sweet,
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;My last thoughts were of her.
</l><l ln="38      ">And lay me where my fathers sleep,
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;Within yon lone churchyard,
</l><l ln="40      ">Where the weird willow seems to keep
</l><l ln="41      ">&indent;A solitary guard.
</l><l ln="42      ">Farewell! I thank you from my heart
</l><l ln="43      ">For all the kindness on your part,
</l><l ln="44      ">May God&mdash;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv>
<speaker>1<hi r="italic">st Sol.</hi></speaker>
<l ln="45      ">            See the celestial light
</l><l ln="46      ">Illume his features, as his spirit takes its flight.</l></pdiv></div4></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="267">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646807</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.

<subhead r="smcap">June 1st, 1679.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>11Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646807</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028244</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028244</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>11Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016945">The Scottish Presbyterians, forbidden by the arbitrary enactments
of Charles II. to hold religious services according to their much&hyphen;cherished
manner, were fain to do so in secret. Graham of Claver&hyphen;house,
Viscount Dundee, has earned immortal infamy by the
cruelties he exercised while dispersing these assemblies with his
troopers. It is one of those occasions which is here attempted to
be described.</note>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646808</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646808</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">'Tis</hi> Sabbath morn&mdash;fair Nature's face
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Showers smiles of freshly glowing grace
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;On mountain, crag, and glen,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">As if to prove to Him above
</l><l ln="5        ">Its silent share of lowly love
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Amid proud sullen men; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And blithely birds chant loud their lays
</l><l ln="8        ">Of adoration and of praise.</l></div4>

<pb n="268">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646809</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646809</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="9        ">Much people from around are here,
</l><l ln="10      ">Yet with a mien of awe and fear,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">But oft their faces seem to cheer
</l><l ln="12      ">As though some blessed boon were near.
</l><l ln="13      ">Women and men with one accord
</l><l ln="14      ">Are gathered now upon the sward,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;&indent;Vanished at once each petty feud,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">They are resolved to serve the Lord
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;In way which unto them seems good.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646810</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
III. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646810</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="18      ">&ldquo;Have ye heard of that rash raid
</l><l ln="19      ">Ruthless Claverhouse has made?&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="20      ">Thus in accents firm yet low
</l><l ln="21      ">Oft they murmur to and fro&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&ldquo;He has ta'en of us the best,
</l><l ln="23      ">But he shall not seize the rest&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">Until at least we struggle sore
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;To hold our own in fight,
</l><l ln="26      ">And pray amid the conflict's roar
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;&lsquo;For Scotland and the right.&rsquo;</l></div4>

<pb n="269">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646811</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
IV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646811</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="28      ">&ldquo;Why should the King dictate to us
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;An alien way to serve the Lord?
</l><l ln="30      ">We will not bear such thrall, and thus
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;Are met this day with one accord; 
</l><l ln="32      ">Place sentinels on every hill
</l><l ln="33      ">&indent;To give us all fit warning due:
</l><l ln="34      ">Then put good trust in God's wise will
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;And in our cause and weapons true.&rdquo;</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646812</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
V. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646812</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="36      ">&ldquo;If our sweet sisters see the sign
</l><l ln="37      ">Of danger passed along the line
</l><l ln="38      ">Of distant scouts, they quit the glen,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="39      ">The strife not left to craven men.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="40      ">So speaks a patriarch in the midst, and now
</l><l ln="41      ">The congregation at God's footstool bow,
</l><l ln="42      ">And with united voices humbly there
</l><l ln="43      ">They plead for pardon and for peace in prayer.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646813</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VI. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646813</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="44      ">Then plaintively they sing a psalm,
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;And hear the &ldquo;Word of Life;&rdquo; 
</l><pb n="270">
<l ln="46      ">Yet bodes around a baneful calm
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;Presaging coming strife.
</l><l ln="48      ">For see! there hastes a messenger,
</l><l ln="49      ">Of toil&hyphen;worn form but dauntless air:
</l><l ln="50      ">&ldquo;Look to your ranks, rouse ye like men,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="51      ">The black dragoons have gained the glen.&rdquo;</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646814</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646814</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="52      ">Full speedily the men divide
</l><l ln="53      ">In companies, on either side
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;According to their arms; 
</l><l ln="55      ">A motley host indeed they seem,
</l><l ln="56      ">As now the sun's meridian beam
</l><l ln="57      ">Makes scythes and mattocks burnished gleam
</l><l ln="58      ">Among the weapons soldiers deem
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;Fitter for war's alarms.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646815</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
VIII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646815</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="60      ">The aged minister with head made bare
</l><l ln="61      ">Amid a solemn silence offers prayer; 
</l><l ln="62      ">&ldquo;Lord, spare the green and take the ripe; we know
</l><l ln="63      ">Thou rulest all things in this world of woe; 
</l><l ln="64      ">Then grant but this and Scotland's just demand,
</l><l ln="65      ">Aught else we leave in Thy Almighty Hand.&rdquo;</l></div4>

<pb n="271">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646816</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
IX. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646816</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="66      ">The pleading ends; each peasant hies
</l><l ln="67      ">&indent;His proper place to fill; 
</l><l ln="68      ">Along their front a marsh there lies&mdash; 
</l><l ln="69      ">&indent;Behind their post a hill.
</l><l ln="70      ">While resolutely thus they tread,
</l><l ln="71      ">&indent;Of father, mother, wife,
</l><l ln="72      ">Doubtless they think, yet dare the dread
</l><l ln="73      ">&indent;And danger of the strife,
</l><l ln="74      ">Feeling its issue will restore
</l><l ln="75      ">Freedom to their down&hyphen;trodden shore.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646817</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
X. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646817</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="76      ">Lo! list to the sound which now bursts on the ear,
</l><l ln="77      ">A sound that full oft hath begotten wild fear&mdash; 
</l><l ln="78      ">The prelude to plunder and rapine and woe,
</l><l ln="79      ">As all in the bold little army well know.
</l><l ln="80      ">Pricking swift as the billows when ploughed by the gale,
</l><l ln="81      ">While their steeds spurn the turf as they dash up the vale,
</l><l ln="82      ">The dragoons are seen moving, and every man
</l><l ln="83      ">Views the dark crest of Claverhouse leading the van.</l></div4>

<pb n="272">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646818</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XI. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646818</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="84      ">&ldquo;Now look to your carbines,&rdquo; cries he with a laugh&mdash; 
</l><l ln="85      ">&ldquo;And each ranting rebel you'll scatter like chaff,
</l><l ln="86      ">The harvest is over, the thrashers are come,
</l><l ln="87      ">With swords for their flails, for their music a drum,
</l><l ln="88      ">And your famous leech&hyphen;craft will certainly heal
</l><l ln="89      ">The festering wound of the Covenant's zeal.&rdquo;</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646819</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646819</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="90      ">Sharp comes the volley&mdash;from the vale
</l><l ln="91      ">&indent;Shrouded in sable smoke
</l><l ln="92      ">Strange sounds arise; and when a wail
</l><l ln="93      ">&indent;Pierces its cloud&hyphen;wrapt cloak,
</l><l ln="94      ">Perchance it is a sign that one
</l><l ln="95      ">&indent;Ends there his earthly strife&mdash; 
</l><l ln="96      ">His lowly race at last hath run,
</l><l ln="97      ">&indent;Entering eternal life.
</l><l ln="98      ">Perchance a sign that one of those
</l><l ln="99      ">&indent;Who scoffed and had no fear,
</l><l ln="100    ">His summons come, reluctant goes
</l><l ln="101    ">&indent;Before God to appear.</l></div4>

<pb n="273">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646820</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XIII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646820</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="102    ">Yet still the peasants ne'er o'erthrown
</l><l ln="103    ">With patient courage hold their own; 
</l><l ln="104    ">Try as they may, the soldiers see
</l><l ln="105    ">They win not thus the victory.
</l><l ln="106    ">So Claverhouse recalls each man
</l><l ln="107    ">Till he direct some further plan,
</l><l ln="108    ">The lines upon his stubborn face
</l><l ln="109    ">Showing he feels the dire disgrace
</l><l ln="110    ">That well&hyphen;tried troops&mdash;false Charles's boast&mdash; 
</l><l ln="111    ">Should vanquished be by peasant host.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646821</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XIV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646821</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="112    ">But soon enraged he orders all
</l><l ln="113    ">The cavalry within his call
</l><l ln="114    ">Full at the charge with frenzied force
</l><l ln="115    ">Across the moss to take their course,
</l><l ln="116    ">Seeking to make the rout complete
</l><l ln="117    ">By crushing all beneath their feet.
</l><l ln="118    ">And gallantly the men advance
</l><l ln="119    ">With pointed sword, and glittering lance,
</l><l ln="120    ">And crests which in the sun&hyphen;beams dance.</l></div4>

<pb n="274">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646822</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646822</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="121    ">But every effort is in vain,
</l><l ln="122    ">And steeds, though guided by the rein,
</l><l ln="123    ">&indent;Are all around fast falling; 
</l><l ln="124    ">And their fierce foemen now are closing
</l><l ln="125    ">Thick in upon them, and opposing,
</l><l ln="126    ">&indent;Their ranks now past recalling.
</l><l ln="127    ">The marsh has stopped their march indeed
</l><l ln="128    ">&indent;There can be no denying,
</l><l ln="129    ">And many a man and many a steed
</l><l ln="130    ">&indent;Dyed darkly now lie dying.
</l><l ln="131    ">And all their splendour melts away
</l><l ln="132    ">Like dew&hyphen;drops at the dawn of day.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646823</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XVI. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646823</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="133    ">Like as a vulture when bereft of prey
</l><l ln="134    ">Long hovers ere it baffled soars away,
</l><l ln="135    ">Stern Claverhouse had waited thus in vain,
</l><l ln="136    ">Till now he turns his rampant charger's rein; 
</l><l ln="137    ">Shouting, in his rough voice, the loud command,
</l><l ln="138    ">&ldquo;Retreat,&rdquo; unto the remnant of his band</l></div4>

<pb n="275">

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646824</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XVII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646824</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="139    ">And thus the victory is won,
</l><l ln="140    ">&indent;And many hearts made glad&mdash; 
</l><l ln="141    ">Yet grieving that a Sabbath's sun
</l><l ln="142    ">&indent;Should see a sight so sad.
</l><l ln="143    ">And well they know they have not broke
</l><l ln="144    ">The rigour of the Despot's yoke,
</l><l ln="145    ">And oft they pause and ponder wearily
</l><l ln="146    ">On what must hap ere Scotland can be free.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646825</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
XVIII. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646825</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE OF LOUDONHILL.  June 1st, 1679.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="147    ">Loudon! thy fame shall ne'er be lost,
</l><l ln="148    ">Even if it only showed the cost
</l><l ln="149    ">Our fathers paid for Liberty,
</l><l ln="150    ">That priceless jewel of the free,
</l><l ln="151    ">Thus nerving us with effort strong
</l><l ln="152    ">To combat Tyranny and Wrong.</l></div4></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="276">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646826</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AN EPISODE IN THE BATTLE OF
FUENTES D'HONORE.

<subhead>1811.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646826</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AN EPISODE IN THE BATTLE OF FUENTES D'HONORE.  1811.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028245</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028245</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AN EPISODE IN THE BATTLE OF FUENTES D'HONORE.  1811.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> horse of the armies, in hostile array,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Haste to prove their proud prowess in mortal affray&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And the soldiers' fierce oaths that are bandied around
</l><l ln="4        ">Add a fresh sense of horror to battle's stern sound.
</l><l ln="5        ">Thus the squadrons are nearing each other, when lo!
</l><l ln="6        ">An hussar leaves our line and makes straight for the foe,
</l><l ln="7        ">And stung by his tauntings to furious force,
</l><l ln="8        ">Direct at one soldier he urges his horse&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">Who, seeing such frenzy of hate with sore fear,
</l><l ln="10      ">Sets spurs to his steed, and swift speeds for the rear,
</l><pb n="277">
<l ln="11      ">While the other his charger gives rashly the rein,
</l><l ln="12      ">And both gallop recklessly over the plain.
</l><l ln="13      ">Our men greet their comrade with cheers long and loud,
</l><l ln="14      ">While the French are struck mute as he flies through their crowd; 
</l><l ln="15      ">So the chase is continued far, far, in advance
</l><l ln="16      ">Of the glancing of bayonet or glittering of lance; 
</l><l ln="17      ">Yet our gallant hussar is in perilous plight,
</l><l ln="18      ">The enemy near him&mdash;no friends now in sight:
</l><l ln="19      ">And to reach his companions perforce he must go
</l><l ln="20      ">Through the densely ranged ranks of the furious foe&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Who, deeming their victory a certainty, vow
</l><l ln="22      ">Though he passed their line once, he will not pass it now.
</l><l ln="23      ">And hard they press on him&mdash;escape seems in vain,
</l><l ln="24      ">Though he spur his steed onward with loose slackened rein.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="25      ">But the men of his regiment are anxious to save
</l><l ln="26      ">A comrade, though reckless, thus daring and brave; 
</l><pb n="278">
<l ln="27      ">So, drawing their sabres, swift forward they dash
</l><l ln="28      ">And charge on the cowards with crest&hyphen;cleaving crash.
</l><l ln="29      ">Thus the moment which seemed his sad fate to have sealed
</l><l ln="30      ">A goodly array of our soldiers revealed,
</l><l ln="31      ">And amid the mad mel&eacute;e of general strife
</l><l ln="32      ">He regained his companions with honour and life.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="279">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646827</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>DEVOTION OF PRINCE PONIATOWSKI.

<subhead r="smcap">Leipsic, 1813.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646827</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>DEVOTION OF PRINCE PONIATOWSKI.  Leipsic, 1813.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028246</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028246</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>DEVOTION OF PRINCE PONIATOWSKI.  Leipsic, 1813.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Bravely</hi> the French have fought, but all by treachery is lost,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And nought is left save to retreat, though now at fearful cost; 
</l><l ln="3        ">In gloomy tones Napoleon gives the unfamiliar word&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">With curses on the enemy it everywhere is heard; 
</l><l ln="5        ">&ldquo;And you, Prince Poniatowski, keep the Southern Faubourg, while
</l><l ln="6        ">Across the Pleisse and Elster the vanguard can defile.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&ldquo;My men are few, your Majesty; they must in time give way.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&ldquo;Still you will surely strive to hold the post as best you may.&rdquo; 
</l><pb n="282">
<l ln="9        ">&ldquo;Doubt us not, sire, we'll keep good guard,&rdquo; speaks he with a deep sigh.
</l><l ln="10      ">&ldquo;None of my Polish legion but for you would gladly die.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="11      ">The morning light soon growing bright, shows clearly to the foe
</l><l ln="12      ">The French retreat has now commenced, though sad and strangely slow; 
</l><l ln="13      ">And columns of the Allies advance to do their duty
</l><l ln="14      ">By dashing on to devastate a scene once filled with beauty; 
</l><l ln="15      ">But gallantly their rushing ranks the brave rearguard restrain,
</l><l ln="16      ">Full long their valiant charge is vain an entrance to obtain,
</l><l ln="17      ">And when, but step by step, the bold defenders are retiring,
</l><l ln="18      ">'Tis whilst resisting steadfastly with still continued firing; 
</l><l ln="19      ">All their companions now have crossed a broad bridge which is mined&mdash; 
</l><pb n="283">
<l ln="20      ">If they can pass securely o'er, they soon may safety find.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="21      ">Hark to the sudden hellish crash! these heroes' hope has gone!
</l><l ln="22      ">The mine has prematurely burst&mdash;the careless stream rolls on; 
</l><l ln="23      ">The people fire from off the roofs, the foe press on the rear,
</l><l ln="24      ">A moment 'tis of agony, of overwhelming fear.
</l><l ln="25      ">Proud Poniatowski sees the flash of hostile sabres rise,
</l><l ln="26      ">And to his Polish cuirassiers, he petulantly cries&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">&ldquo;'Tis best to fall with honour now while each his weapon plies.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="28      ">Turning his horse, he shapes his course 'mong bayonets all opposing,
</l><l ln="29      ">Around his stalwart martial form the enemy are closing&mdash; 
</l><l ln="30      ">One shot has smote him in the arm, another midst his dress,
</l><pb n="284">
<l ln="31      ">Striking the gay insignia which his great renown express.
</l><l ln="32      ">He plunges madly through the Pleisse, the strength at his command
</l><l ln="33      ">Is perfectly exhausted ere he feebly gains the land; 
</l><l ln="34      ">Alas! 'tis but to mark the foe thronging the Elster's shore,
</l><l ln="35      ">And leaping swift into its tide, he sinks to rise no more.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="36      ">Farewell, lost Poland's noble son! how meet the day would be
</l><l ln="37      ">Whereon the land which gave thee birth once more was rendered free.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="285">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646828</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>DUTY STRONGER THAN PAIN.

<subhead>1795.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646828</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>DUTY STRONGER THAN PAIN.  1795.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028247</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028247</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>DUTY STRONGER THAN PAIN.  1795.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> good ship <hi r="italic">Rose</hi> with thirteen men and but eight guns is steering
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Along the gay Italian coast, in quest of privateering,
</l><l ln="3        ">When at the breaking of the day before upon the lee
</l><l ln="4        ">What gallantly her crew have sought at last they gladly see.
</l><l ln="5        ">Three armed feluccas are in view, and soon begins the fight,
</l><l ln="6        ">And the ruthless <hi r="italic">Rose</hi> her broadside fires with overwhelming might,
</l><l ln="7        ">For valiantly her noble crew with vigour ply each gun,
</l><l ln="8        ">When suddenly a shot lays low of their small number, one; 
</l><pb n="293">
<l ln="9        ">His foot is crushed, and eager hands would bear him from the deck,
</l><l ln="10      ">But with a voice which falters not he seeks their care to check&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;I shall not leave you, comrades bold,&rdquo; heroically he cries,
</l><l ln="12      ">&ldquo;For I can use a musket still, although I cannot rise; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Then to your posts, nor think of me, our numbers are too few
</l><l ln="14      ">To spare even one, and readily my duty I can do.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="15      ">The battle rages bravely on, and soon 'tis clear to see
</l><l ln="16      ">That gallantly our doughty men have gained the victory&mdash; 
</l><l ln="17      ">And was it aught of wonder that so it should be when
</l><l ln="18      ">Such fearless hearts impelled the hands of our staunch sailors then?
</l><l ln="19      ">God grant that if once more our tars should fight upon the wave,
</l><l ln="20      ">They may be then as free from fear, as generous, and as brave.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="294">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646829</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SEA ENCOUNTER.

<subhead>1758.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646829</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SEA ENCOUNTER.  1758.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028248</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028248</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SEA ENCOUNTER.  1758.</mainhead><volhead>Old Year Leaves: Being Old Verses Revised: By H. T. Mackenzie Bell ... New Edition (1886)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1886</attpubn1><attpubn2>1886</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> gallant ships <hi r="italic">Southampton</hi> and <hi r="italic">Melampe</hi> brave the gale
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In noble guise, as mutually they forth together sail,
</l><l ln="3        ">With massive mast bent to the blast, and canvas full and free,
</l><l ln="4        ">A stirring sight they seem&mdash;befitting well an English sea&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">With many blithesome hearts on board as heedless and as gay
</l><l ln="6        ">As if Life were merely made for mirth&mdash;nought save a holiday.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="7        ">And now, behold, off Yarmouth roads there burst upon their sight
</l><l ln="8        ">Two Gallic frigates in full sail, which they resolve to fight.
</l><pb n="295">
<l ln="9        ">The <hi r="italic">Melampe</hi> is the swifter barque, and fastest gains the foe,
</l><l ln="10      ">Who to return her fusillade with interest are not slow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">So ere the crew of the <hi r="italic">Southampton</hi> reach the strife, they learn
</l><l ln="12      ">In a distressed disabled state she has been forced astern; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Then, like a dastard, one French ship in dread doth steer away,
</l><l ln="14      ">But madly the <hi r="italic">Southampton's</hi> guns upon the other play
</l><l ln="15      ">Like monsters of destruction, who cannot brook delay.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="16      ">The French engage with reckless rage&mdash;the fight grows hour by hour,
</l><l ln="17      ">Each vessel's crew, with purpose true, striving with passion's power; 
</l><l ln="18      ">Each seaman seeking still to keep the honour of his nation
</l><l ln="19      ">By carrying mid the hostile ranks dire woe and desolation; 
</l><pb n="296">
<l ln="20      ">And the hissing roar of rushing shell and the blinding red&hyphen;hot hail,
</l><l ln="21      ">All demonstrate what dreadful force they now use to prevail.
</l><l ln="22      ">Hour after hour thus passes swift in unremitting strife,
</l><l ln="23      ">And of the French full eighty men have yielded up their life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">But as the sixth hour draweth on they suddenly give way,
</l><l ln="25      ">Their falling flag proclaiming wide that they have lost the day.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="26      ">We trust such times as these shall ne'er again mar Britain's story,
</l><l ln="27      ">Yet bravery, howe'er displayed, shall aye retain its glory.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

</div1></div0>
