<pb n="1">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646833</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;POESY LIVES IN EVERYTHING.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646833</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;POESY LIVES IN EVERYTHING.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028250</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028250</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;POESY LIVES IN EVERYTHING.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Poesy lives in everything,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Though only poets find
</l><l ln="3        ">Her hidden treasures, or can bring
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;These treasures to mankind.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">She lives with Nature evermore
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Alike on land and sea; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Where breakers roar far, far from shore,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And on the quiet lea;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Where yonder mountain's soaring peak
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Scarce fails to touch the sky; 
</l><l ln="11      ">In yonder vale where, fair and sleek,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The drowsy cattle lie;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">In yonder cot where seldom come
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;The cares of human strife; 
</l><l ln="15      ">In yonder city never dumb
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;With sounds of human life;</l></stanza>

<pb n="2">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Where yonder babbling brooklets haste,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Begirt with mossy strands; 
</l><l ln="19      ">And even where Greed makes many a waste
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In many lovely lands;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">'Mid friends and kindred everywhere; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;In talks with those we love; 
</l><l ln="23      ">And when, with humble heart, we dare
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;To think of things above;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">A part of every impulse here,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Of every joy and pain; 
</l><l ln="27      ">She hallows all, is ever near,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;To calm, to cheer again.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Yes; Poesy's white hands can mould
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;From much of earth, pure leaven; 
</l><l ln="31      ">And who shall say she will not hold
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;A noble place in Heaven!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646834</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>DESPONDENCY: A MOOD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646834</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>DESPONDENCY: A MOOD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028251</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028251</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>DESPONDENCY: A MOOD.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Often a word, a look, a jest,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Piercing the veil its depths concealing,
</l><l ln="3        ">Awakens joy within my breast
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;I ne'er again had dreamed of feeling.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">To hear the prattle of a child
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Amid the summer daisies playing,
</l><l ln="7        ">To gaze on Nature, stern and wild,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Or when her summer winds are straying;</l></stanza>

<pb n="3">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">To hear the tones of some loved air
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Familiar in Life's morn of gladness,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Small things, yet they dispel my care,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Small things, yet how they heal my sadness!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">But, ah, their influence dies away,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Leaving life drear as when it found me,
</l><l ln="15      ">Nay, yet more drear, for that one ray
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Of sunshine it has shed around me.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646835</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;NO SUN EVER ROSE WITHOUT SETTING.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646835</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;NO SUN EVER ROSE WITHOUT SETTING.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028252</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028252</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;NO SUN EVER ROSE WITHOUT SETTING.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">No sun ever rose without setting,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;For surely there cometh the night; 
</l><l ln="3        ">No night ever stayed, but begetting
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The dawn, it departed in light.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">No joy ever came without bringing
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;A shadow to tell us of grief; 
</l><l ln="7        ">To sorrow there ever is clinging
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;A something to render relief.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">And therefore in life there remaineth
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;For joy and for sorrow a place,
</l><l ln="11      ">And naught on the earth but containeth
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;A power its effects to efface.</l></stanza>

<pb n="4">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Gird on then your armour of gladness
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To combat despairing with scorn,
</l><l ln="15      ">And live through your night&hyphen;time of sadness
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;In hope of the glories of morn.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646836</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG OF EARLY SUMMER.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646836</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG OF EARLY SUMMER.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028253</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028253</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG OF EARLY SUMMER.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sweet is the time when tender leaves
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Burst forth in all their perfect grace,
</l><l ln="3        ">When swallows twitter from the eaves,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And Spring to Summer yields her place;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">When red and white the chestnut shows,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When fragrance from the hawthorn spreads,
</l><l ln="7        ">When fair the blue wistaria blows,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And iris lilies lift their heads.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet soon the chestnut petals fade,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Wistaria blooms droop one by one,
</l><l ln="11      ">Soon sigh the leaves for welcome shade,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Then fall with dews at set of sun.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Not so the spring&hyphen;time of the heart,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;<hi r="italic">That</hi> knows nor change nor swift decay,
</l><l ln="15      ">The spring&hyphen;time of our nobler part
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Shall never fade or pass away.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="5">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646837</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE HEART'S SUMMER.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646837</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE HEART'S SUMMER.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028254</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028254</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE HEART'S SUMMER.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sweet is the noon of a summer day
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When, through the woodlands coming,
</l><l ln="3        ">The village sounds seem far away
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And drowsy bees are humming.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Sweet are the hours of a summer night
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When kindly dews are falling,
</l><l ln="7        ">And thoughts that come with the fading light
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Are soothing, or enthralling.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Sweet are the tones of a friendly voice
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;When all seems gone but sorrow,
</l><l ln="11      ">Bidding the heart once more rejoice,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;For peace may come to&hyphen;morrow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Sweet is the sound of the world's applause
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;When fame at last hath found us,
</l><l ln="15      ">And (wage for toil in a righteous cause)
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Flings victory's wreath around us.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">But sweeter far is a heart at rest,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;A heart unsoured by sadness&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Which throbs within a blissful breast
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;With a God&hyphen;imparted gladness.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646838</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN ELLINGTON COPSE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646838</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN ELLINGTON COPSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028255</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028255</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN ELLINGTON COPSE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">How lovely are these woodland ways
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Clad in their summer dress,
</l><l ln="3        ">Where come not din and smoke to mar
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Their evening loveliness;</l></stanza>

<pb n="6">

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Where wild&hyphen;rose and convolvulus
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Are wov'n in every hedge,
</l><l ln="7        ">And buttercups and foxgloves glow
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;By this clear brooklet's edge;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Where breezes waft their balmiest scents
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Adown the silent wood,
</l><l ln="11      ">And scarce a songster sings to break
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The hush of solitude;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Where shadows creep across my path
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And softly dies the day&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">And Summer's beauty holds the world
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Within her gracious sway.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">This evening every wild&hyphen;flower here
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;More deeply stirs my heart
</l><l ln="19      ">Than alien flowers or prodigies
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Of man's botanic art;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">This sweet&hyphen;brier bough, that meekly sends
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Its perfume on the air,
</l><l ln="23      ">I would not give for any flower
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;The gardener deems most fair;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">I leave the rich their bowers of art
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Wreathed with the rarest flowers,
</l><l ln="27      ">Enough for me these woodland ways
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;In Summer's twilight hours.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="7">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646839</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE LAME BOY IN THE WOODS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646839</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE LAME BOY IN THE WOODS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028256</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028256</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE LAME BOY IN THE WOODS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Each season hath its sadness, but for me
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Summer hath most of all. I know not why,
</l><l ln="3        ">But though its sylvan beauty soothes my soul
</l><l ln="4        ">And brings sweet reveries&mdash;though the happy birds,
</l><l ln="5        ">Discoursing music, stir my mind with dreams,
</l><l ln="6        ">With melodies, with thoughts of deep delight; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Yet still there lurks within the Summer's heart
</l><l ln="8        ">Or in mine own, a pain&mdash;a deep, wild pain&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">Which, even amid still Autumn's ravages
</l><l ln="10      ">I never feel, nor yet in Winter's storms.
</l><l ln="11      ">Is it, I ask, that Summer's voiceless spell&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">Her loveliness of copse and lea and flower
</l><l ln="13      ">Is all too soon dissolved&mdash;that blossoms fade
</l><l ln="14      ">When Summer's glory dies?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">                                      Ah, no; ah, no!
</l><l ln="16      ">It is that Summer's mocking gladness lends
</l><l ln="17      ">To loss a sharper sting when I recall
</l><l ln="18      ">The joy of buoyant health and tireless limbs
</l><l ln="19      ">Which others feel&mdash;alas! through all my life
</l><l ln="20      ">A joy that knows not me.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646840</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE UNFULFILLED IDEAL.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646840</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE UNFULFILLED IDEAL.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028257</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028257</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE UNFULFILLED IDEAL.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">When youthful Summer decks the sward
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;With flowers on plain and hill,
</l><l ln="3        ">And Nature wins her meet reward
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;For working Winter's will,
</l><l ln="5        ">Even then Life's music lacks a chord:
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Something wanted still!</l></stanza>

<pb n="8">

<stanza><l ln="7        ">In Autumn, when each searing leaf
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;With gentle sorrow fraught,
</l><l ln="9        ">And every garnered golden sheaf
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Yield fruit for mingled thought:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">We feel a void&mdash;there comes a grief&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Something vaguely sought!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">When Winter lays an icy hand
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Where Spring had kissed the ground,
</l><l ln="15      ">And stiff and stark is all the land
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Where Summer erst was crowned:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="17      ">We feel but do not understand:
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Something still unfound!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">When Spring returns with radiant grace
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;To fill the earth with song,
</l><l ln="21      ">And gladness smiles in every place,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And love and life are strong,
</l><l ln="23      ">Still comes the want we cannot trace:
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Something wanted long!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646841</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;THE AUTUMN IS DYING.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646841</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;THE AUTUMN IS DYING.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028258</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028258</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;THE AUTUMN IS DYING.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">The autumn is dying,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And leaves that are still,
</l><l ln="3        ">Grief's tokens, are lying
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;On plain and on hill; 
</l><l ln="5        ">My garden of pleasure
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Lies withered and bare,
</l><l ln="7        ">Oh, the pitiless measure
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Of ruin wrought there!</l></stanza>

<pb n="9">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">In a hedgerow wind&hyphen;shaken
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;To wildest unrest,
</l><l ln="11      ">Forlorn and forsaken
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;I see a bird's nest,
</l><l ln="13      ">Its soft down decaying,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Its fledglings all flown,
</l><l ln="15      ">Naught save the shell staying
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Deserted and lone.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Then the thought rises, cleaving
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;The depths of my mind,
</l><l ln="19      ">Soon we too shall be leaving
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Our loved homes behind,
</l><l ln="21      ">Soon the grave will enclose us&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Life's pilgrimage o'er&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&ldquo;And the place that now knows us
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Shall know us no more.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646842</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ASPIRATIONS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646842</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ASPIRATIONS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028259</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028259</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ASPIRATIONS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">O for the poet's voice and song&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Piercing, yet sweet and clear,
</l><l ln="3        ">Rich as the cushat's note, yet strong
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To reach the great world's ear!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">O for the visions that abide
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Within the poet's mind,
</l><l ln="7        ">The thoughts which through his bosom glide
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Leaving strange joy behind!</l></stanza>

<pb n="10">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">O for the fruit&mdash;immortal fruit
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Soiled by no earthly leav'n,
</l><l ln="11      ">Not fame alone, nor vain repute,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;But something caught from heav'n&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Assurance that my strain has cheered
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;One soul, if only one,
</l><l ln="15      ">And shed on the dark path it feared
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;A passing glimpse of sun!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646843</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>DECEMBER DAISIES AND DECEMBER DAYS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646843</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>DECEMBER DAISIES AND DECEMBER DAYS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028260</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028260</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>DECEMBER DAISIES AND DECEMBER DAYS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ah, how the sight of these untimely flowers
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Brings dear remembrances of summer hours,
</l><l ln="3        ">When the full heart in buoyant mood was filled
</l><l ln="4        ">With happiness&mdash;when the swift moments thrilled
</l><l ln="5        ">The soul with subtle thoughts no words express.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="6        ">Kind halcyon moments! How they soothe and bless
</l><l ln="7        ">And beautify my sordid life. And here,
</l><l ln="8        ">When this December day is stir&hyphen;less, clear
</l><l ln="9        ">At its brief twilight&mdash;when there shines afar
</l><l ln="10      ">From out a cloudless heav'n yon evening star&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">When southern breezes blow, nor storm nor rain
</l><l ln="12      ">Disturb,&mdash;I dream 'tis summer come again.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="11">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646844</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>SOLITUDE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646844</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>SOLITUDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028261</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028261</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SOLITUDE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;&indent;Amid the throng
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Which, restless, moves along
</l><l ln="3        ">With hurrying footsteps o'er the earth
</l><l ln="4        ">But few their noblest thoughts have known,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Seldom save when alone
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;Come thoughts of worth.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">&indent;&indent;It needs the balm
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Of soul&hyphen;restoring calm
</l><l ln="9        ">To purge the mind of Life's alloy; 
</l><l ln="10      ">Thus yielding back Man's highest power,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;His bless&egrave;d pristine dower
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;Of peace and joy.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;&indent;And thus do men
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;With new and eager ken
</l><l ln="15      ">Taste those rich joys that only live
</l><l ln="16      ">In solitude&mdash;joys which uplift
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Their souls to truth&mdash;best gift
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;That Life can give.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646845</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WIND FANCIES.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646845</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WIND FANCIES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028262</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028262</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WIND FANCIES.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Murmuring winds vague fancies carry
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To the heart while sweeping by,
</l><l ln="3        ">And the fancies often tarry
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Though the winds that brought them die.</l></stanza>

<pb n="12">

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Now the fancies are of gladness,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Life itself seems one delight; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Now the fancies are of sadness,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Life itself seems dark as night.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

<div1>
<comhd1><idref>Z100646846</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

POEMS OF CONSOLATION
AND OF RELIGION. <attbytes>43Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100646846</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>

<pb n="13">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646847</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>JOY AND SORROW.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646847</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>JOY AND SORROW.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028263</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028263</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JOY AND SORROW.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph>&lsquo;<hi r="italic">They soon forgat His works</hi>.&rdquo;<signed>&mdash;<hi r="smcap">Psalm</hi> cvi. v. 13.</signed></epigraph>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">As</hi> raindrops falling on a lake
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Leave scarce a ripple's trace behind,
</l><l ln="3        ">Our blessings for an instant break
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The torpor of the thankless mind.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Like letters graven on the steel,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Our trials scourge us, and remain; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And, cleaving to us, make us feel
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The lasting anguish of their pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">And in our strait we come to Thee,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;We bring Thee then our earnest prayer:
</l><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;Grant, Lord,&rdquo; we cry, &ldquo;that we may be
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;More mindful of Thy loving care.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">We pray that all our troubles here
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;May help to give the needed strength
</l><l ln="15      ">To keep our watch&hyphen;fires burning clear
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Till Life's last halt we reach at length.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="14">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646848</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>BY&hyphen;AND&hyphen;BY.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646848</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BY&hyphen;AND&hyphen;BY.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028264</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028264</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BY&hyphen;AND&hyphen;BY.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ofttimes our path seems smooth, and bright as May,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And full of joyance still from day to day; 
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Yet by&hyphen;and&hyphen;by
</l><l ln="4        ">Comes Grief to cast chill shadows on the way.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Soon fair Content, our sun, is lost to sight; 
</l><l ln="6        ">Now shrouded is the track in fearsome night; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Yet by&hyphen;and&hyphen;by
</l><l ln="8        ">Kind Time will bring once more the welcome light.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ever we journey on; through weal, through woe; 
</l><l ln="10      ">Though rough the path even there the wild&hyphen;flowers grow,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;And by&hyphen;and&hyphen;by
</l><l ln="12      ">Gleam God's high bastions, afar, aglow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646849</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG OF COMFORT.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646849</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG OF COMFORT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028265</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028265</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG OF COMFORT.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Not always have we sorrow, there are seasons
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When buoyant joy dispels all dreams of ruth&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Times when our thoughts of sorrow seem but treasons
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;&indent;To king&hyphen;like Truth.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Not always are we vext by cares and troubles,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Often the griefs of life appear no more&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Vanished, as on a lake the rain&hyphen;drop bubbles,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;When showers are o'er.</l></stanza>

<pb n="15">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Not always feel we that our hopes are blighted; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;A glad fruition will they often gain,
</l><l ln="11      ">When we perceive the good are aye requited
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;Who conquer pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Not always should we grieve, each tribulation
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Is sent to purify&mdash;to raise the soul,
</l><l ln="15      ">To fit it for its glorious destination&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;&indent;A heavenly goal.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646850</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>BORROWED LIGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646850</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BORROWED LIGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028266</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028266</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BORROWED LIGHT.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Tis night; and darkness as a pall
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Enwraps the sable scene,
</l><l ln="3        ">Nor doth one glimmering ray recall
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Where sunshine late hath been.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Until the moon 'neath yonder cloud
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Shall bring a borrowed light,
</l><l ln="7        ">And, piercing through the landscape's shroud,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Dispel the gloom of night.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">So 'tis in life; 'mid deepest woe,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Oft drawing nigh despair,
</l><l ln="11      ">God&hyphen;borrowed beams alone still show
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;That joy abideth there.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="16">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646851</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE TRUEST TREASURE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646851</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE TRUEST TREASURE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028267</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028267</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE TRUEST TREASURE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Life may bring us bitter sorrow
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When our hearts refuse submission,
</l><l ln="3        ">When we long for a to&hyphen;morrow
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Bringing balm as Hope's fruition.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Love may bring us bitter sadness
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When we know our love can never
</l><l ln="7        ">Give anew the sense of gladness
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;That we thought it would for ever.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Joy may bring us bitter trouble:
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Faith may die in voiceless anguish; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Hope may seem an empty bubble
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;When bereft of hope we languish.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Worldly peace may bring us only,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;In our heart of hearts, disquiet; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Leaving us&mdash;will leave us lonely
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Battling in the world's rude riot.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Trust in man may bring delusion; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Often, often hath it perished,
</l><l ln="19      ">And we feel, in dim confusion,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;'Twas a phantom that we cherished.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Trust in God in fullest measure
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Holds of earthly change no leaven,
</l><l ln="23      ">And it is the truest treasure,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For it makes of earth a heaven.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="17">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646852</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A MEMORY AND A PRESENCE.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646852</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A MEMORY AND A PRESENCE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028268</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028268</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A MEMORY AND A PRESENCE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">When clasping in mine own the hand
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of him I loved the best,
</l><l ln="3        ">Whose converse cheered, as sight of land
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Cheers mariners distressed,
</l><l ln="5        ">How once I loved the darkening hour
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of Summer's happy day,
</l><l ln="7        ">As gently from each leaf and flower
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The daylight passed away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">For he had learnt to bear his part
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;In Earth's unending strife,
</l><l ln="11      ">To labour with unflinching heart
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Amid the ills of life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">To feel adversity and pain,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Hopes blighted, bitter wrong,
</l><l ln="15      ">And yet, ere long, to find again
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;God's peace which makes men strong.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">So would he talk of bygone years
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In that hush'd eventide,
</l><l ln="19      ">Of former hopes, delights, and fears,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Of early friends who died,
</l><l ln="21      ">And wisely would my future trace,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Then leaving things of Time,
</l><l ln="23      ">In raptured tones, with upturned face,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Would speak of themes sublime.</l></stanza>

<pb n="18">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">He had that wordless eloquence,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;That strange, that wondrous power,
</l><l ln="27      ">Which sways the soul with force intense
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;In calm of such an hour; 
</l><l ln="29      ">And walking where the shadows steal
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Across the garden here,
</l><l ln="31      ">Alone with memory still I feel
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;His spirit ever near.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646853</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BALANCE OF LIFE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646853</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BALANCE OF LIFE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028269</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028269</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BALANCE OF LIFE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Tis false to say the world, though sad,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Hath no redeeming feature,
</l><l ln="3        ">'Tis false to say the world, though glad,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Can hold no hopeless creature.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">The darkest life has oft a ray
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of sunshine on the morrow,
</l><l ln="7        ">The brightest life has many a day
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Whose hours are filled with sorrow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">No life with ceaseless grief is fraught,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;None with all bliss and beauty,
</l><l ln="11      ">By varied teaching are we taught
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The way to walk in duty.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">If happy be our earthly lot,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And free from Sorrow's burden,
</l><l ln="15      ">Greater the need to linger not;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Our work shall have its guerdon:</l></stanza>

<pb n="19">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Yet richer guerdon comes to those
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Whom heav'n hath not exempted
</l><l ln="19      ">From pain, who quell the self&hyphen;same foes
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Although more sorely tempted.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Each grief that sweeps across the heart,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;If sinless be its sadness,
</l><l ln="23      ">In Life's long lesson bears a part
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And yields us future gladness.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646854</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MIRACLES.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646854</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MIRACLES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028270</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028270</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MIRACLES.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">Christ's wondrous miracles were signs indeed
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of wondrous power; yet every miracle
</l><l ln="3        ">Of His had moral purpose, and was wrought
</l><l ln="4        ">To show this moral purpose: and perchance
</l><l ln="5        ">Thus is it that no longer we possess
</l><l ln="6        ">The power to do such deeds. Had you or I
</l><l ln="7        ">Such gifts, we still should heal unceasingly,
</l><l ln="8        ">Nor judge of the effects were cures but made.
</l><l ln="9        ">Where then would be God's discipline of pain?
</l><l ln="10      ">Where His just government of all His world?
</l><l ln="11      ">Where then would be His discipline of sorrow?</l></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646855</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO CHRISTINA ROSSETTI.

<subhead r="italic">Great as a Poet, greater as a Woman.

(Died December 29th, 1894.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646855</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO CHRISTINA ROSSETTI.  Great as a Poet, greater as a Woman.  (Died December 29th, 1894.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028271</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028271</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO CHRISTINA ROSSETTI.  Great as a Poet, greater as a Woman.  (Died December 29th, 1894.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">I marvel not that God hath called away
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Thy peerless soul to where His saints abide; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Rather I praise Him that He bade thee stay
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;On earth so long&mdash;to be a heavenward guide.</l></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="20">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646856</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GOD'S PEACE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646856</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GOD'S PEACE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028272</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028272</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GOD'S PEACE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph>&ldquo;<hi r="italic">The peace of God which passeth all understanding</hi>.&rdquo; 
<signed>&mdash;<hi r="smcap">Phil</hi>. iv. 7.</signed></epigraph>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> oft amid the griefs of life&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Perplexed, misjudged, distressed&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">O God, I waver in the strife,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And long and cry for rest.
</l><l ln="5        ">How oft I feel&mdash;so great my need,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;My courage so outworn&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">As though my griefs were now indeed
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Greater than could be borne.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet oft will come in times like these&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Come like a gracious balm&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">A sense of peace, of joy, of ease,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;A sense of heaven's own calm.
</l><l ln="13      ">Ah! then my heart would fain express
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;What I have felt before&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">'Tis not I feel my griefs are less&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;I feel Thy love is more.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">And some are here, O God, to&hyphen;day,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Here with their voiceless grief,
</l><l ln="19      ">O give the aid for which they pray,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;O give such sweet relief,
</l><l ln="21      ">O give Thy peace, Thy calm, Thy joys,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Here as they humbly bow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Such gifts nor Time nor Change destroys,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Give them, and give them <hi r="italic">now</hi>.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="21">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646857</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HOLY QUIETUDE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646857</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOLY QUIETUDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028273</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028273</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HOLY QUIETUDE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Spirit of holy quietude,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;For thee my soul is sighing&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">For thee in many a mournful mood
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;My soul is blindly crying&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">But still a voice comes softly clear,
</l><l ln="6        ">&ldquo;That spirit seldom cometh here.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Spirit of holy quietude,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;While, weary, I am breasting
</l><l ln="9        ">Life's waves, bring with thee all things good&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Deep peace, and joy, and resting:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Yet still the voice&mdash;&ldquo;No, never here
</l><l ln="12      ">Doth she thy soul would find appear.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Spirit of holy quietude,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Grant me a single token&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Show me that Life's long conflict rude
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;By gleams of peace is broken; 
</l><l ln="17      ">But the voice whispers in mine ear,
</l><l ln="18      ">&ldquo;That spirit never dwelleth here.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">Spirit of holy quietude,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Mine earthly course is ending,
</l><l ln="21      ">Now let thy peace within me brood,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Sin's strongest fetters rending; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&ldquo;In heaven,&rdquo; the voice says at my side&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&ldquo;In heaven alone doth she abide.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="22">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646858</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SUNRISE IN EARLY SUMMER.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646858</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUNRISE IN EARLY SUMMER.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028274</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028274</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SUNRISE IN EARLY SUMMER.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><caption>I</caption>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">Now</hi> lagging black&hyphen;browed Night at last is gone,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And fair and happy Dawn at length is here.
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;How sweet the sights which now I look upon&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The sights of summer beauty growing clear!
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;The meadows yonder and the lawn appear
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Glittering with dewdrops&mdash;dewdrops silvery, white,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Touched by the sun's first beams; while far and near
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Each bird, each flower awakes, and hails the sight
</l><l ln="9        ">Of coming morn: to them like me it brings delight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption>II</caption>

<l ln="10      ">&indent;To eastward lies a mass of sable cloud
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Made glorious by the rising sun, who flings
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;His rays athwart its depths. I hear the loud
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Yet mellow thrush's note&mdash;a blackbird sings
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;With sudden burst of song&mdash;a lark up&hyphen;springs
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;From that wide field of wheat; so more and more
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Sounds Nature's orchestra of myriad strings.
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;I watch the apple&hyphen;bloom, while May&hyphen;buds pour
</l><l ln="18      ">On all the gentle air their matchless, fragrant store.</l></stanza>

<pb n="23">

<stanza><caption>III</caption>

<l ln="19      ">&indent;O, who at sunrise could be aught but glad&mdash; 
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Sunrise, the prototype of perfect day,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;When we shall wake to bliss, nor weak nor sad,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And, feeling swiftly the seraphic ray
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;From God's effulgence, cast the fears away
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Which still cleave to us, and with rapturous soul
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Know that black Trouble can no longer stay
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;In His blest presence&mdash;know the precious goal
</l><l ln="27      ">Where all Earth's grievous wounds are made for ever whole.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646859</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;LORD, TEACH US TO PRAY.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646859</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;LORD, TEACH US TO PRAY.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028275</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028275</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;LORD, TEACH US TO PRAY.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<signed><hi r="smcap">Luke</hi> xi. I.</signed>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">A dark enigma is our life
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Without Thy guiding ray; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Then calm, O Christ, its sordid strife
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;By teaching us to pray.
</l><l ln="5        ">Prayer is Heaven's torch when doubts and fears
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;With darkness cloud our way,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Its holy radiance guides and cheers,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;What peace it brings to pray!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Oft lies our path through pain and woe
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;While in Earth's night we dwell,
</l><l ln="11      ">Yet prayer is still a light to show
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;That aye Thou leadest well; 
</l><pb n="24">
<l ln="13      ">So when Life's mysteries distress,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And Sorrow bars our way,
</l><l ln="15      ">We plead that Thou wouldst make it less
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;By teaching us to pray.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646860</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A RALLYING SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646860</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A RALLYING SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028276</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028276</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A RALLYING SONG.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sometimes trustful, often fearful,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In this world of shifting wrong; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Sometimes joyful, often tearful,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Still be this our rallying song&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;Aye, in sadness
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;&indent;And in gladness,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Nobly act, for God is strong.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="8        ">When, oppressed by deep soul&hyphen;sorrow,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Life beneath the darkest skies
</l><l ln="10      ">Seems so drear that no to&hyphen;morrow
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Holds a threat of worse surprise&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;In such sadness
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;&indent;As in gladness
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Nobly act, for God is wise.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="15      ">When our souls are tried, and tempted
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Some ignoble end to buy,
</l><l ln="17      ">From the coward's bonds exempted,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Let us resolutely cry&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;&indent;Evil sow not,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;That it grow not,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;Nobly act, for God is nigh.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="25">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646861</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MORNING THOUGHTS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646861</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MORNING THOUGHTS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028277</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028277</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MORNING THOUGHTS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sweet&hyphen;voiced songsters softly singing
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Tell me of a day begun,
</l><l ln="3        ">Its appointed portion bringing
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of the duty to be done.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Last day's deeds are gone for ever,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Seems it not most passing strange
</l><l ln="7        ">Their results remain, and never
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Can be touched by time or change?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Like a child, his pebble throwing
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;From the streamlet's sedgy marge,
</l><l ln="11      ">Marking not the ripples growing
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Though they one by one enlarge&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">So, with influence still increasing,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Widening o'er Life's mystic sea,
</l><l ln="15      ">Man deals out his actions,&mdash;ceasing
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Only with Eternity.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Many yesterday, unthinking,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Chose the road which leads to night,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">While a few, with souls unshrinking,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Chose the pathway of the light.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Thus I muse with deep emotion
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Whilst the moments melt away&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Muse upon the boundless ocean
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Of the issues of to&hyphen;day.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="26">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646862</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON A PRESENT CRISIS IN THE CHURCH OF ENGLAND.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646862</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON A PRESENT CRISIS IN THE CHURCH OF ENGLAND.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028278</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028278</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON A PRESENT CRISIS IN THE CHURCH OF ENGLAND.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Who would have deemed the days would come
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;When Superstition's blighting force
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;In this our land would take its course
</l><l ln="4        ">Unchecked, condoned, no longer dumb?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">This land where many a Smithfield fire
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Blazed three short centuries ago,
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;And where &ldquo;the Babylonian woe&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Milton denounced with thunderous lyre.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Three centuries ago our race
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Saw God&hyphen;like Truth, and loved her well; 
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;No visitant, she came to dwell
</l><l ln="12      ">With us; and England took her place</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">First of the nations; glorious youth
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Her dower, and on her queenly brow
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;God's seal of peace. God grant her now
</l><l ln="16      ">Once more a sight of God&hyphen;like Truth.</l></stanza>

<signed r="italic">London, February 26th, 1899.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646863</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HER BOY JUST DEAD.

<subhead r="italic">(A Mother Speaks.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646863</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HER BOY JUST DEAD.  (A Mother Speaks.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028279</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028279</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HER BOY JUST DEAD.  (A Mother Speaks.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">My darling dead! Is all the long endeavour
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To vanquish Death in vain? These wistful eyes,
</l><l ln="3        ">So Truth&hyphen;illumed and loving, will they never
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Check by a look again my futile sighs?</l></stanza>

<pb n="27">

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And shall I weep&mdash;although for him the gladness
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of this world's many pleasures now is o'er,
</l><l ln="7        ">And I am left with this my load of sadness,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Which here on earth is mine for evermore?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">A cripple's lot were his, had he remaining,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Here ta'en his part where grief and care are rife&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Little of sinless happiness obtaining,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Feeling all miseries of earthly life.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">To shorten that hard period of probation
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Given to such as he so often here&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">To raise him soon to an immortal station
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Where comes no thoughtless word, no taunt, no jeer&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">The Master, in His mercy, gently made him
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Fitter among His ransomed ones to be&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">And day by day more perfectly arrayed him
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;In His own peerless robe of purity.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Then shall I cherish an abiding sorrow
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;For him whom God in goodness calls away?
</l><l ln="23      ">Nay, rather let me muse on that blest morrow
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Which joins in bliss our severed souls for aye.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="28">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646864</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>JOHN CLIFFORD: <hi r="smcap">God's Soldier</hi>.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646864</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>JOHN CLIFFORD: God's Soldier.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028280</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028280</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JOHN CLIFFORD: God's Soldier.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016946">[In October, 1908, Fohn Clifford completed his fifty
Years' Ministry to One Congregation.]</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Born of the people, with a scorn of wrong
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Bequeathed from Puritans&mdash;persistent, strong,
</l><l ln="3        ">Eager to serve God's folk, while more and more
</l><l ln="4        ">In this our London, vast, and grim, and hoar,
</l><l ln="5        ">You skilled yourself in academic lore.
</l><l ln="6        ">Noble and selfless was each thought; each aim
</l><l ln="7        ">Pure as a snow&hyphen;flake, pure as is the flame
</l><l ln="8        ">From Truth's undying torch that burns to show
</l><l ln="9        ">Ever an upward path, through weal, through woe.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="10      ">Often you walked through many a London street&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Saw many a man who paused with way&hyphen;worn feet&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">And saw the wrinkled furrows on his brow
</l><l ln="13      ">Proclaim that he was well&hyphen;nigh ag&egrave;d now&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">And this, before stern Time, with ruthless sway,
</l><l ln="15      ">Touching, had turned his sunny locks to grey.
</l><l ln="16      ">You saw how trembling was his nerveless hand,
</l><l ln="17      ">His fingers scarcely under due command; 
</l><l ln="18      ">You saw how devious was his tottering tread,
</l><l ln="19      ">How bent, though not with weight of years, his head; 
</l><l ln="20      ">You saw how his whole face, his gait, his air
</l><l ln="21      ">Showed sad, though all too common, signs of care.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="29">

<pdiv><l ln="22      ">Often you walked through many a London street&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Saw many a girl who paused with way&hyphen;worn feet,
</l><l ln="24      ">And dreamt of her a happy rose&hyphen;lipped child
</l><l ln="25      ">In some far country home where dear ones smiled.
</l><l ln="26      ">Haply you saw her shaping daisy&hyphen;chains
</l><l ln="27      ">While little sisters help, and for their pains,
</l><l ln="28      ">Receiving, on the sward, as payment meet,
</l><l ln="29      ">The pretty chaplet from her, when complete.
</l><l ln="30      ">And as you gazed upon her saddened face,
</l><l ln="31      ">Where sin, or want, or sorrow you could trace; 
</l><l ln="32      ">Alas, alas, how mournful in their birth,
</l><l ln="33      ">Rose dimly, thoughts of these dead days of mirth.
</l><l ln="34      ">Dreams such as these, amid the sounds that jar
</l><l ln="35      ">Our civic music, made you what you are&mdash; 
</l><l ln="36      ">The matchless leader who, by pen or word,
</l><l ln="37      ">Against unnumbered odds at last has stirred
</l><l ln="38      ">Our civic Conscience to take up her task
</l><l ln="39      ">Towards her sons and daughters, and to ask
</l><l ln="40      ">For those who toil, more light, more joy, more air,
</l><l ln="41      ">And homes more clean and spacious everywhere.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="42      ">'Tis only when a lake is calm and clear
</l><l ln="43      ">It well reflects the landscape that is near,
</l><l ln="44      ">And thus men's quiet deeds from day to day
</l><l ln="45      ">With best fidelity their minds display; 
</l><l ln="46      ">So when you pass among us, with your look
</l><l ln="47      ">Or hand&hyphen;shake kindly, or your shrewd rebuke,
</l><l ln="48      ">Or when we see you in some homely hour
</l><l ln="49      ">Of talk, we feel the secret of your power.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="30">

<pdiv><l ln="50      ">Great orator in gesture, voice, and word,
</l><l ln="51      ">Whose lofty eloquence none hear unstirred,
</l><l ln="52      ">You roused our people to take earnest heed
</l><l ln="53      ">Unto their children's teaching: there was need.
</l><l ln="54      ">Passing for fifty years &ldquo;from strength to strength&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="55      ">Your power for good increases, till at length
</l><l ln="56      ">On every problem that confronts the State,
</l><l ln="57      ">On all the things which make our nation great,
</l><l ln="58      ">To you we look for counsel, for we share
</l><l ln="59      ">Your heritage of hope, of faith, of prayer.
</l><l ln="60      ">True ever is the music of your life,
</l><l ln="61      ">Your soul safe anchored, though near shoals of strife.
</l><l ln="62      ">Wise thought on such as you uplifts the heart; 
</l><l ln="63      ">Now lie your years before us, like a chart,
</l><l ln="64      ">Thereon is shown a way whereby each one,
</l><l ln="65      ">Though sore the toil, and scorching be Life's sun,
</l><l ln="66      ">Elated, shall receive God's glad &ldquo;Well done.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="67      ">Forward you move with that eternal youth
</l><l ln="68      ">They only know, who drink from wells of Truth,
</l><l ln="69      ">Your warmth enkindles many an arctic soul
</l><l ln="70      ">To more and more self&hyphen;conquest, more control.
</l><l ln="71      ">God's soldier, 'tis your calling still to fight,
</l><l ln="72      ">Till dawns, with Heav'n's own peace, Heav'n's own calm light.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="31">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646865</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A PLEA FOR FAITH.</mainhead> <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646865</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A PLEA FOR FAITH.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028281</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028281</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A PLEA FOR FAITH.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>7Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Life! How mysterious does it seem, how strange
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Its grief, its happiness, its shame, its sin!
</l><l ln="3        ">How hard its changes are! Can we believe
</l><l ln="4        ">In a great God of kindness infinite
</l><l ln="5        ">Who yet can daily leave His hapless world
</l><l ln="6        ">To be&mdash;for so it seems&mdash;the home of pain,
</l><l ln="7        ">Pain often useless, often showered on those
</l><l ln="8        ">Who seem to need it least? Can we believe
</l><l ln="9        ">In Perfect Goodness and Omniscient Power
</l><l ln="10      ">Permitting Evil to possess and spoil
</l><l ln="11      ">His fair dominions, and to bring a curse&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">An ageless and unceasing curse&mdash;upon them?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Alas, to our poor minds our futile years
</l><l ln="14      ">Seem but a clueless maze. When happiness
</l><l ln="15      ">Is ours, a hidden canker&hyphen;worm reveals
</l><l ln="16      ">Its hateful presence, and too soon there comes
</l><l ln="17      ">Something to vex the spirit, or to jar,
</l><l ln="18      ">Something to cloud or check our perfect joy.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="19      ">One man has buoyant health, and feels delight
</l><l ln="20      ">In living merely, yet he finds how hard
</l><l ln="21      ">Is poverty to bear; it oftentimes
</l><l ln="22      ">Hangs round him as a changeless destiny.
</l><l ln="23      ">Too rich is he to rank among the poor,
</l><l ln="24      ">Too poor is he to rank among the rich; 
</l><l ln="25      ">Of neither class, he knows the ills of both.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="26      ">Another man has ample wealth, and friends
</l><l ln="27      ">Who love to do him honour, and to give
</l><l ln="28      ">To him the zest in living which such friends
</l><l ln="29      ">Alone can give. Yet look!&mdash;alas, 'tis clear
</l><pb n="32">
<l ln="30      ">Disease's curse is on him, fell disease
</l><l ln="31      ">For which weak human skill affords no cure
</l><l ln="32      ">And scarce alleviation. He is doomed
</l><l ln="33      ">To pass a joyless life despite the joys
</l><l ln="34      ">Surrounding him.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="35      ">                        Another man we see
</l><l ln="36      ">With riches and with pulse of flawless health.
</l><l ln="37      ">With steadfast, cheerful face he fronts the world,
</l><l ln="38      ">And all seems well; yet could we look within,
</l><l ln="39      ">Some grief we should perceive which saps his life
</l><l ln="40      ">And makes it full of care&mdash;a grief that springs
</l><l ln="41      ">Not from his fault; or oftentimes we see
</l><l ln="42      ">Innocent children suffer for the sake
</l><l ln="43      ">Of guilty parents, or a mother's heart
</l><l ln="44      ">Guileless and pure, that bleeds for some loved son
</l><l ln="45      ">Or daughter who, alas, has gone astray.
</l><l ln="46      ">Not seldom in despondency we feel
</l><l ln="47      ">As though the wrong is victor o'er the right,
</l><l ln="48      ">As though our life were but a flake of foam
</l><l ln="49      ">Cast by some cruel sea on some bleak shore,
</l><l ln="50      ">A moment seen, and then for ever lost.</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="51      ">And yet, if we deny that God exists
</l><l ln="52      ">As perfect in His goodness as His power,
</l><l ln="53      ">If we deny that Death, God's angel, brings
</l><l ln="54      ">To man a nobler life, what do we gain
</l><l ln="55      ">To compensate us for the hopes we lose?
</l><l ln="56      ">For still we must endure the woes of life,
</l><l ln="57      ">Still must we feel the longings which arise
</l><l ln="58      ">For rest and peace amid our daily toil.
</l><l ln="59      ">These we must still endure, and yet perceive
</l><pb n="33">
<l ln="60      ">Beyond the grave no gleam of gathering light,
</l><l ln="61      ">Nought save the gloom of nothingness before us.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="62      ">But if we greet kind Faith, and let her hand
</l><l ln="63      ">Lead us through all our years, though at the last
</l><l ln="64      ">We find that hope of happier life is vain
</l><l ln="65      ">(That 'twere so would not change the argument)
</l><l ln="66      ">Faith's guidance will have given a mighty boon
</l><l ln="67      ">To us, in gladdening all our days on earth.
</l><l ln="68      ">So even if we wholly set aside
</l><l ln="69      ">Faith's fervent pleading with the intellect&mdash; 
</l><l ln="70      ">A pleading ever present, ever strong,
</l><l ln="71      ">'Tis wiser far to guide our minds to view
</l><l ln="72      ">The problem still in some such wise as this,
</l><l ln="73      ">'Tis true amid our earthly life there runs
</l><l ln="74      ">A tangled thread of strange perplexity
</l><l ln="75      ">And much injustice; yet comes by&hyphen;and&hyphen;by
</l><l ln="76      ">A nobler state of being, when that which seems
</l><l ln="77      ">Unjust will be explained or set aright.
</l><l ln="78      ">'Tis best to hold that there exists a God
</l><l ln="79      ">Who made Man's mind with marvellous powers, though He,
</l><l ln="80      ">In His deep wisdom limited the scope
</l><l ln="81      ">Of what He made, wherefore our reason's sphere
</l><l ln="82      ">Of thought is swiftly reached, and so it seems
</l><l ln="83      ">To us so frequently that human life
</l><l ln="84      ">Hath such injustice in its fleeting years; 
</l><l ln="85      ">That He decrees that it is well for us
</l><l ln="86      ">In humble trust to tread &ldquo;The path of sorrow,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="87      ">Perchance as discipline for some high scheme
</l><l ln="88      ">Of joy hereafter, or perchance to show
</l><l ln="89      ">To others how the brave can conquer pain; 
</l><pb n="34">
<l ln="90      ">That Life's dark mysteries do but transcend,
</l><l ln="91      ">Not contradict our reason, and when soon
</l><l ln="92      ">Our earthly life shall close, there dawns a life
</l><l ln="93      ">When He endows us with new gifts of mind.
</l><l ln="94      ">Then chief among the pleasures it can give
</l><l ln="95      ">Will be the thrill of joy when first we feel
</l><l ln="96      ">That now we understand those mysteries
</l><l ln="97      ">Which vexed our souls before&mdash;when first we find
</l><l ln="98      ">That many &ldquo;themes with which we cannot cope&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="99      ">Grow clear, and &ldquo;Earth's worst phrenzies&rdquo; are at length
</l><l ln="100    ">Forgotten in the joy of Hope's fruition.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646866</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO A WORKER AMONG THE POOR.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646866</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO A WORKER AMONG THE POOR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028282</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028282</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO A WORKER AMONG THE POOR.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Courage like yours has still a mighty power
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">To purify the mind from hour to hour,
</l><l ln="3        ">To permeate with thrilling force the soul,
</l><l ln="4        ">To give new confidence, new self&hyphen;control,
</l><l ln="5        ">To make each faulty faculty so clear
</l><l ln="6        ">That, though you plainly see the danger near,
</l><l ln="7        ">You scorn to dread it&mdash;scorn to turn aside,
</l><l ln="8        ">Duty your first, your chief, your only guide.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">The soldier 'mid the scenes of deadly strife
</l><l ln="10      ">Thinks of his country&mdash;thinks not of his life; 
</l><l ln="11      ">And shall we then in these degenerate days
</l><l ln="12      ">Speak of him lightly, cease to give him praise?
</l><l ln="13      ">Yet Glory has for him her ancient charm,
</l><l ln="14      ">Excitement nerves for him his stalwart arm; 
</l><pb n="35">
<l ln="15      ">When bullets whistle in the dread advance,
</l><l ln="16      ">For him there comes the touch of old Romance.
</l><l ln="17      ">War has its use: sometimes it keeps alive
</l><l ln="18      ">Those qualities that make a nation thrive; 
</l><l ln="19      ">In certain minds it checks the love of self; 
</l><l ln="20      ">It teaches self&hyphen;control, and scorn of pelf; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Once and again it seems to make for good,
</l><l ln="22      ">By teaching patriotism and fortitude&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">That love of country flippant scribes deride
</l><l ln="24      ">As but a foible&mdash;but a foolish pride&mdash; 
</l><l ln="25      ">That love of country which a nation's fame
</l><l ln="26      ">Exalts; whose absence brings a nation's shame.
</l><l ln="27      ">Yet War, alas! not seldom seems to be
</l><l ln="28      ">Only a form of licensed butchery&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">One of the ills that from our passions spring&mdash; 
</l><l ln="30      ">The warrior's courage but a puny thing.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="31      ">Yes; yours is truer courage, for it comes
</l><l ln="32      ">Not from the fife's shrill note, nor roll of drums,
</l><l ln="33      ">Not from the maddening energy of pain
</l><l ln="34      ">Where Horror, heedless, stalks among the slain,
</l><l ln="35      ">But from that hidden strength which has its birth
</l><l ln="36      ">In some sublimer sphere beyond this earth.
</l><l ln="37      ">That bravery is not yours which men acclaim; 
</l><l ln="38      ">That bravery is not yours which gives men fame; 
</l><l ln="39      ">Yours is the courage which but few suspect; 
</l><l ln="40      ">Yours is the courage which can bear neglect; 
</l><l ln="41      ">Yours is the courage which can suffer long,
</l><l ln="42      ">The courage of the man whose soul is strong,
</l><l ln="43      ">Who labours on, still doing silent good,
</l><l ln="44      ">Nor stays his hand for Man's ingratitude.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="36">

<pdiv><l ln="45      ">Although you seem to till a thankless soil,
</l><l ln="46      ">Your prayers are never vain, nor vain your toil; 
</l><l ln="47      ">Some fruit you yet may have to cheer your heart,
</l><l ln="48      ">In some new epoch you may bear a part; 
</l><l ln="49      ">But ev'n if now, through your short span of years
</l><l ln="50      ">Your work be weary, and no fruit appears,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="51      ">Though, in humility, you look within,
</l><l ln="52      ">Deeming your failure the result of sin,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="53      ">It is not so; for still our Father knows
</l><l ln="54      ">What each requires&mdash;on each He still bestows
</l><l ln="55      ">The discipline most needed; still He weighs
</l><l ln="56      ">Our work with heavenly scales; our purblind gaze
</l><l ln="57      ">Finds failure often where He knows success.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="58      ">All are His instruments, and so the less
</l><l ln="59      ">His need of one man for the world's great need; 
</l><l ln="60      ">Righteous He is, to all He gives their meed
</l><l ln="61      ">Of praise or blame; yet not like us He scans&mdash; 
</l><l ln="62      ">We see results, by them we make our plans,
</l><l ln="63      ">And trust or trust not men. Men's character
</l><l ln="64      ">He reads with searching glance that cannot err,
</l><l ln="65      ">And thinks not of results, but values still
</l><l ln="66      ">Patience and faith, and will to do His will.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="67      ">So to His best beloved oft gives He trial,
</l><l ln="68      ">As to His Bless&egrave;d Son, of base denial,
</l><l ln="69      ">And haply most will honour near His throne
</l><l ln="70      ">Some humble follower by the world unknown.
</l><l ln="71      ">Blurred is perspective by our earthly view&mdash; 
</l><l ln="72      ">To God perspective aye is clear and true.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="37">

<pdiv><l ln="73      ">Effort like yours ever to do the right
</l><l ln="74      ">Will raise your soul from height to nobler height,
</l><l ln="75      ">And gives at last that guerdon, full, unpriced,
</l><l ln="76      ">The &ldquo;Well done&rdquo; of your life&hyphen;long master, Christ.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

