<pb n="38">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646868</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>I.&mdash;<subhead>IN PRAISE OF SHAKESPEARE.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646868</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>I.&mdash;IN PRAISE OF SHAKESPEARE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028283</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028283</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>I.&mdash;IN PRAISE OF SHAKESPEARE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016947">(Spoken by Mr. William Miles as a prologue to his
Shakespearean recitals.)</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;He was not of an age, but for all time!&rdquo; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Never was nobler poet&hyphen;tribute paid
</l><l ln="3        ">Than this of stalwart Jonson to his friend&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">To him whose deathless crown of love is wov'n
</l><l ln="5        ">By Nature's royal hand of Nature's flowers.
</l><l ln="6        ">As Shakespeare left this earth his Prospero's wand
</l><l ln="7        ">Waved over England; lo! it hath transformed her!
</l><l ln="8        ">Two thousand years of ever&hyphen;changing life
</l><l ln="9        ">Wrought less of change in her than fifteen score
</l><l ln="10      ">Since face to face men met the bard in London.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="11      ">                                                                     All, all is changed!
</l><l ln="12      ">Save love and joy and laughter, ay, and pain
</l><l ln="13      ">And hope and sin and sorrow, yet he speaks</l></pdiv>

<pb n="39">

<pdiv><l ln="14      ">With clarion voice as ever, witnessing
</l><l ln="15      ">For truth and right, for tenderness and faith.
</l><l ln="16      ">Not with the arid tones of some harsh preacher
</l><l ln="17      ">Who scolds the while he teaches, but with art
</l><l ln="18      ">Which pictures right, which pictures sin and shame,
</l><l ln="19      ">And points to truth.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="20      ">                              Here haggard Shylock stands
</l><l ln="21      ">To show the cruel wrong that racial hate
</l><l ln="22      ">Alike brings to the oppressors and oppressed.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="23      ">Cordelia now approaches, tender&hyphen;eyed,
</l><l ln="24      ">Meek, with kind pity for her father, Lear,
</l><l ln="25      ">A king no longer.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="26      ">                          Radiant Juliet comes,
</l><l ln="27      ">Her Romeo has tranced her eye, and lo
</l><l ln="28      ">Her being all is changed. For Love is here&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">Sweet, early Love that makes a girl a woman,
</l><l ln="30      ">And makes a youth a man. Sorrow and pain,
</l><l ln="31      ">Alas! are later. But their present bliss
</l><l ln="32      ">Is all&hyphen;sufficing to the twain, and they
</l><l ln="33      ">Know heaven when clasped in one another's arms.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="34      ">Macbeth and his too zealous wife appear,
</l><l ln="35      ">And pass before our eyes plotting foul crimes.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="36      ">The &ldquo;banished Duke&rdquo; and kindly Jacques reveal
</l><l ln="37      ">The greatest of the boons that Life may give
</l><l ln="38      ">Is love of Nature and simplicity.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="39      ">Gay Benedick and mirthful Beatrice
</l><l ln="40      ">Make &ldquo;Much Ado,&rdquo; and linger, laughter&hyphen;laden.
</l><pb n="40">
<l ln="41      ">Bold Katherina yields herself at last
</l><l ln="42      ">As conquerered in &ldquo;The Taming of the Shrew.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="43      ">But not till she has railed and railed again
</l><l ln="44      ">At brave Petruchio.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="45      ">                             See Hamlet pass,
</l><l ln="46      ">Profoundest personage in all the host
</l><l ln="47      ">That Shakespeare makes to live, a lofty soul,
</l><l ln="48      ">The study and the marvel of the world.</l></pdiv>

<signed r="italic">March 8th, 1907.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646869</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>II.&mdash;<subhead>SHAKESPEARE IN LONDON.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646869</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>II.&mdash;SHAKESPEARE IN LONDON.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028284</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028284</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>II.&mdash;SHAKESPEARE IN LONDON.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016948">(Composed for the Shakespeare Reading Society's
Commemoration, 1907, and recited by
Mr. Alexander Watson.)</note>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Who comes, a man in mind, a boy in age,&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Hope's golden music ringing in his ears,
</l><l ln="3        ">To conquer London single&hyphen;handed&mdash;wage
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Battle with Chance&mdash;battle with strong compeers?
</l><l ln="5        ">And now, who leaves the conflict&mdash;victory won&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Who bids farewell to London's glorious strife,
</l><l ln="7        ">To brood by Avon&hyphen;lilies that have shone
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Bright in his brain through all that stress of life?
</l><l ln="9        ">As homeward wending towards the little town
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;He left&mdash;how brief the time!&mdash;without a name,
</l><l ln="11      ">What are his visions? Does he see the crown
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;With which the world shall crown him? Does the fame
</l><l ln="13      ">Of Shakespeare reach him? Does the skylark sing
</l><l ln="14      ">&ldquo;Behold our Will come back&mdash;the poet&hyphen;king!&rdquo;?</l></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="41">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646870</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>III.&mdash;<subhead>SHAKESPEARE AT STRATFORD&hyphen;ON&hyphen;AVON.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646870</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>III.&mdash;SHAKESPEARE AT STRATFORD&hyphen;ON&hyphen;AVON.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028285</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028285</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>III.&mdash;SHAKESPEARE AT STRATFORD&hyphen;ON&hyphen;AVON.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">Shakespeare, thy legacy of peerless song
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Reveals mankind in every age and place,
</l><l ln="3        ">In every joy, in every grief and wrong:
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;'Tis England's legacy to all our race.
</l><l ln="5        ">Little we know of all thine inner life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Little of all thy swift, thy wondrous years&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Years filled with toil&mdash;rich years whose days were rife
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;With strains that bring us mirth, that bring us tears.
</l><l ln="9        ">Little we know, and yet this much we know,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Sense was thy guiding star&mdash;sense guided thee
</l><l ln="11      ">To live in this thy Stratford long ago&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To live content in calm simplicity; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Greatest of those who wrought with soul aflame
</l><l ln="14      ">At honest daily work&mdash;then found it fame.</l></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646871</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IV.&mdash;<subhead>PROLOGUE

AND INTERSPERSED LINES</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646871</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IV.&mdash;PROLOGUE  AND INTERSPERSED LINES</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028286</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028286</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IV.&mdash;PROLOGUE  AND INTERSPERSED LINES</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016949">To a performance of Episodes from the Plays of
Shakespeare, illustrative of London life. Given in
the Gardens of Lowther Lodge, South Kensington, on
June 21 and 22, 1907, by the Members of the Shakespeare
Reading Society, in aid of the Funds of the
South Kensington District Branch of the League
<pb n="42">
of Mercy. The poem was spoken throughout in the
first instance by Mr. Otto Sallmann, and subsequently
the eight detached portions were delivered by
eight chosen narrators, one from each group of players.</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Leagued in the angel Mercy's &ldquo;twice&hyphen;blessed&rdquo; cause,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">We bring these scenes before you. Your applause
</l><l ln="3        ">We take not to ourselves, 'tis meant for him&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">London's chief bard whose glory grows not dim&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Shakespeare, whom Coleridge called &ldquo;the thousand&hyphen;souled.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="6        ">'Tis our delight to&hyphen;day that we unfold
</l><l ln="7        ">Some treasures;&mdash;freaks of fancy, genius&hyphen;fraught; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Glimpses of wit and pathos he had caught
</l><l ln="9        ">When dreaming in the London of the past,
</l><l ln="10      ">Where gabled fronts of oak long shadows cast,
</l><l ln="11      ">Where rapiers rattled, and where, far and nigh,
</l><l ln="12      ">The varied garb gave pleasure to the eye.
</l><l ln="13      ">To him each showed an inmost self; and there
</l><l ln="14      ">Perchance the Muse first found him, unaware.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="15      ">Now is presented sad Queen Katherine's trial,
</l><l ln="16      ">Her piteous suit to Henry, and denial;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="17      ">A tale of woman's sorrow long ago,
</l><l ln="18      ">A tale of mingled guile, deceit, and woe.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016950">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;Henry VIII.,&rdquo; Act 2,
Scene 4 (The Trial of Queen Katharine)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="19      ">Then comes from bright Messina, far away,
</l><l ln="20      ">Sage Dogberry. And, have we not to&hyphen;day
</l><pb n="43">
<l ln="21      ">Some of his tribe still with us? Night by night
</l><l ln="22      ">Do they not guard us&mdash;make our slumbers light?</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016951">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;Much Ado About Nothing,&rdquo; 
Act 3, Scene 3 (The Watch Scene)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="23      ">And soon shall you behold the fall of pride
</l><l ln="24      ">As shown by stately Wolsey, placed beside
</l><l ln="25      ">Anne Boleyn's coronation. There 'tis plain
</l><l ln="26      ">How fickle is kingly favour and disdain.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016952">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;Henry VIII.,&rdquo; Act 3,
Scene 3 (the dialogue between Wolsey and Cromwell),
followed by Scene 4 (the Coronation Procession of Anne
Boleyn)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="27      ">Later, you will perceive the measured pace
</l><l ln="28      ">And beauty of the gay Pavane, each grace
</l><l ln="29      ">And gesture setting forth the melody
</l><l ln="30      ">And joy of happy motion, full and free.
</l><l ln="31      ">And then in troop the sprightly Morris throng,
</l><l ln="32      ">Their dance a fitting close to rustic song.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016953">[<hi r="italic">Here was given a Pavane, followed by a Morris
Dance</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="33      ">In the fair Temple Gardens glow the roses,
</l><l ln="34      ">Both white and red, whose plucking soon discloses
</l><l ln="35      ">Fierce cause of deadly feud, for which, alas!
</l><l ln="36      ">Ere many summer joyous days shall pass,
</l><l ln="37      ">Many of England's bravest sons must bleed
</l><l ln="38      ">In direful civic strife, whose root was greed
</l><pb n="44">
<l ln="39      ">Of power: &ldquo;In our dear England's day of need&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="40      ">(Hear this their voiceless cry) &ldquo;'twere sweet indeed
</l><l ln="41      ">Against her foemen to defend her cause,
</l><l ln="42      ">Or die for her&mdash;to uphold her righteous laws.
</l><l ln="43      ">But thus, 'tis ill to die, merely that one
</l><l ln="44      ">Or other despot find his ill work done.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016954">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;Henry V.,&rdquo; Act 1, Scene 4,
(the Plucking of the Roses in the Temple Gardens)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="45      ">See! Gloster here&mdash;Gloster with fawning tongue
</l><l ln="46      ">Envenomed, snake&hyphen;like, deadly; for among
</l><l ln="47      ">Those near him is the youthful prince whose life
</l><l ln="48      ">He seeks; with hatred all his soul is rife.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016955">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;Richard III.,&rdquo; Act 3,
Scene 1 (the Meeting of Edward V. and the Duke of
Gloster)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="49      ">And look, you now shall see that bold, old lover
</l><l ln="50      ">Falstaff, with ardour cooled, abashed discover
</l><l ln="51      ">Himself befooled when he essays to wage
</l><l ln="52      ">Victorious war with &ldquo;merry&rdquo; Mistress Page.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016956">[<hi r="italic">Here was performed &ldquo;The Merry Wives of
Windsor,&rdquo; Act 3, Scene 3 (the Buck&hyphen;Basket Scene)</hi>.]</note>

<pdiv><l ln="53      ">Great Shakespeare now approaches; he will read
</l><l ln="54      ">One of his &ldquo;sugred&rdquo; sonnets; you will heed
</l><l ln="55      ">The matchless lofty music, rich and strong,
</l><pb n="45">
<l ln="56      ">The cadence of his pure, immortal song,
</l><l ln="57      ">Full of rare tact towards proud Elizabeth,
</l><l ln="58      ">Her name, by him enshrined, shall know no death.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="59      ">Leagued in the angel Mercy's &ldquo;twice&hyphen;blessed&rdquo; cause,
</l><l ln="60      ">These scenes we bring before you. Your applause
</l><l ln="61      ">We take not to ourselves, 'tis meant for him&mdash; 
</l><l ln="62      ">London's chief bard whose glory grows not dim.</l></pdiv>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016957">[<hi r="italic">At the close of the Episodes was given a representation
of Shakespeare and his Fellows being received
by Queen Elizabeth and her Court, subsequent to a
performance of &ldquo;The Comedy of Errors.&rdquo; Shakespeare
read his celebrated sonnet beginning: &ldquo;Not marble,
nor the gilded monuments,&rdquo; in praise of the Queen</hi>.]</note></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

