<comhd2><idref>Z200646873</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

PICTURES OF SPAIN. <attbytes>14Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646873</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646874</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SUMMER NOONTIDE.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646874</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER NOONTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028287</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028287</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SUMMER NOONTIDE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646875</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I.&mdash;<subhead>Poverty.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646875</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER NOONTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">It is the silent summer noon:
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And the hour of rest comes never soon,
</l><l ln="3        ">For peasants who have stooped to toil
</l><l ln="4        ">Ere day&hyphen;dawn on the sultry soil; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Who feel the cooling breeze of morn
</l><l ln="6        ">Desert them, surely overborne
</l><l ln="7        ">By the fierce ardour of the sun
</l><l ln="8        ">Even when his race is scarce begun; 
</l><l ln="9        ">Who pass the lagging, weary hours
</l><l ln="10      ">In longing for the pleasant bowers
</l><l ln="11      ">Of vine and olive intertwined,
</l><l ln="12      ">Where, in the shade, at length reclined,
</l><l ln="13      ">They quaff deep draughts of wine in peace,
</l><l ln="14      ">While Life's fierce troubles fade and cease.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646876</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II.&mdash;<subhead>Wealth.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646876</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER NOONTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="15      ">A maiden sits within the shade
</l><l ln="16      ">Of yonder stately, cool arcade,
</l><pb n="47">
<l ln="17      ">By columns of rich marble made,
</l><l ln="18      ">Which bear designs, all chaste and pure,
</l><l ln="19      ">Of fruits and flowers whose shapes allure,
</l><l ln="20      ">And near their base an ancient crest&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">A mailed knight with his lance in rest.
</l><l ln="22      ">The damask curtains here and there,
</l><l ln="23      ">Of richest stuffs, shut out the glare,
</l><l ln="24      ">Yet come faint gusts of cooler air.
</l><l ln="25      ">With what rare gifts&mdash;what loveliness&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">The happy days of Youth's caress
</l><l ln="27      ">Had dowered the maid, my words are cold
</l><l ln="28      ">To tell of. Tresses hued like gold
</l><l ln="29      ">Fall now upon her snow&hyphen;white neck,
</l><l ln="30      ">Like the light clouds which oft&hyphen;times fleck
</l><l ln="31      ">The wide expanse of summer sky
</l><l ln="32      ">At morn, before the sun is high.
</l><l ln="33      ">Her dress is simple, yet beseems
</l><l ln="34      ">Her rank: and but one jewel gleams
</l><l ln="35      ">Upon her bosom. You may trace
</l><l ln="36      ">In her an all&hyphen;pervading grace
</l><l ln="37      ">Of form, of gesture, and of face,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="38      ">Yet so diffused 'tis hard to tell
</l><l ln="39      ">Wherein the perfect grace may dwell.</l></div4></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646877</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SUMMER EVENTIDE.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646877</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER EVENTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028288</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028288</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SUMMER EVENTIDE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646878</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I.&mdash;<subhead>In the Country.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646878</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER EVENTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Tis twilight's brief enchanting hour,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The sun has lost his torrid power,
</l><l ln="3        ">Yet keeps enough of might to fling
</l><l ln="4        ">Sweet magic over everything.
</l><pb n="48">
<l ln="5        ">'Tis not the beauty that you see
</l><l ln="6        ">At sunset on an English lea.
</l><l ln="7        ">'Tis beauty all intensified,
</l><l ln="8        ">As if the Day&hyphen;King in his pride
</l><l ln="9        ">Ordains that where his power is shown,
</l><l ln="10      ">His gifts of beauty shall be known.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">The noon&hyphen;tide glow which all things steep
</l><l ln="12      ">In dreamless lethargy&mdash;the sleep
</l><l ln="13      ">Of busy Nature now is past,
</l><l ln="14      ">And all things are reviving fast.
</l><l ln="15      ">The birds arouse themselves ere long,
</l><l ln="16      ">And sing a cheerful vesper song.
</l><l ln="17      ">The peasant takes his evening round
</l><l ln="18      ">To view his much&hyphen;loved plot of ground,
</l><l ln="19      ">To find by scrutinising gaze
</l><l ln="20      ">How fare his olives, vines or maize.</l></stanza></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646879</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II.&mdash;<subhead>In the City.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646879</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SUMMER EVENTIDE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016958"><hi r="roman">Palacio</hi> is a word applied to a mansion belonging
to an ancient noble family. <hi r="roman">Plaza</hi> is the name given
to a large square.</note>

<pdiv><l ln="21      ">Here in the city's roseal air
</l><l ln="22      ">People are moving everywhere
</l><l ln="23      ">With jest, or laugh, or snatch of song,
</l><l ln="24      ">Through square, through street, a changeful throng.
</l><pb n="49">
<l ln="25      ">And gentle ladies now appear,
</l><l ln="26      ">Graciously bending down to hear
</l><l ln="27      ">The honeyed nothings, soft and slow,
</l><l ln="28      ">Spoken by lovers from below; 
</l><l ln="29      ">Each feigns bewitching bland surprise
</l><l ln="30      ">At praises of her lips or eyes.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="31      ">See yon <hi r="italic">palacio</hi>, grey and cold,
</l><l ln="32      ">Proud of his lineage, high and old,
</l><l ln="33      ">As he who owns it. Full and plain,
</l><l ln="34      ">Like many another such in Spain,
</l><l ln="35      ">From its carved windows you may see
</l><l ln="36      ">The chiefest <hi r="italic">plaza's</hi> revelry.
</l><l ln="37      ">And yet upon the other side
</l><l ln="38      ">Stretches a garden beautified
</l><l ln="39      ">By fountains clear, and still retreats,
</l><l ln="40      ">By terraced walks, and shady seats,
</l><l ln="41      ">And all the loveliness that Art
</l><l ln="42      ">In generous climates can impart.
</l><l ln="43      ">Now the moon rises, flinging far
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Her silvery flood of mellow light,
</l><l ln="45      ">And darkness can no longer mar
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;The peerless loveliness of Night.
</l><l ln="47      ">That palm, which crowns yon neighbouring hill,
</l><l ln="48      ">Stands out, majestic, tall, and still; 
</l><l ln="49      ">White gleam the city walls, and now
</l><l ln="50      ">Fall shadows from each olive bough,
</l><l ln="51      ">While clear against a starry sky
</l><l ln="52      ">Coldly the distant mountains lie.</l></pdiv></div4></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="50">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646880</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE CITY OF THE CID.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646880</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE CITY OF THE CID.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028289</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028289</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE CITY OF THE CID.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Burgos, the city of the Cid, all hail!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Thou standest in the plain of old Castile,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Fragrant with rare romance that still I feel,
</l><l ln="4        ">Albeit no more is heard the clang of mail</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Within thy grass&hyphen;grown streets. And round about
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;No hand of Change is working, and it seems
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Thou art unaltered, throned in thronging dreams
</l><l ln="8        ">Full of the sound of arms and warlike shout.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">How grand is thy cathedral's gorgeous pile!
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;How quaint its frescoed front! These carven forms,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Here sculptured, had their life as many storms
</l><l ln="12      ">Of care as ours throughout its weary while?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">These images of saints within, whose life,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Judging but from their features, was all calm,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Had they than we more nearly reached that balm
</l><l ln="16      ">Which Christians find the antidote of strife?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">No! Life was then a darker, fiercer thing
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Than now it is. For of a truth our lives
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Are moulded by our faith. He only thrives
</l><l ln="20      ">Whose faith is true of flight and strong of wing.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">And theirs, though firm, could never have been true,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Since it forbade the purest Light to shine
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;Which shows the truth on earth, that Light divine,
</l><l ln="24      ">By which God wills that Man his course should view</l></stanza>

<pb n="51">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">And haply change if need be. Thoughts like these
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Come as home fruit seen under alien skies,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;As now I gaze around. Rich musings rise
</l><l ln="28      ">While looking on thee, Burgos,&mdash;some which please,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">And some which sadden. When at close of day
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;I stand in thy cathedral's solemn shades
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;Among its peerless chapels, naught invades
</l><l ln="32      ">To break the sacred rest of aisle and bay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">And more and more departs each common thought,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And more and more I feel my soul is stirred,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;As if low music, sweet, though faintly heard,
</l><l ln="36      ">To me new founts of gentle bliss had brought.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646881</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT TOLEDO.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646881</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT TOLEDO.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028290</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028290</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT TOLEDO.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016959"><hi r="italic">The Fabrica de Armas</hi> at Toledo is celebrated. Toledo, like
Rome, is built on seven hills. <hi r="italic">The Puerta del Sol</hi>, a still remaining
Moorish gateway, is one of its finest relics. Burgos was once
the Christian, and Toledo the Moorish capital of Spain. To
speak <hi r="italic">en proprio Toledano</hi> has, since the fourteenth century, the
time of Cervantes, been equivalent to the best Spanish.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Toledo! what rare gems of memory
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;From olden story gleam along thy name; 
</l><l ln="3        ">What visions rise of victories won by thee
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Fruit of thy strong, thy flawless blades of fame.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Little they reck, thy kings, who gazed around
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;On yon fair city, fitted to be great,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Crowned on yon seven hills as Rome was crowned&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Little they reck of this thy last estate.</l></stanza>

<pb n="52">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ah, yes! most noble once must thou have seemed,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;When the proud capital of lordly power,
</l><l ln="11      ">When in full glory southern sunshine beamed
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;On lofty battlement and soaring tower.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">In days when from the &ldquo;Sun&hyphen;gate&rdquo; oft at morn
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Issued a goodly Moorish martial train
</l><l ln="15      ">Of turbaned knights, ere starting, sternly sworn
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;To conquer for the Crescent more of Spain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">With scimitars unsheathed swift rode they forth,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Their fury spreading terror all around
</l><l ln="19      ">Among the peasants, as towards the North,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;They spurred with Burgos as their furthest bound.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Then afterwards returning, Victory
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Attendant on their flag, with what delight
</l><l ln="23      ">Would comrades greet them who had come to see
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And breathe the cooling freshness of the night.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">And when the sixth Alonso conquered thee,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Thrusting thee back into the Christian fold,
</l><l ln="27      ">Then was thy people's accent held to be
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Of soft Castilian speech the noblest mould.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">And when, in later times, the Spanish name
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Had grown the most renowned in all the world,
</l><l ln="31      ">Lepanto learnt how true could be the aim
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Of keen Toledan darts adroitly hurled.</l></stanza>

<pb n="53">

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Dream&hyphen;pageants dazzle me, again, again&mdash; 
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;As musing thus I pass upon my way,
</l><l ln="35      ">I feel no shame that it has given me pain
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;To see thy sad, thy dull, thy slow decay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">Farewell, far&hyphen;famed Toledo! Nevermore
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Shall I forget thy mien, thou seem'st indeed
</l><l ln="39      ">Plunged in the deepest sleep. None can restore
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Spain's ancient cities. Life is what they need.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646882</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>PALMS BY MOONLIGHT AT ALICANTE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646882</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>PALMS BY MOONLIGHT AT ALICANTE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028291</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028291</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>PALMS BY MOONLIGHT AT ALICANTE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;Palms by moonlight! waving palms,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;How the thought of you embalms
</l><l ln="3        ">In memory still the spot whereon I saw you last!
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Softly, wonderfully clear
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;On that night did you appear
</l><l ln="6        ">Whose blissful hours, swift&hyphen;winged, too soon, too soon, were past.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">&indent;Here the eye could range at will,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And of beauty take its fill,
</l><l ln="9        ">Beauty so rare it soothed as soothes a heav'n&hyphen;sent dream&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Or a mellow Eastern tale
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Where the genii ride the gale
</l><l ln="12      ">And glide among such trees on many a moonlight gleam.</l></stanza>

<pb n="54">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;For the strange ethereal sight
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Thrilled me with a new delight,
</l><l ln="15      ">While still the full&hyphen;orbed moon o'er leaf o'er feathery bough
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;From a sky of purest blue
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Silver glory gently threw.
</l><l ln="18      ">Then rapturous visions came I know not whence or how&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">&indent;Visions, sweet and kind, that stole
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Through my hush'd and happy soul
</l><l ln="21      ">To strive against their power had been a vain endeavour,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And, with ravished eye and heart,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;Wished I never to depart,
</l><l ln="24      ">Looking, I longed to live, and see these sights for ever.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<div2>
<comhd2><idref>Z200646883</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

PICTURES OF MADEIRA. <attbytes>13Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646883</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646884</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>JO&Abar;O TO CONSTAN&Ccedil;A.

<subhead r="italic">(A lest&eacute; Sunrise.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646884</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>JO&Abar;O TO CONSTAN&Ccedil;A.  (A lest&eacute; Sunrise.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028292</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028292</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>JO&Abar;O TO CONSTAN&Ccedil;A.  (A lest&eacute; Sunrise.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016960">The <hi r="italic">lest&eacute;</hi> is a south&hyphen;east wind, frequently prevalent for
several days. At the beginning or close of a <hi r="italic">lest&eacute;</hi> the sunrises
and sunsets are superb. Purple is the colour particularly
prominent.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Yonder flush across the sea
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Brings the morning back to me
</l><l ln="3        ">When you seemed to lend the light
</l><l ln="4        ">That dispersed the lingering night; 
</l><pb n="55">
<l ln="5        ">When I heard your step, and knew
</l><l ln="6        ">Joy of joy! 'twas surely you; 
</l><l ln="7        ">When I turned and saw your face,
</l><l ln="8        ">Saw you glide with girlish grace; 
</l><l ln="9        ">Though before my heart was moved,
</l><l ln="10      ">Then it was that first I loved.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">Rosy cloudlets, lately dun,
</l><l ln="12      ">Seemed as now to hide the sun; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Other cloudlets seemed to stand
</l><l ln="14      ">Ready waiting his command.
</l><l ln="15      ">Brighter, brighter grew the group,
</l><l ln="16      ">Every tint was in the troop,
</l><l ln="17      ">Red, and blue, and rich maroon,
</l><l ln="18      ">Fleecy white appearing soon,
</l><l ln="19      ">As at length we plighted troth,
</l><l ln="20      ">Hallowed moments for us both.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">O'er the peaks the vapoury shrouds
</l><l ln="22      ">Shifted with the shifting clouds; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Faintly purpled clouds were spread
</l><l ln="24      ">O'er the peaceful ocean's bed; 
</l><l ln="25      ">Clouds empurpled now, and grand,
</l><l ln="26      ">Cast a halo o'er the land.
</l><l ln="27      ">Every bird and opening flower
</l><l ln="28      ">Felt the gladness of the hour,
</l><l ln="29      ">As the gentle landward breeze
</l><l ln="30      ">Stirred the tall banana&hyphen;trees.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="31      ">You remember how the day,
</l><l ln="32      ">While dawn's freshness wore away,
</l><pb n="56">
<l ln="33      ">Took a dimmer purple hue
</l><l ln="34      ">As the clouds were changed anew,
</l><l ln="35      ">You remember how we walked,
</l><l ln="36      ">You remember how we talked,
</l><l ln="37      ">How, beneath this trellised vine,
</l><l ln="38      ">Oft you told me you were mine,
</l><l ln="39      ">Each remembrance makes more clear
</l><l ln="40      ">All the debt I owe you, dear.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646885</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>FRANCISCA TO JASPEAR.

<subhead r="italic">An Idyl.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646885</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>FRANCISCA TO JASPEAR.  An Idyl.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028293</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028293</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>FRANCISCA TO JASPEAR.  An Idyl.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">The rich&mdash;the rich alone&mdash;may dream of death
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">As solace for their sorrow, not the poor.
</l><l ln="3        ">Whate'er their grief, the poor have work to do
</l><l ln="4        ">If they would not behold their dear ones starve.
</l><l ln="5        ">Now were <hi r="italic">I</hi> dead there's none to pluck the fruit
</l><l ln="6        ">And sort it on our stall o' market days,
</l><l ln="7        ">Mother is ill, and through the scorching hours
</l><l ln="8        ">Father is busy 'mid the sugar&hyphen;canes.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">It seems but yesterday since you and I,
</l><l ln="10      ">Happy with thoughts of coming happiness,
</l><l ln="11      ">Lived in the future, for the pleasant years
</l><l ln="12      ">Stretched all before us, fraught with all the joy
</l><l ln="13      ">That only love which changes not can give.
</l><l ln="14      ">Never shall I forget how once we sat
</l><l ln="15      ">Here where the orange&hyphen;trees yield grateful shade,
</l><l ln="16      ">As with fond eyes of truth you told to me
</l><l ln="17      ">Once and again the sweet familiar tale
</l><l ln="18      ">That ever to a maiden's heart is new.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="57">

<pdiv><l ln="19      ">Far, far beneath me, shimmering in the sun,
</l><l ln="20      ">Were palms with shapely branches, outlined now
</l><l ln="21      ">More clearly by the strong light pouring down,
</l><l ln="22      ">And nearer, on the left, an avenue
</l><l ln="23      ">Of red and white camellias full in flower
</l><l ln="24      ">Formed one long vista filled with varying hues,
</l><l ln="25      ">While countless clustering vines and citron trees
</l><l ln="26      ">Gleamed in a rare, a radiant mingled glow
</l><l ln="27      ">Of gorgeous colour. The banana&hyphen;trees,
</l><l ln="28      ">Each with its fragrant load of luscious fruit,
</l><l ln="29      ">The graceful guavas with their light&hyphen;green leaves,
</l><l ln="30      ">The loquats with their deeper verdant tints,
</l><l ln="31      ">The stately yam&hyphen;trees with their blossoms white,
</l><l ln="32      ">Stood forth in all their loveliness together.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="33      ">Delightful was it, when the sun declined,
</l><l ln="34      ">To loiter with you as the breath of night
</l><l ln="35      ">Conquered the sultry ardour of the day; 
</l><l ln="36      ">To see the moon rise over silent seas; 
</l><l ln="37      ">To see the summer heavens, now decked with stars,
</l><l ln="38      ">Vie with the shafts of distance&hyphen;mellowed light
</l><l ln="39      ">From many a cottage on the lone crag&hyphen;sides
</l><l ln="40      ">In making a rich girdle round the bay; 
</l><l ln="41      ">To hear the soft <hi r="italic">mach&ecirc;te</hi> <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016961">[1] The Portuguese guitar.</note> play some air
</l><l ln="42      ">Of gayest sound, perhaps a mazy dance.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="43      ">Alas! alas for me, such hours of bliss
</l><l ln="44      ">Can nevermore return, for you are dead.
</l><l ln="45      ">Good were it if I lay where you are laid
</l><l ln="46      ">In that fair spot where one may hear the waves
</l><pb n="58">
<l ln="47      ">Break idly on the shingle beach below
</l><l ln="48      ">In noontide heat when scarce a lizard stirs; 
</l><l ln="49      ">Where scented roses cling around the tombs
</l><l ln="50      ">Still blooming on throughout the sunny year.</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="51      ">Yes, mother, I am coming, you must look
</l><l ln="52      ">At these my oranges, fresh plucked and ripe,
</l><l ln="53      ">And at my custard apples, they will be
</l><l ln="54      ">The finest in the market&hyphen;place to&hyphen;day.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646886</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>VERSES

<subhead r="italic">On a vase filled with sub&hyphen;tropical flowers grown in the
open air in December.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646886</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>VERSES  On a vase filled with sub&hyphen;tropical flowers grown in the open air in December.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028294</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028294</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>VERSES  On a vase filled with sub&hyphen;tropical flowers grown in the open air in December.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;Most beauteous flowers!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Come ye to tell of summer hours,
</l><l ln="3        ">Of balmy breezes&mdash;lengthened days,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of warblers' blithesome lays?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;Thus come ye not,
</l><l ln="6        ">For not in summer lies your lot,
</l><l ln="7        ">No lengthened days attend your birth
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Nor songsters' vocal mirth. <edit>[Footnote 2: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016962">[2] This is hardly true of Madeira to&hyphen;day&mdash;1908&mdash;as so many
species of birds have been brought thither since these lines were
written.</note></l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;Yet gentle gales
</l><l ln="10      ">Are near, and sunshine still prevails,
</l><l ln="11      ">As in frail loveliness ye lie
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Too soon, alas! to die.</l></stanza>

<pb n="59">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Ah fair, how fair,
</l><l ln="14      ">Here Nature working everywhere,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">If winter thus it makes to me,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;What must the spring&hyphen;time be!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;And yet, although
</l><l ln="18      ">Each plant delights in southern glow,
</l><l ln="19      ">Upon no zephyr is there spent
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;One breath of subtle scent.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&indent;'Tis England's flowers&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">The lily and rose of English bowers&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Retain the perfume and the glow:
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;These blossoms only blow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;'Tis England's spring
</l><l ln="26      ">Whose every floweret seems to bring
</l><l ln="27      ">New sweets to blend with every breeze
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Among the budding trees.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">&indent;Yet 'tis a power,
</l><l ln="30      ">This glory of each plant and flower,
</l><l ln="31      ">To make the poet's heart rejoice
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And sing with gladsome voice.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">&indent;The poet feels&mdash; 
</l><l ln="34      ">Yet rarely even he reveals&mdash; 
</l><l ln="35      ">The restful store of blissful thought
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Such flowers to him have brought.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="60">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646887</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;CHRISTMAS IN THE SUMMER SUNSHINE.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646887</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;CHRISTMAS IN THE SUMMER SUNSHINE.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028295</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028295</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;CHRISTMAS IN THE SUMMER SUNSHINE.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


 <edit>[Footnote 2: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note r="italic" idref="LLN016963">(Funchal.)</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Christmas in the summer sunshine! O how wonderful it seems,&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Dowered with gladness are its moments, realizing poet&hyphen;dreams,
</l><l ln="3        ">While its moments hasten from me, how I wish they came to stay,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">How I wish their guileless pleasure nevermore might pass away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Softly play around my forehead breathings of the seaward breeze,
</l><l ln="6        ">As it stirs the swaying branches of the palms and orange&hyphen;trees,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">As it stirs the cactus growing on the gaunt uprising cliffs
</l><l ln="8        ">Hanging o'er the gleaming ocean dotted with the fishing skiffs.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Nature here with slightest tendance grants her gifts of loveliest hue&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">Gives among the vine&hyphen;clad ridges wild&hyphen;flowers purple, golden, blue,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Here azaleas, rich gardenias ope their blossoms to the air,
</l><l ln="12      ">With the rose and trained geranium&mdash;whose wild types are also fair.</l></stanza>

<pb n="61">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Pure and calm the moonlight radiance for the people as they pass
</l><l ln="14      ">On the eve of merry Christmas to and from the midnight mass; 
</l><l ln="15      ">While the jocund serenaders through the balmy hours of night
</l><l ln="16      ">By their songs and sprightly music often bring a brief delight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Christmas in the summer sunshine! neither frost nor snow are here,
</l><l ln="18      ">Buoyant health can welcome winter but it fills the sick with fear&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Here the sick with friends around them spend a cheerful Christmas day,
</l><l ln="20      ">Thinking of but seldom pining for a chill home far away.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646888</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON THE ROAD TO CAMARA DE LOBOS</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646888</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON THE ROAD TO CAMARA DE LOBOS</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028296</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028296</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON THE ROAD TO CAMARA DE LOBOS</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Heroic couplets</attgenre></newatts>


<signed><hi r="italic">January</hi>, 18&mdash;.</signed>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">The sun that is setting afar in the west
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In raiment of glory goes down to his rest,
</l><l ln="3        ">And, like a young maiden who wishes good&hyphen;bye
</l><l ln="4        ">To the lover when leaving her, blushes the sky; 
</l><l ln="5        ">How fair is the picture as now in the west
</l><l ln="6        ">In raiment of glory the sun goes to rest.</l></stanza>

<pb n="62">

<stanza><l ln="7        ">The clouds in apparel of sunset appear,
</l><l ln="8        ">Apparel of beauty while Evening draws near,
</l><l ln="9        ">While calmly they watch o'er the sleep of the sea
</l><l ln="10      ">Unstirred by the breezes. How wondrous to me
</l><l ln="11      ">Is the peace of the picture, as now in the west
</l><l ln="12      ">In raiment of glory the sun goes to rest.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">How peerless and perfect God's painting appears,
</l><l ln="14      "><hi r="italic">His</hi> delicate work never fades with the years; 
</l><l ln="15      "><hi r="italic">His</hi> painting now quiet, now wild beyond speech,
</l><l ln="16      ">Man only can copy, man never can reach
</l><l ln="17      ">In grandeur. So thought I, as now in the west
</l><l ln="18      ">In raiment of glory the sun goes to rest.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<div2>
<comhd2><idref>Z200646889</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

OTHER PICTURES OF TRAVEL. <attbytes>21Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646889</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646890</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT SEA&mdash;OFF THE MOUTH OF THE
GARONNE&mdash;SUNSET.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646890</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT SEA&mdash;OFF THE MOUTH OF THE GARONNE&mdash;SUNSET.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028297</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028297</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT SEA&mdash;OFF THE MOUTH OF THE GARONNE&mdash;SUNSET.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">A twilit halo gilds the troubled sky,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And gilds the heaving waters far and nigh; 
</l><l ln="3        ">About me here is some strange loveliness
</l><l ln="4        ">Which, as the shadows deepen, grows not less.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Hark! Now, not once or twice, but o'er and o'er
</l><l ln="6        ">In solemn grandeur comes the deep&hyphen;voiced roar
</l><l ln="7        ">Of strong Atlantic surges; where I stand
</l><l ln="8        ">I look, but see no welcome speck of land.</l></stanza>

<pb n="63">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">How beautiful is yonder distant sail
</l><l ln="10      ">Illumined yet; but soon my eyes must fail
</l><l ln="11      ">To trace its further course, for it will be
</l><l ln="12      ">Lost in the glory of the sunset sea.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">And as I gaze, and gaze, dim thoughts arise&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Thoughts of Man's destiny; these callous skies
</l><l ln="15      ">Seem types of earthly cruelty, and now
</l><l ln="16      ">The sea, like man, is sad&mdash;I know not how.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">The air is still; no wing&egrave;d wanderer cleaves
</l><l ln="18      ">The silence in his flight, as Night receives
</l><l ln="19      ">Ere long her stately queen the crescent moon,
</l><l ln="20      ">Whose glimmering beams show all the billows soon.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646891</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Gironde</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646891</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC.  (Gironde.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028298</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028298</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AFTER SUNSET OFF PAUILLAC.  (Gironde.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">The day is gone, but yonder fading streaks
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of light still fleck the bosom of the sky.
</l><l ln="3        ">Swart Night comes swiftly. Hark, that sound bespeaks
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;My nearness to the ocean, 'tis the cry
</l><l ln="5        ">Of some belated sea&hyphen;bird, and I hear
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The ripples at my feet. A low sweet song
</l><l ln="7        ">Monotonous, yet musical and clear,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Is breeze&hyphen;borne from a vessel's deck along.
</l><pb n="64">
<l ln="9        ">The crew raise anchor quickly, and away
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;She glides into the gloom, while growing low
</l><l ln="11      ">And ever lower sounds the roundelay.
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;What now may be her fortune none can know.
</l><l ln="13      ">Like her, o'er Life's strange, trackless sea we sail,
</l><l ln="14      ">Nor know if calm or tempest will prevail.</l></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646892</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">The Valley of the Gave de Pau</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646892</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.  (The Valley of the Gave de Pau.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028299</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028299</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.  (The Valley of the Gave de Pau.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ah! lovelier comes the southern night
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Than night of northern skies,
</l><l ln="3        ">Where tedious twilight mocks the flight
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of day that slowly dies&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Here placid Evening's starry veil
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;O'er all is swiftly cast&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Here peace seems wafted on the gale&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And care awhile is past.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">In southern summer's mellow night
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;How sweet it is to stray
</l><l ln="11      ">'Mid fairest scenes which soft moonlight
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Make fairer far than day!</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">How fair the widely stretching woods
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;That gird the spacious plain,
</l><l ln="15      ">While watchful Silence, queen&hyphen;like, broods
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;O'er them in sombre reign&mdash;</l></pdiv>

<pb n="65">

<pdiv><l ln="17      ">How fair the river's crystal thread,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Seen faintly from afar,
</l><l ln="19      ">As silvery starlight now is shed
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;From many a tranquil star.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="21      ">In southern summer's mellow night
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;How sweet it is to stray
</l><l ln="23      ">'Mid fairest scenes which soft moonlight
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Make fairer far than day!</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="25      ">How fair the crested mountains lie,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Distant, yet wondrous clear,
</l><l ln="27      ">Their snow&hyphen;capt peaks against the sky
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Uprising tier on tier;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">How fair the sleeping landscape seems,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;While here and there are heard
</l><l ln="31      ">Sounds bringing Music's richest dreams
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Or laughter&hyphen;laden word.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="33      ">In southern summer's mellow night
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;How sweet it is to stray
</l><l ln="35      ">'Mid fairest scenes which soft moonlight
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Make fairer far than day!</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646893</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WILD ROSES AND SNOW.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Basses Pyren&eacute;es</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646893</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WILD ROSES AND SNOW.  (Basses Pyren&eacute;es.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028300</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028300</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WILD ROSES AND SNOW.  (Basses Pyren&eacute;es.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">How</hi> sweet the sight of roses
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In English lanes of June,
</l><l ln="3        ">When every flower uncloses
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To meet the kiss of noon.</l></stanza>

<pb n="66">

<stanza><l ln="5        ">How strange the sight of roses&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Roses both sweet and wild&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Seen where a valley closes
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;'Mid mountain heights up&hyphen;piled</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Upon whose sides remaining
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Is strewn the purest snow,
</l><l ln="11      ">By its chill power restraining
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The tide of Spring's soft glow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Yet God who gave the pureness
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To yon fair mountain snow,
</l><l ln="15      ">Gives also the secureness
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Whereby these roses blow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646894</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>NEAR ST. SAUVEUR.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Hautes Pyren&eacute;es</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646894</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>NEAR ST. SAUVEUR.  (Hautes Pyren&eacute;es.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028301</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028301</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>NEAR ST. SAUVEUR.  (Hautes Pyren&eacute;es.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Topographical poem</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Lo</hi>, what a glorious prospect is revealed&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Mountains and snow, and pine&hyphen;trees beauty&hyphen;clad!
</l><l ln="3        ">On many a sloping edge of awesome heights
</l><l ln="4        ">Reposes gracefully a misty veil
</l><l ln="5        ">In wreaths almost transparent; but ev'n now
</l><l ln="6        ">Its mass divides, and clear against the sky
</l><l ln="7        ">Rises each giant summit, still and grand,
</l><l ln="8        ">Proud that its lone, its vast, its God&hyphen;wrought strength
</l><l ln="9        ">Defies so long decay. I needs must feel
</l><l ln="10      ">Nature is great, and Man is impotent,
</l><pb n="67">
<l ln="11      ">Yet ah, how much his art hath made increase
</l><l ln="12      ">To this rare store of beauty. Each small patch
</l><l ln="13      ">Perceived upon the mountain side, reclaimed
</l><l ln="14      ">From barren wilderness, what power it hath
</l><l ln="15      ">To cheer the eye. To me it often seems
</l><l ln="16      ">As though no prospect reached perfection till
</l><l ln="17      ">It showed some kindly trace of human toil.</l></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646895</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF CAUTERETS BY NIGHT.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Hautes Pyren&eacute;es</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646895</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF CAUTERETS BY NIGHT.  (Hautes Pyren&eacute;es.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028302</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028302</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON LOOKING UP THE VALE OF CAUTERETS BY NIGHT.  (Hautes Pyren&eacute;es.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Topographical poem</attgenre></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;&indent;Though night is here,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In outline soft I see
</l><l ln="3        ">A vista through the gloom, where, mirrored clear,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Gleam rock and peak and tree.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;The mountain forms
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;In solemn grandeur rise,
</l><l ln="7        ">Each summit still the strength of countless storms
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;For countless years defies.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;&indent;The dark&hyphen;green pines
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Clothe all the slopes around&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">How lone these slopes on which each cold star shines!
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Nor doth a single sound</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;&indent;Invade the calm,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Or by its presence change
</l><l ln="15      ">The sense of vastness, soothing like a balm
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;From heaven, so new and strange.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="68">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646896</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON THE LAKE OF GENEVA.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646896</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON THE LAKE OF GENEVA.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028303</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028303</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON THE LAKE OF GENEVA.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Topographical poem</attgenre></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">A silvern haze is over all. At hand
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Are gently swaying poplars, rippling larches,
</l><l ln="3        ">And firmly rooted firs, while further off
</l><l ln="4        ">Gleam azure waters of the waveless lake.
</l><l ln="5        ">Beyond again are mountains; not, as oft,
</l><l ln="6        ">Gaunt snow&hyphen;capped monarch peaks, but bright with verdure.
</l><l ln="7        ">The rocks throw shadows quaint upon the grass; 
</l><l ln="8        ">White <hi r="italic">ch&acirc;lets</hi> peep among the clustering vines
</l><l ln="9        ">Gay boats glide smoothly on with placid sails
</l><l ln="10      ">Widely outspread.</l></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646897</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>LINES</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646897</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LINES</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028304</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028304</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LINES</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016964">Suggested by seeing, at the summit of the Simplon Pass, a stone,
fragment of some rude ancient carving, brought perhaps from
a neighbouring valley for road&hyphen;making purposes. The stone
had lain doubtless for a long time near the spot where I saw
it. There was some desultory fighting in the Italian Alpine
Valleys before Napoleon the First's decisive victory at
Marengo.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Many, perchance, have been, quaint carven stone,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Your harsh vicissitudes, how came you here?
</l><l ln="3        ">Change spares not even you, though you have known
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;No soul&hyphen;distress, nor Sorrow's blinding tear,
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Nor deep unutterable heart&hyphen;wrought fear.</l></stanza>

<pb n="69">

<stanza><l ln="6        ">Did you of some small fane once form a part
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Where vesper hymns arose at close of day,
</l><l ln="8        ">Where lovers true were link&egrave;d heart to heart,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;And humble villagers approached to pray,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Then, rising, went refreshed upon their way?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">And did fierce war destroy your place of peace
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Where some forgotten skirmish happened there
</l><l ln="13      ">Ere yet the Austrian yoke was made to cease
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;By famed Marengo? Bullets did not spare
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;The lowly church, and fire soon laid it bare.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="16      ">Maybe, when fickle Time had brought neglect,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;When reverence was a thing of long ago,
</l><l ln="18      ">When none in all the hamlet had respect
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;For its old ruined shrine, they came to throw
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Its remnants thus away, and used you so.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Near you, must oft have wandered weary men
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;'Mid dire storm&hyphen;battles fought on wintry nights;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Near you, perchance, have happened now and then
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;More wondrous deeds, more awe&hyphen;inspiring sights
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Than sages know in whom the world delights.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="26      ">What mighty tempests must have passed you by
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;When 'mid the riven mountains thunder pealed,
</l><l ln="28      ">And storm&hyphen;clouds came apace athwart the sky
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;In mad career, while Nature half revealed
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;The grandeur of the tumult, half concealed</l></stanza>

<pb n="70">

<stanza><l ln="31      ">Its majesty and power. The silent snows
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Must oft have lain upon you, when the hands
</l><l ln="33      ">Of Winter framed his lofty couch, and chose
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;His glacier lairs&mdash;when all the higher lands
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Loomed ghastly, shuddering at his dread commands</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="36      ">In solemn midnight hours when callous stars
</l><l ln="37      ">&indent;Shine down on snow&hyphen;drifts, on the glaciers lone,
</l><l ln="38      ">And on snow&hyphen;laden pines: when nothing mars
</l><l ln="39      ">&indent;That spectacle to human eyes scarce known,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Where Nature rears 'mid rocks her frost&hyphen;bound throne.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">Yet are you broken now to make a road&mdash; 
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Fallen from your pristine state, and haply too
</l><l ln="43      ">You will be worthless in your chill abode,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;And shrink from man's unfeeling, heedless view
</l><l ln="45      ">&indent;In your small nook, ignoble, poor, and new.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646898</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>SUNDAY MORNING OFF MAZAGAN, MOROCCO.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646898</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>SUNDAY MORNING OFF MAZAGAN, MOROCCO.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028305</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028305</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SUNDAY MORNING OFF MAZAGAN, MOROCCO.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;A magic city Fancy&hyphen;dight,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Thou seem'st this tranquil Sabbath day,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Strange town all glittering, treeless, white,
</l><l ln="4        ">Begirt with sand and seething spray&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;Lit by the sun whose rays reveal
</l><l ln="6        ">Each flat&hyphen;roofed Orient dwelling&hyphen;place,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Each stately mosque, each well whose wheel
</l><l ln="8        ">A camel turns with tireless pace.</l></stanza>

<pb n="71">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;Dark Moors in their fantastic dress,
</l><l ln="10      ">In haste to reach us, leave the shore,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;They make the distance less and less,
</l><l ln="12      ">So strong the stroke of each long oar.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;Now they have reached us and with pride
</l><l ln="14      ">Disdain the aid the steps afford,
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Bare feet from heel&hyphen;less slippers glide,
</l><l ln="16      ">And, cat&hyphen;like, quick they spring on board.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;All speak at once, with gestures quaint,
</l><l ln="18      ">And few but in an unknown tongue,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Those in the boats take up the plaint,
</l><l ln="20      ">And on the deck still more have sprung.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&indent;A single ship is in the bay
</l><l ln="22      ">Besides our own,&mdash;no others ride
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;At anchor. And she goes her way&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">But not until to&hyphen;morrow's tide.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;And from her mizen&hyphen;mast there floats&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">Dear sight to every British heart&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;That flag whose mingled hue denotes
</l><l ln="28      ">A union naught should ever part.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">&indent;A welcome standard! 'tis a sign&mdash; 
</l><l ln="30      ">A welcome sign&mdash;that some are here
</l><l ln="31      ">&indent;Who worship at a common shrine,
</l><l ln="32      ">Who pray like me&mdash;like me revere.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="72">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646899</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN THE NEW FOREST.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646899</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN THE NEW FOREST.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028306</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028306</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN THE NEW FOREST.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;&indent;Most clear! most fair!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The swelling woodland lies,
</l><l ln="3        ">Stretching in leafy glory everywhere
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Before my wondering eyes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">&indent;&indent;Here mighty oaks,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Stalwart, and vast, and strong,
</l><l ln="7        ">A thousand years have faced the tempest's strokes,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Have been the home of song.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&indent;&indent;Here wave the boughs
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Of tall and sombre pines,
</l><l ln="11      ">Here stands &ldquo;the temple of beeches,&rdquo; made for vows
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of love when softly shines</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;&indent;The summer moon.
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Here tremulous branches sway
</l><l ln="15      ">Of sun&hyphen;lit birches,&mdash;on the sward at noon
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Their shadows seem at play.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&indent;&indent;I linger still
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;In this sweet solitude,
</l><l ln="19      ">Wishing my care&hyphen;sick mind could taste at will
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The healing sylvan mood.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="73">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646900</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>EVENING IN THE FOREST OF MEUDON.

<subhead r="italic">(Seine et Oise.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646900</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>EVENING IN THE FOREST OF MEUDON.  (Seine et Oise.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028307</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028307</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>EVENING IN THE FOREST OF MEUDON.  (Seine et Oise.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Returning sometimes &ldquo;from the fields of sleep,&rdquo; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;I seem to see that twilight once again,
</l><l ln="3        ">That twilight as mysterious, rich, and deep,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;As yonder blackbird's strain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">I see the sombre loveliness around; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;I feel the sense of awe, the enthralling peace,
</l><l ln="7        ">Of Nature's woodland silence, for no sound
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Makes here that silence cease.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Anon I see the waters of the lake
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Gleam in the last hues of the sunset glow,
</l><l ln="11      ">While here and there the lazy cattle slake
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Their thirst, and homeward go.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">But hear, O hear, that sudden burst of song,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;At last it is the full&hyphen;voiced nightingales!
</l><l ln="15      ">While mellow cuckoos sing, and so prolong
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Music as daylight fails.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Long hours have passed, and man and beast and bird
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Rest; yet my heart is filled with pure delight; 
</l><l ln="19      ">And lo, a single nightingale is heard
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Amid the moonless night.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="74">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646901</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE CHILD COWPER AT BERKHAMPSTEAD.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646901</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE CHILD COWPER AT BERKHAMPSTEAD.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028308</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028308</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE CHILD COWPER AT BERKHAMPSTEAD.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Lyric</attgenre></newatts>


<epigraph>
<l>&indent;&ldquo;where the gard'ner Robin, day by day,
</l><l>Drew me to school along the public way.&rdquo; 
</l><signed r="italic"><hi r="smcap">Cowper</hi>, My Mother's Picture.</signed></epigraph>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Bright beams of sunshine lit the lawn,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And all the landscape seemed as drawn
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;From some enchanter's treasure;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">The birds were singing loud and clear,
</l><l ln="5        ">But most perchance he loved to hear
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The blackbird's cheery measure.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">And while he loiter'd 'neath the trees
</l><l ln="8        ">Soft scents were wafted by the breeze
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;That blew across the hay&hyphen;field
</l><l ln="10      ">Where village children then resorted,
</l><l ln="11      ">And as among the swaths they sported
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Transformed it to a play&hyphen;field.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Did these dear visions fade away?
</l><l ln="14      ">They did&mdash;and for their death that day
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;He felt a throb of sorrow; 
</l><l ln="16      ">But gladness came in sorrow's place
</l><l ln="17      ">When Hope said with her smiling face,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&ldquo;'Twill live again to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2></div1>

