<pb n="75">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646903</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE KEEPING OF THE VOW.

<subhead>A.D. 1330.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>10Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646903</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE KEEPING OF THE VOW.  A.D. 1330.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028309</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028309</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE KEEPING OF THE VOW.  A.D. 1330.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>10Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">King Robert Bruce is dying now,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Heavily comes his breath,
</l><l ln="3        ">And that last strife 'twixt death and life
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Will soon be won by death;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Around his couch the liegemen stand; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;They heave full many a sigh,
</l><l ln="7        ">In dire dismay and grief are they
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To know their liege must die.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&ldquo;Sir James of Douglas, come!&rdquo; he cries,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&ldquo;Ever wert thou my friend,
</l><l ln="11      ">And though we part, 'tis well thou art
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;With me unto the end.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&ldquo;When great my need I vowed to God
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;If He would grant to me
</l><l ln="15      ">That war's surcease should bring us peace,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And Scotland should be free,</l></stanza>

<pb n="76">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">&ldquo;His bless&egrave;d banner I would bear
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;To holy Palestine,
</l><l ln="19      ">With arms to quell the Infidel:
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Such was your King's design.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&ldquo;Sore grieved am I that here I lie&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Death's hand upon my brow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">In vain, in vain, 'mid gnawing pain,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Do I recall my vow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&ldquo;Then promise me right faithfully,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;When I am laid at rest,
</l><l ln="27      ">That with my heart thou wilt depart
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;To do my last behest!&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">&ldquo;My liege, I pledge my knightly word,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Thy bidding shall be done,
</l><l ln="31      ">The work is sad, yet am I glad
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Such favour to have won!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">&ldquo;Safe in my bosom shall thy trust
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Abide with me for ever,
</l><l ln="35      ">Unless, perchance, in peril's hour,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;'Twere best that we should sever.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">&ldquo;So shall thy vow be kept, my king,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;To do thy last behest
</l><l ln="39      ">I swear upon the holy Rood,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;So shall thy soul have rest.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<pb n="77">

<stanza><l ln="41      ">The king smiles faintly in reply&mdash; 
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Then slowly droops his head,
</l><l ln="43      ">And on the breast of him he loved
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Robert the Bruce lies dead.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="45      ">In fit array at break of day
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;Doth Douglas soon depart,
</l><l ln="47      ">And in a casket carefully
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;He keeps that Kingly Heart.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="49      ">Crossing the main and sighting Spain,
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;He joins the truceless war
</l><l ln="51      ">Of Moor and Christian&mdash;that fierce strife
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Which rages as of yore;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="53      ">For here he knows that of a truth
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;His devoir first should be,
</l><l ln="55      ">And with his host he swells the boast
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Of Spanish chivalry.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="57      ">The armies twain on Tebas's plain
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Outspread&mdash;a goodly sight!
</l><l ln="59      ">Eager they wait with hope elate,
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;Impatient for the fight;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">The summer sunbeams on the shields
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Of warriors brightly glancing,
</l><l ln="63      ">Illume the mail of many a man
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;And many a charger prancing,
</l><l ln="65      ">And gallant crest that in the breeze
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;Full gaily now is dancing;</l></stanza>

<pb n="78">

<stanza><l ln="67      ">Each Moslem there with scimitar,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;Upon his Arab horse,
</l><l ln="69      ">Moves with a calm, a fearless mien,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;Unswerving in his course.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="71      ">Lo here at length the stately strength
</l><l ln="72      ">&indent;The Cross and Crescent wield,
</l><l ln="73      ">As deadly foes now darkly close
</l><l ln="74      ">&indent;Upon this fatal field.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="75      ">The Spaniards' stroke hath broken through
</l><l ln="76      ">&indent;The dense opposing line!
</l><l ln="77      ">Yet none the less both armies press
</l><l ln="78      ">&indent;Around their standard&hyphen;sign,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="79      ">And many a jennet of Castile
</l><l ln="80      ">&indent;Runs free with dangling rein,
</l><l ln="81      ">While many a Paynim once so proud
</l><l ln="82      ">&indent;Lies lifeless on the plain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="83      ">First in the van the Douglas rides,
</l><l ln="84      ">&indent;With all his men&hyphen;at&hyphen;arms,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="85      ">A worthy company are they
</l><l ln="86      ">&indent;To front the Paynim swarms.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="87      ">With bloody spur and loosened rein
</l><l ln="88      ">&indent;They break the stubborn foe,
</l><l ln="89      ">So swift the chase they scarce can trace
</l><l ln="90      ">&indent;The course by which they go,</l></stanza>

<pb n="79">

<stanza><l ln="91      ">Till, looking back upon their track,
</l><l ln="92      ">&indent;The Paynim ranks they see
</l><l ln="93      ">Have closed them in, 'mid dust and din
</l><l ln="94      ">&indent;With shout of wolfish glee.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="95      ">&ldquo;We find full late the danger great,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="96      ">&indent;Sir Douglas cries, &ldquo;return!
</l><l ln="97      ">And charge the foe like Scots we know
</l><l ln="98      ">&indent;The rout at Bannockburn.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="99      ">&ldquo;Surely the men who conquered then
</l><l ln="100    ">&indent;Vain Edward's mighty host
</l><l ln="101    ">Will never yield this sacred field
</l><l ln="102    ">&indent;Nor let the base Moor boast.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="103    ">So, boldly speaking, quick he turns&mdash; 
</l><l ln="104    ">&indent;He gallops to the rear&mdash; 
</l><l ln="105    ">This dauntless quest through fierce unrest
</l><l ln="106    ">&indent;As gallant doth appear
</l><l ln="107    ">As his who braves the foam&hyphen;flaked waves
</l><l ln="108    ">&indent;To succour one most dear.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="109    ">As Douglas passed the blows fell fast&mdash; 
</l><l ln="110    ">&indent;Stern was the conflict wild,
</l><l ln="111    ">With steeds and men, who ne'er again
</l><l ln="112    ">&indent;Would rise, the field was piled.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="113    ">Yet, with his followers not a few,
</l><l ln="114    ">&indent;Now he has cleft his way
</l><l ln="115    ">With flashing eye and flashing blade
</l><l ln="116    ">&indent;Straight through the grim array,</l></stanza>

<pb n="80">

<stanza><l ln="117    ">Once more he glances round, and sees,
</l><l ln="118    ">&indent;Still in the thickest fight,
</l><l ln="119    ">William Sinclair, his well&hyphen;beloved,
</l><l ln="120    ">&indent;A very valiant knight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="121    ">Full oft had they in tourney gay
</l><l ln="122    ">&indent;Their chargers deftly wheeled,
</l><l ln="123    ">Full oft were nigh in days gone by
</l><l ln="124    ">&indent;On many a battle field,&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="125    ">&ldquo;Ride to the rescue!&rdquo; Douglas shouts,
</l><l ln="126    ">&indent;&ldquo;Ride on, and do not spare,
</l><l ln="127    ">To save him from a woeful death
</l><l ln="128    ">&indent;Which of you will not dare!&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="129    ">Urging his horse with headlong force,
</l><l ln="130    ">&indent;He seeks to render aid,
</l><l ln="131    ">And many a tunic's fold is cleft
</l><l ln="132    ">&indent;By his resistless blade;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="133    ">Yet is he left, of friends bereft,
</l><l ln="134    ">&indent;Swart foemen all around,
</l><l ln="135    ">Through the echoing strokes on helm and shield
</l><l ln="136    ">&indent;Of help there comes no sound.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="137    ">Now snatches he the jewelled casque
</l><l ln="138    ">&indent;Where lies the heart he loves,
</l><l ln="139    ">('Tis strange to see how tenderly
</l><l ln="140    ">&indent;His mailed hand o'er it moves),</l></stanza>

<pb n="81">

<stanza><l ln="141    ">And flings it forward, forward yet,
</l><l ln="142    ">&indent;With this his battle cry,
</l><l ln="143    ">&ldquo;Press on, brave Heart, as thou wert wont:
</l><l ln="144    ">&indent;I follow thee, or die!&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="145    ">With lifted lance he makes advance
</l><l ln="146    ">&indent;To where his treasure fell,
</l><l ln="147    ">Each crash of blow&mdash;now fast, now slow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="148    ">&indent;Like a rude requiem knell,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="149    ">And left alone, yet ne'er o'erthrown,
</l><l ln="150    ">&indent;He grapples with the foe,
</l><l ln="151    ">Until a sword&hyphen;thrust piercing him
</l><l ln="152    ">&indent;At last doth lay him low.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="153    ">Then gallantly he struggles still,
</l><l ln="154    ">&indent;Half kneeling on the plain,
</l><l ln="155    ">And there, o'erwhelmed by many a wound,
</l><l ln="156    ">&indent;The peerless knight is slain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="157    ">So died the chief, his life well lost
</l><l ln="158    ">&indent;In Scottish hero's work,
</l><l ln="159    ">The stainless Douglas, he who sleeps
</l><l ln="160    ">&indent;In mossy Douglas kirk.</l></stanza></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="82">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646904</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE PURITAN'S FAREWELL TO HIS
BETROTHED.

<subhead>(1642.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646904</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE PURITAN'S FAREWELL TO HIS BETROTHED.  (1642.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028310</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028310</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE PURITAN'S FAREWELL TO HIS BETROTHED.  (1642.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<speaker>SHE&mdash;</speaker>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">When Love arose and taught my heart
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To hold thee first and chief,
</l><l ln="3        ">I never dreamed that we should part
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;In pain beyond belief,
</l><l ln="5        ">Then wherefore bring this aching woe
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;To me, to thee, to all,
</l><l ln="7        ">E'en though harsh Duty bids thee go
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To obey thy faction's call?</l></stanza>

<speaker>HE&mdash;</speaker>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Nay, speak not so; that sigh, that look,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Wound worse than blades of steel,
</l><l ln="11      ">Yet what were I if I forsook,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Because of thine appeal,
</l><l ln="13      ">No &ldquo;faction&rdquo; but God's righteous cause,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;No struggle of greed and shame&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">One stern last stand for Right and laws
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;That win His high acclaim?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Truth, Justice, Conscience plead with me,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Then wouldst thou have me, dear,
</l><l ln="19      ">For calm and ease and joy with thee
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;To yield to craven fear&mdash; 
</l><pb n="83">
<l ln="21      ">To prove a recreant from the right&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;A coward sore afraid&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">A traitor in the coming fight
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Where England needs mine aid?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Thou murmur'st, &ldquo;We shall meet no more:&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;I know, I know thy pain,
</l><l ln="27      ">Our life is brief, but when 'tis o'er
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;True lovers live again&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">They live again in that fair land
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Where comes nor strife nor sword&mdash; 
</l><l ln="31      ">Where Truth and Joy go hand in hand&mdash; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And Love hath Faith's reward.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">There, where each feeling stands confessed,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Wilt thou know all my sorrow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="35      ">Wilt know what pangs have rent my breast
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Ere leaving thee to&hyphen;morrow.
</l><l ln="37      ">Lo, hearken to the distant chime,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;To us a knell of sadness,
</l><l ln="39      ">Then let us spend our span of time
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;In peace more deep than gladness.</l></stanza>

<speaker>SHE&mdash;</speaker>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">The weakness goes: oh, heed it not!
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;My fears have done thee wrong; 
</l><l ln="43      ">My pain is but my woman's lot,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;And Love shall make me strong:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="45      ">In these brave arms I will be brave,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;And while thou still art here,
</l><l ln="47      ">To God will lift my soul, and crave
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;The peace which casts out fear.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="84">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646905</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE TAKING OF THE FLAG.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646905</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE TAKING OF THE FLAG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028311</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028311</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE TAKING OF THE FLAG.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;The dawning light
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Hath banished Night,
</l><l ln="3        ">Breaking the ocean's sleep&mdash; 
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;For all around
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;Is heard a sound
</l><l ln="6        ">Of war upon the deep.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">&indent;The Dutch and we
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Are met at sea
</l><l ln="9        ">On this blithe summer day,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;To try at length
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Our fighting strength
</l><l ln="12      ">In battle's bloody fray.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">&indent;See! on the right
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Two ships in fight
</l><l ln="15      ">In struggle long and hard,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And though so near,
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;They know not fear,
</l><l ln="18      ">Close grappling yard to yard.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">&indent;In very joy
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;An orphan boy
</l><l ln="21      ">Speaks 'mid the battle's roar:
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;&ldquo;Since morning's sun
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;The fight has run,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">When will it then be o'er?&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<pb n="85">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">&indent;&ldquo;'Twill never lag
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Till yon Dutch rag <edit>[Footnote 3: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016965">[3] The epithet &ldquo;Dutch rag&rdquo; is said to have been the actual
phrase used by the sailor whom Hopson addressed. The boy
had only joined the fleet on the day before as a volunteer, and
had previously been a tailor's apprentice. <hi r="italic">Vide</hi> &ldquo;Sea Fights,&rdquo; 
p.73. Professor Sir J. K. Laughton, in &ldquo;The Dictionary of National
Biography,&rdquo; expresses his opinion, however, that the incident on
which this poem is based has no historical foundation.</note>
</l><l ln="27      ">Down from the mast&hyphen;head runs,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;No other sign
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Along our line
</l><l ln="30      ">Can silence British guns.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="31      ">&indent;&ldquo;If thus it be,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Then swift quoth he
</l><l ln="33      ">With keen and flashing eye; 
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;&ldquo;'Twill soon be past,
</l><l ln="35      ">&indent;Nor longer last,
</l><l ln="36      ">Though if I fail, I die.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">&indent;Hid by the cloak
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Of sable smoke,
</l><l ln="39      ">All noiselessly he goes; 
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;He springs elate
</l><l ln="41      ">&indent;Where Death may wait
</l><l ln="42      ">Among his country's foes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="43      ">&indent;High up their mast
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;He clambers fast:
</l><l ln="45      ">He grasps his precious prize:&mdash; 
</l><pb n="86">
<l ln="46      ">&indent;He knows no check&mdash; 
</l><l ln="47      ">&indent;He gains the deck,
</l><l ln="48      ">With triumph in his eyes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="49      ">&indent;He bounds once more
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;'Mid smoke and roar
</l><l ln="51      ">To his appointed place; 
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;Fearless, serence,
</l><l ln="53      ">&indent;Is still his mien,
</l><l ln="54      ">Fearless, serene his face.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="55      ">&indent;Our men with glee
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Shout &ldquo;Victory!&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="57      ">Right glad of heart are they; 
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;And from each gun
</l><l ln="59      ">&indent;The Dutchmen run
</l><l ln="60      ">In wonder and dismay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">&indent;A sudden shame,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;Half rage, half blame,
</l><l ln="63      ">Their captain overpowers; 
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;With one accord
</l><l ln="65      ">&indent;Our sailors board,
</l><l ln="66      ">And soon the ship is ours.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="67      ">&indent;And of the youth
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;Who thus in truth
</l><l ln="69      ">Had won a hero's meed,
</l><l ln="70      ">&indent;We spoke with pride
</l><l ln="71      ">&indent;Till far and wide
</l><l ln="72      ">Was known his peerless deed.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="87">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646906</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE DEATH OF CAPTAIN HUNT.

<subhead><hi r="italic">January</hi> 8<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1761.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646906</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE DEATH OF CAPTAIN HUNT.  January 8th, 1761.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028312</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028312</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE DEATH OF CAPTAIN HUNT.  January 8th, 1761.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016966">See &ldquo;Battles of the British Navy,&rdquo; vol. i., p. 210.</note>

<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">The watch on board the <hi r="italic">Unicorn</hi> 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Look out at dawn of light,
</l><l ln="3        ">The sails are here, the sails at last!
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;The Frenchman heaves in sight.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And swiftly now the order comes
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;To give the Frenchman chase,
</l><l ln="7        ">The Frenchman who is lost, we know,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;If we can win the race.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Hurrah! the coward's flight is vain,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The ships are drawing nigh,
</l><l ln="11      ">Each man prepares to win the fight&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To win the fight or die.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">And soon the cannons' smoke and boom
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Are rolling all around,
</l><l ln="15      ">Through two fierce hours of clangorous strife
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Is heard the deadly sound;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Wild scene of strange delirious joy,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Yet desolating woe,
</l><l ln="19      ">For now a shot our captain fells,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And he is borne below.</l></stanza>

<pb n="88">

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Two seamen gently bear him down,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And while the surgeon tries
</l><l ln="23      ">To bind his wound, he looks on us
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;With tender, pitying eyes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">The strife ne'er stays&mdash;the bearers bring
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Another blood&hyphen;stained man.
</l><l ln="27      ">&ldquo;Surgeon,&rdquo; our captain says at once,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;&ldquo;Go, save him if you can.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">&ldquo;My wound is mortal; thus for me
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Your care is all in vain,
</l><l ln="31      ">Not so with him, then use your power
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;To ease his heavier pain.&rdquo;</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="33      ">Soon ebbed our captain's tide of life&mdash; 
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Short was the time for him&mdash; 
</l><l ln="35      ">Yet still his constant mind was clear
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Although his eyes grew dim.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">And in a while his heart was glad
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;For we had won the day,
</l><l ln="39      ">His noble heart was satisfied&mdash; 
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;His spirit passed away.</l></stanza></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="89">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646907</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</mainhead> <attbytes>24Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646907</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028313</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028313</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>24Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016967">(<hi r="italic">Supposed episodes at Waterloo during an imaginary
cessation of the strife and din</hi>.)</note>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646908</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

I. <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646908</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">At daybreak on a lonely sea
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Strange is the silence; heavily
</l><l ln="3        ">The louring clouds loom dim and dun,
</l><l ln="4        ">Till comes at length the far&hyphen;off sun; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Strange is the silence of the day
</l><l ln="6        ">Where waves are hushed in some fair bay; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Strange is the silence,&mdash;awesome, deep,
</l><l ln="8        ">At nightfall in an ancient keep; 
</l><l ln="9        ">Strange is the silence that ofttimes
</l><l ln="10      ">Broods o'er the city's shame and crimes; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Strange is the silence of the night
</l><l ln="12      ">Where throned in space the stars give light; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Strange is the silence of the room
</l><l ln="14      ">Where lingering sickness hangs in gloom; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Strange is the silence after death
</l><l ln="16      ">Where anguished sound departs with breath; 
</l><l ln="17      ">But stranger is the silence when
</l><l ln="18      ">The moans are stilled of wounded men,
</l><l ln="19      ">Where stilled an instant are the cries
</l><l ln="20      ">That from wild scenes of strife arise
</l><l ln="21      ">As noise of rapid volleys cease,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">As God grants here and there release,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">As suddenly the senses yield
</l><l ln="24      ">To silence on the battle&hyphen;field.</l></div3>

<pb n="90">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646909</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

II. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646909</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<l ln="25      ">In these fleet moments interposed
</l><l ln="26      ">Ere yet once more the foemen closed,
</l><l ln="27      ">In inner vision every man
</l><l ln="28      ">Lived o'er again his whole life's span.
</l><l ln="29      ">Only of plunder many thought,
</l><l ln="30      ">But here and there was one who caught
</l><l ln="31      ">Swift glimpses, borne on spirit&hyphen;wings,
</l><l ln="32      ">Of God, of Heaven, of holy things&mdash; 
</l><l ln="33      ">Who felt his courage no less high
</l><l ln="34      ">Because he was prepared to die.</l></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646910</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

III. <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646910</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<l ln="35      ">One dreams of his betrothed in France,
</l><l ln="36      ">A dark&hyphen;eyed girl with laughing glance,
</l><l ln="37      ">And wonders if he soon shall meet
</l><l ln="38      ">Her tender looks, her smile so sweet.
</l><l ln="39      ">&ldquo;Ah, ma Lucille,&rdquo; with tears he cries,
</l><l ln="40      ">&ldquo;Fain would I see the glad surprise
</l><l ln="41      ">Break the calm gaze of your dear eyes,
</l><l ln="42      ">As with high hope I come once more,
</l><l ln="43      ">Unwounded from the field of war.
</l><l ln="44      ">Fain would I see your rippling curls,
</l><l ln="45      ">More precious than those lustrous pearls
</l><l ln="46      ">My gift to you&mdash;that sometimes deck
</l><l ln="47      ">The stately beauty of your neck&mdash; 
</l><l ln="48      ">That on your bosom rise and fall,
</l><l ln="49      ">White rivals of its whiteness, all
</l><l ln="50      ">Eclipsed in utter loveliness.
</l><pb n="91">
<l ln="51      ">Fain would I see again that dress; 
</l><l ln="52      ">Its dainty hue of mellow brown
</l><l ln="53      ">Sets off the clustering curls that crown
</l><l ln="54      ">Your shapely head. Fain would I see
</l><l ln="55      ">The happy village revelry
</l><l ln="56      ">That joyous day which makes you mine&mdash; 
</l><l ln="57      ">When underneath the ancient vine
</l><l ln="58      ">Around Saint Etienne's porch we pass
</l><l ln="59      ">Just coming from the wedding Mass,
</l><l ln="60      ">And leaving near to the altar stair
</l><l ln="61      ">The <hi r="italic">cur&eacute;</hi> with his silvery hair,
</l><l ln="62      ">Low kneeling now in holy prayer,
</l><l ln="63      ">To crave a blessing on us there,
</l><l ln="64      ">His guileless, gladsome, saintly soul
</l><l ln="65      ">As spotless as his pure white stole.&rdquo;</l></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646911</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

IV. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646911</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<l ln="66      ">Another soldier sees a room
</l><l ln="67      ">O'ershadowed by a partial gloom,
</l><l ln="68      ">As heavy curtains shade the light
</l><l ln="69      ">From a wan sufferer's weakened sight,
</l><l ln="70      ">And on a couch is seen a boy,
</l><l ln="71      ">Whose wasted face, all flushed with joy,
</l><l ln="72      ">Looks on a portrait, newly there,
</l><l ln="73      ">Of a tall youth with raven hair,
</l><l ln="74      ">Clad in a garb of martial hue.
</l><l ln="75      ">And then in accents heartfelt, true,
</l><l ln="76      ">He speaks the words: &ldquo;Would that I too
</l><l ln="77      ">With my dear brother still could be
</l><l ln="78      ">Where Valour leads to Victory.&rdquo;</l></div3>

<pb n="92">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646912</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

V. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646912</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<pdiv><l ln="79      ">A Scotsman here among &ldquo;The Greys&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="80      ">Chafes inly now at war's delays,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="81      ">Would but the bugle sound the charge!
</l><l ln="82      ">Would that he were once more at large
</l><l ln="83      ">Among the flying cuirassiers!
</l><l ln="84      ">He knows no pity, knows no fears,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="85      ">For him each instant passes slow
</l><l ln="86      ">Passed not in fight against the foe,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="87      ">'Tis hard to stand, nor give one blow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="88      ">It suits his fiery humour ill
</l><l ln="89      ">To be a living target still,
</l><l ln="90      ">Nor use his good sword at his will.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="91      ">Near him &ldquo;The Inniskillings&rdquo; share
</l><l ln="92      ">A post of danger,&mdash;everywhere
</l><l ln="93      ">True soldiers they,&mdash;who greatly dare.</l></pdiv></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646913</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

VI. <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646913</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<l ln="94      ">Before an English soldier lie
</l><l ln="95      ">Down&hyphen;trodden fields of wheat and rye,
</l><l ln="96      ">But his tired vision does not meet
</l><l ln="97      ">These blood&hyphen;stained fields of rye and wheat.
</l><l ln="98      ">He sees not how his comrades here
</l><l ln="99      ">Reveal no sign of craven fear; 
</l><l ln="100    ">While they with bandaged hand or face,
</l><l ln="101    ">Still struggle on, nor quit their place.
</l><l ln="102    ">He sees not, as in many rifts
</l><l ln="103    ">The smoke of battle, rising, lifts,
</l><l ln="104    ">How everywhere all undismayed
</l><pb n="93">
<l ln="105    ">Still firm they stand as on parade,
</l><l ln="106    ">Although their thinning ranks disclose
</l><l ln="107    ">How hard with them the conflict goes.
</l><l ln="108    ">He sees the Mersey; fresh and cool
</l><l ln="109    ">The east wind blows from Liverpool
</l><l ln="110    ">To Seacombe beach, where, loitering,
</l><l ln="111    ">He stood one early morn of spring
</l><l ln="112    ">A month or two before. The day
</l><l ln="113    ">At first had seemed but chill and grey
</l><l ln="114    ">Till brilliant sunshine suddenly
</l><l ln="115    ">Had flooded all the estuary.
</l><l ln="116    ">For weeks the west wind had prevailed&mdash; 
</l><l ln="117    ">No ship, if outward bound, had sailed; 
</l><l ln="118    ">But now the fickle wind had veered,
</l><l ln="119    ">And now the sailors' hearts were cheered,
</l><l ln="120    ">While a whole fleet&mdash;a gallant show
</l><l ln="121    ">Of eager ships&mdash;was free to go.
</l><l ln="122    ">Full many a vessel, towards the bar
</l><l ln="123    ">Across the waters near and far,
</l><l ln="124    ">Moves buoyantly. With what delight
</l><l ln="125    ">He looks upon the goodly sight
</l><l ln="126    ">Of canvas spread to catch the breeze
</l><l ln="127    ">That dances o'er the rippling seas!
</l><l ln="128    ">How shapely are the skiffs which pass
</l><l ln="129    ">Between him and St. Nicholas!
</l><l ln="130    ">How graceful is the distant town,
</l><l ln="131    ">Which gaily o'er the waves looks down!
</l><l ln="132    ">Changed is the scene since 'mid the snow
</l><l ln="133    ">He saw it scarce a year ago.
</l><l ln="134    ">Then many a white and large ice&hyphen;floe
</l><l ln="135    ">Reared its strange shape on every side,
</l><l ln="136    ">While tossing idly on the tide.</l></div3>

<pb n="94">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646914</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

VII. <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646914</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<l ln="137    ">Another soldier sees his home
</l><l ln="138    ">Where whirls the wild Biscayan foam; 
</l><l ln="139    ">Where surges beat with sullen roar
</l><l ln="140    ">Upon a dreary pine&hyphen;clad shore.
</l><l ln="141    ">There his good mother yet must wait
</l><l ln="142    ">For many a month disconsolate,
</l><l ln="143    ">Waiting, still waiting for her child,
</l><l ln="144    ">With heavy heart unreconciled
</l><l ln="145    ">To his long absence&mdash;her distress
</l><l ln="146    ">At times most pitiful to guess.
</l><l ln="147    ">He sees her in her peasant's dress
</l><l ln="148    ">At household duties, at her door
</l><l ln="149    ">At eve and morning, evermore
</l><l ln="150    ">Thinking with heavy heart of him; 
</l><l ln="151    ">With unshed tears her eyes grow dim,
</l><l ln="152    ">Looking, aye looking constantly,
</l><l ln="153    ">Across the same sad, dreary sea.
</l><l ln="154    ">Again he hears the gleeful noise
</l><l ln="155    ">And clatter of the village boys,
</l><l ln="156    ">He even hears the sound once more
</l><l ln="157    ">Of <hi r="italic">sabots</hi> on a cottage floor.
</l><l ln="158    ">Again it seems that mournful day
</l><l ln="159    ">When he, alas, was called away; 
</l><l ln="160    ">Again he sees the fishing&hyphen;boat
</l><l ln="161    ">&indent;That comes to bear him to the town; 
</l><l ln="162    ">Again his home grows more remote
</l><l ln="163    ">&indent;As o'er the sea the sun goes down.
</l><l ln="164    ">Still he beholds his mother's face,
</l><l ln="165    ">And still he feels her warm embrace,
</l><l ln="166    ">He knows her anguished doubts, her fears,
</l><pb n="95">
<l ln="167    ">And would&hyphen;be smiles, he feels her tears.
</l><l ln="168    ">He hears the heaving waters nigh&mdash; 
</l><l ln="169    ">He sees, above, an angry sky,
</l><l ln="170    ">Dark, yet with streaks of mingled grey,
</l><l ln="171    ">Fading while swiftly dies the day.
</l><l ln="172    ">He passes to the gathering gloom
</l><l ln="173    ">As though to some impending doom; 
</l><l ln="174    ">Drear seems the earth, the sky, the main&mdash; 
</l><l ln="175    ">He feels that Nature knows his pain.</l></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646915</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

VIII. <attbytes>8Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646915</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<pdiv><l ln="176    ">A youthful soldier looked around
</l><l ln="177    ">Upon the ghastly battle ground.
</l><l ln="178    ">He was a conscript, ne'er before
</l><l ln="179    ">Had he beheld the face of War,
</l><l ln="180    ">He saw not all its deeps of pain,
</l><l ln="181    ">For former scenes arose again,
</l><l ln="182    ">Once more he was a child at play,
</l><l ln="183    ">In that steep village street which lay,
</l><l ln="184    ">Crag&hyphen;perched, 'mid tree&hyphen;boles gnarled and grey
</l><l ln="185    ">With age. It was the close of day.
</l><l ln="186    ">Was that the church he knew of old,
</l><l ln="187    ">That the rude cross where he was told
</l><l ln="188    ">The story of the ancient time
</l><l ln="189    ">So full of mystery, lust, and crime?
</l><l ln="190    ">Ah, how he loved yon olive wood,
</l><l ln="191    ">To him how sweet its solitude,
</l><l ln="192    ">How oft on many a summer night
</l><l ln="193    ">He watched from there the fading light,
</l><l ln="194    ">Till grew more bright and yet more bright
</l><l ln="195    ">The distant lamps of great Marseilles,
</l><pb n="96">
<l ln="196    ">And when at length the daylight fails,
</l><l ln="197    ">Fair seem the stars, fair seems the sea,
</l><l ln="198    ">Ah, how at once his memory
</l><l ln="199    ">Brings back for him these moonlit hours
</l><l ln="200    ">'Mid fragrance of the orange flowers.
</l><l ln="201    ">Fresh is the air, and soft and still,
</l><l ln="202    ">Save when the <hi r="italic">mistral</hi> brings its chill.
</l><l ln="203    ">Once more he feels the morning breeze
</l><l ln="204    ">Which gently curls the azure seas
</l><l ln="205    ">Around his father's fishing&hyphen;boat,
</l><l ln="206    ">That like a live thing seems to float.
</l><l ln="207    ">Lovely it looks with dark brown sail,
</l><l ln="208    ">Outspread to catch each gentle gale.
</l><l ln="209    ">And when the noontide comes at length
</l><l ln="210    ">The crew refresh their waning strength
</l><l ln="211    ">By frugal meal, or merry jest,
</l><l ln="212    ">By games, or cheerful talk, or rest.
</l><l ln="213    ">One man had fought where waned the star
</l><l ln="214    ">Of France in fight off Trafalgar; 
</l><l ln="215    ">Another speaks of Austerlitz,
</l><l ln="216    ">And shows the combat as he sits.
</l><l ln="217    ">With eager words, with eyes aflame,
</l><l ln="218    ">He tells the tale, &ldquo;The Emperor came
</l><l ln="219    ">To our right flank when sore distressed:
</l><l ln="220    ">We needed succour, needed rest,
</l><l ln="221    ">Yet better was his presence then
</l><l ln="222    ">Than of a thousand untired men.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="223    ">So, early stirred the martial fire
</l><l ln="224    ">In the boy's breast&mdash;the fond desire
</l><l ln="225    ">To win the soldier's honoured name,
</l><l ln="226    ">To win the soldier's meed of fame.
</l><pb n="97">
<l ln="227    ">To him an order comes ere long
</l><l ln="228    ">To join the army; 'mid a throng
</l><l ln="229    ">Of youths he gains a barrack square,
</l><l ln="230    ">Strange seems the ceaseless bustle there.
</l><l ln="231    ">Here well&hyphen;groomed horses drink their fill; 
</l><l ln="232    ">Here is an active squad at drill; 
</l><l ln="233    ">Here words of gaiety he hears; 
</l><l ln="234    ">And here a mother stands in tears; 
</l><l ln="235    ">Here stands a veteran hale, erect,
</l><l ln="236    ">In garb that points to no neglect,
</l><l ln="237    ">Though he has marched full many a mile,
</l><l ln="238    ">In blazing sunshine all the while,
</l><l ln="239    ">A faultless soldier he has been,
</l><l ln="240    ">No chance of war could change his mien; 
</l><l ln="241    ">Here stands a youth with shambling gait,
</l><l ln="242    ">In soldier's dress, yet unelate,
</l><l ln="243    ">With stupid look, and vacant face,
</l><l ln="244    ">As though his garb were some disgrace; 
</l><l ln="245    ">Here agile gunners clean a gun; 
</l><l ln="246    ">And here, his day's work nearly done,
</l><l ln="247    ">A driver of the army train
</l><l ln="248    ">Brings in his store of food and grain.
</l><l ln="249    ">The conscript thinks with what glad heart
</l><l ln="250    ">In scenes like these he took a part.
</l><l ln="251    ">With joy his boy's heart overflows,
</l><l ln="252    ">He longs to smite his country's foes,
</l><l ln="253    ">Of what he leaves he scarce takes heed,
</l><l ln="254    ">Civilian clothes he doffs with speed,
</l><l ln="255    ">To him his uniform brings life,
</l><l ln="256    ">He thinks of glory in the strife.
</l><l ln="257    ">He thinks, as now the sun goes down,
</l><pb n="98">
<l ln="258    ">Of lasting honour and renown; 
</l><l ln="259    ">To him War is not sad, but strange&mdash; 
</l><l ln="260    ">It gives him motion, stir, and change.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="261    ">Through all the long, the happy marches
</l><l ln="262    ">&indent;Across Provence, now bright with spring,
</l><l ln="263    ">He sees the gay triumphal arches,
</l><l ln="264    ">&indent;He hears once more the joy&hyphen;bells ring.
</l><l ln="265    ">And then one day, through beat of drums,
</l><l ln="266    ">He hears the cry, &ldquo;The Emperor comes,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="267    ">&ldquo;The Emperor comes&rdquo;&mdash;on every side
</l><l ln="268    ">They pass the word with looks of pride.
</l><l ln="269    ">Each soldier feels his courage rise,
</l><l ln="270    ">Fresh pleasure sparkles in his eyes,
</l><l ln="271    ">And while he stands the more upright,
</l><l ln="272    ">Sees his accoutrements are bright,
</l><l ln="273    ">And hopes his bayonet, sword, or lance
</l><l ln="274    ">Will seem to that all&hyphen;piercing glance
</l><l ln="275    ">As sword or bayonet ought to look.
</l><l ln="276    ">For who could bear the sharp rebuke
</l><l ln="277    ">Or face his comrades' words or jeers,
</l><l ln="278    ">Or worse, his comrades' covert sneers,
</l><l ln="279    ">At one the Emperor deigned to chide?</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="280    ">An hour has gone; the corps espied
</l><l ln="281    ">The staff approaching, near a wood.
</l><l ln="282    ">It stood to arms. Kind Nature's mood
</l><l ln="283    ">Was peaceful: there the stock&hyphen;dove coo'd; 
</l><l ln="284    ">The dreamer sees one purple flower,
</l><l ln="285    ">Which decked the spot that sunny hour.
</l><l ln="286    ">&ldquo;The Emperor is an altered man
</l><pb n="99">
<l ln="287    ">Since Leipsic,&rdquo; says a veteran.
</l><l ln="288    ">And yet the great Napoleon seems
</l><l ln="289    ">The ideal of a soldier's dreams,
</l><l ln="290    ">As now he passes on his course,
</l><l ln="291    ">Erect upon his snow&hyphen;white horse
</l><l ln="292    ">Amid his marshals. Soult and Ney,
</l><l ln="293    ">Heroes of many a well&hyphen;fought day,
</l><l ln="294    ">Ride near him now, in gayest trim.
</l><l ln="295    ">They jest, and sometimes speak with him&mdash; 
</l><l ln="296    ">Yet never seem to lose the sense&mdash; 
</l><l ln="297    ">Of that strange man's strange influence&mdash; 
</l><l ln="298    ">Of that magnetic, cruel power
</l><l ln="299    ">By which Napoleon, hour by hour,
</l><l ln="300    ">Until his fiery race was run,
</l><l ln="301    ">Remorselessly swayed every one.
</l><l ln="302    ">Firm are his lips, stern are his eyes&mdash; 
</l><l ln="303    ">Hard eyes, where naught of gladness lies; 
</l><l ln="304    ">Yes signs there are of wasting life,
</l><l ln="305    ">Wasting through care and lust of strife,
</l><l ln="306    ">That drooping lip, that haggard cheek,
</l><l ln="307    ">Of pain, of ebbing force, they speak.
</l><l ln="308    ">But none, save veterans here and there,
</l><l ln="309    ">Perceive his chill, his altered air; 
</l><l ln="310    ">The troops, o'erjoyed to see his face,
</l><l ln="311    ">See in his glance a sign of grace:
</l><l ln="312    ">His presence cures their every ill,
</l><l ln="313    ">And &ldquo;Vive l'Empereur!&rdquo; their shout is still.</l></pdiv></pdiv></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646916</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

IX. <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646916</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<pdiv><l ln="314    ">A tranquil, sunlit village green
</l><l ln="315    ">Sees one young Englishman: between
</l><pb n="100">
<l ln="316    ">A row of elms he catches sight
</l><l ln="317    ">Of one dear cottage; to the right
</l><l ln="318    ">Lies the grey rectory, and beyond
</l><l ln="319    ">Old Farmer Granger's ricks and pond,
</l><l ln="320    ">Just where the high road quickly dips.
</l><l ln="321    ">Here as a child he sailed his ships,
</l><l ln="322    ">While loafers from the alehouse near
</l><l ln="323    ">Gladdened his heart by words of cheer,
</l><l ln="324    ">And showed him how to set his sail,
</l><l ln="325    ">To woo the soft, the favouring gale.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="326    ">He sees again the long sea beach
</l><l ln="327    ">A mile or two from home; the reach
</l><l ln="328    ">The farm&hyphen;folk call the Little Broad
</l><l ln="329    ">Gleams in the sun, while boys applaud
</l><l ln="330    ">His feats of strength; or on the sea
</l><l ln="331    ">Perchance he rows right merrily,
</l><l ln="332    ">While myriad skylarks, singing, soar
</l><l ln="333    ">Above the sand cliffs on the shore; 
</l><l ln="334    ">Or looking seaward from the land
</l><l ln="335    ">He views the sunset vague and grand.</l></pdiv></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646917</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

X. <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646917</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<pdiv><l ln="336    ">A Frenchman thinks with many a fear
</l><l ln="337    ">Of his one sister&mdash;very dear
</l><l ln="338    ">Is she to him, a girl most fair.
</l><l ln="339    ">He sees e'en now her dark&hyphen;brown hair,
</l><l ln="340    ">And inly speaks, &ldquo;Herself a flower
</l><l ln="341    ">She hawks sweet blossoms hour by hour
</l><l ln="342    ">Through many a parched Parisian street,
</l><pb n="101">
<l ln="343    ">Gladly, though oft with toil&hyphen;worn feet.
</l><l ln="344    ">'Tis she who wins the daily bread
</l><l ln="345    ">And shelter for my father's head,
</l><l ln="346    ">Since age and sickness disallow
</l><l ln="347    ">Him strength to earn his living now; 
</l><l ln="348    ">While I, who should have been their stay,
</l><l ln="349    ">Without appeal am forced away,
</l><l ln="350    ">Simply because some men&mdash;whose aims
</l><l ln="351    ">I do not know and scarce their names&mdash; 
</l><l ln="352    ">Have fixedly resolved on War.
</l><l ln="353    ">And I&mdash;one of their human store&mdash; 
</l><l ln="354    ">Am made to face death at their will
</l><l ln="355    ">Till kings and emperors have their fill.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="356    ">How strange are we! he who so dreamed
</l><l ln="357    ">And all unpatriotic seemed,
</l><l ln="358    ">When fierce again began the strife,
</l><l ln="359    ">Fought with the best&mdash;cared not for life.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="360    ">The vision changes, and he sees
</l><l ln="361    ">The comely, the belov&egrave;d trees
</l><l ln="362    ">That droop in summer's sultry blaze,
</l><l ln="363    ">Along the white Parisian ways.
</l><l ln="364    ">In one old street he sees a spot
</l><l ln="365    ">Shaded by lime&hyphen;trees: there is not
</l><l ln="366    ">A cooler nook, and side by side
</l><l ln="367    ">An old man and a maid abide
</l><l ln="368    ">In sweet affectionate converse there,
</l><l ln="369    ">To rest, to breathe its fresher air.
</l><l ln="370    ">'Tis those he loves, and for a space
</l><l ln="371    ">He treads himself that well&hyphen;known place,
</l><pb n="102">
<l ln="372    ">So keen his inner sight. And soon
</l><l ln="373    ">His sister starts through afternoon
</l><l ln="374    ">Long hours, and near the Tuileries
</l><l ln="375    ">She stays, then moves along the quays.
</l><l ln="376    ">She is so fair, so pure, so sweet,
</l><l ln="377    ">She seems to gladden all the street.
</l><l ln="378    ">And many glance at her, and smile; 
</l><l ln="379    ">They note her brave looks all the while,
</l><l ln="380    ">They know her toil of every day,
</l><l ln="381    ">Toil such as wears her youth away.
</l><l ln="382    ">And one, an honest artisan,
</l><l ln="383    ">A homely, upright, thrifty man,
</l><l ln="384    ">Poring o'er some long cherished plan,
</l><l ln="385    ">Passing, thinks, &ldquo;Would she were my wife,
</l><l ln="386    ">Happy were I though hard my life.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="387    ">And with a Frenchman's frugal care
</l><l ln="388    ">He saves, and saving, dreams of her.
</l><l ln="389    ">Although from childhood's earliest days
</l><l ln="390    ">She knew the drear Parisian ways
</l><l ln="391    ">(Gay to the rich, drear to the poor),
</l><l ln="392    ">From every harm she walks secure,
</l><l ln="393    ">From virtue none her steps allure.
</l><l ln="394    ">In thought, in actions, she is good,
</l><l ln="395    ">Kindness her constant habitude.
</l><l ln="396    ">She raises soft and pleading eyes
</l><l ln="397    ">With something of a chaste surprise
</l><l ln="398    ">At many a word, at many a sight,
</l><l ln="399    ">That comes to her by day, by night.
</l><l ln="400    ">All innocence without, within,
</l><l ln="401    ">She sees, yet sees not, all their sin.</l></pdiv></div3>

<pb n="103">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646918</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

XI. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646918</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BATTLE'S PAUSE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<pdiv><l ln="402    ">Thus runs each hapless soldier's dream
</l><l ln="403    ">In that short pause&mdash;that restful gleam
</l><l ln="404    ">Of bless&egrave;d peace.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="405    ">                          But, hark, there comes
</l><l ln="406    ">The gathering roll of distant drums
</l><l ln="407    ">Beating the charge, and then the sound
</l><l ln="408    ">Of musketry. Men gaze around
</l><l ln="409    ">Half in surprise&mdash;then hear again
</l><l ln="410    ">The clash of arms, the cry of pain,
</l><l ln="411    ">The wounded horse's neigh; and so
</l><l ln="412    ">Fateful with pain the gaunt hours go.</l></pdiv></div3></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646919</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE LOSS OF H.M.S. &ldquo;VICTORIA.&rdquo; 

<subhead><hi r="italic">June 22nd</hi>, 1893.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646919</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE LOSS OF H.M.S. &ldquo;VICTORIA.&rdquo;   June 22nd, 1893.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028314</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028314</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE LOSS OF H.M.S. &ldquo;VICTORIA.&rdquo;   June 22nd, 1893.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Let Britain mourn for these her gallant sons,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Who, seeing death was certain, yet remained
</l><l ln="3        ">Steadfast to duty, all unconsciously
</l><l ln="4        ">Grown to be heroes,&mdash;mourn for them whose souls,
</l><l ln="5        ">Fired with immortal courage, conquered fear.
</l><l ln="6        ">Let Britain grieve with them who, silent, weep
</l><l ln="7        ">A loss irreparable with bitter tears.
</l><l ln="8        ">Let Britain grieve for him who, though he erred
</l><l ln="9        ">Soon felt perchance, in feeling he had erred,
</l><l ln="10      ">An agony more great than death itself.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="11      ">Let Britain still rejoice, for now she knows,
</l><l ln="12      ">Though Time and Science change the face of war,
</l><l ln="13      ">The stuff of British hearts they cannot change.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="104">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646920</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TRUE SONS OF BRITAIN.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646920</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TRUE SONS OF BRITAIN.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028315</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028315</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TRUE SONS OF BRITAIN.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph r="italic">&ldquo;The heart of the colony is with her Imperial mother.&rdquo;&mdash;</epigraph>
<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016968">Extract from a resolution at a meeting to raise a volunteer contingent
for South Africa, held at St. John's, Newfoundland.</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">True sons of Britain, though your home
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Is not these isles amid the foam,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Ye come across the unfettered sea,
</l><l ln="4        ">Speaking the world&hyphen;speech of the free.
</l><l ln="5        ">Your mother needs you; and from far
</l><l ln="6        ">Ye haste, with dreams of Trafalgar,
</l><l ln="7        ">Of Wolfe, of Wellington, and all
</l><l ln="8        ">Who, like heroic Gordon, fall.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">Her daughter&hyphen;lands no more apart,
</l><l ln="10      ">Proud Britain feels her mother's heart
</l><l ln="11      ">Throb with fond joy as now she shows
</l><l ln="12      ">A steadfast front to all her foes.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Constant ye stand; nor fear the foe,
</l><l ln="14      ">True is your aim as his; although
</l><l ln="15      ">Each league upon the veldt he knows,
</l><l ln="16      ">And every league is strange to those
</l><l ln="17      ">Who come, like you, from far and nigh,
</l><l ln="18      ">In Britain's cause to live or die; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Ready for her to shed their blood,
</l><l ln="20      ">To seal eternal brotherhood.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="21      ">Her daughter&hyphen;lands no more apart,
</l><l ln="22      ">Proud Britain feels her mother's heart
</l><l ln="23      ">Throb with fond joy as now she shows
</l><l ln="24      ">A steadfast front to all her foes.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="105">

<pdiv><l ln="25      ">Greater than Carthage, Rome, or Greece,
</l><l ln="26      ">Is now your mother grown; and peace
</l><l ln="27      ">Is still her watchword, prayer, and hope,
</l><l ln="28      ">Yet with her foes she aye must cope; 
</l><l ln="29      ">Or cast her honour from its place; 
</l><l ln="30      ">Or lose the freedom of her race; 
</l><l ln="31      ">Or lose the Empire, all her own,
</l><l ln="32      ">The vastest that the world has known.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="33      ">Her daughter&hyphen;lands no more apart,
</l><l ln="34      ">Proud Britain feels her mother's heart
</l><l ln="35      ">Throb with fond joy as now she shows
</l><l ln="36      ">A steadfast front to all her foes.</l></pdiv>

<signed><hi r="italic">November</hi> 10<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1899.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646921</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>QUEEN VICTORIA.

<subhead><hi r="italic">Obiit., January</hi> 22<hi r="italic">nd</hi>, 1901.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646921</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>QUEEN VICTORIA.  Obiit., January 22nd, 1901.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028316</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028316</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>QUEEN VICTORIA.  Obiit., January 22nd, 1901.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">The musician Grief
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With mystic power hath played upon the heart,
</l><l ln="3        ">And, through the heart, hath opened wide the door
</l><l ln="4        ">Of that most sacred sanctuary&mdash;the soul.
</l><l ln="5        ">Each of us is an instrument; and each
</l><l ln="6        ">Is, in some notes at least, diversely strung
</l><l ln="7        ">From all our fellows; yet in this we know
</l><l ln="8        ">One harmony of universal love.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">                                             We seem to see
</l><l ln="10      ">The wintry woods around thy &ldquo;palace walls&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Above the tossing Channel, fraught with much
</l><pb n="106">
<l ln="12      ">Of Britain's story, and we think of him,
</l><l ln="13      ">Thy friend, our Tennyson, whose &ldquo;clear call&rdquo; brought
</l><l ln="14      ">&ldquo;No moaning of the bar.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">                                    No more, no more
</l><l ln="16      ">Shall thy loved Scotland know thy kindly face
</l><l ln="17      ">Among her hills and glens; nor shalt thou join
</l><l ln="18      ">Again in her dear customs; or in these
</l><l ln="19      ">Religious rites of hers, homely and sweet.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="20      ">Once we remembered that thou wert for us
</l><l ln="21      ">The mighty Personage whose reign hath seen
</l><l ln="22      ">A grandeur greater even than the days
</l><l ln="23      ">Of Shakespeare and of Ralegh; that to thee
</l><l ln="24      ">We owed wise counsel, fruit of toilsome hours
</l><l ln="25      ">Of patient thought, and converse with the men
</l><l ln="26      ">Of genius who have graced our commonwealth
</l><l ln="27      ">For three and sixty years; a queen whose realms
</l><l ln="28      ">Rich with the spoils of Science, had grown strong
</l><l ln="29      ">With valiant Colonies which girt the world.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="30      ">To&hyphen;day we deem that thy long, blameless life
</l><l ln="31      ">Hath aided, under God, our race to grow
</l><l ln="32      ">The noblest on this earth.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="33      ">                                       And now, and now
</l><l ln="34      ">For thee we pray not; for ourselves we pray:
</l><l ln="35      ">With thee 'tis well.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

<div1>
<comhd1><idref>Z100646922</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

MISCELLANEOUS
SONNETS. <attbytes>11Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100646922</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>

<pb n="107">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646923</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AN AUTUMN REMINISCENCE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646923</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AN AUTUMN REMINISCENCE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028317</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028317</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AN AUTUMN REMINISCENCE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">A radiant garden rises on my view
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Where through the glowing hours the sunrays fall
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Gently through hazel boughs; while brooklets brawl
</l><l ln="4        ">O'er beds where gleam the pebbles brown and blue.
</l><l ln="5        ">Here, in that calm which never once they knew
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;On earth, dead heroes keep the slopes in thrall&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;And russet ferns thereon, and dahlias tall,
</l><l ln="8        ">And lilies white, and flowers of mingled hue.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">Small wonder that these storied warrior forms
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Should now in sculptured stone have rest, when I
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;&indent;Find here that Life's fierce conflicts seem to cease&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">Find respite here from all Life's rudest storms:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Where still and silent 'neath a pale grey sky
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Fair and contented Nature lies at peace.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="108">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646924</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT THE GRAVE OF DANTE GABRIEL
ROSSETTI.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646924</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT THE GRAVE OF DANTE GABRIEL ROSSETTI.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028318</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028318</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT THE GRAVE OF DANTE GABRIEL ROSSETTI.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<signed><hi r="italic">April</hi> 9<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1883.</signed>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016969">Rossetti died at Birchington&hyphen;on&hyphen;Sea, Kent, on the 9th of
April, 1882.</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Here of a truth the world's extremes are met:
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Amid the grey&mdash;the moss&hyphen;grown tombs of those
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Who led long lives obscure till came the close
</l><l ln="4        ">When, their calm days being done, their suns were set&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Here stands a grave, all monumentless yet,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Wrapt like the others in a deep repose; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;But while yon wakeful ocean ebbs and flows
</l><l ln="8        ">It is a grave the world shall not forget&mdash;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">This grave on which meek violets grow and thyme,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Summer's fair heralds; and a stranger now
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;&indent;Pauses to see a poet's resting&hyphen;place,
</l><l ln="12      ">But one of those who will in many a clime
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;On each return of this sad day avow
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Fond love's regret that ne'er they saw his face.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646925</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>BROWNING'S FUNERAL.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646925</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BROWNING'S FUNERAL.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028319</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028319</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BROWNING'S FUNERAL.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Elegy</attgenre><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646926</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

I.

<subhead><hi r="italic">Venice, December</hi> 15<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1889.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646926</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BROWNING'S FUNERAL.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016970">&ldquo;The body of Robert Browning was conveyed to a gondola
which had the figure of an angel at the prow and a lion at the
stern, and was covered with flowers. The relations and friends
followed in gondolas across the lagoon, in the light of the setting
sun, to the cemetery.&rdquo;</note>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Now &ldquo;past they glide,&rdquo; and bear the flower&hyphen;wreathed bier
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Across the soundless waters, cold and grey,
</l><pb n="109">
<l ln="3        ">Ere Night falls, sable&hyphen;vestured and austere,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And Day dies in one roseate flush away,
</l><l ln="5        ">While they who follow, tearful, in the train
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;See wonted sights with unfamiliar eyes;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Like dreams, amid the fevered sleep of pain,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Rich domes and frescoed palaces arise.
</l><l ln="9        ">Yet haply, mixed with sorrow, dawns the thought
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;How fit such obsequies for him whose pen
</l><l ln="11      ">Hath given a wondrous poem, <edit>[Footnote 4: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016971">[4] See Browning's poem, entitled &ldquo;In a Gondola.&rdquo;</note> passion&hyphen;fraught,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Breathing of love and Venice,&mdash;unto men:
</l><l ln="13      ">And so hath added to her deathless glory
</l><l ln="14      ">A shining scroll of pure and ageless story.</l></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646927</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

II.

<subhead><hi r="italic">Westminster Abbey, December</hi> 31<hi r="italic">st</hi>, 1889.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646927</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BROWNING'S FUNERAL.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016972">The music of Croft and Purcell was used &ldquo;as the body was
brought into Church, and for the processional parts of the burial
service. This was followed by a &lsquo;meditation,&rsquo; composed for the
service by Dr. Bridge, the words from Elizabeth Barrett Browning's
&lsquo;He giveth His belov&eacute;d Sleep.&rsquo;&rdquo;</note>

<l ln="15      ">Croft's solemn music swells; then comes at last
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;The dim procession through the panelled choir; 
</l><l ln="17      ">And in the cloistral gloom, so still and vast,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Many who loved him listen. Higher and higher
</l><l ln="19      ">Rise Purcell's dirge&hyphen;like tones, Grief's very soul,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Yet soon &ldquo;He giveth His belov&egrave;d Sleep&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Brings to our anguished hearts relief, control,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Memories of stately Florence, and the deep
</l><l ln="23      ">Love&hyphen;sacrament which bound him to his spouse
</l><pb n="110">
<l ln="24      ">&indent;Changeless through changeful years. And now in heaven
</l><l ln="25      ">They meet in bliss&mdash;meet to renew their vows
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Beyond the soiling touch of earthly leaven.
</l><l ln="27      ">While England, as 'tis right, in sacred trust
</l><l ln="28      ">Keeps through the centuries his hallowed dust.</l></div3></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646928</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN MEMORIAM, W. E. FORSTER.

<subhead><hi r="italic">Obiit., April</hi> 5<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1886.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646928</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN MEMORIAM, W. E. FORSTER.  Obiit., April 5th, 1886.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028320</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028320</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN MEMORIAM, W. E. FORSTER.  Obiit., April 5th, 1886.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Elegy</attgenre><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">O stalwart man and pure, whose earnest face
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Mirrored thy fair&hyphen;orbed soul, whose every deed
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Made answer to thy word, who gav'st no heed
</l><l ln="4        ">To selfish babble or the lust of place,
</l><l ln="5        ">Who&mdash;grieving at thy country's perilous case
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Grown dire by lack of knowledge&mdash;in her need
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Cam'st with thy succour&mdash;thou whose civic creed,
</l><l ln="8        ">Too wide for party, dealt with all the race.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">A year hath passed since thou wast laid to rest,
</l><l ln="10      ">Yet fragrant is thy memory; thy bequest
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;A work whose scope and grandeur Time shall gauge.
</l><l ln="12      ">Britain some day&mdash;her daughter&hyphen;lands apart
</l><l ln="13      ">No longer&mdash;will remember thee whose heart
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Fired hers to win her world&hyphen;wide heritage.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="111">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646929</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO A LADY PLAYING THE HARP IN HER

CHAMBER.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">The Countess Rosalie Von Sauerma&hyphen;Z&uuml;lzendorf,
niece of Spohr</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646929</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO A LADY PLAYING THE HARP IN HER  CHAMBER.  (The Countess Rosalie Von Sauerma&hyphen;Z&uuml;lzendorf, niece of Spohr.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028321</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028321</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO A LADY PLAYING THE HARP IN HER  CHAMBER.  (The Countess Rosalie Von Sauerma&hyphen;Z&uuml;lzendorf, niece of Spohr.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<stanza><caption>I</caption>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Lady, whose conscious fingers sweep the strings
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;With all the true musician's living power,
</l><l ln="3        ">I watch your hand, your gentle hand, which clings
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To that loved harp which has your touch for dower.
</l><l ln="5        ">How perfect is your skill, the fruit of years&mdash; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Years full of labour, years of patient thought
</l><l ln="7        ">Such tones as yours can move the heart to tears:
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;With keen delight such tones as yours are fraught.
</l><l ln="9        ">Now while the soft notes in their sweetness rise,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Now while the wave of music dies away,
</l><l ln="11      ">I seem to see the soul which lights your eyes&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The soul which lends the magic while you play.
</l><l ln="13      ">To Music's self how deep is your devotion!
</l><l ln="14      ">Your strains are not mere Art&mdash;they are Emotion.</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption>II</caption>

<l ln="15      ">You told me once of that dear mother's love
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Whose goodness was the sunshine of your youth,
</l><l ln="17      ">Whose smile &ldquo;made paradise&rdquo; for you, who strove
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;To point the way to happy paths of Truth.
</l><pb n="112">
<l ln="19      ">You told me how through Life's dark days of grief&mdash; 
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Through all Life's dreary days of changeful care&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">The thought of her fond love could bring relief,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;The thought of her fond love could quell despair.
</l><l ln="23      ">And now I know that in your music's sweetness,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;In its most subtle power to move the heart,
</l><l ln="25      ">In its true grandeur, in its rare completeness,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Your mother's hallowed influence has a part&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">An influence present yet and ceasing never,
</l><l ln="28      ">An influence gathering strength and beauty ever.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646930</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>OLD YEAR LEAVES.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646930</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>OLD YEAR LEAVES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028322</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028322</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>OLD YEAR LEAVES.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Sonnet</attgenre></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Tossed by the storms of Autumn chill and drear,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The leaves fall auburn&hyphen;tinted, and the trees
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Stand reft and bare, yet on the silent leas
</l><l ln="4        ">The leaves lie drifted still&mdash;while cold, austere,
</l><l ln="5        ">Grim Winter waits&mdash;while early snowdrops cheer
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The woodland shadows&mdash;while the happy bees
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Are wakened by the balmy western breeze,
</l><l ln="8        ">And birds and boughs proclaim that Spring is here.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">So lost hopes severed by the stress of life
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Lie all unburied yet before our eyes,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;&indent;Though none but we regard their mute decay; 
</l><l ln="12      ">And ever amid this stir and moil and strife
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Fresh aims and growing purposes arise
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;&indent;Above the faded hopes of yesterday.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

