<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646932</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE TWO TRYSTS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646932</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE TWO TRYSTS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028323</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028323</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE TWO TRYSTS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Where tangled boughs of hazel cast
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Deep shadows on their way,
</l><l ln="3        ">A lingering youth and maiden stand
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;As dies the summer day; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Sweet is the air, and fragrant yet
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;With many a wayside flower; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Nature is joyous; yet their hearts
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Are sad this twilight hour.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&ldquo;How shall I bear to lose you, dear,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The hapless lover cries; 
</l><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;No more to see your face, nor find
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The love&hyphen;glow in your eyes?&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="13      ">One kiss, one sob, and then they part,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And life is bitterness,
</l><l ln="15      ">As through their tears each form beloved
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Grows dimly less and less.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Slow pass the lagging years; and now
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;They meet&mdash;they meet at last,
</l><pb n="114">
<l ln="19      ">Each fairer in the other's eyes
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;For all their sorrow past:
</l><l ln="21      ">Upon their way no shadows fall
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;On this fair morn of June; 
</l><l ln="23      ">When birds and happy bees rejoice,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And all the world's in tune.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646933</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE HAWTHORN SPRAY.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646933</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE HAWTHORN SPRAY.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028324</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028324</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE HAWTHORN SPRAY.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Happy, with that strange happiness
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Which Spring spreads o'er the land,
</l><l ln="3        ">I see a girl, I see a boy,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;They are walking hand in hand.
</l><l ln="5        ">I hear them as they gaily talk,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;They heed no future care,
</l><l ln="7        ">He plucks a flushing hawthorn spray
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To deck her fairer hair.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&ldquo;And let this be a token now,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The merry boy exclaims,
</l><l ln="11      ">&ldquo;That, some time in the coming years,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;We two may link our names.
</l><l ln="13      ">The may&hyphen;buds are a symbol meet
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of this our treaty pure,
</l><l ln="15      ">So may our compact bring us joy
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And evermore endure.&rdquo;</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">These two&mdash;though many years have fled&mdash; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Fled like a dream away,
</l><l ln="19      ">Are still as true of heart as on
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;That unforgotten day.
</l><pb n="115">
<l ln="21      ">And so together oft again
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Amid the spring&hyphen;tide's glow
</l><l ln="23      ">They walk, remembering thankfully
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Their love&hyphen;pledge long ago.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646934</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>SPRING'S IMMORTALITY.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646934</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>SPRING'S IMMORTALITY.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028325</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028325</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SPRING'S IMMORTALITY.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">The buds awake at touch of Spring
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;From Winter's joyless dream; 
</l><l ln="3        ">From many a stone the ouzels sing
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;By yonder mossy stream.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">The cuckoo's voice, from copse and vale,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Lingers, as if to meet
</l><l ln="7        ">The music of the nightingale
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Across the rising wheat&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">The bird whom ancient Solitude
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Hath kept for ever young,
</l><l ln="11      ">Unaltered since in studious mood
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Calm Milton mused and sung.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Ah, strange it is, dear heart, to know
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Spring's gladsome mystery
</l><l ln="15      ">Was sweet to lovers long ago&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Most sweet to such as we&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">That fresh new leaves and meadow flowers
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Bloomed when the south wind came; 
</l><pb n="116">
<l ln="19      ">While hands of Spring caressed the bowers,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;The throstle sang the same.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Unchanged, unchanged the throstle's song,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Unchanged Spring's answering breath,
</l><l ln="23      ">Unchanged, though cruel Time was strong,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And stilled our love in death.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646935</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A MUSICIAN'S WIFE TO HER HUSBAND.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646935</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A MUSICIAN'S WIFE TO HER HUSBAND.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028326</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028326</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A MUSICIAN'S WIFE TO HER HUSBAND.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">As</hi> rain each fainting flower revives
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Which droops at close of day,
</l><l ln="3        ">Thy music cheers my soul, and drives
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Its weariness away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Then play to me to&hyphen;night, my love,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Some sweet pathetic air,
</l><l ln="7        ">To raise my burthened soul above
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;This woeful world of care.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">For when the player's heart is found
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Responsive to mine own,
</l><l ln="11      ">It seems as if the very sound
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Were sweeter in its tone.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Then play to me; and make me glad; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And banish all my fear,
</l><l ln="15      ">What though the world be cold and sad; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Still thou, &ldquo;my life,&rdquo; art here!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="117">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646936</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>REMONSTRANCE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646936</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>REMONSTRANCE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028327</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028327</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>REMONSTRANCE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016973">(<hi r="italic">Written for Music</hi>.)</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Twas here, when last we met, you promised me
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;That on this spot, and on a certain day,
</l><l ln="3        ">Once more we should embrace and kiss: yet see
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;&indent;Still, still you stay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Ah, if you knew the yearning of my heart
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;And all its grief, love, when you are away,
</l><l ln="7        ">And saw how oftentimes the tear&hyphen;drops start,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;You would not stay.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Like some faint scent of flowers borne on the air,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Dispelling languor during Summer's sway,
</l><l ln="11      ">Your coming, dearest, soon dispels my care&mdash; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;&indent;Then wherefore stay?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Come now, my darling, come, as erst of yore,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;A touch of your soft hand will make me gay,
</l><l ln="15      ">Light with your smile my dark path as before,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;&indent;Nor longer stay.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646937</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BRIDE'S SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646937</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BRIDE'S SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028328</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028328</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BRIDE'S SONG.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack><attgenre>Lyric</attgenre></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">A few days more, a few days more,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;And all the world will change!
</l><l ln="3        ">For I shall enter through Love's door
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To something sweet yet strange&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">To that new home where comes no fear
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Unshared by him I love&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And I shall always, always hear
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;His voice where'er I rove.</l></stanza>

<pb n="118">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ah then, ah then, my duty lies
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;With him, and him alone,
</l><l ln="11      ">Less duty than delight, surprise,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To me before unknown&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Delight that I am ever nigh
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;To do each fond behest,
</l><l ln="15      ">Surprise that I, and only I,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Can make his life more blest.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Oft does he praise my sunny hair,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;The bloom upon my cheeks&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Would that I were indeed so fair
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;When thus my dear one speaks.
</l><l ln="21      ">I feel myself unworthy, yet
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;He takes me for his wife,
</l><l ln="23      ">But I will yield&mdash;to pay my debt&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;The service of my life.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646938</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO &lblank; 

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">A Summer Evening in the Woods</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646938</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO &lblank;   (A Summer Evening in the Woods.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028329</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028329</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO &lblank;   (A Summer Evening in the Woods.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><caption>I</caption>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;<hi r="smcap">How</hi> lovely are the woodland glades to&hyphen;night,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The boughs slow moving in the balmy air,
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;As birds sing now and then from pure delight
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;With melody low&hyphen;pitched, though scarce aware
</l><l ln="5        ">&indent;They sing. The branches, erewhile gaunt and bare,
</l><pb n="119">
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Have donned their daintiest dress; the insects keep
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;A dreamy revel, murmuring everywhere; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;In these dear glades, so still, so dim, so deep,
</l><l ln="9        ">Save for these lulling sounds kind Nature seems to sleep.</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption>II</caption>

<l ln="10      ">&indent;The voiceless stars shine out, and all too soon
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;The calm delicious summer twilight ends; 
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Yet but a little space, and lo! the moon
</l><l ln="13      ">&indent;Has ris'n, and thence a flood of light descends,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;While she among the clouds, majestic, wends
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Her queen&hyphen;like way; obsequious stand they near,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Like courtiers round a throne; each object lends
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Fresh beauty to the landscape made so clear
</l><l ln="18      ">In this rare light that all its richer hues are here.</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption>III</caption>

<l ln="19      ">&indent;Now in this evening walk there lives anew
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;That joyous summer evening long ago,
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;Sweet as to&hyphen;night, when first I walked with you&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;When, as the westering sun was sinking low,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;I first knew all your love for me; and so
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Each year since then more swiftly than the last
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Has gone, for Time but made our love to grow.
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Yes, while the years are hurrying to the past,
</l><l ln="27      ">My one regret it is that still they fly so fast.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="120">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646939</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;WHILE THE SUNSET, SLOWLY DYING.&rdquo;</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646939</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;WHILE THE SUNSET, SLOWLY DYING.&rdquo;</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028330</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028330</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;WHILE THE SUNSET, SLOWLY DYING.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">While the sunset, slowly dying,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Sheds a light o'er sea and strand,
</l><l ln="3        ">And the night&hyphen;chilled breeze is sighing
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;As the darkness wraps the land&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">Come, with influence strong yet tender,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Mingled thoughts of vanished years,
</l><l ln="7        ">Waking soul&hyphen;thrills that can render
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Sometimes joy and sometimes tears.
</l><l ln="9        ">All the past, returning, seems
</l><l ln="10      ">Present with its living dreams.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">When the kindly summer's glory
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Filled the earth with myriad charms,
</l><l ln="13      ">First I breathed a lover's story&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;First I felt true love's alarms&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">First I pleaded with a maiden,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Hazel&hyphen;eyed, and pure, and fair
</l><l ln="17      ">As that eve whose gales love&hyphen;laden
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Wantoned with her auburn hair.
</l><l ln="19      ">All the past, returning, seems
</l><l ln="20      ">Present with its living dreams.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Now to me how swiftly thronging
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Come the visions of the past&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Treasured past to me belonging&mdash; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Span of bliss too deep to last:
</l><l ln="25      ">Still do I remember clearly
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;What I asked in trembling tone,
</l><pb n="121">
<l ln="27      ">And her words, &ldquo;I love you dearly,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Yours I am, and yours alone.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="29      ">All the past, returning, seems
</l><l ln="30      ">Present with its living dreams.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="31      ">We were &ldquo;wedded, happy&hyphen;hearted,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;And our future path seemed bright,
</l><l ln="33      ">Who could tell we should be parted,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Love's glad sun obscured in night?
</l><l ln="35      ">Yet one eve, when softly sighing
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Summer breezes lulled the rose,
</l><l ln="37      ">I beheld her, fainting, dying,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;I beheld her dim eyes close.
</l><l ln="39      ">Ah, how living, fraught with woe,
</l><l ln="40      ">Rise the sights of long ago!</l></stanza></pdiv>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">Yet amid my sore dejection
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Comes the comfort ever new&mdash; 
</l><l ln="43      ">Comes the balm, the sweet reflection,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;To each other we were true.
</l><l ln="45      ">For some end God sendeth sorrow,
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;When that end is gained at last,
</l><l ln="47      ">In the radiant heavenly morrow
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;We shall meet&mdash;all sorrow past.
</l><l ln="49      "><hi r="italic">There</hi>, no longer fraught with woe,
</l><l ln="50      ">Rise the days of long ago.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="122">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646940</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THROUGH MISTS OF YEARS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646940</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THROUGH MISTS OF YEARS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028331</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028331</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THROUGH MISTS OF YEARS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ofttimes arise through mists of years,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;In hours of gentle sadness,
</l><l ln="3        ">Dreams of a face once seen with tears,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Whose smile was then my gladness!
</l><l ln="5        ">Like, yet unlike, the light that guides
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;The storm&hyphen;tossed o'er the ocean,
</l><l ln="7        ">Deep in my soul that face abides,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Cherished with true devotion.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Such moments come to soothe and bless,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;To touch with gleams of glory,
</l><l ln="11      ">Drawn from a by&hyphen;gone happiness,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Life's sometime dreary story.
</l><l ln="13      ">So well it is when lonely lies
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Life's pathway girt with sorrow,
</l><l ln="15      ">That this dear vision should arise,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Which from the past I borrow.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

<div1>
<comhd1><idref>Z100646941</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

LYRICAL AND OTHER
POEMS. <attbytes>19Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100646941</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>

<pb n="123">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646942</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ON LOSING THE FRIENDSHIP OF ONE

HITHERTO ESTEEMED A FRIEND.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646942</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ON LOSING THE FRIENDSHIP OF ONE  HITHERTO ESTEEMED A FRIEND.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028332</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028332</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ON LOSING THE FRIENDSHIP OF ONE  HITHERTO ESTEEMED A FRIEND.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Twas nightfall, and sadness
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Around me was cast,
</l><l ln="3        ">My visions of gladness
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Were dreams of the past&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">As Love was forsaking
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Her former abode,
</l><l ln="7        ">I felt the heart&hyphen;aching
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;For joy once bestowed.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">I felt all the sorrow&mdash; 
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The pitiless void&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">When I woke on the morrow
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;With friendship destroyed.
</l><l ln="13      ">Keen, keen was the anguish
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of these weary days,
</l><l ln="15      ">When, alas! I must languish
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;In Life's dreary maze.</l></stanza>

<pb n="124">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">How weak was each token
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Of love given here,
</l><l ln="19      ">Shown now to be broken
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;When friendship grew sere!
</l><l ln="21      ">In bitter bewailing
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;I poured forth my grief,
</l><l ln="23      ">Till a new thought prevailing
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Brought calm and relief.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      "><hi r="italic">Some</hi> friends are for ever,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Through joy and through tears,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">The friends who can never
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Grow cold with the years,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="29      ">And when from Earth's prison
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;My spirit ascends&mdash; 
</l><l ln="31      ">From Death's swoon arisen&mdash; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Still, still they are friends.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646943</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO SIR WALTER SCOTT.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Written after reading his &ldquo;Journal</hi>.&rdquo;)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646943</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO SIR WALTER SCOTT.  (Written after reading his &ldquo;Journal.&rdquo;)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028333</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028333</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO SIR WALTER SCOTT.  (Written after reading his &ldquo;Journal.&rdquo;)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">Poet, 'twas no strange sun that shone on thee
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Through thy pure life so crowned with dignity,
</l><l ln="3        ">No sun with light now clouded, now intense,
</l><l ln="4        ">But aye the unclouded sun of common sense.</l></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646944</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE POET'S INSPIRATION.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646944</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE POET'S INSPIRATION.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028334</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028334</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE POET'S INSPIRATION.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">True inspiration ever seems
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;A joy and yet a pain,
</l><l ln="3        ">To light the poet's lofty dreams,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To purify his strain.</l></stanza>

<pb n="125">

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Its presence glorifies the line
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Whose rhythmic measure halts,
</l><l ln="7        ">Makes hackneyed thoughts seem half divine,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Till few perceive such faults.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">And thus, although we sometimes find
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Imperfect cords like these
</l><l ln="11      ">In songs of many a master&hyphen;mind,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;How seldom they displease:</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">But when its presence is not felt,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Though smooth the verses roll&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Though cadences in sweetness melt&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;They cannot stir the soul.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646945</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TWO LIVES.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646945</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TWO LIVES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028335</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028335</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TWO LIVES.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">A cottage home: a peaceful place
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where Sorrow hides her pallid face; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Husband and wife, a happy pair,
</l><l ln="4        ">Who thankfully Life's blessings share; 
</l><l ln="5        ">And living far from towns' turmoil,
</l><l ln="6        ">They simply crave a &ldquo;leave to toil!&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="7        ">&indent;A workhouse full of dreary din,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Full of the signs of want and sin.
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;A man and woman sinking fast,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Sinking, yet conscious to the last,
</l><l ln="11      ">&indent;Their senses steeped in wrathful woe
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;None but the frugal poor can know
</l><pb n="126">
<l ln="13      ">&indent;When first, despite their care, is spent
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Their all through sickness and the rent; 
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;When first, despite their abject grief,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;No kindly landlord grants relief; 
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;When first, despite their abject gloom,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;His agent comes&mdash;decrees their doom; 
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;When first within the workhouse gate
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Silent they stand, how desolate!
</l><l ln="21      ">&indent;When first they feel, with sorrow bowed,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;The loneliness amid a crowd&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;When first they feel in their distress
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;<hi r="italic">That</hi> is the deepest loneliness; 
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;When first they feel they near their end,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Yet by their bed no former friend; 
</l><l ln="27      ">When now, despite their struggles&mdash;struggles long and brave&mdash; 
</l><l ln="28      ">Their death but fills&mdash;but helps to fill&mdash;a pauper's grave.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646946</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO FREDERICK TENNYSON.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">Died February</hi> 26<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1898, <hi r="italic">in his ninety&hyphen;first year</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646946</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO FREDERICK TENNYSON.  (Died February 26th, 1898, in his ninety&hyphen;first year.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028336</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028336</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO FREDERICK TENNYSON.  (Died February 26th, 1898, in his ninety&hyphen;first year.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Eldest of your august, poetic race,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">You go the last to your calm resting&hyphen;place; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Yet though you pass from out our earthly view,
</l><l ln="4        ">Your work remains, and Time shall give your due.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Whether beneath the tranquil Tuscan skies
</l><l ln="6        ">You mused as all too soon the daylight dies; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Whether you watched from your far island home
</l><l ln="8        ">The English Channel's eddying miles of foam; 
</l><pb n="127">
<l ln="9        ">Or whether in your mild declining days
</l><l ln="10      ">You sojourned 'mid our clamorous London's ways; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Yours was the poet's life through length of years; 
</l><l ln="12      ">Yours were the poet's joys, and hopes, and fears; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Yours were the tender ministries of song; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Yours were the pleasures which to bards belong
</l><l ln="15      ">Who, dwelling in the world, yet &ldquo;dwell apart,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="16      ">And think but of their God and of their art.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="17      ">Our gain from lives like yours no verse can tell:
</l><l ln="18      ">Eldest of English poets, fare you well.</l></pdiv>

<signed><hi r="italic">London, February</hi> 26<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1898.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646947</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A GOLDEN WEDDING:

<subhead r="italic">Lines addressed to Friar Farlow Wilson

on behalf of the Brotherhood of the Whitefriars,

October <hi r="roman">6th</hi>, <hi r="roman">1899</hi>.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646947</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A GOLDEN WEDDING:  Lines addressed to Friar Farlow Wilson  on behalf of the Brotherhood of the Whitefriars,  October 6th, 1899.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028337</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028337</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A GOLDEN WEDDING:  Lines addressed to Friar Farlow Wilson  on behalf of the Brotherhood of the Whitefriars,  October 6th, 1899.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Take this our gift which after many years
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Comes from a circle of your firmest friends; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Remembering your true&hyphen;hearted words of cheer
</l><l ln="4        ">And kindly deeds towards them, oftentimes.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Yes; Life is rich whate'er the cynics say,
</l><l ln="6        ">So long as 'mid its ceaseless toil and fret
</l><l ln="7        ">Men play their parts as you do, seeking ever
</l><l ln="8        ">To show your fellow&hyphen;workers sympathy.</l></pdiv>

<pb n="128">

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">To her we owe our thanks who did not grudge
</l><l ln="10      ">To you the hours spent in our Brotherhood,
</l><l ln="11      ">Fraught with the mellow treasured memories
</l><l ln="12      ">Of many a by&hyphen;gone wit whose name is dear.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">What matters it though callous Time has now
</l><l ln="14      ">Turned, with resistless touch, your locks to grey,
</l><l ln="15      ">If still your heart be young; and this it is
</l><l ln="16      ">We know. May all your coming days prolong
</l><l ln="17      ">For you and yours Earth's highest, choicest joy.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646948</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE PHILOSOPHY OF OUR FEELINGS.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646948</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE PHILOSOPHY OF OUR FEELINGS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028338</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028338</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE PHILOSOPHY OF OUR FEELINGS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Tis strange that what seems grief to&hyphen;day
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Should seem like joy to&hyphen;morrow,
</l><l ln="3        ">That present bliss should pass away
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And seem, in future, sorrow.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Yet in the web of life we find,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;While its vague threads we measure,
</l><l ln="7        ">The pattern of our mood of mind
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Traced out in pain or pleasure.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646949</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BOY CHATTERTON TO HIMSELF.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646949</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BOY CHATTERTON TO HIMSELF.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028339</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028339</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BOY CHATTERTON TO HIMSELF.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph r="italic">&ldquo;Sublime of thought, and confident of fame.&rdquo; 

<signed><hi r="smcap">Coleridge</hi>, Monody on the Death of Chatterton.</signed></epigraph>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">That dotard soul I cannot comprehend,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Who knows no hope that, after many years
</l><l ln="3        ">His name shall be preserved by other means
</l><pb n="129">
<l ln="4        ">Than by an entry in the parish books&mdash; 
</l><l ln="5        ">The soul who never knew the proud desire
</l><l ln="6        ">To be remembered in far days unborn
</l><l ln="7        ">By some great deed accomplished.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="8        ">                                                Therefore here
</l><l ln="9        ">I make a vow&mdash;a vow unchanging, strong:
</l><l ln="10      ">I will redeem the time, and, though the days
</l><l ln="11      ">Are evil, yet it will be my delight
</l><l ln="12      ">To toil unceasingly, that at the last
</l><l ln="13      ">It shall be seen I have not lived in vain.
</l><l ln="14      ">Men's hours are passed as sacred Scripture saith&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">&ldquo;They eat, they drink, are merry, and they die.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="16      ">Few daily doings are of much account
</l><l ln="17      ">In fifty years; then let my mind be set
</l><l ln="18      ">On some fit theme meet for my noblest powers.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646950</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE BOY COLERIDGE TO HIMSELF.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646950</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE BOY COLERIDGE TO HIMSELF.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028340</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028340</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE BOY COLERIDGE TO HIMSELF.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph r="italic">&ldquo;O capacious soul!&rdquo; 

<signed><hi r="smcap">Wordsworth</hi>, The Prelude, Book xiv.</signed></epigraph>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;I wonder wherefore?&rdquo; is the soul&hyphen;stirred cry
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Which wells up from the depths of human hearts
</l><l ln="3        ">In every sphere of life&mdash;from lowly homes
</l><l ln="4        ">And princely palaces&mdash;from hermit cells
</l><l ln="5        ">And seething crowds&mdash;from youth and riper age
</l><l ln="6        ">And longest length of years&mdash;from rich and poor
</l><l ln="7        ">From all who have the manliness to think&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">In health or sickness&mdash;happiness or woe&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">In Life's supremest moments or its trifles
</l><pb n="130">
<l ln="10      ">Which often makes men ponder most. And this
</l><l ln="11      ">Incessant questioning is surely meant
</l><l ln="12      ">As greatest food for hope&mdash;a token given
</l><l ln="13      ">That, notwithstanding its abyss of sin,
</l><l ln="14      ">Within man's soul the germs of good abide.
</l><l ln="15      ">&indent;Mysterious are the links that firmly weld
</l><l ln="16      ">Our trains of thought together. First we brood
</l><l ln="17      ">On some small trivial matter&mdash;now the germ
</l><l ln="18      ">Of musings somewhat loftier&mdash;then behold
</l><l ln="19      ">A thread is woven with our thought, and lo
</l><l ln="20      ">It leads to higher themes!&mdash;vast vistas new
</l><l ln="21      ">For serious contemplation:&mdash;and we gain
</l><l ln="22      ">Sublimest heights, as God&hyphen;reflected thoughts
</l><l ln="23      ">Transcending reason throng our kindled minds.</l></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646951</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>PASSION'S SLAVE.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646951</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>PASSION'S SLAVE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028341</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028341</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>PASSION'S SLAVE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">Blind passion ever showed its maddening power
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Enthroned within him&mdash;a sin&hyphen;garnered dower
</l><l ln="3        ">Of quenchless loves and longings. That fierce storm
</l><l ln="4        ">Which breaks the boughs of Life, where sheltered warm
</l><l ln="5        ">Repose, like unfledged nestlings, Life's chief joys,
</l><l ln="6        ">Swept o'er his soul&mdash;the wave that swift destroys
</l><l ln="7        ">Man's store of peace. What years of labour cost
</l><l ln="8        ">He by one fatal step for ever lost.</l></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="131">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646952</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE PHILOSOPHY OF FREQUENT FAILURE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646952</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE PHILOSOPHY OF FREQUENT FAILURE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028342</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028342</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE PHILOSOPHY OF FREQUENT FAILURE.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        ">In Youth's glad morning hours of strenuous life
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Great contemplations often fill the mind
</l><l ln="3        ">With noblest aspirations, while it seems
</l><l ln="4        ">To us, as yet scarce touched by sordid care
</l><l ln="5        ">And blighting prejudice, quite possible
</l><l ln="6        ">Through our unaided strength to win at last
</l><l ln="7        ">Some shining goal which glitters in our sight&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">A goal which, when 'twas won, would crown with good
</l><l ln="9        ">The Universal Brotherhood of Man.
</l><l ln="10      ">But as the years roll on we find the dream
</l><l ln="11      ">Less easy of fulfilment,&mdash;for we feel
</l><l ln="12      ">Our ardour less intense&mdash;our weary feet
</l><l ln="13      ">Glide gently into that poor old&hyphen;world groove
</l><l ln="14      ">We so despised of yore,&mdash;and we are fain
</l><l ln="15      ">To use fast&hyphen;failing energy in strife
</l><l ln="16      ">'Gainst daily troubles; higher aims forgotten.</l></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646953</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT HAZELHURST.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646953</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT HAZELHURST.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028343</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028343</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT HAZELHURST.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">This, the loved hour of twilight's close,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The landscape is revealing
</l><l ln="3        ">Haloed, where last the sunset glows,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Ere Night comes, all concealing.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Rich foliage hides yon rippling stream
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;From the fair view completely; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And gently, as in some kind dream,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;It murmurs softly, sweetly.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="132">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646954</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO EDMUND CLARENCE STEDMAN.</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646954</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO EDMUND CLARENCE STEDMAN.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028344</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028344</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO EDMUND CLARENCE STEDMAN.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Severed from you by sundering seas I dwell&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Never have clasped your hand, nor heard your voice&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">&indent;Never have seen your eyes make loving choice
</l><l ln="4        ">Of mine to tell the truths words may not tell.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And yet I know you&mdash;oft in tranquil mood
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Your welcome songs&mdash;your wealth of critic lore&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;To me have brought a joy unfelt before,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">Or letters from you cheered my solitude.</l></stanza>

<signed><hi r="italic">January</hi> 19<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1895.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646955</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TO THE WOMEN OF GREAT BRITAIN.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">A Man's Exhortation</hi>.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646955</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TO THE WOMEN OF GREAT BRITAIN.  (A Man's Exhortation.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028345</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028345</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TO THE WOMEN OF GREAT BRITAIN.  (A Man's Exhortation.)</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016974">Song: Tune, any &ldquo;eight and six&rdquo; air.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Hope on, though dark may seem the way,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;All will be altered soon,
</l><l ln="3        ">Changing, as changes some dark day,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;When sunshine comes at noon;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Hope on, for hoping will impart
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;New strength to bear the strain,
</l><l ln="7        ">The efforts of each dauntless heart
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Can never be in vain.</l></stanza>

<pb n="133">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet, hoping, cease not still to act
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Unchecked by gibe or jeer; 
</l><l ln="11      ">With passion plead each stubborn fact,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;The hour of dawn is near&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">When man&hyphen;made laws shall cease to vex
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;The thinkers of our race&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">When justice is no word of sex&mdash; 
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;As each has found its place.</l></stanza>

<signed><hi r="italic">May</hi> 31<hi r="italic">st</hi>, 1908.</signed></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

<div1>
<comhd1><idref>Z100646956</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

HUMOROUS POEMS. <attbytes>7Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100646956</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>

<pb n="134">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646957</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WAITING FOR THE DENTIST.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646957</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WAITING FOR THE DENTIST.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028346</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028346</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WAITING FOR THE DENTIST.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Though many dismal years I've been
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To dull old Care apprenticed,
</l><l ln="3        ">Of smaller woes the worst I've seen
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Is&mdash;waiting for the dentist!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">How dreary is the cheerless room
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Where pain must bide his pleasure,
</l><l ln="7        ">The very chairs are steeped in gloom
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;And seem to grieve at leisure,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">As if his patients' molar grief,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;So uncontrolled its swelling,
</l><l ln="11      ">For its fierce tide had sought relief
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;By deluging the dwelling!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Books cannot soothe a rampant tooth
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Though they enrich a table,
</l><l ln="15      ">Sorrow alone seems kin to truth,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And joy a lying fable.</l></stanza>

<pb n="135">

<stanza><l ln="17      ">When from the window you, perchance,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Behold sweet girlhood's graces,
</l><l ln="19      ">They only make you look askance
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And think how sore your face is.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">On many chairs and sofas, too,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;More martyrs round you languish,
</l><l ln="23      ">You glance at them, they glance at you,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;And give a groan of anguish.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">You deem it hard their turn arrives
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Before you in rotation,
</l><l ln="27      ">Or they wax wrath that yours deprives
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Their case of consolation.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">You muse upon the ruthless wrench
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;That buys a tooth's departing,
</l><l ln="31      ">Or how the stopping&hyphen;pangs to quench,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;In which you may be starting;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Or haply on these ivory chips
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Harsh Nature may deny you,
</l><l ln="35      ">But which the &ldquo;golden key&rdquo; equips
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Man's genius to supply you.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">No words your mood of mind express,
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;A mood devoid of quiet,
</l><l ln="39      ">Where pain, delight, and keen distress
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Mingle in hopeless riot.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">Yes, though much sorrow one must know
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;While to old Care apprenticed,
</l><l ln="43      ">The greatest unheroic woe
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Is&mdash;waiting for the dentist!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="136">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646958</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>APOSTROPHE TO AN INK&hyphen;BOTTLE IN A
HOTEL COFFEE&hyphen;ROOM.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646958</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>APOSTROPHE TO AN INK&hyphen;BOTTLE IN A HOTEL COFFEE&hyphen;ROOM.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028347</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028347</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>APOSTROPHE TO AN INK&hyphen;BOTTLE IN A HOTEL COFFEE&hyphen;ROOM.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">'Tis strange to think how oft your aid
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Has been invoked, and then
</l><l ln="3        ">To think how often you are made
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;A confidant, and when.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Prosaic words of business life
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;By you have been expressed; 
</l><l ln="7        ">And you have told what fears were rife
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Within a lover's breast.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Perchance a little girl or boy
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Released from schoolday fetters,
</l><l ln="11      ">Intent on games, and flushed with joy,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Employs you for home letters.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">A husband forced, though leal and true,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;In some new land to dwell,
</l><l ln="15      ">To his dear wife indites by you
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;A passionate farewell.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">There enters now a seeming &ldquo;swell,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Eager, yet half afraid, he
</l><l ln="19      ">Impresses you for a &ldquo;billet doux&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;On business rather &ldquo;shady.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&ldquo;Commercials&rdquo; pen a dazzling dream
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Of greatly grown &ldquo;connection&rdquo;; 
</l><l ln="23      ">And next you aid the swelling stream
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Of filial affection</l></stanza>

<pb n="137">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Which flows in sorrow, as a son,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;From his fond mother parted,
</l><l ln="27      ">Grieves that his course, alas, has run
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;So far from whence it started.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Helper of all! from day to day,
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;What'er their situation,
</l><l ln="31      ">You win no thanks; each goes away,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Feeling no obligation!</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646959</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>MOONLIGHT ON THE TAGUS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646959</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>MOONLIGHT ON THE TAGUS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028348</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028348</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>MOONLIGHT ON THE TAGUS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">The moon shines o'er the Tagus. Now a flood
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of soft&hyphen;spun sparkling radiance clothes the scene
</l><l ln="3        ">With dazzling splendour, save where shadows lie
</l><l ln="4        ">Upon the river's bosom, sheltering there
</l><l ln="5        ">The coward Darkness, here dethroned awhile,
</l><l ln="6        ">By the moon's great though seeming gentle might.
</l><l ln="7        ">Ah me, how beautiful! Deep azure sky,
</l><l ln="8        ">Deep azure sea, and steadfast&hyphen;beaming stars,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="9        ">A dreamy blissful languor stealeth fast
</l><l ln="10      ">Over my soul while musing pensively
</l><l ln="11      ">On this fair vista steeped in rapt repose,
</l><l ln="12      ">And I forget the busy throng of life
</l><l ln="13      ">That it presents by day,&mdash;and almost now
</l><l ln="14      ">I could imagine it some magic realm
</l><l ln="15      ">Enchanted in far fairyland, beyond
</l><l ln="16      ">The power of mortal reach.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="17      ">                                       But soon a voice
</l><l ln="18      ">Says, &ldquo;Supper's come at last, let's eat, and then to bed.&rdquo;</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>
</div1>

