<pb n="138">




<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646961</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646961</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028349</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028349</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646962</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

I.&mdash;<subhead>To the Violet.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646962</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">I love you, little violet,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Your beauty I shall not forget; 
</l><l ln="3        ">You smell so sweet, you are so blue,
</l><l ln="4        ">Under the hedge the springtime through.</l></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646963</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

II.&mdash;<subhead>To the Daffodils.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646963</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">You pretty little daffodils
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Beside the budding trees; 
</l><l ln="7        ">I love to watch your yellow heads
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;A&hyphen;nodding in the breeze.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">I love to touch with tenderness
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Or smell all springtide flowers,
</l><l ln="11      ">But most I love you, daffodils,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;A&hyphen;stir in sunny hours.</l></stanza></div3>

<pb n="139">

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646964</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

III.&mdash;<subhead>To a Drooping Plant.</subhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646964</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE AMY TO HER FLOWERS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Drooping plant, your pretty flower
</l><l ln="14      ">Wants the sunshine, wants the shower,
</l><l ln="15      ">And the happy, balmy day
</l><l ln="16      ">Of the summer, passed away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Do you dread the wintry blast
</l><l ln="18      ">Whirling round you, fierce and fast,
</l><l ln="19      ">And the snow&hyphen;drift, cruel, cold,
</l><l ln="20      ">Gathering now upon the wold?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Do you dread the frosty night,
</l><l ln="22      ">Bringing with it bitter blight,
</l><l ln="23      ">Like a giant holding all
</l><l ln="24      ">Captive in his icy thrall?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Yet dream not that Hope is past
</l><l ln="26      ">Winter will not always last; 
</l><l ln="27      ">Soon his dreary reign will close,
</l><l ln="28      ">Soon comes Spring to end your woes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Soon will come the gentle breeze
</l><l ln="30      ">Whispering softly through the trees,
</l><l ln="31      ">And the happy lengthening day
</l><l ln="32      ">Making all the gardens gay.</l></stanza></div3></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="140">


<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646965</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>LITTLE BERTIE.

<subhead r="italic">(His Mother Speaks).</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646965</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE BERTIE.  (His Mother Speaks).</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028350</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028350</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>LITTLE BERTIE.  (His Mother Speaks).</mainhead><volhead>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1909</attpubn1><attpubn2>1909</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646966</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

I. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646966</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE BERTIE.  (His Mother Speaks).</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Rest you in quiet now, my baby boy,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">You are in truth your parents' highest joy;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">For though our home has ever been a place
</l><l ln="4        ">Where Happiness has deigned to show her face,
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet still your birth increased its bliss much more,
</l><l ln="6        ">And filled a void there was in it before.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">O may your life continue ever free
</l><l ln="8        ">From taint of shame, whate'er your lot may be:
</l><l ln="9        ">As spotless as the snow&hyphen;drops oft appear
</l><l ln="10      ">When first they come to tell us Spring is near:
</l><l ln="11      ">Such is my wish for you, my jewel prized; 
</l><l ln="12      ">May I yet live to see it realized.</l></stanza></div3>

<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300646967</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

II. <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646967</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>LITTLE BERTIE.  (His Mother Speaks).</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Poems of Mackenzie Bell (1909)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Your mother's love is tender, true, and kind,
</l><l ln="14      ">From all the dross of selfishness refined; 
</l><l ln="15      ">In childhood's years it is a tender guide
</l><l ln="16      ">To keep you safe from harm on every side; 
</l><l ln="17      ">And when your childhood's cherished days are passed,
</l><l ln="18      ">'Twill help you to endure the world's rough blast.</l></stanza>

<pb n="141">

<stanza><l ln="19      ">Her love abides; hallowed by memory still,
</l><l ln="20      ">Through joy or sorrow, happiness or ill; 
</l><l ln="21      ">And, like some flower, growth of a holier sphere,
</l><l ln="22      ">To gladden earth awhile, transplanted here,
</l><l ln="23      ">'Twill shed its fragrance still o'er all your ways
</l><l ln="24      ">And cheer your drooping heart in life's dark days.</l></stanza></div3></poem>
</div2>


