<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646972</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AUGUST, 1914.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646972</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AUGUST, 1914.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028353</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028353</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AUGUST, 1914.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Methought before mine inner sight there came
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;A vision of the present. Line on line
</l><l ln="3        ">Of brown&hyphen;clad listening men, with eyes aflame,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Stood waiting, brows intent, to hear the sign</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Of combat. As I looked, and looked, alas!
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Full many a good man dropped, and, writhing, fell,
</l><l ln="7        ">For lo! I saw,&mdash;I saw, as in a glass,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Foe slain by unseen foe&mdash;a glimpse of Hell.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Once more I gazed. I heard young children cry
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;In yonder villages, where rolling smoke
</l><l ln="11      ">Showed where large shells had burst, while far and nigh
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Women clasped tight their babes, who ne'er awoke.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Then, there, the corn stood, all unreaped, till crushed,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Futile for human food, while ravening strife
</l><l ln="15      ">Made earth Gehenna. Gaunt&hyphen;eyed Famine hushed
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Myriads of silent mothers, worn with life.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="17      ">Methought before mine inner sight arose
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;A vision of the future. Gone for aye
</l><l ln="19      ">Were &ldquo;war&hyphen;lords,' and the peoples bowed to those
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Who worshipped calm&hyphen;eyed Peace, and only they.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646973</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>BRITAIN'S APPEAL TO HER MEN.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646973</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>BRITAIN'S APPEAL TO HER MEN.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028354</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028354</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>BRITAIN'S APPEAL TO HER MEN.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Yours, not for self, to wield the sword&mdash; 
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Yours, not for self, to speak the word,
</l><l ln="3        ">Duty&mdash;which leads, perchance, to death,
</l><l ln="4        ">Ay, self&hyphen;less death, your mortal breath
</l><l ln="5        ">Is doubly glorified, thereby; 
</l><l ln="6        ">'Tis ever thus that heroes die.
</l><l ln="7        ">&indent;Awakened from inglorious ease,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;&indent;Your call has come at length,
</l><l ln="9        ">&indent;Floats now your flag in every breeze,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;&indent;Put on, put on, your strength!</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">Remember, English lads, Louvain; 
</l><l ln="12      ">Dream, stalwart Scotsmen, once again
</l><l ln="13      ">Of old oppression; ye from Wales
</l><l ln="14      ">Think how a little State prevails
</l><l ln="15      ">When just. Let sons of Ireland feel
</l><l ln="16      ">For Belgium 'neath the foeman's heel.
</l><l ln="17      ">&indent;Let each, awakening from his ease,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;&indent;Hear his &ldquo;clear call&rdquo; at length,
</l><l ln="19      ">&indent;Behold his flag in every breeze,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;&indent;And so put forth his strength.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">What! though amid the noontide glare,
</l><l ln="22      ">What! though amid the balmy air
</l><l ln="23      ">Of August nights your comrades died
</l><l ln="24      ">Retreating. Let it be your pride
</l><l ln="25      ">Aye to outshine them&mdash;till at last
</l><l ln="26      ">War's lurid stormclouds all are past.
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;Awakened from inglorious ease
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;&indent;Here sounds your call at length!
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;There! floats your flag o'er lands and seas!
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;&indent;Be glad! put forth your strength!</l></stanza>
<signed><hi r="italic">September</hi> 12<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1914.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646974</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>SOLDIER'S SONG.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646974</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>SOLDIER'S SONG.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028355</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028355</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>SOLDIER'S SONG.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">March on, my lads! March on, my lads!
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Not dreaming of the morrow; 
</l><l ln="3        ">While all is well, let well suffice,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Why should we dream of sorrow?
</l><pb>
<l ln="5        ">Still on, still on, with backs unbowed,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Faces alert and bright,
</l><l ln="7        ">Remembering, aye, that all we do
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Helps Britain and the right.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">An hour ago poor Ned was hit,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;I fear he lies in pain,
</l><l ln="11      ">'Tis sad, no doubt, yet sooner now
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;He'll see his Bess again.
</l><l ln="13      ">Still on, still on, with backs unbowed,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And give another blow; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Aim straight! strike hard! nor think of self,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Faces toward the foe.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Still on, still on, with backs unbowed,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;So, when the night is here,
</l><l ln="19      ">Mayhap we'll sleep, though autumn mist
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Makes trenches cold and drear&mdash; 
</l><l ln="21      ">Mayhap we'll sleep, yet wake to fight,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;To fight, and, once more fight,
</l><l ln="23      ">Remembering, aye, that all we do
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Helps Britain and the right.</l></stanza>
<signed><hi r="italic">September</hi> 28<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1914.</signed></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646975</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A SONG FOR BELGIUM.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646975</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A SONG FOR BELGIUM.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028356</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028356</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A SONG FOR BELGIUM.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<signed><hi r="italic">October</hi> 9<hi r="italic">th</hi>, 1914.</signed>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Not a throb of our hearts but in anguish responds
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To the sight of the dire desolation!
</l><pb>
<l ln="3        ">Oh! cruel the thraldom and bitter the bonds
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Of our wretched and down&hyphen;trodden nation!
</l><l ln="5        ">And in scarce&hyphen;spoken words we are heard to declare,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;War hath made us well&hyphen;nigh broken&hyphen;hearted,
</l><l ln="7        ">Ah! often, alas! we are fain to despair
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Since joy from our land hath departed.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet, arouse ye, undaunted, remembering that still
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Retribution is certainly waiting,
</l><l ln="11      ">Still strive with the foemen who work us such ill
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;'Mid their bland hypocritical prating.
</l><l ln="13      ">Keep our nation awake! though down&hyphen;trodden she lies!
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Not a moment be longer down&hyphen;hearted!
</l><l ln="15      ">And rejoicing will come if fair Belgium arise,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;And her freedom return which departed.</l></stanza></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646976</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AUTUMN, 1914</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646976</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AUTUMN, 1914</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028357</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028357</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AUTUMN, 1914</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Death's work had lyddite and shrapnel done
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">On friend, on foe, ere set of sun,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="3        ">And yet Hell's havoc ceased not with night,
</l><l ln="4        ">But still went on till dawn of light.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">But then, with the rose&hyphen;hued hint of day,
</l><l ln="6        ">The rouse of battle passed away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="7        ">Then, then, was shown what night had hid,
</l><l ln="8        ">Alas! that eyes should see what they did.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Behold a prospect, half ridge, half plain,
</l><l ln="10      ">Cumbered, good God, with maimed and slain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="11      ">Here lies a soldier, scarce more than boy; 
</l><l ln="12      ">Tending rare flowers his home employ.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">His jaw is shattered, his face all blood,
</l><l ln="14      ">Near is his dead horse, smeared with mud.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="15      ">There lies one dead; to his evil face
</l><l ln="16      ">Even Death itself hath brought no grace.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">And here is one, who, once, was a man,
</l><l ln="18      ">By Nature built on her kindly plan,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="19      ">One leg is mangled; two hands are gone,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="20      ">And yet,&mdash;and yet,&mdash;life lingers on!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Unseen by the searchers, and longing for death,
</l><l ln="22      ">Painfully heaves he breath after breath.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="23      ">But why prolong the gruesome tale
</l><l ln="24      ">Of what now cumbers hill and dale?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Because, even here, there comes oft&hyphen;times
</l><l ln="26      ">Heaven's light, amid War's sin and crimes.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="27      ">Yonder a Frenchman and German lie,
</l><l ln="28      ">Mortally wounded, and, soon, to die.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">The German, his water&hyphen;bottle burst,
</l><l ln="30      ">Feels all the pangs of a feverish thirst;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="31      ">And, by a look of mute appeal,
</l><l ln="32      ">Makes even the heart of his foeman feel,</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">And says, as he shares the Frenchman's store,
</l><l ln="34      ">&ldquo;Where we are going is no more war.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="35      ">And, as he passed to the Other Land,
</l><l ln="36      ">He bent and kissed his foeman's hand.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="37      ">O! who shall say that none keep tryst
</l><l ln="38      ">Here, on this grisly field, with Christ?</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>



<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200646977</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE CHIEF RABBI OF LYONS.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200646977</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE CHIEF RABBI OF LYONS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028358</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028358</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE CHIEF RABBI OF LYONS.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<signed>(<hi r="italic">Autumn</hi>, 1914).</signed>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Among the sunny vineyards of fair France
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Creeps the slow agony of War's mischance; 
</l><l ln="3        ">And, day by day, more villagers awake
</l><l ln="4        ">To find their homesteads, wrapt in battle, quake; 
</l><l ln="5        ">To find their low, ridged terraces of vines,
</l><l ln="6        ">On which, it seems to them, the kind sun shines
</l><l ln="7        ">In countless autumns past, so lovingly,
</l><l ln="8        ">Are trampled by the surge of cavalry.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="9        ">On yonder wooded heights men see for days
</l><l ln="10      ">The charge and counter&hyphen;charge 'mid sulphurous haze.
</l><l ln="11      ">Yet, hourly, hourly, men of mercy stir
</l><l ln="12      ">With gentle touch to tend the wounded there,
</l><pb>
<l ln="13      ">Or soothe the dying in their direst need&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Men of kind hearts, though differing as to creed.
</l><l ln="15      ">A rabbi here, bravest of these brave souls,
</l><l ln="16      ">Who know no fear although War's thunder rolls,
</l><l ln="17      ">Happily, hitherto, untouched by scathe,
</l><l ln="18      ">Still cheers and comforts those of his own faith.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="19      ">Once, as he moves on his heroic round,
</l><l ln="20      ">To him, faint yet distinct, there comes a sound
</l><l ln="21      ">Of piteous entreaty, and he sees,
</l><l ln="22      ">A little way removed among the trees,
</l><l ln="23      ">A soldier dying. He deceived, perchance,
</l><l ln="24      ">By grievous pain, or by a fleeting glance,
</l><l ln="25      ">The rabbi, in his dark&hyphen;hued garb, mistakes
</l><l ln="26      ">For some good <hi r="italic">cur&eacute;</hi>, and, with voice which quakes
</l><l ln="27      ">With death on&hyphen;coming, asks before his eyes
</l><l ln="28      ">The crucifix be held. Without surprise
</l><l ln="29      ">The rabbi does his bidding. O wise man!
</l><l ln="30      ">To rank Humanity above the ban
</l><l ln="31      ">Of dogma. Shall not this be thy reward
</l><l ln="32      ">Thy soul made happy by thy high soul's Lord?</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb>

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200646978</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

