<newatts><attidref>LL3028359</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;THE COMRADE IN WHITE.&rdquo;</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016976">It is said, especially in the French lines, that after many
encounters a man in white has been seen succouring the
wounded. The French call him &ldquo;The Comrade in White.&rdquo;</note>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Adown the long, long avenues of fight
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Dark Jean and Pierre beheld Him come. He looked,
</l><l ln="3        ">Said they, as though indeed, He were, in truth,
</l><l ln="4        ">Incarnate deathless Courage; yet withal
</l><l ln="5        ">Calm with eternal calmness. Much they told
</l><l ln="6        ">About Him. Yet, I smiled, and wondered if
</l><l ln="7        ">Their toil and weariness made them distraught.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="8        ">One night the order came; our company
</l><l ln="9        ">Was bidden to advance. At first it seemed
</l><l ln="10      ">That all was well, the thunder of our guns
</l><l ln="11      ">Had opened, so appeared to us, a way
</l><l ln="12      ">To win the point desired. Then suddenly
</l><l ln="13      ">We saw that all was lost. A soldier fell
</l><l ln="14      ">To right and left of me. I was alone; 
</l><l ln="15      ">A moment more, and, I dropt, wounded, then
</l><l ln="16      ">No more I knew; nor was aware until
</l><l ln="17      ">The night was here.
</l><l ln="18      ">                                When I came to myself
</l><l ln="19      ">The stars were shining, and clear was the night.
</l><l ln="20      ">I lay in a small hollow. Soon, too soon
</l><l ln="21      ">The firing re&hyphen;commenced. Lo! then a step
</l><l ln="22      ">Majestic, slow, (how calm and unafraid)
</l><l ln="23      ">Approached. At first, so little did I dream
</l><pb>
<l ln="24      ">Of Who He was, that, when I saw the white,
</l><l ln="25      ">Pure texture of His raiment, 'twas, methought,
</l><l ln="26      ">Some woman, full of strange forgetfulness,
</l><l ln="27      ">Or, haply, some poor peasant, whose white smock
</l><l ln="28      ">Casts shadows thus. He raised His arms aloft
</l><l ln="29      ">Unfearing whirling bullets, as though He
</l><l ln="30      ">Were now in act to bless, and spake sweet words,
</l><l ln="31      ">Old and familiar. Then He raised me up,
</l><l ln="32      ">And bore me hence, to where soft waters flowed&mdash; 
</l><l ln="33      ">Me, tall, large&hyphen;limbed, and, there, He washed my wounds,
</l><l ln="34      ">And bound them. Great, great was my agony
</l><l ln="35      ">Of body; yet, when He but touched me, lo!
</l><l ln="36      ">Mine inmost soul was bathed in very bliss.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="37      ">I slept; and, when I woke, around I looked,
</l><l ln="38      ">The Friend was with me still. He stood apart
</l><l ln="39      ">As if in prayer. Anon, with hand outstretched,
</l><l ln="40      ">Toward me He gazed. Mine eyes beheld a wound
</l><l ln="41      ">Upon that hand. &ldquo;Wounded you, likewise, are,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="42      ">I murmured low. Perchance He heard, perchance
</l><l ln="43      ">The look upon my face told Him my meaning.
</l><l ln="44      ">&ldquo;Old is my wound,&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;and, yet, it hath
</l><l ln="45      ">Troubled Me much of late.&rdquo; Swiftly He rose,
</l><l ln="46      ">&ldquo;Lie there, beside the water, for to&hyphen;day,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="47      ">He told me, &ldquo;and, to&hyphen;morrow, I will come,
</l><l ln="48      ">Of you I have much need.&rdquo; And, so I lie
</l><l ln="49      ">Lonely and weak, my pain increasing, yet
</l><l ln="50      ">Anchored in joy because He comes to&hyphen;morrow.</l></pdiv>
<signed><hi r="italic">June</hi> 18, 1915. <hi r="italic">Centenary of Waterloo</hi>.</signed></poem>
</div3>


<pb>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646980</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>IN THE FRENCH TRENCHES.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646980</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>IN THE FRENCH TRENCHES.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028360</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028360</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>IN THE FRENCH TRENCHES.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016977">It is said that a French private soldier, colloquially
&ldquo;un poilu&rdquo; of volatile disposition, bought a small Bible one
day, soon after the war began, on one of the Quais at
Paris; and that, when in subsequent danger and fear, he
opened it in the trenches, almost inadvertently he found
the words: &ldquo;Be strong, fear not,&rdquo; and was impelled
thereby to do his duty. The Legion of Honour is usually
designated merely as &ldquo;The Legion.&rdquo;</note>

<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Strange is my Paris, here and now,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;My Paris once so gay,
</l><l ln="3        ">No heart have I to sit and drink
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;An absinthe here to&hyphen;day.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Achille is gone, and tall Jean, too,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;And where we used to sit,
</l><l ln="7        ">At P&egrave;re Odette's, why, there I see
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Scarce one, when lights are lit.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">At noontide where we used to play
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Vive l'Amour in the shade
</l><l ln="11      ">Talk they of wounds, talk they of death,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Or how the shells are made.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">I'm glad that I'm &ldquo;un poilu&rdquo; now,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;I'm glad that I must go,
</l><l ln="15      ">For naught can check &ldquo;the vapours&rdquo; like
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Swift marching to and fro.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="17      ">Cold is the night, cold is my heart,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;And yet no coward I; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Yet cold it is to sit and think,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;And cold 'tis here to lie.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Cold is my heart for tall Jean's sake
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;'Twas here, just here, he died; 
</l><l ln="23      ">Cold is my heart for Achille's sake,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Here, bleeding, by my side.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Cheerless it is, and gloomy, too,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;As breaks the heavy day.
</l><l ln="27      ">I'll read the Book I bought erewhile
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;To wile the hour away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Ah! here it is: never before
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Have I read such a Book,
</l><l ln="31      ">At such a time little it recks
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;In what I read, or look.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">I turn the page: &ldquo;Be strong, fear not,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;The very word for me,
</l><l ln="35      ">For lo! the cannonade begins,
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;The shot fall heavily.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stage>[He awakes in a hospital, wounded.]</stage>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">&ldquo;Be strong, fear not!&rdquo; Where am I now?
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;This place, large&hyphen;roomed, high&hyphen;walled,
</l><l ln="39      ">Brings back no memories; yet they say
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;'Twas mine, when Duty called</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">To hurl the Boches rearward; and they say
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;That, while I lie at rest,
</l><l ln="43      ">&ldquo;Mon G&eacute;n&eacute;ral&rdquo; will come and pin
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;&ldquo;The Legion&rdquo; on my breast.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<signed><hi r="italic">France's Day</hi>, 1915.</signed></poem>
</div3>


<pb>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646981</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE DESERTER.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646981</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE DESERTER.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028361</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028361</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE DESERTER.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;There is a soul of goodness in things evil.&rdquo; 
</l><signed r="smcap">Shakespeare.</signed></epigraph>
<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;He showed no grace till the hour he died.&rdquo;&mdash; 
</l><signed r="smcap">Dante Rossetti.</signed></epigraph> 
<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;I can smoke a cigar to the glory of God.&rdquo;&mdash; 
</l><signed r="smcap">Charles Haddon Spurgeon.</signed></epigraph>

<argument>A British private soldier served at the Front for some
time. He was given to drink, however, and other bad
influences, and, at last deserted. In about two months he
was caught. Then he was tried, and sentenced to be shot.
On the night before the execution a minister of religion
came to offer him spiritual consolation. On leaving he
asked whether he could do anything for him. The man
desired tobacco, and, on receiving four cigarettes, all the
enquirer had, he bestowed two on the sentinel guarding
him.</argument>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Haggard, and stern of mien, he sits
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">As, seen by inner sight, there flits
</l><l ln="3        ">Through some strange and obscuring haze,
</l><l ln="4        ">Vague visions of his dull, past days.
</l><l ln="5        ">His life, one long, dull tragedy
</l><l ln="6        ">Before him lay; 'twas well that he
</l><l ln="7        ">Felt not as others would have felt.
</l><l ln="8        ">Of gentler nurture, few had dealt
</l><l ln="9        ">With him in kindness. Now, alas!
</l><l ln="10      ">Short were the hours 'twere his to pass
</l><l ln="11      ">On earth. Scarce thought he of his crime
</l><l ln="12      ">Save with one slow regret; the time
</l><l ln="13      ">Moved grimly; a well&hyphen;meaning man
</l><l ln="14      ">Repentance talked&mdash;a stupid plan
</l><pb>
<l ln="15      ">To him, unwilling, then had asked
</l><l ln="16      ">Did he crave aught. It had not tasked
</l><l ln="17      ">The fancy of the prisoner,
</l><l ln="18      ">To crave one boon, and, now, lay there
</l><l ln="19      ">Within his hand, four cigarettes.
</l><l ln="20      ">&ldquo;Poor bloke,&rdquo; cried he, his vain regrets
</l><l ln="21      ">All gone, &ldquo;the bloke who guards me here
</l><l ln="22      ">Wants two, as well as me, no fear,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="23      ">And holding out a friendly hand,
</l><l ln="24      ">He makes the other understand.</l></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646982</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE WISE HORSE.

<subhead>(<hi r="italic">A True Story of</hi> 1914.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646982</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE WISE HORSE.  (A True Story of 1914.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028362</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028362</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE WISE HORSE.  (A True Story of 1914.)</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ere the trench warfare is begun,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And men change post ere rise of sun,
</l><l ln="3        ">A troop of our best cavalry
</l><l ln="4        ">Are called to charge the enemy.
</l><l ln="5        ">Onward! with faces all a&hyphen;glow
</l><l ln="6        ">With martial ardour, now they go,
</l><l ln="7        ">No man in bearing seems to err,
</l><l ln="8        ">No gallant steed deserves the spur,
</l><l ln="9        ">One moment sees their proud advance,
</l><l ln="10      ">With whirling sword or glittering lance.
</l><l ln="11      ">The next beholds a bursting shell
</l><l ln="12      ">Fall in their midst&mdash;a bolt of Hell.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="13      ">A soldier, wounded nigh to death,
</l><l ln="14      ">Drops slowly, panting now for breath,
</l><l ln="15      ">Seeing him fall, his faithful horse
</l><l ln="16      ">With bent neck, looks, then checks his course,
</l><pb>
<l ln="17      ">Once more he looks, looks yet again,
</l><l ln="18      ">Sure is it, now, he knows the pain,
</l><l ln="19      ">Then, by kind instinct gentle made,
</l><l ln="20      ">He bends, and seeks to render aid.
</l><l ln="21      ">The man's torn raiment holding fast,
</l><l ln="22      ">He lifts him up; and gallops past
</l><l ln="23      ">All danger: then, and not till then,
</l><l ln="24      ">Amid a picket of our men,
</l><l ln="25      ">From his kind mouth he loosed his load
</l><l ln="26      ">And softly neighed for help, nor strode
</l><l ln="27      ">Away although that help had come.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="28      ">Later, amid the gathering hum
</l><l ln="29      ">Of friendly tones, and friendly hands,
</l><l ln="30      ">He looks; he knows; he understands; 
</l><l ln="31      ">And takes his sugar quietly,
</l><l ln="32      ">While men say, for his bravery,
</l><l ln="33      ">Now he deserves the famed V.C.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646983</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE FAITHFUL DOG.

<subhead r="italic">(A French Soldier's True Tale.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646983</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE FAITHFUL DOG.  (A French Soldier's True Tale.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028363</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028363</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE FAITHFUL DOG.  (A French Soldier's True Tale.)</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Slowly I come from poignant dreams of pain,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Wounded how sorely. Weak yet all too weak
</l><l ln="3        ">To know my weakness, once, and yet again,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Something stirs near me, though it does not speak.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Grievous are my dire hurts. A piece of shell
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Is lodged within my arm; a sabre thrust
</l><l ln="7        ">Has wounded now my head; and, lo! as well
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;A rifle ball is in my cheek. I must</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Lie prone among the dead, yet life is sweet,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Yea, sweet, despite mine agony. Methought
</l><l ln="11      ">Anon some living thing has touched me,&mdash;meet
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;To render aid&mdash;Oh! helplessness unsought</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Which leaves me thus to suffer 'mid the dead
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Bearing mine anguish, anguish constant, sore
</l><l ln="15      ">Would, would, that I could rouse me, if instead
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Of death, there comes the kindly touch once more.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Once more comes the soft touch. With opened eyes
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;I see it is our faithful dog who comes
</l><l ln="19      ">To aid his wounded friends. With sad surprise
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;He sees me in this dreadful case. The drums</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Were beating &ldquo;the attack&rdquo; when last we met,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;And triumph seemed in sight. How different now!
</l><l ln="23      ">Yet he may save me. I will not regret
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;My pain in calling him should Fate allow</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">This much of good. He sees. He understands.
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;He goes to call my comrades. Not too late
</l><l ln="27      ">Perchance they yet may reach me,&mdash;gentle hands
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;May raise me, or with drink my thirst abate.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="29      ">I hear, I hear at last the measured tread
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Of hurrying footsteps! Soon will they be here.
</l><l ln="31      ">Thank God I shall not perish 'mid the dead,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Living, may yet His holy name revere.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>


<pb>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646984</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646984</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028364</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028364</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016978"><p>The three pictures sought to be depicted in this poem
are the expression of the strong feeling raised in me by
what I have recently heard and seen.</p>
<p>The first is a general picture of a condition of affairs
known to all of us&mdash;the picture of men willingly sacrificing
life, or suffering mutilation, for pure and selfless love of
country. The second was inspired by a very recent
occurrence at a London Hospital, where the visiting of the
wounded has lost its early popularity as a Sunday duty.
The third picture describes the disgust with which I, having
occasion of late to visit a fashionable hotel in the South of
England, witnessed the extravagant living of well&hyphen;dressed,
well&hyphen;to&hyphen;do people, amidst the poverty around, and at a
time when poor people are being urged to economise.</p></note>

<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;Thy Mercy on Thy People, Lord.&rdquo; 
</l><signed r="smcap">Rudyard Kipling.</signed></epigraph>
<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;There He could do no mighty works because of their unbelief.&rdquo; 
&mdash;</l><signed r="smcap">The New Testament.</signed></epigraph>
<epigraph r="italic"><l>&ldquo;The British Army is an army of lions led by asses.&rdquo; 
</l><signed r="roman">A French proverb, adapted from a saying of Napoleon I.</signed></epigraph>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646985</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
I. <subhead><hi r="smcap">The Trenches</hi>.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646985</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Is it, oh, is it, that our countrymen
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Born of the people, loyally and well,
</l><l ln="3        ">Have given their bodies in their country's cause,
</l><l ln="4        ">Have suffered wounds, disablement, and hurts
</l><l ln="5        ">Worse far than death itself? It is! It is!</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646986</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
II. <subhead><hi r="smcap">The Hospital</hi>.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646986</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="6        ">Is it, oh, is it, that one autumn Sunday,
</l><l ln="7        ">Lately, in London's central heart there stood
</l><pb>
<l ln="8        ">A Home of Healing with wide&hyphen;opened doors?
</l><l ln="9        ">Two days before it had received a load
</l><l ln="10      ">Of maimed and helpless ones: part of the fruit,
</l><l ln="11      ">The ghastly fruit&mdash;of one week's work in Flanders.
</l><l ln="12      ">Yet, on that autumn Sunday, came there not
</l><l ln="13      ">One single visitor to soothe or cheer,
</l><l ln="14      ">Despite the parrot cry of &ldquo;Brotherhood&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Uttered in churches&mdash;can it be sincere?
</l><l ln="16      ">Churches, alas! where Caste still reigns, although
</l><l ln="17      ">Christ died upon the Cross to thrust out Caste.
</l><l ln="18      ">Can this be true? Yea, it is even so.</l></div4>

<div4><comhd4><idref>Z400646987</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
III. <subhead><hi r="smcap">The Hotel</hi>.</subhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z400646987</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>WHY WE DO NOT WIN THE WAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd4>

<l ln="19      ">Is it, oh, is it, that one autumn Sunday,
</l><l ln="20      ">In one fair hostel, all embowered in trees,
</l><l ln="21      ">Foul gluttony there was of men and women,
</l><l ln="22      ">For there, they lived to eat, not ate to live?
</l><l ln="23      ">Alas! Alas! Yea, it is even so.</l></div4>

<signed><hi r="italic">Oct</hi>. 29, 1915.</signed></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

