<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646989</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>PRAISE TO THE BRAVE.</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646989</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>PRAISE TO THE BRAVE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028365</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028365</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>PRAISE TO THE BRAVE.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph><l>&ldquo;Dulce et decorum est patria mori.&rdquo; 
</l><l>Sweet and fitting is it to die for the fatherland.
</l><signed r="italic">Old Roman Proverb.</signed></epigraph>

<epigraph><l>&indent;. . . &ldquo;naught can make us rue
</l><l>If England to herself remain but true.&rdquo; 
</l><signed r="italic">Shakespeare.</signed></epigraph>
<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016979">A quotation which, I think, peculiarly appropriate to the
national circumstances of his country at this, his third
centenary.</note>

<argument>Police Constable Alexander Dundas, T Division of the
Metropolitan Force, stationed at Teddington, was a very
<pb>
early member of the National Union of Police and Prison
Officers (he was No. 23 on the roll), and had contributed
often to the Union <hi r="italic">Journal</hi>, using the pen name of &ldquo;White
Ensign.&rdquo; He had been in the Navy, originally, and, on the
outbreak of war, he rejoined that service. One day, when
on watch, he detected the periscope of an enemy submarine,
and judging the position critical, without waiting for orders,
he fired at, and hit it. For firing without orders he was
arrested, but when the actual facts came to the knowledge
of his captain, he was released, the whole ship's company
was assembled, and he was thanked, publicly, before them.
Later, he received the Distinguished Service Medal. On the
29th of February, 1916, the Auxiliary Cruiser &ldquo;Alcantara,&rdquo; 
on which Dundas was serving as Leading Seaman, was
engaged, on patrol duty, off the East Coast of Scotland,
searching for contraband. She encountered the German
Cruiser, &ldquo;Greif,&rdquo; disguised as a Norwegian merchantman.
The &ldquo;Alcantara&rdquo; approached the &ldquo;Greif,&rdquo; and while
Dundas, as coxswain, was waiting, with his boat's crew, at
her side, to take his officer on board the &ldquo;Greif,&rdquo; suddenly
the latter lowered her false bulwarks, and fired a broadside
at the &ldquo;Alcantara.&rdquo; One of the shots killed Dundas and
the boat's crew. The &ldquo;Alcantara&rdquo; replied, and fought
bravely; but, alas! was, at last, sunk. Eventually H.M.S.
&ldquo;Andes&rdquo; came up, and sank the &ldquo;Greif.&rdquo;</argument>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Men of the Union! see to it,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;That aye, 'mid joy or ruth,
</l><l ln="3        ">Worthy are ye of such a one
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;In constancy and truth.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Constant since boyhood's day he strives to serve
</l><l ln="6        ">Wherever Duty calls him, and to nerve
</l><l ln="7        ">His soul to truth. At first a sailor's life
</l><l ln="8        ">Is his, with many a pleasant change how rife!
</l><pb>
<l ln="9        ">But soon, he finds his duty just as sweet
</l><l ln="10      ">In changeless circuits of a London &ldquo;beat.&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="11      ">When war's fierce stormcloud bursts, how suddenly!
</l><l ln="12      ">To him there comes once more the call to sea.
</l><l ln="13      ">Then, ever brave, he leaves his much&hyphen;loved home
</l><l ln="14      ">To fight for Britain on the northern foam.
</l><l ln="15      ">One day on him there dawns a sense of harm,
</l><l ln="16      ">He knows not why,&mdash;a subtle, vague alarm,
</l><l ln="17      ">Though, like young Nelson, &ldquo;never saw&rdquo; he &ldquo;Fear,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="18      ">His inmost soul is thrilled by danger near.
</l><l ln="19      ">His is the watch. Eager he scans the deep
</l><l ln="20      ">With eyes all vigilant, and sees, up&hyphen;creep
</l><l ln="21      ">A periscope. It is! it is the foe!
</l><l ln="22      ">'Tis instant now to strike ere yet below
</l><l ln="23      ">The dread torpedo speeds. He fires his gun,
</l><l ln="24      ">And saves his ship. What then? What he has done
</l><l ln="25      ">He lacks an order for, so speedily
</l><l ln="26      ">Behold him made a prisoner, but when he
</l><l ln="27      ">At length, hath justice, gone is dire disgrace,
</l><l ln="28      ">His mates are called, and, now, before his face,
</l><l ln="29      ">He hears himself high praised, and, for the rest,
</l><l ln="30      ">The D.S.M. he wears upon his breast.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="31      ">But, ah! the gallant hearts foredoomed to die!
</l><l ln="32      ">One day a seeming merchantman drew nigh
</l><l ln="33      ">His ship, the &ldquo;Alcantara,&rdquo; which was sent
</l><l ln="34      ">To search for contraband. Swiftly she went
</l><pb>
<l ln="35      ">Towards the stranger. See! she lowers a boat
</l><l ln="36      ">To take the searchers. Scarce is that a&hyphen;float
</l><l ln="37      ">(Dundas is in her) than all suddenly
</l><l ln="38      ">False bulwarks dropt are by the enemy,
</l><l ln="39      ">A broadside, winged with death, booms o'er the wave,
</l><l ln="40      ">Striking the boat, and slaying all the brave
</l><l ln="41      ">Therein.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="42      ">            Dundas's torch of life is out!
</l><l ln="43      ">But puissant Death can never put to rout
</l><l ln="44      ">Courage like his. It lives from age to age,
</l><l ln="45      ">A glorious, mighty, deathless heritage.
</l><l ln="46      ">Britain shall live long as her sons can say
</l><l ln="47      ">&ldquo;Our mother still exults in &lsquo;heroes of to&hyphen;day.&rsquo;&rdquo;</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="48      ">Men of the Union! see to it,
</l><l ln="49      ">&indent;That aye, 'mid joy or ruth,
</l><l ln="50      ">Worthy are ye of such a one
</l><l ln="51      ">&indent;In constancy and truth.</l></pdiv>

<signed><hi r="italic">Easter Monday, April</hi> 24, 1916.</signed></poem>
</div3>


<pb>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646990</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>OUR BROTHERS AT THE FRONT</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646990</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>OUR BROTHERS AT THE FRONT</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028366</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028366</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>OUR BROTHERS AT THE FRONT</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016980">The Brotherhood Federation was much cheered by
hearing of Brotherhood gatherings in the trenches, and the
following hymn was written by me in response to a special
request for a hymn which could be sung both at the meetings
at home, and at those in the trenches, and be one more
proof to our brothers at the front that they are all, ever
and always, in our loving memory. Of set purpose I used
the familiar common metre so that the words would lend
themselves to many tunes long much loved, and at the
Brotherhood connected with the Marylebone Presbyterian
Church, London, &ldquo;Belmont&rdquo; has been employed, Sunday
by Sunday, for several months with marked acceptance.</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Our hearts are with you all the week,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;But must when Sunday comes
</l><l ln="3        ">While musing, in our homes at peace,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;On you, where roll the drums.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">And when, on Sunday afternoon,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;We see your vacant place,
</l><l ln="7        ">We were not brothers did not gloom
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Fall on our hearts a space.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Yet you and we, on shore or sea,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;By faith can surely meet,
</l><l ln="11      ">And re&hyphen;unite our sundered souls,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Before the mercy&hyphen;seat.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">There shall we greet you, soul by soul,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;There shall we watch and pray,
</l><l ln="15      ">There shall we keep our courage up,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Till dawns the happy day</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Soon, soon, it cannot be too soon,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;When, home from sea or shore,
</l><l ln="19      ">With joy that war at last is o'er
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;With you we meet once more.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646991</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646991</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028367</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028367</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>AT SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016981">Whatever view may be taken about War, and, personally
I agree with Tolstoi both as to its horror and its inherent
futility, nothing but contempt ought to be felt for the
smug hyprocrisy which would condemn selfless courage,
even if, sometimes, mistaken. Very early in life I stayed at
this most interesting spot, during what I thought, then,
to be the permanent ascendency of &ldquo;The Manchester
School&rdquo; as it was called, or &ldquo;the peace&hyphen;at&hyphen;any&hyphen;price party,&rdquo; 
and wrote the stanzas which follow:&mdash;</note>

<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">When war is gone, our people say
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The heroes of the war were wrong&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">That they who formed our Britain's sway,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And made her Empire firm and strong,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Were callous cut&hyphen;throats nothing less,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Who joyed in war for slaughter's sake; 
</l><l ln="7        ">Who yearned to banish happiness; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Who loved with blood their thirst to slake.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">But I, with swelling heart, to&hyphen;day
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Land on this shore, which years ago
</l><l ln="11      ">Saw from its crag&hyphen;encircled bay
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Our Nelson's only overthrow,</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">And ask, do those who grub and prose,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;And by their lights our heroes try,
</l><l ln="15      ">Perform their life&hyphen;tasks more than those
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Whose task is but &ldquo;to do or die&rdquo;?</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


