<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646992</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A VETERAN OF 1870.

<subhead r="italic">(In the Basse Plante, Pau, France.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646992</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A VETERAN OF 1870.  (In the Basse Plante, Pau, France.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028368</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028368</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A VETERAN OF 1870.  (In the Basse Plante, Pau, France.)</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">A regiment's band stands up to play
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Within a sheltered wood,
</l><l ln="3        ">To make its friends and strangers gay,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And please them, if it could.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">It plays full many a soldier's air,
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Now tender, low, and sweet,
</l><l ln="7        ">Now surely meant to banish care,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;With martial fire replete&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Telling of conquest and renown,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;With scarce a note of pain,
</l><l ln="11      ">Of trophies ta'en, of arms laid down,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Of heroes home again.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Smart citizens on every side,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Are pacing up and down,
</l><l ln="15      ">And &ldquo;ladies fair,&rdquo; with graceful pride,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Show each to each their gown.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Yet see I a poor cripple lean
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Against an ag&egrave;d tree,
</l><l ln="19      ">I see his thread&hyphen;bare blouse is clean,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Despite his poverty.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Once had he borne a soldier's part,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Had learnt how to endure,
</l><l ln="23      ">God grant him still the steadfast heart; 
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;For him there is no cure.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Would he but speak? What does he think
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Of the fierce joys of war?
</l><l ln="27      ">Would he now&mdash;gaily near their brink,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Or shun them evermore?</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646993</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE CHARGE.

<subhead r="italic">(A real incident.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646993</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE CHARGE.  (A real incident.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028369</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028369</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE CHARGE.  (A real incident.)</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<epigraph>&ldquo;I believe in the next world, and, do all I can
not to send my patients into it, drunk.&rdquo; 
<signed>The actual remark of an experienced physician.</signed></epigraph>

<epigraph>&ldquo;About six o'clock every man was given a glass
of rum to drink the King's health and success to
our attack.&rdquo; 
<signed>From an article, printed in a weekly newspaper, written
by one who was present.</signed></epigraph>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016982">Whatever view may be held as to the taking
of alcohol in normal circumstances, few, one would
suppose, would justify, on moral grounds, its being
served out, neat, just before deadly combat, to
men, mostly young, and many of whom are, unfortunately,
totally unacquainted with its effects.</note>

<pdiv>
<speaker>1st Soldier.</speaker>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">And is it thus we slay? I will not drink.</l></firstl>
</pdiv>
<stage>[Pours out the contents.]</stage>

<pdiv>
<speaker>An Officer.</speaker>

<pdiv><l ln="2        ">Righteous, say they, the war is. So it is!
</l><l ln="3        ">Then why degrade the splendid trade of war
</l><l ln="4        ">By usage like to this?</l></pdiv>

<pb>

<pdiv><l ln="5        ">                                 Surely the race
</l><l ln="6        ">Who fought, and bled, and won, at Waterloo,
</l><l ln="7        ">And many a hard&hyphen;fought field before and since,
</l><l ln="8        ">Are not the cravens basely thus to need &ldquo;Dutch courage.&rdquo;</l></pdiv></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<speaker>A colour&hyphen;sergeant of the swash&hyphen;buckler variety,</speaker>
<stage>(gulping down his liquor.)</stage>
<l ln="9        ">&ldquo;See! what come of all the cant
</l><l ln="10      ">Of &lsquo;temperance&rsquo; to win the war, when now
</l><l ln="11      ">Rum, and such rum! is given to make us fight.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646994</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>&ldquo;GOOD&hyphen;BYE, OLD MAN.&rdquo; 

<subhead r="italic">(An actual occurrence.)</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646994</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>&ldquo;GOOD&hyphen;BYE, OLD MAN.&rdquo;   (An actual occurrence.)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028370</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028370</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>&ldquo;GOOD&hyphen;BYE, OLD MAN.&rdquo;   (An actual occurrence.)</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<argument>A battery of Field Artillery is ordered into action
with a call of extreme urgency. As it advances at the
gallop the favourite horse of one of the gunners is wounded
mortally, and falls, helpless, on the ground. Instinctively,
almost involuntarily, and quick as lightning, the soldier
who loves it leaps from his limber and rushes to its help.
Disentangling the harness, and unloosing the collar, he
relieves somewhat its sufferings. Then he encircles the
poor head, with its piteous eyes, in his affectionate arms; 
and, kissing the forehead, exclaims, &ldquo;Good&hyphen;bye, old man.&rdquo; 
At the same instant, a ruined cottage, ten yards to the
left, is struck by a shell, whose bursting fragments illumine
the sky and air, and a sergeant, observing his absence,
though already far ahead, beckons him, imperatively, to
rejoin.</argument>

<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Good&hyphen;bye, Old Man, I seem to see
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The meadow where, how quietly,
</l><l ln="3        ">You grazed, at first, a happy foal
</l><l ln="4        ">Harmless in happiness. The whole
</l><pb>
<l ln="5        ">Green country&hyphen;side had scarce another
</l><l ln="6        ">Creature more joyous&mdash;gladsome brother
</l><l ln="7        ">To streams, and winds, and soaring&hyphen;birds.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="8        ">Then, later, would that halting words
</l><l ln="9        ">Of mine could paint my Nellie's ride
</l><l ln="10      ">With laughing eyes, and legs a&hyphen;stride,
</l><l ln="11      ">Her first ride on your friendly back.
</l><l ln="12      ">E'en now I see yon woodland track,
</l><l ln="13      ">Soft with the fallen russet leaves.
</l><l ln="14      ">Alack! alack! my poor heart grieves
</l><l ln="15      ">To quit you, tortured. By what right
</l><l ln="16      ">Are you made victim in a fight
</l><l ln="17      ">It is not yours to comprehend?
</l><l ln="18      ">Yea; men are hard; some day, good friend,
</l><l ln="19      ">May we judge differently; and think; 
</l><l ln="20      ">May we judge differently; and shrink,
</l><l ln="21      ">From torture given without appeal.
</l><l ln="22      ">For me, I know not; yet can feel.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="23      ">Good&hyphen;bye, Old Man, may Death come soon
</l><l ln="24      ">For you, I crave that only boon,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="25      ">And, yet, another would I seek; 
</l><l ln="26      ">May no dog scent, afar, your sleek
</l><l ln="27      ">And well&hyphen;kept flesh before you die,
</l><l ln="28      ">Lest he, with hungry eyes, draw nigh,
</l><l ln="29      ">And, with his hot and famished breath,
</l><l ln="30      ">Pollute you in the pangs of death.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb>

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200646995</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

Fourth Series <attbytes>9Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200646995</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>

<pb>


<div3>
<poem>

<signed>[<hi r="italic">Marylebone Presbyterian Church, Home Sunday School,
Christmas Carol Service, Sunday, December</hi> 23<hi r="italic">rd</hi>, 1917,
<hi r="italic">at</hi> 3.15 <hi r="italic">p.m</hi>.]</signed>

<comhd3><idref>Z300646996</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>CHRISTMAS IN THE TRENCHES
AND AT HOME.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646996</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>CHRISTMAS IN THE TRENCHES AND AT HOME.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028371</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028371</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>CHRISTMAS IN THE TRENCHES AND AT HOME.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv>
<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016983">The famous hymn &ldquo;There came upon the midnight clear,&rdquo; 
sung at a Parade Service in the Trenches brings visions of
Home.</note>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;There came upon the midnight clear
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;The glorious song of old&rdquo;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">The words brought to a soldier's eyes,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;His lad, amid the cold:
</l><l ln="5        ">Ay, gloom and cold had passed away
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;When now, how suddenly,
</l><l ln="7        ">He saw his little girl at prayer
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Beside her mother's knee.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016984">The famous hymn, sung at a Children's Service, brings
visions of the Trenches.</note>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&ldquo;There came upon the midnight clear
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;The glorious song of old&rdquo;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="11      ">The words brought to that lad's kind eyes
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;His father, 'mid the cold&mdash; 
</l><l ln="13      ">The words brought to that daughter's heart
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;A true, if child&hyphen;like prayer
</l><l ln="15      ">That God, the Father of us all,
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Would keep him safe while there.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">O Christ, who looks upon Thy earth!
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Which once Thou foundest &ldquo;good,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="19      ">Cleanse Thou our eyes that we may see,
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Restrain each savage mood&mdash; 
</l><pb>
<l ln="21      ">Cleanse Thou our eyes that we may see&mdash; 
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Restrain from foolish fear,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">So, all Thy children, young and old,
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;May know that Thou art near.</l></stanza></pdiv>

<signed><hi r="italic">December</hi>, 1917.</signed></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646997</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>HOW WE REWARD OUR HEROES.

<subhead r="italic">(A true story of personal experience).</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646997</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>HOW WE REWARD OUR HEROES.  (A true story of personal experience).</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028372</attidref><attrhyme>n</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028372</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>HOW WE REWARD OUR HEROES.  (A true story of personal experience).</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016985">A crippled soldier speaks.</note>

<edit>[Note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016986">[Written at the request of my friend, Mr. Charles Vernon,
for March 4th, 1918, and recited by him].</note>

<firstl><l ln="1        ">Keen is the wind, although the sun is bright,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">But where's the sun for me! It seems the day
</l><l ln="3        ">On which I won my Lucy. As we walked
</l><l ln="4        ">Home from the village church life was a&hyphen;glow
</l><l ln="5        ">With love, and health, and peace. Then comes this war,
</l><l ln="6        ">And I am forced to go, leaving behind
</l><l ln="7        ">My wife and babes&mdash;to face the world alone.
</l><l ln="8        ">Soon am I wounded&mdash;feel the stinging pain
</l><l ln="9        ">And swoon. When consciousness comes back to me
</l><l ln="10      ">Maimed am I all my days. Soon am I told
</l><l ln="11      ">No longer am I needed&mdash;that a pittance
</l><l ln="12      ">Is graciously bestowed, but at the pleasure
</l><l ln="13      ">Of those above me. Stand I here, ay, here,
</l><l ln="14      ">Craving mutely for alms. I who have given
</l><l ln="15      ">More than my life to keep my Britain free!
</l><pb>
<l ln="16      ">Yon carriage splashes me! My betters say
</l><l ln="17      ">Not by their <hi r="italic">words</hi>, but by their <hi r="italic">deeds</hi>, 'tis right
</l><l ln="18      ">That I endure in silence! Yet my lord
</l><l ln="19      ">Who drives, had not been here this afternoon
</l><l ln="20      ">In splendour and in comfort, were it not
</l><l ln="21      ">For me and such as me;&mdash;yon gay, young lady
</l><l ln="22      ">Who walks erstwhile, caressing her pet dog,
</l><l ln="23      ">Looks on me coldly! Then, like to the man,
</l><l ln="24      ">Of whom the Bible, in its candour, speaks,
</l><l ln="25      ">Passes upon the other side! Well! Well!
</l><l ln="26      ">I'd rather face the hail of hostile bullets!
</l><l ln="27      ">Death would I rather face, than life! if life
</l><l ln="28      ">Brings me such cruelty, such bitter scorn!</l></poem>
</div3>



<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300646998</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TRAFALGAR.</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300646998</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TRAFALGAR.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028373</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028373</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TRAFALGAR.</mainhead><volhead>Poetical Pictures of the Great War. Suitable for Recitation. First Series ... Second Series ... Third Series ... Fourth Series. By Mackenzie Bell (1917&ndash;1918)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1917</attpubn1><attpubn2>1918</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<edit>[Note: <bytes>3Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016987"><p>Written in 1913 at the request of my friend, Mr. William
Miles, and given by him at his recitals.</p>
<p>It is a fortunate circumstance, even for the imperishable and
world&hyphen;wide renown of Nelson, that it is enshrined in two such
masterpieces of English prose as the <hi r="italic">Lives</hi> by Robert Southey,
and by Admiral Mahan, of the American Navy. If the
advisability of allusion in this ballad to certain incidents in
Nelson's career be questioned, it may, at least, be said, that
such allusions are an inseparable part of both the biographies
aforenamed, right up to the very end. The metaphor of the
&ldquo;feet of clay&rdquo; in one of the stanzas is taken from a Biblical
passage (the book of Daniel, chapter ii. verse 33). The phrases
&ldquo;Nelson,&mdash;the faithful sailor's friend,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Nelson, the just,
and kind,&rdquo; are no mere generalities. The touching anecdote
respecting the &ldquo;faithful sailor&rdquo; can be read in the second volume
of Admiral Mahan's work, page 360; and why Nelson was
&ldquo;just&rdquo; and &ldquo;kind,&rdquo; <hi r="italic">i.e</hi>. humane, is set forth at pages 374 and
381 of the same narrative. Owing to Nelson's battle&hyphen;scheme,
<pb>
the British ships had to come close to their enemies before they
were allowed to reply to their cannonade.</p>
<p>In reference to the line &ldquo;Bold Hardy come again&rdquo; it may
be said that the epithet &ldquo;Bold&rdquo; is used advisedly, as no other
epithet adequately describes Flag&hyphen;Captain Hardy from the
time of Nelson receiving his death&hyphen;wound to that Admiral's
death. For it must be recollected that he would <hi r="italic">not</hi> relinquish
the command to Vice&hyphen;Admiral Collingwood, and his conduct
placed Hardy in much difficulty. Hardy visited twice his
striken commander and life&hyphen;long friend lying in the cockpit of
his flagship, and it was on the latter occasion that the pathetic
occurrence mentioned took place.</p>
<p>In my opinion it is a striking testimony to the unity of
America and Great Britain in essentials, that Nelson's most
satisfying biographer should be a distinguished American
officer. For, great as are the merits of Southey, he has not the
fulness of detail, or of accuracy, possessed by Admiral Mahan.
The latter has not only the immeasurable advantage of writing
in the temper of a later age, when evidence could be more
readily and more convincingly sifted, but has, also, much wider
knowledge. In very early life I knew intimately the son of a
man who had served under Nelson during his last seven years,
and, consequently, had been in the <hi r="italic">Victory</hi> at Trafalgar. I was
never weary of the old man's stories, and for this, and other
reasons, have always taken a deep interest in the events,
memorable or otherwise, of the first Napoleonic period.</p></note>

<pdiv>
<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">Why do we dream of Nelson still?
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Why dream of Trafalgar?
</l><l ln="3        ">Swift moves the world; and oftentimes
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Dim seem these days afar.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">No longer have we &ldquo;wooden walls,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Seldom we plough the seas,
</l><l ln="7        ">With roods of sail,&mdash;nor are we now
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;The slaves of every breeze.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Is it because our British tars
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Are staunch,&mdash;yea, staunch as then; 
</l><l ln="11      ">Such are they. But that is not why
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;We dream, and dream again.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Is it because for us they died?
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;For us that there they bled?
</l><l ln="15      ">Is it because for Britain's might
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;High poop and deck ran red?</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Is it because our Nelson's fame
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Never shall pass away?
</l><l ln="19      ">And yet, methinks, we see him now
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;With &ldquo;feet&rdquo; of common &ldquo;clay.&rdquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">&ldquo;Enough! enough!&rdquo; here one exclaims,
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;&ldquo;Why Nelson's fame assail?&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="23      ">&ldquo;Enough!&rdquo; would we reply, &ldquo;his Judge
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Shall see the right prevail.&rdquo;</l></stanza></pdiv>

<pdiv>
<stanza><l ln="25      ">What'er his faults, where'er his face
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;And war&hyphen;worn form were seen,
</l><l ln="27      ">'Twas as if Bravery's very self
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Had donned man's garb and mien.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="29      ">Britons will dream of Trafalgar
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Oft as they call to mind
</l><l ln="31      ">Nelson,&mdash;the faithful sailor's friend&mdash; 
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Nelson, the just and kind.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Perchance, some day (may it be soon!),
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;Grim War at last may cease,
</l><l ln="35      ">And trumpets sound, but to proclaim
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;The halcyon years of peace.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">Yet while, in human life, abides
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Some unredeem&eacute;d wrong,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="39      ">While matchless courage still we love,
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Or theme of stirring song&mdash;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="41      ">Still shall we see him hurl his fleet
</l><l ln="42      ">&indent;Nigher, and yet more nigh
</l><l ln="43      ">Towards the foe's relentless fire,
</l><l ln="44      ">&indent;Silent&mdash;without reply.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="45      ">Yea,&mdash;almost feel&mdash;oh, fearful pause!
</l><l ln="46      ">&indent;These forty moments flee.
</l><l ln="47      ">The <hi r="italic">Victory</hi> fires not:&mdash;and her men
</l><l ln="48      ">&indent;Perish&mdash;all silently!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="49      ">Still shall we hear his deathless words
</l><l ln="50      ">&indent;Of praise, which tell us how,
</l><l ln="51      ">Never before, in all his fights,
</l><l ln="52      ">&indent;His men face Death as now.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="53      ">Yea&mdash;almost&mdash;shall our deafened ears
</l><l ln="54      ">&indent;Hear that appalling roar,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="55      ">His ships first broadside&mdash;almost see
</l><l ln="56      ">&indent;Him fall, to rise no more.</l></stanza>

<pb>

<stanza><l ln="57      ">Still see (as though before our eyes),
</l><l ln="58      ">&indent;Amid his cruel pain,
</l><l ln="59      ">His care for others:&mdash;almost see
</l><l ln="60      ">&indent;Bold Hardy come again</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="61      ">And touch his chieftain's ghastly brow,
</l><l ln="62      ">&indent;And kiss his pallid cheek,
</l><l ln="63      ">With touch, as soft as woman's touch,
</l><l ln="64      ">&indent;Too tender to be weak.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="65      ">Still shall we see, with inner sight,
</l><l ln="66      ">&indent;Across the sunset wave,
</l><l ln="67      ">The battle won; and then at length,
</l><l ln="68      ">&indent;The burial of the brave.</l></stanza></pdiv>
</poem>
</div3>

</div2>


