<attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z100647001</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd1>


<pb n="53">





<div2>
<poem>

<comhd2><idref>Z200647002</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>The Soldier and his Betrothed.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200647002</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>The Soldier and his Betrothed.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028375</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028375</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>The Soldier and his Betrothed.</mainhead><volhead>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1900</attpubn1><attpubn2>1900</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">One</hi> dreams of his betrothed in France,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A dark&hyphen;eyed girl with laughing glance,
</l><l ln="3        ">And wonders if he soon shall meet
</l><l ln="4        ">Her tender looks, her smile so sweet.
</l><l ln="5        ">&ldquo;Ah, ma Lucille,&rdquo; with tears he cries,
</l><l ln="6        ">&ldquo;Fain would I see the glad surprise
</l><l ln="7        ">Break the calm gaze of your dear eyes,
</l><l ln="8        ">As with high hope I come once more,
</l><l ln="9        ">Unwounded from the field of war.
</l><l ln="10      ">Fain would I see your rippling curls,
</l><l ln="11      ">More precious than those lustrous pearls
</l><l ln="12      ">My gift to you&mdash;that sometimes deck
</l><pb n="54">
<l ln="13      ">The stately beauty of your neck&mdash; 
</l><l ln="14      ">That on your bosom rise and fall,
</l><l ln="15      ">White rivals of its whiteness, all
</l><l ln="16      ">Eclipsed in utter loveliness.</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="17      ">Fain would I see again that dress; 
</l><l ln="18      ">Its dainty hue of mellow brown
</l><l ln="19      ">Sets off the clustering curls that crown
</l><l ln="20      ">Your shapely head. Fain would I see
</l><l ln="21      ">The happy village revelry
</l><l ln="22      ">That joyous day which makes you mine&mdash; 
</l><l ln="23      ">When underneath the ancient vine
</l><l ln="24      ">Around Saint Etienne's porch we pass
</l><l ln="25      ">Just coming from the wedding Mass,
</l><l ln="26      ">And leaving near to the altar stair
</l><l ln="27      ">The <hi r="italic">cur&eacute;</hi> with his silvery hair,
</l><l ln="28      ">Low kneeling now in holy prayer,
</l><l ln="29      ">To crave a blessing on us there,
</l><l ln="30      ">His guileless, gladsome, saintly soul
</l><l ln="31      ">As spotless as his pure white stole.&rdquo;</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>


<pb n="55">


<div2>
<poem>

<comhd2><idref>Z200647003</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>A Soldier's Sight of the Great Napoleon.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200647003</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>A Soldier's Sight of the Great Napoleon.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL2028376</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL2028376</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>A Soldier's Sight of the Great Napoleon.</mainhead><volhead>The Taking of the Flag And Other Recitations: By Mackenzie Bell ... With an Introduction by the Rev. J. J. Nesbitt (1900)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1900</attpubn1><attpubn2>1900</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Through</hi> all the long, the happy marches
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Across Provence, now bright with spring,
</l><l ln="3        ">He sees the gay triumphal arches,
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;He hears once more the joy&hyphen;bells ring.
</l><l ln="5        ">And then one day, through beat of drums,
</l><l ln="6        ">He hears the cry, &ldquo;The Emperor comes,&rdquo; 
</l><l ln="7        ">&ldquo;The Emperor comes&rdquo;&mdash;on every side
</l><l ln="8        ">They pass the word with looks of pride.
</l><l ln="9        ">Each soldier feels his courage rise,
</l><l ln="10      ">Fresh pleasure sparkles in his eyes,
</l><l ln="11      ">And while he stands the more upright,
</l><l ln="12      ">Sees his accoutrements are bright,
</l><l ln="13      ">And hopes his bayonet, sword, or lance
</l><l ln="14      ">Will seem to that all&hyphen;piercing glance
</l><l ln="15      ">As sword or bayonet ought to look.
</l><pb n="56">
<l ln="16      ">For who could bear the sharp rebuke
</l><l ln="17      ">Or face his comrades' words or jeers,
</l><l ln="18      ">Or worse, his comrades' covert sneers,
</l><l ln="19      ">At one the Emperor deigned to chide?</l></pdiv>

<pdiv><l ln="20      ">An hour has gone; the corps espied
</l><l ln="21      ">The staff approaching, near a wood.
</l><l ln="22      ">It stood to arms. Kind Nature's mood
</l><l ln="23      ">Was peaceful: there the stock&hyphen;dove coo'd; 
</l><l ln="24      ">The dreamer sees one purple flower,
</l><l ln="25      ">Which decked the spot that sunny hour.
</l><l ln="26      ">&ldquo;The Emperor is an altered man
</l><l ln="27      ">Since Leipsic,&rdquo; says a veteran.
</l><l ln="28      ">And yet the great Napoleon seems
</l><l ln="29      ">The ideal of a soldier's dreams,
</l><l ln="30      ">As now he passes on his course,
</l><l ln="31      ">Erect upon his snow&hyphen;white horse
</l><l ln="32      ">Amid his marshals. Soult and Ney,
</l><l ln="33      ">Heroes of many a well&hyphen;fought day,
</l><l ln="34      ">Ride near him now, in gayest trim.
</l><l ln="35      ">They jest, and sometimes speak with him&mdash; 
</l><l ln="36      ">Yet never seem to lose the sense
</l><l ln="37      ">Of that strange man's strange influence&mdash; 
</l><l ln="38      ">Of that magnetic, cruel power
</l><l ln="39      ">By which Napoleon, hour by hour,
</l><l ln="40      ">Until his fiery race was run,
</l><pb n="57">
<l ln="41      ">Remorselessly swayed every one.
</l><l ln="42      ">Firm are his lips, stern are his eyes&mdash; 
</l><l ln="43      ">Hard eyes, where naught of gladness lies; 
</l><l ln="44      ">Yet signs there are of wasting life,
</l><l ln="45      ">Wasting through care and lust of strife,
</l><l ln="46      ">That drooping lip, that haggard cheek,
</l><l ln="47      ">Of pain, of ebbing force, they speak.
</l><l ln="48      ">But none, save veterans here and there,
</l><l ln="49      ">Perceive his chill, his altered air; 
</l><l ln="50      ">The troops, o'erjoyed to see his face,
</l><l ln="51      ">See in his glance a sign of grace:
</l><l ln="52      ">His presence cures their every ill,
</l><l ln="53      ">And &ldquo;Vive l'Empereur!&rdquo; their shout is still.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div2>

