MISCELLANEOUS PIECES. <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200647007</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>

<pb n="3">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300647008</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647008</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028378</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028378</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE RIVER OF THOUGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">The</hi> strong River of Thought has an aye&hyphen;changeful course,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Yet for ever it springs from the same changeless source
</l><l ln="3        ">Where God&hyphen;given Truth in its grandeur doth reign,
</l><l ln="4        ">The regal physician of Man's mental pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Sometimes in high joyance it glideth along
</l><l ln="6        ">With glamour of music and gladness of song:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">While borne on its bosom gay pleasure&hyphen;boats sail,
</l><l ln="8        ">Rejoicing a while in the light laughing gale.</l></stanza>

<pb n="4">

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Sometimes like the stream which has sunk under ground,
</l><l ln="10      ">Yet still keeps its course mid the darkness profound,
</l><l ln="11      ">Unknown and alone it must hold on its way,
</l><l ln="12      ">Till emerging at length in the full light of day.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Sometimes like the mountain's fierce torrent it flows,
</l><l ln="14      ">And all that can hinder its progress o'erthrows;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="15      ">Possessing the power of immutable right,
</l><l ln="16      ">And strong in the strength of invincible might.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">Crass Ignorance surely succumbs to its sway,
</l><l ln="18      ">As boldly it takes its all&hyphen;conquering way,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="19      ">While keen&hyphen;sighted Knowledge appears in its train,
</l><l ln="20      ">The sweetener of pleasure, the soother of pain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Unceasingly hated by many, yet some
</l><l ln="22      ">Unceasingly love it, though oft they are dumb.
</l><l ln="23      ">Yet whatever betides, and wherever it flows,
</l><l ln="24      ">'Tis the noble who love it, the weak who oppose</l></stanza>

<pb n="5">

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Great River of Thought! our strange world doth not know
</l><l ln="26      ">The evil you check, and the good you bestow:&mdash; 
</l><l ln="27      ">May Time teach the lesson, 'twill then comprehend
</l><l ln="28      ">How well and how often you prove its true friend.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="8">

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200647009</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

SONNETS ON THE POWER OF
THOUGHT. <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200647009</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300647010</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>ASPIRATIONS.</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647010</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>ASPIRATIONS.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028379</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028379</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>ASPIRATIONS.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">O for</hi> the feelings which abide
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Within the poet's mind,
</l><l ln="3        ">That softly through his bosom glide
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And leave strange joy behind!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">O for a little of the power
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Strong, piercing, pure and clear,
</l><l ln="7        ">Which is his ever&hyphen;potent dower,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;To reach the cold world's ear!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">O for a little of the fruit
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Untinged with earthly leaven,
</l><l ln="11      ">Not fame alone, nor vain repute,
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;But something caught from Heaven.</l></stanza>

<pb n="60">

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Assurance that one's strain has cheered
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Even though it be but one,
</l><l ln="15      ">And shed on the dark path he feared
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;A little glimpse of sun.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>
</div2>

<pb n="61">

<div2><comhd2><idref>Z200647011</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

VERSES OF TRAVEL. <attbytes>12Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z200647011</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd2>


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300647012</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647012</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028380</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028380</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>THE SOUTHERN NIGHT.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Ah!</hi> how unlike the Southern night
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;To that of Northern skies,
</l><l ln="3        ">Where tedious twilight mocks its flight
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;And day but slowly dies!
</l><l ln="5        ">For there pale Eve's star&hyphen;studded veil
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;O'er all is swiftly cast,
</l><l ln="7        ">Peace seemeth wafted on the gale;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Care for a while is past.</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption r="italic">Chorus.</caption>
<l ln="9        ">O! the mellow Southern summer's night,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;How sweet it is to stray
</l><l ln="11      ">Mid scenes which the moonbeam's fairy light
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Makes lovelier far than day!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">How fair the widely&hyphen;stretching woods,
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;That clothe the spacious plain; 
</l><l ln="15      ">While Silence, queen&hyphen;like, o'er them broods
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;In solitary reign:&mdash; 
</l><pb n="99">
<l ln="17      ">How fair the river's crystal thread,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Seen faintly from afar,
</l><l ln="19      ">And glimmering pure as on it shed
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;Are gleams from many a star!</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption r="italic">Chorus.</caption>
<l ln="21      ">O! the mellow Southern summer's night, etc.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="22      ">How fair perchance the mountains lie,
</l><l ln="23      ">&indent;Though distant wondrous clear,
</l><l ln="24      ">Their snow&hyphen;wrapt peaks against the sky
</l><l ln="25      ">&indent;Viewed dimly tier on tier;&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">How fair the sleeping landscape seems,
</l><l ln="27      ">&indent;While here and there are heard
</l><l ln="28      ">Sounds breathing music's softest dreams
</l><l ln="29      ">&indent;Or laughter&hyphen;laden word!</l></stanza>

<stanza><caption r="italic">Chorus.</caption>
<l ln="30      ">O! the mellow Southern summer's night, etc.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="100">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300647013</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>TOLEDO IN 1879.</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647013</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>TOLEDO IN 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028381</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028381</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>TOLEDO IN 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Toledo!</hi> what a mint of memories,
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;Of olden tale and legend, round the name
</l><l ln="3        ">Are clustered! Mingled with such dreams as these
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;Come flashes of its brilliant blades of fame.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">How proudly must old kings in joy have thought
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;Of their fair city fitted to be great,
</l><l ln="7        ">Placed on a hill, by streams surrounded! Naught,
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;Deemed they, can alter now its high estate.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">Ah! most imperial it must once have seemed,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;When capital of many a mighty power,
</l><l ln="11      ">And Spanish sunshine in its fierceness gleamed
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;On lofty battlement and soaring tower.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">In days when from the &lsquo;Sun&hyphen;gate&rsquo; <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016988">[1] The &lsquo;Puerta del Sol,&rsquo; a still&hyphen;remaining Moorish gateway, is one
of the finest relics of old Toledo.</note> oft at morn
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Issued a goodly Moorish martial train
</l><pb n="117">
<l ln="15      ">Of turbaned knights, ere starting sternly sworn
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;To conquer for the Crescent more of Spain.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">With scimitars unsheathed swift rode they forth,
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Not seldom causing terror all around
</l><l ln="19      ">Among the peasants,&mdash;as towards the north
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;They rode, with Burgos <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016989">[1] Burgos was then the Christian capital of Spain.</note> as their utmost bound.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Then afterwards returning, Victory
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Attendant on their standards, with what joy
</l><l ln="23      ">Would comrades greet them who had come to see
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Night's cooling wings Day's sultriness destroy!</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">And when the sixth Alonso <edit>[Footnote 2: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016990">[2] There is an anachronism here which it is hoped will be
pardoned for the sake of the symmetry of the piece. Alonso VI.
flourished in the eleventh century, Cervantes in the fourteenth.</note> conquered it,
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Forcing it back into the Christian fold,
</l><l ln="27      ">Made statelier still, 'twas deemed the seat of wit,
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Its people's speech the nation's purest mould.
 <edit>[Footnote 3: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016991">[3] &lsquo;To speak <hi r="italic">en propro Toledano</hi> has since the time of Cervantes
been equivalent to <hi r="italic">the best Spanish</hi>.&rsquo;</note></l></stanza>

<pb n="118">

<stanza><l ln="29      ">When in more recent days the Spanish name
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;Had grown the most renowned of all the world,
</l><l ln="31      ">St. Quentin and Lepanto knew the aim
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;Of keen Toledan darts at foemen hurl'd.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">All these reflections come in ceaseless train,
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;While gazing sadly on its fell decay.
</l><l ln="35      ">I feel not shame that it has given me pain
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;To think its relics soon must pass away.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="37      ">Farewell, far&hyphen;famed Toledo! I shall ne'er
</l><l ln="38      ">&indent;Forget thy mien,&mdash;appearing as indeed
</l><l ln="39      ">Plunged in the deepest sleep. Few could repair
</l><l ln="40      ">&indent;Spain's ancient cities; Life is what they need.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="119">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3 r="smcap"><idref>Z300647014</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>CINTRA in 1879.</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647014</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>CINTRA in 1879.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028382</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028382</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>CINTRA in 1879.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<firstl><l ln="1        "><hi r="smcap">Cintra</hi>, <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016992">[1] See <hi r="italic">Childe Harold's Pilgrimage</hi>, canto 1.</note> our Byron gave thy name to fame
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">By his description grand, and sweet, and true; 
</l><l ln="3        ">But though thy &lsquo;mountain's ever beauteous brow&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="4        ">And many other objects are unchanged,
</l><l ln="5        ">Yet altered are full many of the scenes
</l><l ln="6        ">On which the poet looked, and mused and sang.
</l><l ln="7        ">No &lsquo;frugal monks their little relics show&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="8        ">To strangers at &lsquo;Our Lady's house of woe.&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="9        ">One sees their tiny cells, their cork&hyphen;wood walls,
</l><l ln="10      ">Honorius's cave, and that is all.
</l><l ln="11      ">The former home of &lsquo;England's wealthiest son&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="12      ">No longer has its &lsquo;portals gaping wide,&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="13      ">Its &lsquo;halls deserted,&rsquo; or great &lsquo;giant weeds&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="14      ">Within its garden ground:&mdash;but it is fair,
</l><l ln="15      ">Fair as the lordly traveller declared
</l><l ln="16      ">It was of yore. While &lsquo;Marialva's dome&rsquo; 
</l><l ln="17      ">Is changed in that 'tis now historical,
</l><pb n="123">
<l ln="18      ">Its fame a lasting one, whilst in his day
</l><l ln="19      ">Its interest was eclipsed by other themes
</l><l ln="20      ">Of ever&hyphen;varying War:&mdash;the deed performed
</l><l ln="21      ">Within its gates too recent not to be
</l><l ln="22      ">Left unto record of the daily gossip,
</l><l ln="23      ">And comments of the press which rarely live.
</l><l ln="24      ">All now is different:&mdash;a classic scene
</l><l ln="25      ">Thou standest, Cintra, clothed with more of fame
</l><l ln="26      ">(To English minds at least) from Byron's words
</l><l ln="27      ">Than from thy matchless beauty, could that be.
</l><l ln="28      ">And mayhap, in the years to come, some poet
</l><l ln="29      ">Treading the self&hyphen;same scenes will tell how one,
</l><l ln="30      ">A writer of poor verses, tried to tell
</l><l ln="31      ">What changes there had been since Byron wrote; 
</l><l ln="32      ">And he, in turn, with glowing eloquence
</l><l ln="33      ">Will paint with poet's art the tide of Change
</l><l ln="34      ">On Cintra since these lines were given forth.</l></poem>
</div3>


<pb n="127">


<div3>
<poem><comhd3><idref>Z300647015</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930<sombiog>5165</sombiog></somauth> <mainhead>GIBRALTAR.

<subhead>1880.</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300647015</ID><A1>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</A1><T1>GIBRALTAR.  1880.</T1><PBL>T. Fisher Unwin</PBL><Y1>1886</Y1><T2>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Bell, Henry Thomas Mackenzie, 1856-1930</attpoet><attidref>LL3028383</attidref><attrhyme>y</attrhyme></attribs>

<newatts><attidref>LL3028383</attidref><attdbase>English Poetry 2nd Edition</attdbase><atttitle><mainhead>GIBRALTAR.  1880.</mainhead><volhead>Verses of varied life: by H. T. Mackenzie Bell (1882)</volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi></attperi><attpubn1>1882</attpubn1><attpubn2>1882</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>5165</attautid><litpack></litpack></newatts>


<stanza><firstl><l ln="1        ">&lsquo;<hi r="smcap">Sweet</hi> Seville&rsquo; <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016993">[1] See &lsquo;Seville,&rsquo; by J. E. Carpenter.</note> has been sung&mdash;and Cadiz too
</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">&indent;By Byron, <edit>[Footnote 2: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016994">[2] Vide Lord Byron's song, &lsquo;The Girl of Cadiz.&rsquo;</note> for the beauty of her girls,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="3        ">Yet know I not that one hath given thy due
</l><l ln="4        ">&indent;To thee on whose proud crest the cloud&hyphen;wreath curls.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="5        ">Let me attempt thy praise, then, for I know
</l><l ln="6        ">&indent;That worthier pens will write of foreign towns,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="7        ">For now no place has praise with us, if so
</l><l ln="8        ">&indent;It be mayhap a jewel of our Crown's.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="9        ">&lsquo;Sweet Seville's&rsquo; Guadalquivir, famed in song,
</l><l ln="10      ">&indent;Is nothing save a nearly stagnant stream.
 <edit>[Footnote 3: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016995">[3] Except when in flood.</note>
</l><pb n="136">
<l ln="11      ">The beauty of the Cadiz maiden throng
</l><l ln="12      ">&indent;Exists,&mdash;but in a &lsquo;poet's airy dream.&rsquo;</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="13      ">Here in Gibraltar all retains an air
</l><l ln="14      ">&indent;Of honest truth. Odourless streets are clean,
</l><l ln="15      ">And everything is made the most of, where
</l><l ln="16      ">&indent;Man's art avails to soften down the scene.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="17      ">The gardens of the Alameda, full
</l><l ln="18      ">&indent;Of semi&hyphen;tropic plants and shady trees,
</l><l ln="19      ">Pleasant to lounge in their recesses cool
</l><l ln="20      ">&indent;On summer eves to catch the soft sea&hyphen;breeze.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="21      ">Yet great the toil and patience must have been
</l><l ln="22      ">&indent;Before at last was made such rocky ground
</l><l ln="23      ">To nourish shrub, or plant, or aught of green.
</l><l ln="24      ">&indent;Cheering it is to hear the home&hyphen;like sound</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="25      ">Of English tongues,&mdash;to see our cared&hyphen;for men,&mdash; 
</l><l ln="26      ">&indent;Contrasted with the Spaniards wan and weak,
</l><l ln="27      ">Guarding their posts, as they with eager ken
</l><l ln="28      ">&indent;Look on our cannon, which have but to speak&mdash;</l></stanza>

<pb n="137">

<stanza><l ln="29      ">To put their lines to rout. <edit>[Footnote 1: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="LLN016996">[1] A conspicuous row of white stone sentry&hyphen;boxes are erected at
the extremity of Spanish territory, and from them Spanish soldiers
continually watch us. Doubtless they are within easy range of our
artillery, and it is equally certain that were we to fire on them,
they have no guns in position with which to answer us.</note> How lovely gleams
</l><l ln="30      ">&indent;The Rock at sunrise! The grey looming clouds
</l><l ln="31      ">Glow in the new&hyphen;born light like glorious dreams,
</l><l ln="32      ">&indent;While Shadow still the tranquil bay enshrouds.</l></stanza>

<stanza><l ln="33      ">Ay, grim Gibraltar, thou indeed art fair!
</l><l ln="34      ">&indent;And more than that, a place in which one may
</l><l ln="35      ">Live with true home&hyphen;like comfort, and a share
</l><l ln="36      ">&indent;Of a good climate, brightening Life's dull day.</l></stanza></poem>
</div3>

</div2>

